bid for american standard inc. a second time, raising its offer to $68 from $65 per share and promising court action to block the target's recapitalization plan
the latest offer from black &amp; decker on tuesday _ worth about $2.11 billion _ surprised some analysts who said the bidding was becoming inflated
texaco inc. has agreed to pay $1.25 billion to the government to settle claims it overcharged customers for oil during the 1973-81 period of price controls
the nation's third largest oil company said tuesday it would make a first installment of $400 million when the agreement was closed and pay the rest over the following 5{ years
the white plains, n.y.-based oil giant is the latest in a series of companies forced to pay billions to resolve charges they violated pricing restrictions on crude oil and refined products during the period of federal controls
a federal judge has ruled occidental chemical corp. is liable for the estimated $250 million cost of cleaning up the love canal landfill that became synonymous with environmental disaster
after nine years of deliberations, u.s. district judge john curtin said tuesday that occidental produced the wastes that created the disaster and stored them in a way that would eventually result in toxic leakage
occidental spokesman james green said the company was disappointed by the ruling but would not comment until its attorneys had studied the decision
a former police sergeant and a suspended officer were convicted wednesday of torturing a drug suspect with an electric stun gun three years ago
in addition, a former officer was convicted of beating of the man at his home, and a suspended lieutenant was found guilty of abetting the beating
the defendants were among several police officers from the same queens precinct implicated in 1985 in the alleged torture of drug suspects with the stun gun, which delivers a powerful, temporarily disabling jolt of up to 40,000 volts
everton evelyn had testified that four officers beat him in his home in 1985, and that two of them had later used a stun gun on him at the station, holding him down and giving him shocks from the hand-held device
the 34-year-old taxi driver testified that the stun gun was used on his abdomen seven to 10 times for five seconds at a time. he has also filed a $50 million lawsuit against the city and the police department
former sgt. richard pike and suspended officer loren maccary were convicted of assault, official misconduct and coercion and could receive up to seven years in prison
jeffrey gilbert, a former officer, was convicted of the same charges in the beating. suspended lt. steven cheswick, who supervised the other three, was convicted of official misconduct and faces up to a year in jail
the jury had begun deliberating monday afternoon
pike was found guilty in both the beating and the stun gun attack; maccary was convicted in the stun gun attack; and gilbert was found guilty in the beating
cheswick, prosecutors said, had blocked evelyn's wife from aiding her husband during the beating and had not tried to stop the beating
the four defendants will be sentenced march 29
the trial was the second of four scheduled for officers of the 106th precinct who allegedly tortured suspects with stun guns in 1985. pike and gilbert already are serving two to six years for their convictions in the first trial, in 1986
a suitcase reportedly containing $30,000 has been recovered from a plane that crashed in the woods here, killing three people, authorities said
the suitcase of simon siegel, 66, of brookline, mass., was found saturday, said police lt. frank lentz
he would not discuss the contents, saying only that it contained personal belongings. the press of atlantic city on tuesday quoted sources as saying it contained $30,000
siegel, owner of siegel's egg company in roxbury, mass., was flying to an atlantic city casino friday when the plane crashed, killing him, the pilot and co-pilot
the siegel family attorney is expected to arrive later this week to reclaim the bag, lentz said
a 2-foot-long slab of ice fell from a 2,000-foot-high plane and crushed a car, authorities said. no injuries were reported
no other details were available about the plane involved in monday's incident, said federal aviation administration spokesman peter nelson, who noted that about 600 planes fly daily over the area to newark airport
workers at the penske gm power co. plant said they heard a thump and when they looked outside, saw the chunk of blue ice on the roof of employee charles reid's car
reid said he recently spent $1,400 on a new engine for his 1979 ford and joked that his insurance company would never believe what had happened. to update with motion to arrest absent senators.</note>
the senate launched a ``full-fledged filibuster'' tuesday as majority leader robert byrd ordered 24-hour sessions to subdue republican opposition to a democratic campaign financing bill
the talking, broken by occasional roll calls, began about 2 p.m. and continued into the night. appointments were canceled, schedules revised, senators began catching up on paperwork and cots were set up in rooms near the chamber
shortly after 11 p.m., the democrats used their numbers to approve a rarely-used motion ordering the sergeant-at-arms to take to the streets to arrest senators who had been absent from a series of quorum calls
democrats said the move was made because republicans were taking turns holding the floor, forcing democrats to stay close by the chamber to prevent the loss of a quorum, which would immediately end the session
byrd, lacking the votes to prevent republicans from stalling action on the legislation, threatened to keep the senate in session indefinitely
we've decided we'll just go around-the-clock,'' the west virginia democrat said at midafternoon after republican and democratic negotiators reported making no progress on the central question of spending limits
we're going to talk or we're going to vote,'' said byrd, warning that foes of the campaign finance legislation would have to keep control of the floor to prevent a vote
democrats and republicans have been at loggerheads for nearly a year over a democratic bill with 52 co-sponsors that would set up a system of voluntary spending limits for senate general election campaigns
the limit would be from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a state's population. the bill's supporters say limits are needed to put a brake on the increasing cost of getting elected, up from an average of $600,000 in 1976 to $3 million in 1986
in larger states, growing numbers of candidates are spending more than $10 million to win a senate seat, with increasing amounts of campaign funds being supplied by special-interest political action committees
a candidate observing the voluntary limit would get campaign funds from the treasury if the opponent exceeded the limit or an independent group spent large amounts of money against the candidate
republicans, who have made opposition to limits a party issue, succeeded last year in preventing the senate from voting on the legislation, winning a record seven cloture votes during 22 days of floor time
byrd, even with the support of three of the senate's 46 republicans, is believed to be five votes short of the 60 needed to cut off debate and force a vote on the bill
the senate is in a full-fledged filibuster,'' said byrd, adding that he would no longer confine debate to daylight hours
there's no point in continuing the casual, gentlemanly, good-guy filibuster because it will just turn out like it did last year,'' he said. ... let's have it on the floor where the american people can see it.''
four democrats and four republicans have been negotiating since last week. they reported progress on some facets of the bill but not on spending limits, which republicans say will discriminate against them in states with a heavy democratic edge in registered votes
the chief negotiators said their positions on the key issue were solid
a limit on spending ``is something this side is not going to agree to,'' said mitch mcconnell, r-ky. ``that is not one of the negotiable items.''
his counterpart, david boren, d-okla., was just as adamant: ``any bill that does not limit campaign spending would not be real reform.''
boren said, however, that democrats are willing to discuss higher spending limits in states where their party enjoys a big advantage in registration or historically has dominated congressional elections
there was no public response from mcconnell, who said republicans were willing to discuss compromise on another democratic demand: putting a ceiling on how much money a candidate can get from political action committees
boren and mcconnell said negotiators had neared informal agreement on other issues, including controling how much personal money a millionare can put into his or her campaign; requiring broadcasters to charge rock-bottom rates for political ads; better disclosure of money going to political parties; and getting controls on so-called ``soft money,'' which includes groups like labor unions supplying people to help candidates with canvassing and phone banks
this is one of a series of periodic reports by associated press correspondents on the way of life in other countries
india is taking the bullock-cart into the 21st century
at least 500 researchers in about a dozen government-aided institutes are at work modernizing the ancient, creaking, plodding carts, and even the world bank has donated funds. carts of various shapes and designs, made of plastic and aluminum, are being tested or have been developed
there is nothing funny about our project,'' said mittar pal dhir, director of the road research institute in new delhi. ``for us, animal-drawn carts are of great importance.''
india has an estimated 13 million bullock carts drawn by about 26 million of the neutered bulls, along with 2 million carts pulled by water buffaloes, camels, horses, mules and donkeys
the carts are seen most often in villages, where about 640 million of the india's 800 million people live
but they also are seen on major highways and an estimated 3 million plod along city streets, often slowing engine-powered traffic and infuriating motorists
bullock carts have even been used to pull mig fighter jets to parades and earth satellites to launching pads
dhir said it would be 50 years before india could eliminate animal-drawn carts, given their crucial role in indian life
capital investment in animal-drawn carts is put at $7.6 billion
more than 20 million indians earn their living by driving, renting, and repairing the carts
the figure is striking given the fact that indian railways, the fourth largest in the world, employ only 16.3 million people,'' said rupinder gupta, a mechanical engineer for the road research institute. gupta has designed six types of bullock cart for field trials
each year, animal-drawn carts move 14.4 million ton-miles of freight
dhir estimates that india's animal-drawn carts provide about 40 million horse-power, equal to about 320,000 medium-duty trucks used in the united states as city delivery vehicles
without bullock carts, india also would have had to import an additional 6 million tons of fuel each year. it now imports 17 million tons of crude oil annually
one of the innovations is the replacement of the carts' wooden-spoke wheels with pneumatic tires
engineer gupta said carts with pneumatic tires can pull 2.5 tons of weight against the maximum capacity of 1.5 tons for conventional carts
researchers in the southern state of karnataka also have come up with plastic bullock carts, and in neighboring andhra pradesh state a tire company has produced carts of lightweight aluminum
another idea behind non-wooden carts is to reduce demand for lumber. an estimated 165,000 medium-sized trees are felled each year to make conventional carts
so you see, there is a solid logic behind metal carts,'' said gupta
he listed other reasons for updating the carts
we want to increase tillage and output, reduce damage to roads and injury to animals so that the poor animals can have a longer lifespan,'' he said
to protect the animals, curved and padded yokes are being introduced. studies have shown that some draft animals' lives are cut short by cancerous infections on the neck from unpadded and uncurved yokes
reflectors are being added as another safety feature
other new fittings are bush bearings, cast-iron springs, shock absorbers, draw bars that adjust for animals of different height, and mud scrappers
a fodder box can be put on carts that go long distances
as for road damage, director dhir said the biggest culprit is wooden wheels
in monetary terms the annual damage is to the tune of 7,000 million rupees ($538 million) to the roads,'' he said
farmers seem to like the idea of improving bullock carts
it is an excellent idea,'' said jhandu singh, 64, of jharsa, a village 30 miles south of new delhi
but this should have had been done 25 years ago. we have suffered for long, and so did the animals.''
officials, too, say the new carts are catching on, but this itself is creating problems
we do not have enough new types of carts for all,'' said kalle khan, project economist of the district rural development agency in jharsa, whose office received only 16 new carts
there are more than 200 claimants. even some gypsies saw the carts and were attracted. they wanted at least one. i told them no. these are for farmers.''
another reason for high demand is that the government is subsidizing the price by about 35 percent
it is estimated that the largest of the old wooden carts costs the equivalent of about $300. newer wooden carts, without the government subsidy, cost $270 to $460. the plastic and aluminum carts are 25 percent more expensive
the town that was mao tse-tung's civil war haven in remote northwest china is struggling to catch up with a revolution that left it behind when the communist party leadership marched out 40 years ago to triumph
the caves mao called home in yenan's arid mountains are preserved much as he left them, the spartan desks and bedstands still in place
since then, yenan's population has grown from 10,000 to 80,000, and a smattering of eight- and 10-story concrete apartment blocks give the town an urban air. but the lives of most of its residents have changed little compared with the rest of china
two-thirds of yenan's people still live in caves in the steep brown cliffs overlooking two narrow rivers that meet at yenan
the cave-dwellers fetch water from nearby wells and grind their grain using old-style millstones turned by donkey or by hand. they cook on coal stoves that also heat the family sleeping platform, the kang
the caves have electricity, but few people have major electrical appliances
the average annual per capita income of yenan's peasants is $59 _ less than half the national average and barely above the official poverty level of $54. non-peasants average $108 a year, compared with a national figure of $248
the communist revolution was intended to free the peasants from the whims of nature and those in power. but in yenan, nature has been stingy and those in power are far away
we rely on heaven for food,'' said lei zhifu, a former guerrilla leader and retired communist party official, quoting an ancient saying about china's dependence on nature
mao, who arrived here in 1937 at the end of the long march, a 6,000-mile retreat from chiang kai-shek's nationalist troops, left yenan in 1947 as the country's civil war raged. he never returned
premier chou en-lai returned briefly in 1973, to attend the opening of a revolutionary museum. he ordered that small factories be set up with central government help to supplement the perennially drought-stricken area's meager agricultural income
the factories were built: fertilizer, steel, cement and textiles among others. but nothing was done to ensure that their products reached markets
only one narrow, twisting road and three weekly flights link yenan to the outside world. the nearest big city, xian, is more than 185 miles to the south, an eight-hour trip by car
since 1985, beijing has moved to end yenan's isolation by providing more than $54 million toward construction of a railroad. tracks have been laid nearly halfway from xian to yenan, and plans are to finish by 1990
there's a snag _ $43 million more is needed to build the final stretch. li guanhua, deputy director of yenan's planning commission, said he expected beijing to provide at least part
even with a railroad, li's plans for yenan's future are modest. he envisioned gradual growth fueled by wider sales for the town's factories, especially its leading industry, cigarettes
lu derong, the cigarette factory's deputy director, said they'll double production to 64 million packs a year once the railroad is finished
the workers earn an average of $405 a year, making them the best paid in town
but the railroad is unlikely to help the 200-employee match factory next door, already hard hit by competition from larger, mechanized factories elsewhere
it shut down for 10 months last year because it had no money to buy wood for matches. yenan officials finally loaned it $27,000 _ enough to reopen but not to buy modern machinery that would make it competitive
elsewhere in china, state-owned factories that lose money are being closed or leased to entrepreneurs under top leader deng xiaoping's decade-old program to stimulate the economy and reduce central controls
but li said ``no one in yenan has enough money'' to lease the match factory. and it can't be shut, officials said, because the workers need the jobs
yenan's agriculture also needs massive investment, in the form of irrigation canals, to significantly raise production. with less than 16 inches of rain annually, yields are less than half those in china's lush southeast
no efforts are made to encourage the one industry for which yenan is historically equipped: tourism. more than 50 hotels are under construction in xian alone as part of a nationwide tourism boom, but yenan offers only five small guest houses
xian, site of the ancient city of chang-an, is known for its temples and tombs. its biggest attraction is the thousands of life-size terra cotta warriors built more than 2,000 years ago to guard the tomb of emperor qin shi huangdi, who united china
of the 80,000 visitors to mao's old headquarters every year, only about 500 are foreigners, who bring far more money than chinese
yenan's dust-covered streets are uninviting and things are sleepy
even a confirmed marxist like lei zhifu said he attends ceremonies at the local buddhist temple ``for excitement.''
actor-comedian steve martin had a question as soon as he received the hasty pudding club man of the year award at harvard university: ``there is a cash prize for this, right?''
appearing tuesday in a rumpled, oversize tuxedo and rubber-soled suede shoes without laces, martin delighted the audience of nearly 200 when he leaped like a game-show contestant, shouting, ``i won, i won.''
he received a brass pudding pot, but no cash
the nation's oldest undergraduate theatrical organization gave its annual award to martin for ``his lasting and impressive contribution to the world of entertainment,'' said program co-producer andrea campbell
martin said receiving the award made up for his movie ``roxanne'' not being nominated for an oscar this year
yes it does, because it's such a prestigious award, and so few people have gotten one,'' he said
martin's first two comedy albums won grammy awards and he has written and co-starred in such box-office hits as ``the jerk'' and ``pennies from heaven.''
the hasty pudding club awarded lucille ball its woman of the year award last week
a judge in oregon makes some convicts buy newspaper ads to apologize. slumlords in california and new york are sentenced to live in their own buildings. in new jersey, executives convicted of securities violations are ordered to read up on ethics, and write reports
such innovations are sometimes motivated by overflowing jails, but in other cases are intended to tailor the punishment to the crime
on tuesday, for instance, circuit judge stuart nudelman in chicago sentenced a white man convicted of threatening blacks to do 200 hours of community service with the national assocaition for the advancement of colored people
he's going to learn how to be a responsible human being,'' nudelman said in sentencing james kalafut, 22, who was part of a group of whites and hispanics who menaced two blacks with baseball bats and bottles last year
last month, anne arundel county in maryland joined a growing number of jurisdictions that are using electronic gadgets to enforce non-jail sentences. the county's program for repeat drunken driving offenders calls for them to continue working, but turn over one-fourth of their pay to the county and spend their free time exclusively at home
to make sure they do, television cameras are installed in the homes, and a jailer calls at random times to make sure the subject is at home
there simply isn't enough room in the detention center to lock everyone up,'' explains district judge thomas j. curley, who envisions expanding the program to include those convicted of drug abuse, petty thievery or battery
the obvious selling point is the cost,'' said richard grinter, president of program monitor inc. the dallas-based firm contracts with government agencies to operate monitoring systems, and charges $7 per case per day
program monitor has only 45 cases in texas now and isn't making money, grinter said tuesday, but he said a state commission estimated in 1986 that as many as 6,000 prisoners might be suitable for electronic monitoring
program monitor provided the hardware to monitor a new york landlord, morris gross, who was convicted of multiple building violations and sentenced to live in one of his buildings in brooklyn. he was released last week after spending eight days in his newly plastered and painted apartment in the rundown building
a similar sentence was imposed last year on dr. milton avol, a beverly hills neurosurgeon convicted of numerous violations in buildings he owned
in other recent cases:
_ multimillionaire industrialist victor posner, who pleaded no contest to evading more than $1.2 million in federal taxes, was sentenced on feb. 12 to work 5,000 hours of community service over the next five years
u.s. district judge eugene spellman also ordered the 69-year-old financier to pay $4 million in back taxes and penalties, and contribute $3 million to programs for the homeless. the maximum sentence for the conviction was in excess of 40 years in prison
at your age, i doubt you'd be in jail more than six to nine months regardless of the sentence,'' spellman said
_ a city judge in charleston, w.va., ordered a man convicted of destroying a newspaper vending box to spend the next month guarding its replacement. christopher a. jones, 25, was sentenced to stand watch from 7 p.m. to 3 a.m. for 30 days
_ last september, u.s. district judge dickinson r. debevoise in newark, n.j., sentenced four former executives of a collapsed securities brokerage to read six books about suffering and afflicted people and submit reports after serving prison terms of up to 2{ years
the executives had pleaded guilty to charges in connection with the collapse of bevill, bresler &amp; schulman inc. they testified against a fifth executive, who was convicted and sentenced to eight years in prison
among the assigned books were john steinbeck's ``the grapes of wrath,'' biographies of george washington and martin luther king, and ``working your way to the botton _ the feminization of poverty.''
_ in lincoln county, ore., district attorney ulys stapleton began a program two years ago requiring convicts to apologize for their crimes in community newspapers. one of the first ads was placed by a former sheriff's detective convicted of possessing a controlled substance
sometimes the experiments don't pan out
district judge dorothy baker in portland, ore., gained national attention when she sentenced child molester richard j. bateman to post signs on his house and car warning, ``dangerous sex offender. no children allowed.''
bateman, 47, later dropped out of sight for three weeks, was rearrested and sentenced to 10 years in prison
georgia won an ``innovation in government'' award from the ford foundation last year in recognition of its comprehensive program to provide alternatives to jail time
the state has about 18,500 prison inmates, but 109,000 other convicts have been placed in programs ranging from basic probation to boot camp-style life in a diversion center, to 90-day ``shock incarceration'' for offenders aged 17 to 25
shock incarceration is intended convince violators who haven't been in prison before that they don't want to come back. a study in 1986 found that 23 percent of those who went through shock incarceration committed further crimes, compared to 22 percent for the general prison population, said larry anderson, coordinator of the state's diversion programs
at first blush you are prone to say there is no appreciable difference,'' anderson said tuesday, ``but the other way of looking at it is that we can give someone a 90-day prison experience, as opposed to an experience that may last for years, and do no worse.''
in other words, the state gets the same results for less money
in the diversion centers, where the state can accommodate up to 750 people, prisoners work during the day, and pay $6.50 a day for board and room. thus, the state's cost is $27.50 a day, compared to $37 day for each prison inamte, anderson said
the state also has an intenive probation program, in which probationers have to meet four times a week with an officer. that program is self-supporting, because judges may impose fees up to $50 a month as part of the sentence, anderson said
in 1982, anderson said, 63 percent of criminal convicts in georgia received a probated sentence. in 1985, that had increased to 73 percent
if you look at 1981, the state of georgia had the highest per-capita incarceration rate in the united states. it exceeded the incarceration rate of the soviet union and the union of south africa,'' he said
we began putting our emphasis on alternative programs in 1982, and by 1985 we had dropped down to no. 11 in per-capita incarceration rates.''
the real issue now,'' he emphasized, ``is that we cannot afford to build any more prisons.''
nbc, cbs, abc and cnn all plan to televise president reagan's news conference tonight
abc said it will interrupt its coverage of the winter olympics in calgary to televise the news conference live at 8 p.m. est
sen. bob dole defeated former television evangelist pat robertson to win minnesota's republican presidential caucuses tuesday night, with vice president george bush a distant fourth behind rep. jack kemp
two men were dead; valuable manuscripts had changed hands; false names were involved
the mystery was solved tuesday as columbia university announced that it had been given the papers of ellery queen, the dashing, upper-crust detective whose adventures helped elevate american detective fiction to an art form
ellery queen was created by brooklyn-born cousins frederic dannay and manfred b. lee, who entered a 1928 mystery contest that required a pseudonym
they invented queen and made him both author and protagonist, thinking an author would be better remembered if his name appeared throughout the book
more than 40 ellery queen novels were written before lee died in 1971. his partner, dannay, died in 1982, and dannay's sons richard and douglas gave the ellery queen papers to columbia
the manuscripts show that lee and dannay often were at odds over their work, with intense disagreements and personality clashes. there are extensive revisions; in one case, 50 pages were deleted from a novel
we're not so much collaborators as competitors. it has produced a sharper edge,'' dannay once said
the 25,000-item collection includes the only surviving manuscript of the first ellery queen novel, ``the roman hat mystery,'' and the notes, outlines and corrected manuscripts of the last, ``a fine and private place.''
also included are letters and manuscripts of dashiell hammett, cornell woolrich, john dickson carr, agatha christie and others whose work already can be found in columbia's archive of mystery and detective writing
the ellery queen novels led to a series of movies, radio and television shows, and to ellery queen's mystery magazine, which first appeared in 1941 and is still published monthly
the ellery queen archives include the first issue of the magazine, along with manuscripts from such contributors as william faulkner
selections from the archives will be on exhibit at columbia's butler library from march 3 to july 6
repeat drunken drivers convicted in a new program are being allowed to keep their jobs, but as soon as the whistle blows they must go home, stay home and stay sober. big brother will be watching, and calling
anne arundel county has invested $15,000 in 30 video monitoring systems, which are installed in offenders' homes and linked by telephone lines to a master control in the county jail
under the program launched jan. 26, offenders are not watched all the time, but they never know when a jail officer will call and ask them to step before the camera
a lot of people say i got off easy, but you're stopped in your tracks at the front door,'' said one of the first four men sentenced under the program, a three-time offender who agreed to be interviewed on condition his name not be used. ``it's not exactly a slap on the wrist, but it's better than sitting in jail.''
for this offender, the hardest part of the program is turning over $336 a month _ one-fourth of his salary _ to the county during his 90-day sentence. ``it's a big dent in our pocket,'' said his wife
an operator at the the jail dials each offender once, and often twice, a night and instructs him to turn on the video equipment and stand in front of the camera
the county also has purchased hand-held breath analyzers to make sure the offender is complying with a judge's no-drinking stipulation. the equipment displays alcohol levels in bright red numerals that can be read over the tv monitor
house detainees also are required to turn over one-quarter of their take-home pay to the county. if an offender's home doesn't have an adequate telephone jack, he has to pay for one
violation of any condition brings a jail sentence
john sellers, government marketing coordinator for mitsubishi electric, said the visitel system has been used in several states to monitor probationers, but he said anne arundel county is apparently the first to use the system as an alternative to prison sentences
at least 11 manufacturers are marketing systems, according to the national institute of justice
the program has been endorsed by the local chapter of mothers against drunk driving. jean heald, president of the group, said that when the program is combined with an alcohol counseling program it may help make highways safer
we're hopeful. sending them to jail we know doesn't work,'' said ms. heald, who said the program is in keeping with a philosophy of ``punishment for the crime, treatment for the disease and monitoring for the citizen.''
county officials plan to review the program in the next few weeks and decide whether to buy 90 additional monitors this smmer
district judge thomas j. curley drug users, petty thieves and those convicted of minor battery charges are also likely candidates for house detention
asked if he expects public opposition, curley was frank: ``are you kidding? nothing is ever tough enough for them. but i have to live in the real world.''
house detention is an alternative to paying up to $40 a day to keep a prisoner in the county jail, as well as putting off the cost of constructing new prisons
there simply isn't enough room in the detention center to lock everyone up,'' said curley
electronically enforced home-detention programs have expanded rapidly since the first reported test in albuquerque, n.m., in 1983
as of last february, according to the national institute of justice, an arm of the u.s. justice department, 53 house-detention programs in 21 states electronically monitored more than 800 offenders. most programs rely on electronic bracelets that signal when an offender has strayed from home
the institute reported that offenders in such programs tended to be males under the age of 30. about one-third were convicted of serious traffic violations, particularly drunken driving. another large category included parolees and probationers. israeli was offered discount on oil from proposed pipeline. pickup 6th graf ``the memo...'' ^with am-israel, bjt</note>
foreign minister shimon peres on tuesday denounced as ``complete nonsense'' a memo that described plans to funnel millions of dollars to his labor party for assurances that israel would not bomb a proposed iraqi pipeline
the 1985 memo, made public monday, was addressed to u.s. attorney general edwin meese iii and written by e. robert wallach, a longtime meese friend and lawyer for swiss oilman bruce rappaport, a partner in the pipeline project
the $1 billion pipeline was to have carried oil from iraq through jordan to the gulf of aqaba, but was never built
israeli officials ``all agreed that we favored the laying of the pipeline. so why would anyone need to use bribes?'' peres told reporters during a tour of the occupied west bank's largest city. ``i don't understand this.''
however, peres through a spokesman in jerusalem acknowledged tuesday that the israeli government had been offered a discount on oil purchases amounting to $65 million to $70 million a year in return for approving the pipeline, the washington post reported in wednesday's editions
but the aide said that peres did not take the offer seriously and failed to pass it on to colleagues, the newspaper said. he said the offer was made by rappaport but there was no proposal for paying part of the discount to peres' party, the post reported
an israeli military analyst on tuesday told the associated press it would not have been in israel's interest to destroy the pipeline because israel has sought a dialogue with iraq to counter growing hostility from iran
the memo said rappaport ``confirmed the arrangement with peres to the effect that israel will receive somewhere between $65 million and $70 million a year for 10 years out of the conclusion of the project.''
what also was indicated to me,'' wallach wrote to meese, ``and which would be denied everywhere, is that a portion of those funds will go directly to labor.''
the memo is central to a criminal investigation of meese. at issue is whether meese knew of a possibly improper payment plan involving the labor party and, if so, why he did nothing about it
in a handwritten note from peres to meese, also made public monday, the israeli leader said of the pipeline project: ``i would go a long way to help it out. but then discretion is demanded on our part.''
asked about the wallach-meese memo, peres said: ``no one said he gave the labor party anything or proposed anything to the labor party. as far as i'm concerned, it's complete nonsense.''
earlier, a foreign ministry aide close to peres told the associated press: ``mr. peres did not see a penny out of this, and neither did the labor party.''
we repeatedly have denied the whole story,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``no money was offered to mr. peres and if it had been, he would have thrown the man out the window.''
another ministry official told the ap that several cabinet ministers privately discussed the pipeline project, but no decision about israel's position was ever made
dore gold, a researcher at tel aviv university's jaffee center for strategic studies, said bombing the project would not have been in israel's interest, but iraq probably ``sought as many assurances as possible regarding a pipeline that would come so close to israeli borders.''
gold said israel has sought to open a dialogue with iraq to counter growing hostility from iran following that country's 1979 islamic fundamentalist revolution
for example, israel several years ago made an offer to iraq to reactivate a pipeline built in the 1930s from the iraqi city kirkuk to the israeli port city of haifa. gold said iraq never responded to the offer
but zeev eytan, another jaffee center researcher, said israel had good reason to oppose the iraqi pipeline because it would have turned the jordanian city of aqaba into an oil port and destroyed the economic base of the neighboring israeli resort elat
said eytan: ``we need this like we need stones in the (occupied) territories.'' elections</head>
people who observe the sabbath on saturdays have the right to cast absentee ballots in elections held on saturdays, a federal judge ruled
in a case arising from west virginia's march 5 constitutional amendment election, u.s. district judge william m. kidd issued a preliminary injunction tuesday in favor of two seventh-day adventists who had been told they could not submit absentee ballots for the saturday voting
the ruling also affects jews, seventh-day baptists, and members of other religious groups who believe that they should not participate in any civic, business, governmental or non-essential work on saturdays
karen and howard conner, school bus drivers in barbour county, contended that because of their religious beliefs, they were being deprived of their right to vote on a proposed amendment that would establish a statewide property tax for education
west virginia usually holds elections on tuesdays, but moved this one to saturday in hopes of boosting turnout. the election was set after a state court ruled that the state must equalize spending among school systems
the conners were told by the secretary of state's office that they did not qualify for absentee voting under state law. they then filed suit in state court against secretary of state ken hechler and barbour county circuit clerk jean green
the state supreme court earlier this month refused to hear the case, so the conners took it to the federal court
kidd ordered hechler to submit by friday a plan ``outlining measures to be taken to ensure that plaintiffs and members of this class are permitted to vote in the forthcoming election.''
radio personality wolfman jack has been named host of a new ``rock 'n' roll palace'' cable television show on the nashville network
the weekly 30-minute program beginning april 2 will feature music stars from the 1950s and 1960s, including the coasters, the shirelles, del shannon, the diamonds, paul revere, bobby vee, the comets, and joey dee and the starliters, tnn announced tuesday
wolfman jack was host of the ``midnight special'' show on nbc-tv for nine years and now has various radio programs. he played himself in the movie ``american graffiti.''
his new show will be taped at little darlin's rock 'n' roll palace in kissimmee, fla
basketball star earvin ``magic'' johnson told 1,200 teen-agers that he never should have dropped out of college and still intends to get his degree
johnson, who led the los angeles lakers to four national basketball association championships in his eight years with the club, spoke to a cheering throng monday at westchester high school, which has a 30 percent dropout rate
i am 40 hours short of my degree in telecommunications, but i intend to get it,'' he said
my first year of high school, i was hoopin' good,'' recalled johnson of his childhood in lansing, mich. ``but my grades were real low. my counselor pulled on my coattails and told me, `you are getting ds and cs and es. you won't go to college and play ball if you don't pull 'em up.''
there were a few gasps from the audience
if she didn't get to me i might not be standing here rapping to you. i might be somewhere else. it's never too late to get yourself together.''
asked about his future, johnson said he hoped to play five or six more years with the lakers, ``then i'd like to get into my businesses. hopefully, i will own a building 18-20 stories high and maybe hire a few of you.''
jazz pianist-composer billy taylor says money spent sending american artists to festivals abroad is money well spent
in traveling to places like a jazz festival in india, i've seen russia, japan, france, australia, sent their best,'' taylor said tuesday. other nations know about american music through records, but ``that knowledge is flawed if they don't get some of our very best. we have to find measures to at least be competitive in this way.''
taylor was attending an announcement by the rockefeller foundation, u.s. information agency and national endowment for the arts of a fund to support the sending of u.s. artists to international festivals and exhibitions
one of the things i find, traveling around the world, is that i become intensely patriotic,'' said taylor
aston martin, the u.s.-owned purveyor of expensive sports cars, kept up its ties with the british royal family by giving scaled-down cars to the young sons of prince charles and princess diana
company chairman and chief executive victor gauntlett made the presentation tuesday. but 5-year-old prince william and 3-year-old prince harry may have to wait a while before getting behind the wheels. asked if his children are ready to drive, the prince of wales said, ``gracious, no.''
the 8.5-foot-long, 4@7-scale aston martins each cost about $17,500. they are equipped with stereo radios and cassette players, electrically powered aerials, five-speed gearboxes, leather upholstery, headlights and turn signals
aston martin, which is controlled by the american manufacturer ford, said the junior cars are like the aston martin v-8 volante that charles drives in virtually every detail. instead of a v-8 british-built engine capable of a maximum speed of 153 mph, however, they are powered by a honda engine made in japan and tuned to reach 25 mph
