fbi agents illegally interrogated a suspected lebanese terrorist about a 1985 airplane hijacking when they kept him aboard a navy ship four days after his arrest in the mediterranean, a federal judge says
sharply critical of the fbi's arrest and interrogation of fawaz younis, u.s. district judge barrington d. parker on tuesday ruled that oral and written confessions were obtained illegally from the defendant
the judge suppressed the statements as evidence against younis, who is charged with leading five armed men who hijacked a royal jordanian airliner on june 11, 1985, at beirut international airport. the trial is scheduled to begin march 22 before parker
the operation occurred after former fbi director william h. webster had moved on to head the cia and before william sessions, the bureau's current head, took office last fall
defense lawyer francis d. carter said he was pleased with the decision but conceded it won't necessarily help younis' case. prosecutors have a variety of other evidence, including a videotape of younis delivering a statement to reporters before the plane was blown up in the background
oliver revell, the bureau's executive assistant director, participated in the arrest of younis last sept. 13 in waters off cyprus
parker concluded that fractures younis suffered on both wrists were sustained when he was grabbed by two agents and slammed onto the deck of an fbi-chartered yacht, to which he had been lured by the prospect of a drug deal
throbbing pain from the fractured wrists, sea sickness and the lack of proper medical treatment ``placed him at a distinct disadvantage where he could scarcely understand intelligently his rights as explained and translated to him, much less be able to voluntarily waive them.''
the fbi agents gave younis the only warning of his constitutional right to remain silent shortly after he arrived seasick on the uss butte, a munitions boat that steamed four days before meeting with the aircraft carrier uss saratoga, parker noted
they saw and knew that he was in a weakened state and susceptible to persuasion,'' parker said
younis was kept in a windowless overheated room during the voyage, which parker called ``a clear abuse of the obligation to bring the defendant before a judicial officer immediately following his arrest.''
the ship's ``slow voyage across the mediterranean appeared to serve only the government's purposes _ ample time to educe a confession,'' parker said in his 47-page opinion
only after his arrival in washington were younis' fractured wrists ``correctly diagnosed and appropriately treated,'' the judge said
we are reviewing the decision carefully,'' timothy j. reardon iii, principal assistant u.s. attorney, said in a statement. fbi officials declined to comment on the decision, said spokeswoman susan schnitzer
the judge said he was also ``extremely troubled'' by the fbi's failure to provide younis with a lawyer during the interrogation, particularly since the operation to arrest him had been carefully planned
the government was not just bringing another defendant into the station house for questioning,'' he said, also criticizing the fbi for not using a video camera to record the interrogations
in addition to the videotape of younis at the scene, the government also plans to present testimony from two americans who were among the passengers and crew taken off the plane before its destruction
the fbi also can rely on the testimony of jamal hamdan, a one-time friend of younis who lured him onto the yacht. hamdan, who lived in cyprus, secretly taped conversations he had with younis about the hijacking
now that a sculpture of three battle-weary infantrymen stands near the vietnam veterans memorial, some senators want to place a bronze statue of an army nurse nearby to honor the 10,000 women who served in the southeast asia conflict
several leading veterans' organizations applaud the proposal by sens. david durenberger, r-minn., and alan cranston, d-calif. but maya lin, the young woman architect who designed the memorial, isn't happy
i cannot see where it will all end,'' she said at a senate hearing tuesday. ``what is to stop someone from trying to add a female statue to the iwo jima memorial?''
ms. lin was supported by others who warned that unless officials stop caving in to pressure for more additions, the vietnam memorial will turn into a ``sculpture garden'' of special interests ranging from native americans to scout dogs
j. carter brown, chairman of the commission of fine arts which rejected the women's statue proposal last october, said the original memorial _ now bearing the names of 58,156 war dead including eight nurses on its black granite walls _ symbolically includes all vietnam veterans
he said the addition of the sculpture of three infantrymen triggered envy among other groups who felt left out. his commission believed that ``including a white, army nurse would only continue and exacerbate that process of exclusion,'' he said
at a crowded hearing by a senate energy and natural resources subcommittee, robert w. doubek, former executive director of the vietnam veterans memorial fund, said a woman's sculpture would ``destroy the symbolism and aesthetics of the memorial.''
but john p. wheeler iii, chairman of the private fund which raised $11 million to build the memorial, supported the nurse's statue and discounted ``the threat of a sculpture garden'' cited by critics
donna-marie boulay, a minneapolis lawyer who served in vietnam as an army nurse, testified that the statue should be erected because nurses shared ``the intensity, the trauma, the carnage of war'' with infantrymen
she is chairman and co-founder of the vietnam women's memorial project, a non-profit organization founded in 1984
durenberger's bill, which has 56 senate co-sponsors, specifies that after a woman's statue is placed at the 2.2-acre site near the lincoln memorial, ``the vietnam veterans memorial will be complete and no further additions to the site should be authorized or undertaken.''
the bill, if enacted, would require the three agencies whose approval is required _ the interior department, the fine arts commission and the national capital planning commission _ to reconsider the proposal within 90 days. the statue has been approved by the interior department but rejected by the other two agencies
the memorial, which is administered by the national park service, has become the most popular tourist attraction among all the federal monuments in the capital. an estimated 20 million people have visited the memorial since it was dedicated in 1982
america's commitment to necessities such as transportation, water supply and waste disposal is barely adequate and will fall far short of future needs without sharply increased spending on public works, a federal council warned today
the report to the president and congress calls for twice as much annual capital spending for public works projects over the next dozen years and suggests a broad range of possible money sources from higher federal fuel taxes to local ``impact fees'' on developers
in most cases we cannot rely simply on wiser spending. we also must generate additional sources of funding,'' declared the report by the national council on public works improvement
the council was established by congress four years ago to take a close look at the nation's problems with its ``infrastructure,'' a bureaucratic term covering a variety of public projects from highway and airport construction to water management and disposal of toxic wastes
the quality of america's infrastructure today is barely adequate to meet current requirements and insufficient to meet the demands of future economic growth,'' the report concludes
the group acknowledged that major increases in spending for public works may be difficult amid growing federal budget pressures, and perhaps even impossible until the federal budget deficit is reduced. but it said such spending ``must rank high among our priorities.''
in a report card on each major type of public works, the council gave no failing grades but suggested that a far better job needs to be done in all areas. the country's battle to deal with toxic wastes was given a d, and a c or c-minus was awarded for coping with mass transit, solid waste disposal and waste water treatment needs
managing water resources was given a b, the best grade, followed by b-minuses for aviation and water supply management
in general the aviation system has handled rapid increases in demand safely and effectively. ... congestion is the system's primary problem,'' said the council
discussing hazardous wastes, the council said that while spending to clean up contaminated sites has increased fivefold in the last two years, ``only a small fraction of the 2 tons of waste per capita produced in america each year is being treated safely.''
on water quality, the council suggested that governments at all levels have been fighting a losing battle
despite (a) $44 billion federal investment in sewage treatment since 1972, water quality has not improved significantly. ... due in part to uncontrolled sources of pollution such as run-off from farmland and roadways,'' said the report
overall capital spending for public works projects totaled $45 billion in 1985, the latest year for which figures were available. the council said the amount of spending by all levels of government and the private sector will have to double by the end of this century if future needs are to be met
the report said overall spending on public works has declined from 3.6 percent of gross national product in 1960 to 2.6 percent in 1985. while spending on operations and maintenance has kept pace with economic growth, capital spending has fallen from 2.3 percent of gnp to 1.1 percent
government spending for public works at all levels has declined from 20 percent of total government spending in 1950 to 7 percent in 1984, the report continued
in effect we're drawing down past investments without making commensurate investments of our own,'' said the report. ``failure to reverse this decline will exact a high price for the nation in the future both in the cost of deferred investment and in reduced economic competitiveness.''
the council endorsed the ``general principle'' that users and beneficiaries of public works projects, including developers, be required to pay a greater share of the cost of such projects
it also criticized the hoarding of money in various federal public works trust funds so that the federal budget deficit will appear smaller. in 1987 the unspent balances in the federal highway, transit, aviation and waterway trust funds totaled nearly $24 billion, the council said
federal user fees paid in good faith by beneficiaries to preserve and protect public works systems (should) be spent for that purpose,'' the report said
u.s. officials say they are receiving signs that panamanian president eric arturo delvalle may be ready to disassociate himself from military strongman manuel antonio noriega
any such move would further weaken noriega and possibly hasten his demise as the dominant force in panamanian politics, the officials said
the reagan administration looks upon noriega as the principal obstacle blocking its goal of an eventual transition to elected, civilian-led rule in panama
the officials, who asked not to be identified, said delvalle has privately expressed his intention for many weeks to distance himself from noriega but they recognize that such a step would require considerable courage
we get information from all sorts of sources, including friends and relatives, that he is about to do something along these lines,'' one official said. congressional sources, also insisting on anonymity, said they have heard the same reports
since last summer, the administration has been publicly encouraging panama's military officers to withdraw from politics as a means of promoting a return to rule by civilians. in the meantime, much of the u.s. aid program to panama has been suspended and panama has expelled all u.s. aid personnel
two federal indictments against noriega on drug trafficking charges added a new dimension to the already strained relationship. the indictments, handed down in florida earlier this month, portrayed noriega as a key member of an international drug smuggling conspiracy. in the congress, opposition to noriega spans the political spectrum
delvalle assumed the presidency in 1985 under circumstances which strongly suggested that noriega had forced his predecessor, nicolas ardito barletta, from office
it was a constitutional succession but delvalle has been widely perceived as no more than panama's titular head
noriega has maintained that executive authority rests with delvalle and that panama has achieved a full transition to democracy. noriega says his u.s. critics are campaigning against him for the purpose of annulling the panama canal treaties, under which the waterway reverts to panamanian control at the end of 1999
attempts to obtain comment from the panamanian embassy on delvalle's purported intentions were not successful
for the united states, the stakes in panama are extraordinarily high. the administration believes that a democratic, politically stable panama offers the best assurance for the continued efficient operation of the canal
the u.s. officials noted that challenging noriega would not be an easy step for delvalle. they said delvalle's extensive business interests and his family could be threatened if he breaks with noriega. in addition, delvalle's health is said to be tenuous because of a heart operation
however, the officials said delvalle has become increasingly disturbed by his ties to noriega and that some of his friends have rebuffed him because of that association
delvalle also may be tempted to act because of panama's growing financial crisis. ``the country is falling apart all around him,'' said one source
lawrence chewning fabrega, a panamanian diplomat who resigned recently in protest over noriega's rule, said in an interview this week that the country's financial problems are so severe the government may not be able to meet its payroll next month
stung by complaints that it revived vietnam-era spying on political protesters, the fbi has initiated top-level reviews of terrorism investigations that could interfere with legitimate activity
fbi officials said tuesday that the policy results from problems with an increasingly controversial investigation of a group opposing president reagan's central america policies
in that probe, some fbi field offices came ``very close'' to conducting an improper political investigation of the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador, despite warnings from headquarters, said fbi executive assistant director oliver b. revell
while vigorously defending the legitimacy of the march 1983-june 1985 investigation, revell told the senate intelligence committee that neither he nor former fbi director william webster _ now head of the cia _ closely supervised the probe
the investigation ended without filing of any charges, but before it was completed fbi agents had collected information not only on cispes members but also more than a hundred other groups and individuals opposed to reagan policies. targets of the surveillance included roman catholic nuns, college professors and labor union officials
fbi spokeswoman sue schnitzer acknowledged to a reporter that the new reviews were ``related to'' the first amendment concerns arising from the cispes investigation
in addition, fbi director william sessions has ordered an internal investigation of the bureau's conduct specifically in the cispes case
cispes has accused the fbi of investigating its members solely because of its political stance, recalling fbi surveillance of opponents of the vietnam war
the vietnam-era surveillance came under intense congressional criticism in the 1970s and led to attorney general's guidelines intended to govern the bureau's investigative conduct
tuesday, several members of the senate intelligence committee told revell they believe the bureau acted on flimsy evidence to keep the cispes investigation alive
sen. william cohen, r-maine, complained that cispes was targeted for ``a nationwide dragnet-type operation'' while investigations of reagan's central america supporters were ``much more limited, more surgical.''
revell said ``we have taken interim steps to increase the level of review'' of sensitive investigations conducted under the largely classified guidelines for international terrorism probes
under the new policy, ms. schnitzer said, the conduct of international terrorism investigations will be reviewed by a deputy assistant director who reports to revell _ who has responsibility for all criminal investigations
revell told the senators that webster was ``aware of several cables sent to him for informational purposes'' in the cispes probe, but ``he did not authorize, nor did i authorize any supervisory activity. that occurred at the sectional level'' three steps below revell
ms. schnitzer said webster and revell ``had a limited amount of knowledge'' of the cispes investigation
international terrorism investigations _ such as the cispes probe _ are conducted under guidelines which do not require the fbi to have evidence of a specific crime
in the cispes investigation, the fbi said it had information that some cispes members were planning violent activities in the united states, possibly in conjunction with the fmln _ the coalition fighting the u.s.-backed government of el salvador. the bureau characterizes the fmln as a ``terrorist'' organization
the bureau also said cispes members were investigated after bombings at the u.s. capitol and the army national war college at fort mcnair in washington in 1983, although no evidence against them was found
revell said much of the information that started and fueled the investigation came from frank varelli, a former informant in dallas whose information proved to be a ``mixed bag ... some blatantly false, some concocted in his own mind.''
that did result in the investigation being misled in certain material facts,'' said revell, adding the bureau only discovered the problem ``after the fact.''
varelli is now suing the fbi, saying it still owes him money for his informant work
revell also said the fbi made a mistake when it disseminated _ under a ``secret'' classification _ derogatory information received about cispes from a conservative group. the information from the young america's foundation was sent to 33 field offices
i did not approve it or sign it,'' revell said. ``i would not have. ... it was inappropriate to indicate that the views of another organization should be considered by our investigators.''
this west african nation votes for president and national assembly on sunday in a multiparty election, a rarity on a continent dominated by one-party and military governments
with only five days left until national elections, the war of words escalated tuesday as four presidential candidates and six political parties wound up campaigning
opposition politicians accused the socialist party, which has ruled since independence from france in 1960, of rigging sunday's elections in advance and sending armed militias to break up opposition party gatherings
the president and socialist leader, abdou diouf, 52, a tall, angular technocrat, is widely expected to retain his seat and legislative majority
but young voters in some urban areas may back abdoulaye wade, a 61-year-old lawyer who leads the senegalese democratic party, the country's largest opposition group. wade has called for change in the government's generally conservative, pro-western policies
tensions were high in the cities, where there have been sporadic student strikes and stone-throwing incidents between young supporters of the different parties
wade's party has formed its own ``people's resistance committees'' to safeguard its meetings
we will mobilize our supporters to go to the polling stations,'' said ousmane ngom, a party spokesman. ``if we see fraud, we will occupy the interior and communications ministries to prevent them from announcing their fraudulent results. if we think we have the majority, we will declare victory and declare a new government.''
diouf said monday the government was ``prepared to deal with all excesses,'' and there will be ``no liberty for the enemies of liberty.'' he has insisted the elections will be free, fair and democratic
diouf has governed the country since 1981, when he took over from retiring leader leopold sedar senghor
other candidates in the presidential race are babacar niang, 59, of the people's liberation party, and landing savane, 43, of the revolutionary movement for a new democracy
niang and savane, a maoist, have both said they have little chance of winning and are participating to show there is an alternative to the socialists
serigne diop, former wade supporter and leader of the senegalese democratic party for renovation, backed diouf's candidacy but hoped to win legislative seats for his own party
the marxist-oriented democratic league-labor movement, led by abdoulaye bathily, 43, also offered only legislative candidates
in 1983, diouf retained the presidency and his party took 111 of the 120 seats in the national assembly in the country's first multiparty elections. wade and other opposition politicians claimed that election was marred by fraud
wade has again accused the government of distributing voter registration cards through diouf's party rather than through independent registration committees. he also said the government radio, television and semi-official le soleil newspaper have given preferential coverage to socialist candidates
opposition politicians have criticized the country's austerity program, which is backed by the international monetary fund and world bank, but which has brought a reduction on civil service openings for university graduates and other belt-tightening measures
earlier this month, four senegalese gendarmes, two non-commissioned officers and three police sergeants were arrested on charges of plotting the secession of the casamance, senegal's southernmost province
violent separatist demonstrations led by ethnic diola agitators in the casamance capital, ziguinchor, in december 1983, caused more than 100 deaths. scores of ringleaders were later sentenced to long prison terms and the main secessionist association was outlawed
senegal has a population of 7 million. the largely agricultural nation has suffered from recurring droughts and the southern advance of the sahara desert. its chief export is groundnuts
the nikkei stock average closed at 24,968.65 points, up 19.20 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on wednesday
