up to 20 million americans are in line for some temporary tax relief when they file their returns this year _ and many apparently are totally unaware
president reagan considers the relief so important that he has asked congress to make it permanent, at a cost to the treasury of $400 million a year
the benefits are limited to owners of shares in publicly offered mutual funds that have at least 500 shareholders. the provision is one of those special-interest amendments that seem to find their way into every tax bill, especially when those bills are written behind closed doors
this one has its roots in the 1986 tax overhaul. as part of that big change, the itemized deduction for miscellaneous expenses was limited to those that exceed 2 percent of adjusted gross income
thus, a taxpayer's deduction of union dues, subscriptions to job-related publications, work uniforms and the like would be restricted to the portion exceeding that income threshold. for example, if adjusted gross income was $30,000 and miscellaneous deductions totaled $2,000, only $1,400 could be deducted
in writing the 1986 tax law, the senate at the last minute included a section, aimed at preventing tax evasion, that prohibits a ``pass-through entity'' _ such as a mutual fund _ from deducting an expense that an individual could not deduct
as a result, managers of mutual funds are dividing up their operating costs among shareholders, who are treated as if they had received those costs as income. they must list this income on their tax return
this ``phantom income,'' argued the investment company institute, which represents managers and underwriters of mutual funds, ``cannot be banked, cannot be invested and cannot be used to buy groceries. the only thing it is good for is to pay taxes on.''
but could not the recipient simply write off the ``phantom income'' as an investment expense? sure _ if the recipient itemized deductions. maybe
unless a shareholder's total miscellaneous expenses exceeded 2 percent of his or her adjusted gross income, the mutual-fund writeoff would be lost. but the shareholder would still have to list the money as taxable income
in the closing days of the 1987 congressional session, tax-writers meeting behind closed doors agreed there was some inequity and gave shareholders relief for another year
that means mutual-fund expenses that are reported to a shareholder as income for 1987 may be deducted as a miscellaneous expense without regard to the 2-percent threshold. other miscellaneous expenses will, of course, still be subject to the threshold
this relief became law in late december, but word is slow getting out. money magazine, in asking 50 professional tax preparers to calculate the liability of a hypothetical family, found that 20 of the 50 were not aware of the change
internal revenue service offices in several cities say they have never heard of the change. the only mention of the provision in irs publications is a caution to taxpayers that congress was considering some relief when the literature went to press
but the last chapter has yet to be written. in the 1989 budget that he sent to congress last week, reagan asked to make permanent the relief for mutual-fund holders _ an idea that already has wide support among congressional tax-writers
civil defense workers found two more bodies when they blew up what remained of a building that collapsed during flooding and mudslides that killed at least 80 people in rio de janeiro
president jose sarney toured some of the worst-hit areas on tuesday as residents of the city of 5.6 million cleared away dirt and debris left by three days of torrential rains that began friday
civil defense workers on tuesday combed through the wreckage of the three-story building in the santa teresa district overlooking downtown rio after using dynamite to explode what was left of the structure
most of the building, which housed a medical clinic, collapsed under a mudslide, killing at least 11 elderly patients. a civil defense spokesman, bruno avila, said workers expected to find 10 to 15 more bodies in the rubble
he said rescue workers found two other bodies in rio on tuesday
sarney, flanked by cabinet ministers and rio state officials, flew aboard an air force helicopter to view the hillside shantytowns where cascading mud and rocks buried dozens of shacks. the president also visited the mountain resort city of petropolis, 40 miles north of rio, where floods and landslides earlier this month killed at least 167 people
according to civil defense figures, a total of 276 people have died in the rio de janeiro area because of unusually heavy rains since feb. 2
in the working-class neighborhood of abolicao, on rio's north side, firefighters and volunteers dug through the rubble of a three-story apartment building on tuesday. since it collapsed sunday, 12 bodies and 14 survivors have been pulled from the debris. residents said a teen-age girl remained missing
government and private engineers said there was still a risk of new landslides in 27 mountain shantytowns
donations and pledges of food, clothing, medicine, tents, beds and money poured in from other states and foreign countries, including the united states
state health officials vaccinated rio residents against tetanus and leptospirosis, a potentially deadly disease carried by rat droppings
rio state hospitals reported 162 cases of leptospirosis and at least six deaths from the disease
after four months without a news conference, president reagan faces questions tonight on hostage-taking in lebanon, israel's crackdown in the occupied territories, and the bitter fight by republicans wanting to succeed him
reagan also may be asked about his embattled attorney general, edwin meese iii, the target of an investigation by an independent counsel, and the separate felony convictions of former white house aides and presidential confidants lyn nofziger and michael k. deaver
also still awaited is reagan's reaction to a plan by house democrats for $25 million in ``humanitarian'' aid for nicaragua's contras, a package that was put together after rejection of the president's proposal to give the rebels new weapons
on the political front, reagan has doggedly steered clear of involvement in the gop presidential race. however, he may be tempted to comment on the increasingly sharp words between republicans, given that he is the author of the so-called 11th commandment forbidding republicans to speak ill of each other
the 8 p.m. est session in the east room will be reagan's first news conference since last oct. 22, which was dominated by questions about the 508-point collapse of the stock market
a lot has happened since then, and reagan has had little to say except in prepared speeches. he has been largely isolated from the press, commenting only occasionally in response to a shouted question as he boards a helicopter or to a query during a picture-taking ceremony in the oval office
tonight's session comes amid intense diplomatic activity by secretary of state george shultz in moscow and the middle east
shultz, who arrived back in washington on tuesday evening, was reporting to reagan today on his talks in moscow about arms control, the timing of a superpower summit and the likelihood of a red army pullout from afghanistan
all of those issues pose possible questions for reagan
with barely a day back in the capital, shultz leaves again tonight, this time to the middle east where he will meet with arab and israeli leaders about efforts to revive peace negotiations
white house officials say there is an urgency to shultz' efforts in the middle east because of the violence in the occupied west bank and gaza. the united nations says 63 palestinians have been killed by israeli gunfire since violence began dec. 8
shultz said tuesday he has encountered ``intense skepticism'' about the chances of a breakthrough on middle east negotiations, but the united states has ``a few ideas'' that could help end the deadlock
reagan likely will be asked about the kidnapping in lebanon of marine lt. col. william r. higgins and the eight other americans seized there
higgins, onetime aide to former defense secretary caspar weinberger, was serving with u.n. forces when he was taken in southern lebanon last wednesday. reagan raised some questions by saying he wanted ``to rescue'' higgins, but aides later clarified that he was referring to diplomatic efforts, not a military maneuver
a group calling itself the organization of the oppressed on earth claims to have abducted higgins. the group is demanding israeli withdrawal from the ``security zone'' it maintains in south lebanon, release of palestinian and lebanese prisoners held by israel and suspension of u.s. diplomatic activity in the middle east. surgery</head>
sen. joseph r. biden jr. wore a blue baseball cap to hide his scar as he left walter reed army medical center 12 days after undergoing brain surgery that will have to be repeated in a few months
doctors said they were ``delighted'' with biden's recovery from surgery feb. 12 to repair an aneurysm in an artery supplying blood to the senator's brain
but a hospital statement said that a second aneurysm has been found and will have to be corrected later
biden, 45, left the hospital tuesday by car with his wife, jill, and his brother, jim biden of washington
a family spokesman, larry rasky, said the democrat from delaware was under orders to rest at home and was to have no visitors nor be given office work
biden, said rasky, is ``in great shape and great spirits. he's full of vigor. i think if the doctors hadn't told him to rest, he could have gone to the office.''
rasky said the family purposely avoided announcing the senator's plan to leave the hospital in order to avoid the stress of any media interest
but biden and his wife paused briefly beside their car to pose for a photographer. biden's blue cap covered the scar on his left temple where the surgical incision was made. he smiled broadly as the camera shutter clicked
the hospital statement said neurosurgeons earlier had found the additional aneurysm on the opposite side of the brain from the aneurysm that was repaired
the second aneurysm is smaller and could not be approached during the earlier surgery,'' the statement said. ``there were no signs of leakage, but the second aneurysm will require surgical repair.''
no date has been set for the new operation, the statement said. it added: ``procedures of this type are usually done after the patient has fully recovered from any earlier surgery, usually within two to three months.''
rasky said doctors told biden the second surgery could come in less than three months, if his recovery went well, and that recovery from the new operation would take less time. but the spokesman said the senator will not return to his washington office until he has recovered from the second surgery
a doctor associated with the case, who asked not to be identified, said that about 15 percent of all patients with one cerebral aneurysm will develop another. if the aneurysm is small, stable and not bleeding, he said, it can be left and repaired later
biden's release just 12 days after surgery, said the doctor, shows ``he is doing very well.''
an aneurysm is a weakened area in an artery. the pressure of blood flow causes the area to balloon, forming a blister-like flaw on the artery side
aneurysms are dangerous because they can rupture suddenly and hemorrhage, or they can leak. such bleeding from a cerebral aneurysm can quickly cause brain damage or death
biden was admitted to walter reed on feb. 12 after a middle-of-the-night, emergency transfer from a delaware hospital. he had been taken to the delaware hospital the day before after experiencing severe neck pain and nausea
an x-ray test located the aneursym within his skull and he underwent surgery within hours
the doctor associated with the case said then that about one-third of all patients with cerebral aneurysms die
typically, the doctor said, surgery for a brain aneurysm requires an incision in the temple area. surgeons then cut a small window in the skull to enable them to lift the brain slightly and locate the flawed artery
the aneurysm is corrected by permanently attaching a clip, a small metal device with locking jaws, at the base of the blister-like flaw and parallel to the blood flow. eventually, the artery will heal itself
biden had been treated for a neck pain that started two weeks before his surgery. a doctor diagnosed the ailment as a pinched nerve and possibly a viral infection of neck muscles. the senator wore a neck brace as treatment
when the pain left after several days, biden abandoned the brace and went on a speaking tour. but the pain, along with nausea, recurred. the senator was admitted to a hospital near his wilmington, del., home and then transferred by ambulance to walter reed
a doctor said an aneurysm leaking into the brain cavity can cause neck pain
the ``quid pro quo'' in a memo to attorney general edwin meese iii may be a planned payoff to the israeli labor party, say government sources familiar with a criminal investigation of meese
the sept. 25, 1985, memo from longtime meese friend e. robert wallach discusses an israeli commitment not to bomb a proposed $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline
we all recognize that there would be no progress to this point'' had israeli-born swiss oilman bruce rappaport ``not been able to obtain the security package which involves the never-to-be-stated but fully understood quid pro quo which helped to produce that commitment,'' said wallach's memo. the memo doesn't elaborate
meese's attorneys say the ``quid pro quo'' is a reference to an agreement that rappaport, a partner in the proposed pipeline, would make available to israel substantial amounts of oil generated from the project. wallach was rappaport's lawyer
however, investigators for independent counsel james mckay question the explanation of meese's lawyers and are seeking to determine whether the language may be a reference to planned payments to the labor party, said the government sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity
wallach gave meese the ``quid pro quo'' memo, along with a handwritten letter from then-israeli prime minister shimon peres in which peres said he ``would go a long way to help'' the pipeline
one of meese's lawyers, james rocap, said the attorney general doesn't recall any discussion of the memo with wallach, who hand-delivered the documents to the attorney general. rocap said meese did not read the memo closely
wallach's memo urged meese to enlist support for the pipeline project from top u.s. officials, hinting that he might talk to secretary of state george shultz about it and then proposing a discussion with president reagan
meese's lawyers say he took none of the initiatives suggested by wallach, but only referred peres to the office of then-national security adviser robert mcfarlane
a separate wallach-to-meese memo also dated sept. 25, 1985, spells out rappaport's close ties to peres, saying the businessman described an arrangement in which israel will receive up to $700 million over 10 years from the pipeline
what was also indicated to me, and which would be denied everywhere, is that a portion of those funds will go directly to labor,'' says the second memo, the focal point of mckay's criminal investigation. meese says he doesn't recall reading the portion of the document relating to labor party payments
the independent counsel is investigating whether meese knew of a possibly improper payment plan involving the israeli political party and, if so, why he did not do something about it
the foreign corrupt practices act makes it illegal for u.s. citizens, companies or their agents to offer foreign officials anything of value to influence them to provide help in business matters
the law states that the attorney general may file a civil suit if it appears the person or company is about to engage in an act that would violate the law
both memos were publicly released monday, along with an exchange of notes between peres and meese
peres, now israel's foreign minister, on tuesday defended his communications with meese, saying: ``we all agree that we favor the laying of the pipeline. so why would anyone need to use bribes? nobody said he (meese) gave the labor party anything or proposed anything to the labor party.''
however, peres acknowledged tuesday through a spokesman in jerusalem that the israeli government had been offered a discount on oil purchases amounting to $65 million to $70 million a year in return for approving the pipeline, the washington post reported in today's editions
but the aide said that peres did not take the offer seriously and failed to pass it on to colleagues, the newspaper said
in another development, arthur l. liman, the chief counsel for the senate committee that investigated the iran-contra affair, says the justice department should have turned over wallach's memos when the committee subpoenaed material
one of the memos refers to israeli help in efforts to free american hostages held in lebanon, and quotes rappaport as saying, ``there is a feeling the united states `owes' and that the accomplishment of this (pipeline) project ... is appropriate.''
i would like to have questioned meese about this,'' liman was quoted as saying in today's editions of the new york times. source; will be topped.</note>
senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., said today it would be unwise to threaten to pull u.s. troops out of europe to counter pressures inside west germany for the removal of all nuclear weapons from german soil
the appearance of the use of threats by the united states does the germans a disservice,'' byrd said in testimony prepared for delivery before the senate foreign relations committee
threatening europe with a diminished american commitment if europe does not undertake certain specific actions would be counterproductive,'' the senate leader said
byrd said that the senate delegation he led to europe earlier this month concluded that ``no responsible german official contemplates denuclearizing germany.''
some west germans do advocate eliminating all u.s. nuclear systems in the aftermath of the successful negotiation of the u.s.-soviet treaty eliminating medium-range nuclear weapons from the continent
but byrd said most west german leaders reject that as a step leading to domination by moscow's superior weight in non-nuclear arms such as tanks, artillery and aircraft
byrd said the top priority for nato now must be the forging of a detailed and comprehensive proposal on conventional arms reduction to present to the soviet union this year
on tuesday, former secretary of state henry a. kissinger said president reagan's vision of a world free of nuclear weapons is neither obtainable nor desirable
i do not believe this is possible and i do not believe our leaders should create the impression that it is possible, let alone desirable,'' he said
kissinger said he was concerned about the west being exposed to soviet superiority in conventional weapons should nuclear weapons be abolished
kissinger told the committee he believes the senate should ratify the new treaty eliminating medium-range nuclear weapons in europe, if only to avoid a bruising and divisive political upheaval inside the nato alliance
but kissinger said he believes the treaty is ``flawed and leaves us in a weaker position, both politically and militarily.''
he said he was especially troubled by the treaty's reduction of u.s. and soviet missiles to zero on each side because of the expectations that may create in the negotiation of a treaty reducing long-range strategic nuclear arms
it implies that zero in all categories is obtainable, and it is not obtainable,'' kissinger said
he said the treaty should be ratified, if for no other reason, because keeping a force of u.s. pershing and ground-launched cruise missiles in western europe is now politically impossible
the treaty is the result of nato's 1979 ``dual-track'' decision to deploy u.s. weapons to counter soviet ss-20 medium-range missiles while at the same time negotiating their removal
it calls for the destruction of all missiles with a range from 300 miles to 3,400 miles
kissinger said he believes the treaty is flawed because it will not reduce in any significant way the ability of the soviet union to devastate europe with other nuclear weapons and because it substantially reduces the ability of the united states to retaliate with nuclear weapons based in europe
nuclear deterrence in europe will now rely primarily on weapons based in the united states and kissinger said that creates ``a psychological and political imbalance,'' especially when weighed against soviet superiority in conventional forces
the dollar closed slightly higher against the japanese yen in tokyo today after a sharp decline the previous day, while share prices gained for the 10th consecutive day
the dollar closed at 128.75, up 0.25 yen from its closing figure of 128.50 yen tuesday, when it lost 1.45 yen. it had opened at 128.90 yen today but never went higher, changing hands between 128.57 and 128.90 yen
the dollar came under selling pressure after a statement by satoshi sumita, head of the japan's central bank, who told reporters today that the u.s. currency's sharp decline has hit bottom, but that unstable factors remained, such as large external imbalances among major economic countries
the dollar rebounded somewhat as life insurance and securities firms went on buying the currency just before the end of trading, abe said
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei average of 225 selected shares, a 102.74-point winner tuesday, took on an additional 19.20 points, or 0.07 percent, to close today's session at 24,968.65 points
the small gain shows investors are becoming careful,'' said an analyst with sanyo securities, who spoke on condition of anonymity
but he noted that the volume of trading was a hefty 1.1 billion shares, the heaviest this year, and said: ``if the volume stays at the current level, the stock average will easily top the 27,000-point level.''
large-size issues, such as shipbuildings and steels, were bought, and chemicals, papers, brokerages and real estate issues were firm. innovations</head>
president reagan wants congress to bar federal agencies from releasing information that he says could harm the economic competitiveness of the united states in the new field of superconductivity
the proposed change in the freedom of information act was one of three proposals reagan submitted to congress on tuesday in a message in which he said the united states sometimes falls short in making commercial use of laboratory breakthroughs
the other proposals would broaden the present protection for patents on manufacturing processes and require courts to consider the effects of joint commercial ventures on international competitiveness before deciding they violate antitrust laws
reagan said he was proposing the information law change because ``commercially valuable scientific and technological information generated in federal facilities loses potential commercial value when it is released wholesale'' under the act
mandatory disclosure of such information under foia could encourage u.s. competitors to exploit the u.s. science and technology base rather than making investments in their own research and development infrastucture,'' the president said
under his proposal, reagan said, ``federal agencies will be required to withhold information of this nature requested under the freedom of information act where disclosure could reasonably be expected to harm the economic competitiveness of the united states.''
reagan said his proposal would apply to ``federal government-generated, government-owned scientific and technical information.'' in addition, he said, the administration is developing ``a uniform policy to permit federal contractors to own the rights to technical information that they develop for the government.''
although the three legislative proposals were lumped together under the title ``superconductivity competitiveness act of 1988,'' the president's message did not indicate that their application would be limited to the field of superconductivity
the federal government spent about $55 million on superconductivity research in fiscal year 1987 and will spend more than $100 million in the current fiscal year, reagan said
there is no time to waste in this effort,'' he said. ``there is a growing realization that, although the united states has long been a leader in breakthroughs in the laboratory, it has occasionally failed to convert these breakthroughs into commercial applications.''
reagan proposed amending patent laws to give u.s. companies the right to sue and collect monetary damages in u.s. courts when someone else uses their processes abroad to manufacture products that are then shipped to, and sold in, the united states
they can already file such suits to prevent the use of their processes by domestic manufacturers, but must sue foreign manufacturers in foreign courts in order to collect damages. the white house said the proposed change ``is consistent with the treatment of process patents in many foreign countries.''
the 1988 presidential campaign is making a quick side trip to the nation's northeast corner this week for lobster, maple syrup and votes, with michael dukakis and george bush nervously hoping for neighborly victories in maine and vermont
with their strong regional ties, dukakis and bush need to win their parties' caucuses in maine this weekend and the vermont primaries tuesday to build momentum for super tuesday
but former television evangelist pat robertson and senate gop leader bob dole would like to embarrass bush in his home territory _ especially in the wake of bush's weak showings in tuesday's south dakota primary and minnesota caucuses
in both maine and vermont, strong bush and dukakis organizations will carry the burden, for all the candidates will be spending most of the next seven days campaigning in the south, focus of the super tuesday's primaries on march 8
the republican vice president will touch down for airport news conferences today in portland, me., and burlington, vt. _ his last scheduled visits for the week. dukakis may be back in maine by the weekend
bush has a home in maine and is widely expected to be the winner in the town caucuses in the state scattered over the weekend
but his campaign is worried about robertson in maine
with a usual turnout of only about 5,000 republicans, the caucuses are a good opportunity for success using robertson's tactics from other states _ flooding caucuses with new participants and winning surprising victories
the dukakis campaign, which has a strong organization on the ground as it did in new hampshire, faces less opposition among democrats, who have mostly left the states to the governor from neighboring massachusetts
it doesn't appear that the other campaigns are taking these states seriously,'' said dukakis spokesman leslie dach
the one possible exception to the rest of the democratic field's bypassing of the states is jesse jackson in vermont. the rainbow coalition _ formed during jackson's 1984 presidential bid _ actually has remained active in the state and burlington's socialist mayor, bernie sanders, has endorsed him
the rainbow coalition has been working hard,'' said vermont democratic chief violet coffin
but dukakis, in contrast has had 12-15 paid staffers working the state, she said
neither of the states' events has drawn a great deal of candidate's attention for several reason
first, maine and vermont together will send 41 delegates to the democratic national convention and 39 delegates to the republican meeting this summer. the super tuesday events decide which candidates have the allegiance of 1,307 democratic delegates and 712 gop delegates
only the maine caucuses actually begin the delegate selection processes; the vermont primary on tuesday is simply a beauty contest expression of preference. vermont's delegates will be picked in the late spring in a separate caucus process
but the close ties that bush has with maine make it an excellent chance for robertson to stun the front-runner in his home turf
it will be a battle,'' said ron kaufman, bush's northeastern coordinator. ``dole has had a lot of people on the ground in maine. ... but my concern is the rev. robertson.''
it is the potential of robertson's ``invisible army'' of supporters to take over the gop caucuses that worries the bush staff
maine gop state chairwoman karen stram of dresden sees the caucuses this way:
the bush campaign has the broadest organization. robertson has organized a lot of new voters. ... the dole people have an organization that has been working here.''
on the democratic side in maine, state party chief rick barton acknowledges that dukakis has a home-field advantage, but he says another candidate could have an impact. ``the question is whether anybody is making an effort here'' besides dukakis, barton said
and he pointed out that there is a seventh candidate contending in the maine caucuses _ uncommitted. led by maine house leader john diamond, party activists have been pushing for uncommitted delegates to be elected at the city and town meetings
in vermont, dole has the potential for a good showing, although the vice president is credited with a broader organization. dole has the backing of several gop leaders, including former gov. richard snelling
vermont republican party chief ralph howe said dole _ from the farm state of kansas _ has also won points with the state's dairy farmers by supporting changes in the milk price support program that bush has not endorsed
in dukakis' home state of massachusetts, which votes on super tuesday, the governor enjoys a prohibitive lead among democratic presidential candidates, while bush leads the gop field, a new poll indicates
the survey, commissioned by wcvb-tv in boston, weei radio and the boston globe, was conducted by the gallup organization among massachusetts voters last weekend. it said dukakis led with 61 percent support, with gephardt trailing with 13 percent. the other democrats finished in single digits
in the republican race, bush _ a massachusetts native _ led with 49 percent, compared to 29 percent saying they support dole. those others were in single digits, with 8 percent undecided
the telephone survey of presidential preference involved 639 registered democrats with a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percent. the poll also reached 331 republicans, with a margin of error of plus or minus 6 percent
a dinosaur egg discovered in a central utah quarry may contain the oldest embryo ever found and change perceptions about how some of the creatures became extinct, a scientist says
a scan of a partially collapsed egg the size of a human fist has revealed a 2-centimeter-long gray area that appears to be the crude outline of an embryo, said wade miller, a brigham young university paleontologist
in the scan, the egg shell appears white. most of the egg's interior is dark gray except for a tiny area that has the shape of a head and other features, miller said
the egg was discovered last september in the cleveland lloyd quarry where scientists have uncovered thousands of allosaurus bones, a meat-eater that stood up to 20 feet high
miller said skeletal remains of the dinosaurs that lived during the jurassic period, which began around 210 million b.c. and ended 145 million b.c., have ranged from 100-pound juveniles to 3-ton adults
william lloyd stokes, professor emeritus at the university of utah and one of the scientists who excavated most of the bones, said dinosaur eggs usually cannot be associated with a particular species, but because this egg was found among a great deposit of allosaurus bones, it likely was from an allosaurus
it is among the oldest eggs or egg fragments ever discovered, and if it in fact contains an embryo, would be the oldest dinosaur embryo found, stokes said
miller said the egg could lead to a new theory of how dinosaurs in the area became extinct
miller said geologists previously believed the dinosaurs in the quarry were trapped in a bog
a dinosaur is not going to lay an egg in a bog while it's sinking,'' he said
but stokes disputed that
the egg has to be formed within a body, and while it is in a body that body may sink,'' he said tuesday night
stokes said the fact that other eggs and egg fragments were not found in the quarry indicates this egg was not in a nest
miller said the egg will be taken to maryland where columbia scientific inc. will take three-dimensional x-rays of it
some elections are more equal than others, fortunately for george bush. he was trounced twice in republican presidential contests, but he'd left the scene of the landslides
sen. bob dole, who won a runaway in south dakota and a comfortable victory in minnesota, said he had gained major headway as the gop race moved toward the south
it pays to come to south dakota,'' he said tuesday night in sioux falls
but the pay wasn't very high
dole apparently swept the delegates at stake in south dakota _ all 18 of them. pat robertson was second, just below the 20 percent it took to share in the delegation. bush lagged narrowly behind him
but compare that delegate payoff to texas. republicans there will choose 111 nominating delegates on march 8, and bush ranks as the favorite. his role and dole's are reversed in texas _ the vice president leads and the senator from kansas has virtually written off the state
in democratic competition tuesday, rep. richard gephardt captured south dakota, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis won in minnesota, and nobody got any nominating delegates. the results were purely advisory; the real prizes come later
those results, especially the defeats bush absorbed by running third in south dakota and fourth in minnesota, were muted for lack of the attention concentrated on the leadoff presidential contests in iowa and new hampshire
dole and gephardt won in iowa, bush and dukakis in new hampshire, in contests played to national television audiences, with anchormen on location. the states were comparable, the stakes were comparable, but tuesday's contests were not magnified by being first
so bush, campaigning in london, ky., absorbed the twin defeats without a word of comment. it's time for targeting, and the next one on his list comes this weekend in maine, where he maintains a home and where he expects to win in gop caucuses
that's also a robertson target, and the bush camp says the former television evangelist could pose a significant challenge in caucuses, the kind of competition that best fits his organization
robertson said bush should pay in the national public opinion polls for the defeats on tuesday. ``i don't see how he's going to continue to ride so high,'' robertson said. ``the vice president is definitely wounded.''
but it is nothing maine, and the just-for-show vermont primary on march 1, can't heal
those contests, and the south carolina primary on march 5, with robertson formidable and claiming he can win, all preface super tuesday, march 8. that's a 20-state primary and caucus day, with 1,307 democratic delegates and 712 republicans at stake
that competition is concentrated in the south, but it includes a half-dozen contests in other regions, massachusetts to washington
with candidates picking their spots and with delegates to be won through proportional representation among the democrats, super tuesday isn't likely to be any more conclusive than what has gone before
republican rules make it more likely that one candidate can pile up a significant delegate lead on march 8
ironically, for all the efforts at calendar rigging and early-season decisions, the pivotal primaries may still be weeks away, in populous industrial states like pennsylvania, new york, ohio, and, finally, california
house lawmakers are hoping to melt some of the ice around their sweeping trade bill with proposals to drop senate-sponsored curbs on lamb imports and $400 million in payments to sugar refiners
i think there is a need for trade legislation,'' house ways and means committee chairman dan rostenkowski, d-ill., said tuesday after the plan was sent to senators on a conference committee drafting the trade bill. ``if we don't get it this year it could very well mean that we won't get it for some time in the future.''
senate finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen, d-texas, promised early consideration of the offer proposed by ways and means committee members who are also part of the conference committee
bentsen said there could be a reply as early as the weekend from finance committee members on the conference committee. the so-called ``subconference'' of ways and means and finance members is one of 17 such bodies that have been formed to draw up portions of the 1,000-page bill
the lamb provision would limit imports of fresh chilled or frozen lamb meat. it was attached to the senate version of the trade bill at the urging of sen. max baucus, d-mont
the sugar provision would let some refining companies that claim tney are being hurt by high tariffs recover some $400 million in duties they paid a number of years ago on imported sugar that was refined and re-exported
the reagan administration was fiercely opposed to it, saying insufficient documents existed to administer the plan properly
at a news conference, rostenkowski again expressed hope the house would pass an overall compromise ``before the easter recess'' but said that might not be possible
one issue remaining is democratic presidential aspirant richard gephardt's amendment to require 10 percent annual rollbacks in japanese trade surpluses with the united states
the measure, approved by the house, does not appear in the senate version and it seems likely to be changed in the final product
gephardt, a member of the ways and means committee, has been basing part of his campaign on his trade proposal and other democrats on the panel have been reluctant to do anything that might be interpreted as undercutting him
rostenkowski indicated that no reshaping of provisions dealing with unfair foreign trade barriers is likely before the ``super tuesday'' primaries in the south on march 8. the chairman was an opponent of gephardt's plan when it was debated in the house last year
he indicated, however, that he would present the case for gephardt's plan
i've been commissioned by the house of representatives to do as much as i can to keep as much of it in as i can, and i'm going to do that,'' he said
after a report on monday that lawmakers would ``dump'' the gephardt provision following the super tuesday voting, rostenkowski issued a statement saying that ``mr. gephardt's amendment has not been scuttled or jettisoned.''
country music's reigning top entertainer hank williams jr. says his academy of country music awards nominations would have made his legendary father, and his mama, proud
i keep thinking in ernest tubbs' last song `leave them boys alone,' it says, `his daddy would be proud if he could see bocephus now,''' williams, whose nickname is bocephus, said after receiving six nominations tuesday
i think of mama, too, she would have said, `i told you honey, he was going to do it all the time,''' the 38-year-old son of hank williams said from his home in paris, tenn
gentleman ex-frycook randy travis also got nominations in the same categories: entertainer of the year, vocalist, single, song, album and video categories
williams, current country music association and academy entertainer of the year, and travis, who dominated the awards last year with four trophies, are also up for grammy awards next month
we're very happy to be nominated and to be in such good company,'' said travis, 28, who fried catfish and burgers at the nashville palace before getting his break
it's a great feeling to know that the industry enjoys our music.''
george strait got four nominations _ top vocalist, single, song and album. nominees with three each were perennial favorite alabama, shut out on last year's show, and newcomers k.t. oslin and ricky van shelton
the bellamy brothers, crystal gayle, the judds, reba mcentire and restless heart got two apiece
nominees for the 23rd annual acm awards were announced by country entertainers dwight yoakam, the group restless heart, charlie pride and lacy j. dalton
ballots go in the mail this week to the 2,500 academy members. the winners will be announced march 21 during a two-hour nbc-tv special with williams and miss mcentire hosts
in addition to williams and travis in the entertainer of the year category are alabama, miss mcentire and willie nelson
the only major surprise was the poor showing of the multiple grammy nominee ``trio'' album, which got the academy's best album nomination but no other mention for singers dolly parton, linda ronstadt and emmylou harris
here is a list of the nominees for academy of country music awards, to be presented march 21
entertainer of the year: alabama, reba mcentire, willie nelson, randy travis and hank williams jr
album: ``always and forever,'' randy travis; ``born to boogie,'' hank williams jr.; ``heart land,'' the judds; ``ocean front property,'' geroge strait; and ``trio,'' dolly parton, linda ronstadt and emmylou harris
single record: ``all my ex's live in texas,'' george strait; ``born to boogie,'' hank williams jr.; ``forever and ever, amen,'' randy travis; ``i'll still be loving you,'' restless heart; and ``somebody lied,'' ricky van shelton
song: ``80's ladies,'' k.t. oslin; ``born to boogie,'' hank williams jr.; ``forever and ever, amen,'' randy travis; ``ocean front property,'' george strait; and ``somebody lied,'' ricky van shelton
male vocalist: ronnie milsap, george strait, randy travis, steve wariner and hank williams jr
female vocalist: rosanne cash, crystal gayle, kathy mattea, reba mcentire and tanya tucker
new male vocalist: larry boone, marty haggard, lyle lovett, jo-el sonnier and ricky van shelton
new female vocalist: nanci griffith, libby hurley, k.d. lang, dana mcvicker and k.t. oslin
vocal group: alabama, exile, highway 101, restless heart and the oak ridge boys
vocal duet: foster &amp; lloyd, crystal gayle &amp; gary morris, sweethearts of the rodeo, the bellamy brothers and the judds
video: ``80's ladies,'' k.t. oslin; ``forever and ever, amen,'' randy travis; ``little sister,'' dwight yoakam; ``my name is bocephus,'' hank williams jr.; ``santa fe,'' the bellamy brothers; and ``tar top,'' alabama
president reagan's nominee to be secretary of the navy, william l. ball iii, is just one more reason to see triple when looking at the administration
a look through the directory of top government officials shows that this administration doesn't take a back seat to anybody in the roman numeral department
at the pentagon: frank c. carlucci iii, secretary of defense; h. lawrence garrett iii, undersecretary of the navy
at the treasury department, james a. baker iii, secretary
at the office of management and budget: james c. miller iii, director; l. wayne arny iii, assistant director for national security
at the commerce department: orson g. swindle iii, assistant secretary for economic development
at the justice department: edwin meese iii, attorney general
at the interstate commerce commission: j.j. simmons iii, commissioner
in addition, the list shows charles tyroler ii of the intelligence oversight board; j. curtis mack ii, assistant secretary of commerce for the national oceanic and atmospheric administration; lt. col, claudius watts ii, comptroller of the department of the air force; and wendell l. willkie ii, general counsel of the department of education
they are all pikers, however, compared with carlucci's deputy, william h. taft iv, and transportation secretary james h. burnley iv. conservatives</head>
republicans across the ideological spectrum helped bob dole win the south dakota primary, with the exception of strong conservatives, whose support could prove important in later contests, exit polls said
those republicans, one fifth of the total, favored pat robertson, helping the former television minister challenge vice president george bush for second place in the state primary tuesday, an nbc news exit poll found
among democrats, many voters chose a candidate in the final days of the south dakota campaign, and they went strongly for rep. richard gephardt, who employed aggressive television advertising in his winning effort, polls said
a third of the democratic voters told cbs news they made up their minds in the last three days of the race, and 45 percent of them backed gephardt, to 23 percent for massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who finished second
the television networks based their analyses of the voting on random surveys of south dakotans as they left polling places. the networks did not conduct surveys in minnesota, which held party caucuses tuesday
dole, the senate minority leader from kansas, campaigned determinedly in south dakota. bush, sensing his disadvantage, steered clear of the state. the polls said dole prevailed in nearly all categories; abc news, for example, said he won more than seven in 10 liberals and moderates and four in 10 conservatives
nbc separated out another category, ``very conservative'' voters, and said 42 percent went for robertson to 32 percent for dole and 17 percent for bush. dole did poorly among very conservative voters in new hampshire, where bush won last week's primary, and nbc noted that more such voters may turn out in the super tuesday southern state primaries march 8
when considering dole's overall strong showing, ``the caveat is that bush didn't contest it,'' and that republican turnout was light, said doug muzzio, an abc poll analyst. still, he said, ``bush lost almost every group he won in new hampshire,'' including republicans who support president reagan and those who are concerned about foreign policy
one important outcome was ``a narrowing of the margins,'' muzzio said: sen. paul simon, a liberal democrat, fared poorly, as did rep. jack kemp of new york, a conservative republican
abc said kemp got just 8 percent of the conservative republican vote, to robertson's 27 percent. robertson also won more than half the evangelical or fundamentalist christians, about a fifth of all gop voters, abc and cbs said
among the democrats, gephardt and dukakis split the liberal vote, but gephardt won moderate and conservative democrats, won the male vote while splitting the female vote with dukakis, and won among the less wealthy and the less educated, again splitting the others with dukakis
gephardt ``went upscale'' by doing better among the better-educated and wealthier democrats than he had in the past, muzzio said. ``the good news for dukakis is that he did well in a downscale state,'' he added
surprisingly, the nbc news poll found that a plurality of south dakota democrats, 46 percent, said they believed dukakis eventually will win the presidential nomination, though not all voted for him
even 28 percent of those who voted for gephardt said they expected dukakis to be the nominee
cbs reported that 40 percent of the democrats chose farm policy as a key issue, more than the number that selected any other subject
gephardt was definitely strong among people who cared about farm policy,'' with 55 percent support to 18 percent for dukakis, said cbs surveys manager pam mitchell
among the losing democrats, nbc found that former sen. gary hart of colorado was viewed unfavorably by twice as many south dakotans as viewed him favorably, and 55 percent were not pleased that hart re-entered the race after withdrawing last summer amid questions about his marital fidelity
nbc's poll had a margin of sampling error of 3 percent. the cbs poll's margin of error was 4 percent, and abc's was 5 percent
the 4,000 nuclear weapons that would remain in western europe after elimination of intermediate-range nuclear weapons should stay there until its conventional forces are better balanced with the warsaw pact, president reagan told a european television audience
ensuring the peace requires that these nuclear weapons stay where they are until we can achieve a better balance of conventional forces on the continent,'' reagan said tuesday. ``because of them and the soviet knowledge that we have them, we can maintain the balance that maintains the peace.''
reagan spoke in a televised address broadcast by satellite to europe by the ``worldnet'' facilities of the u.s. information agency. the address came a week before leaders of the 16 nato countries gather at the alliance's headquarters in brussels for their first full-scale summit in six years
reagan said the recently signed u.s.-soviet treaty to abolish intermediate-range nuclear forces _ missiles with a range of about 300 miles to 3,000 miles _ was ``a victory for nato.''
nevertheless, he said, nato must continue to have battlefield nuclear weapons, those with a range of under 300 miles
the alliance's adversaries must not believe that our only possible response to a limited attack is to begin an intercontinental nuclear exchange,'' reagan said. ``if they do, they may doubt that we would risk such a response and be tempted to test us.''
west germany has expressed opposition to upgrading short-range missiles until nato develops an overall arms control strategy and the soviet union reduces it conventional force strength
reagan said nato must insure that it maintains ``all the modern forces, both conventional and nuclear,'' to uphold a strategy of flexible response to soviet aggression
after all, our goal is not a nuclear-free or a tank-free or an army-free europe but a war-free europe,'' reagan said
kansas sen. bob dole scored a solid victory in south dakota's republican presidential primary tuesday, far outpacing vice president george bush, who had written off the state. and rep. richard gephardt came out on top on the democratic side after a campaign blitz
i took south dakota very seriously,'' dole said. ``let the message go out, that it pays to come to south dakota.''
bush had sidestepped the midwest contests and headed directly south after his new hampshire primary victory
gephardt's win over massachusetts gov. michael dukakis delivered no nominating delegates, but gave gephardt a victory to point to as the candidates campaign in the super tuesday states. dukakis, however, scored a win of his own tuesday night, in minnesota's caucuses
dukakis was the resounding victor in the new hampshire primary a week ago; gephardt won the iowa caucuses eight days before that
the south dakota primary was moved from its traditional june date to the front of the nominating calendar this year
gephardt, dukakis and illinois sen. paul simon campaigned heavily here. sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, gary hart and jesse jackson also vied for support
republican voters were choosing all 18 delegates the state will send to their national convention next summer, while 15 of the 19 democratic delegates were to be allocated on the basis of the primary
the democratic primary is legally non-binding because it falls prior to the date allowed by democratic national party rules. but state party officials have said they expect the march 12 statewide caucus to apportion those 15 delegates according to the results of tuesday's primary
the south dakota legislature moved the presidential primary from june to february in an attempt to draw candidates to a state that was largely ignored by presidential contenders in past elections. backers of the move said it would force the candidates to pay attention to south dakota and the problems of rural america
with 99 percent of the precincts reporting, gephardt had 44 percent; dukakis, 31 percent; gore, 8 percent; simon, 6 percent; hart and jackson, 5 percent
for the republicans, with 99 percent of precincts reporting, dole had 55 percent; robertson 20 percent; bush 19 percent and kemp 5 percent. former delaware gov. pete du pont, who dropped out last week, drew 1 percent
an eagle scout's project that began in 1979 has been realized as a national park service trail illustrating the rich history of blacks in the nation's capital
the scout, willard andre hutt, now 27, was present tuesday at the dedication of the black history national recreation trail. the trail winds from a 179-year-old cemetery in the exclusive georgetown neighborhood to the home of 19th century black leader frederick douglass in the city's poor anacostia section
other landmarks on the 7.5-mile trail include the downtown home of educator and presidential advisor mary mcleod bethune; the metropolitan african methodist episcopal church, created in 1822; and howard university, founded after the civil war to provide higher education to blacks
federal oversignt of state-run family assistance programs should pay closer attention to the social purposes of programs instead of just looking at financial accountability, a new study says
the report by the national research council, an arm of the national academy of sciences, also said federal monitors should penalize only those states with excessive rates of overpayments
the recommendations were based on an 18-month study ordered by congress and released tuesday. it said federal officials should measure the states against each other and penalize only those with ``excessively large'' error rates. becoming law</head>
a $375 million child care improvement bill introduced by republicans to counter the multibillion-dollar democratic version would rely on state grants, liability pools and capital improvements, the two sponsors say
it would also give tax credits to employers with on-site child care and offer a double tax exemption to families in which a parent stayed home for six months to care for a newborn. the break would be worth about $500 to $600 to the average family
it's closer to what the president is going to sign than anything else on the table or under discussion,'' rep. nancy johnson, r-conn., house sponsor of the gop bill. said tuesday, the day the bill was introduced. the cosponsor is sen. orrin hatch, r-utah
the army, navy, marine corps and air force had 2.17 million men and women on active duty as of jan. 31, the pentagon says
the active-duty strength of the nation's military services in january was more than 12,000 below the same period last year, the pentagon said tuesday
according to the latest ``military strength'' assessment, two of the four armed services reported declines in personnel in january from december
the marine corps reported 198,243 men and women on active duty, down 194 from december. the air force reported 604,574, down 755
the army had an active-duty strength of 778,835 as of jan. 31, up 1,155 from december. and the navy reported 585,726 on active duty last month, up 561 from december
some teachers are blasting a decision by richland high school students to retain a nuclear mushroom cloud as their symbol, but supporters said the emblem did not signify atomic destruction
students in this ``atomic city'' voted overwhelmingly tuesday to formally adopt the mushroom cloud as the symbol of the bombers
it stands for nuclear holocaust and the end of the world,'' said jim deatherage, a teacher who has long opposed the symbol. ``it's an inappropriate symbol for high school kids to be glorifying.''
deatherage said students should not have made the decision since they were easily swayed by emotions and did not understand the objections of outsiders
they were tied to the symbol because of school pride,'' he said. ``the whole process was a farce.''
deatherage and teacher rick wigre said opponents had only a few chances to communicate with students or other teachers
it never came up at a faculty meeting,'' wigre said, because the administration did not want to divide the staff
but most students and administrators expressed satisfaction with the process
clearly that's what the kids wanted,'' said lisa koch, 18. ``i'm very pleased.''
students have a very simple view of it,'' said activities director steve potter, who helped organize the election
to them it was a symbol of richland high school,'' he said. ``no more and no less.''
the issue is an emotional one in this city of 30,000 adjacent to the hanford nuclear reservation, where for more than 40 years the federal government has made plutonium for nuclear weapons
richland was a sleepy village of a few hundred residents when hanford was carved out of the central washington desert as part of the manhattan project to produce atomic bombs in world war ii
many of parents of the school's 1,300 students are employed at the site _ where the government announced last week that plutonium production is being phased out at the cost of 2,600 jobs during the next two years
the symbol, which is the letter ``r'' with a mushroom cloud rising above it, has been used for some 17 years, but was never formally adopted by the student body
over the years there have been attempts to eliminate it, and some student leaders decided it was time to formally adopt a symbol
during a morning class tuesday, students were given white ballots with four symbols portrayed in black
there was no place to write in new ideas and no opportunity to reject all four options, a factor criticized by some teachers and students
the mushroom cloud received 1,084 votes, said principal gus nash. a caricature of an atomic bomb got 45, a b-17 bomber plane 40 and the symbol of three atomic rings 36 votes
i don't think the student body sees it as a symbol of destruction or weaponry,'' said marcia cillan, vice president of the associated student body. ``i don't think it signifies anything other than richland high school.''
we're not going to change it just because a bunch of people are making fun of it,'' said student glenn goldberg. robertson, bush</head>
democrat michael dukakis racked up a win outside his home turf of new england in the minnesota democratic presidential caucuses, while republican bob dole beat out george bush _ as did former television evangelist pat robertson and rep. jack kemp
with 80 percent of the republican precincts reporting _ the last official tally provided early today _ dole had 43 percent; robertson, 28 percent; kemp, 15 percent; and bush, 11 percent. the uncommitteds were 3 percent
and with 74 percent of the democratic precincts reporting, dukakis, the governor of massachusetts, scored 34 percent; jesse jackson had 20 percent, sen. paul simon, 18 percent and rep. richard gephardt, 8 percent. gore and hart each had 1 percent, and 19 percent were uncommitted
gephardt won the south dakota primary tuesday night, setting the scene for more battles for the front-running spot as he and dukakis head into a new round of contests
dukakis won last week's new hampshire primary, while gephardt was the victor in the iowa caucuses on feb. 8
both gore and jackson have been campaigning heavily in the south, and gore, who bypassed iowa and new hampshire, is vowing to come on strong in his native region
gore, along with hart, virtually ignored minnesota
bush, the republican front-runner nationwide, made no effort in minnesota. in kentucky, where he was campaigning, he went to bed tuesday night without commenting to reporters on the returns
for the first time in minnesota, an attempt was being made to report results of the caucuses on the night they occurred _ meaning the preferences of all those who attended republican caucuses based on a straw poll and the preferences of delegates elected at the democratic caucuses
the caucuses began the process of selecting 78 of the state's 87-member delegation to the democratic national convention and the 31 delegates to the republican national convention
moving the caucus date from march to february resulted in a lengthy dispute between the state and national democratic parties because the new date is earlier than national party rules allow
the state party agreed that a presidential preference poll taken at the democratic caucuses would be kept secret until 5 p.m. march 8 and that the state party would not cooperate in reporting of caucus-night results
share prices opened fractionally higher on the london stock exchange today but then fell slightly in early trading
the financial times-stock exchange 100 index was down 1.6 points at 1,756.3 at 9:45 a.m. when the market officially opened at 9 a.m., the index was up 0.9 points at 1,758.8
dealers said share prices had moved ahead strongly on bullish sentiment about the british economy, but the market didn't find a direction and major shares were narrowly mixed
the largest fall among the index of 100 shares was consolidated goldfields, which dropped 12 pence to 818 pence because of weakness in the gold price
banks showed some of the largest gains, with barclays up 6 at 480 and national westminster up 8 at 558. barclays increase was due to release its 1987 earnings later today following national westminster which released its results on tuesday
the early trend followed a small drop tuesday in new york, where the dow jones industrial average fell 1.17 to 2,039.12, and a small gain in tokyo overnight, where the nikkei index rose 19.20 to 24,968.65
the attorney for a chain-smoking woman under court order not to smoke in her family's presence says he will appeal the decision as ``outrageously unconstitutional.''
the order barring elizabeth roofeh, 41, from smoking in front of her husband and their three children was issued tuesday by justice ralph diamond of the trial-level state supreme court
mrs. roofeh also was directed to confine her cigarette puffing to a small television room in the couple's kings point mansion
this is clearly a violation of her first amendment rights,'' said her attorney, joel brandes
who is going to enforce this? ... are the children going to become policemen and turn their mother in for smoking?''
the ruling is ``outrageously unconstitutional,'' he added
mrs. roofeh's husband, jahanshah, 42, a non-smoking surgeon, went to court in an attempt to get his wife to stop lighting up in front of him and their children, ages 6, 7 and 9
he claimed he tried unsuccessfully for 12 years to get his wife to curtail her two-pack-a-day habit. he described her smoking as ``offensive and detrimental to the health of the children.''
the roofehs, who were married in 1976, have been feuding since may when mrs. roofeh filed for divorce, which is pending before diamond
the roofehs are still living together
mrs. roofeh, who called her iranian-born husband ``an ayatollah,'' said she smokes ``just to annoy'' him. ``i'll quit when i get him out of the house,'' she said
neal shayne, the dean of the academy of law for the nassau county bar association, said he believes the order was legal because it's not mrs. roofeh's rights but the rights of her family that were violated by her smoking
i think it's been established that smoking is certainly hazardous to a person's health, especially to a young child,'' said shayne
mrs. roofeh said she has been limiting her smoking to the one small room in the couple's six-bedroom home in recent months
it's nothing new,'' said mrs. roofeh in referring to the constraints the judge has placed on her. ``i've always tried not to smoke in front of the children.''
roofeh said when they were married his wife promised him she would not smoke in front of him
she admits that she broke her promise in 1984 but it was because of stress from a stroke she suffered. she also has admitted that she used to sneak outside when she got an uncontrollable nicotine craving before 1984
in issuing his ruling, the judge denied a request by roofeh for an order of protection against his wife
roofeh had argued that smoking cigarettes may be as ``detrimental and reprehensible'' as would be ``hitting, slapping, punching, or spitting.''
the court found, however, that an order of protection is a tool designed to protect family members from domestic violence and not to protect against a spouse that smokes
stephen schlissel, attorney for roofeh, commended the judge on the decision
it is a natural extension of the law that if a child is being harmed by a parent's conduct it should step in and safeguard the child,'' said schlissel
this is one of a series of periodic reports compiled by associated press bureaus on how the u.s. presidential election process is viewed in other countries
as the u.s. presidential election campaign picks up pace, it is coming more and more under scrutiny in other nations. here is what some newspapers and commentators said recently about the election process in general and about super tuesday in particular
_ sueddeutsche zeitung of munich (liberal): ``in a nation like the federal republic (of germany), where the parties have extended their power into every corner of society, the drama par excellence now occurring on the american stage would be unimaginable
not the party, but the primary determines who will enter the `final match' on nov. 8. and the primary is close to the ideal democracy imagined by jean-jacques rousseau
the contenders must meet the voters face to face _ from alabama to wyoming, in living rooms, schools and shopping centers. and a candidate can climb into the ring with or without the blessing of his party
surprises are guaranteed.''
_the japan times of tokyo (english-language, independent): ``the strong belief remains that none of the democratic candidates will emerge as an unbeatable front-runner after super tuesday or later. in this case, brokering will choose the candidate at the convention, and waiting on the sidelines for just such a development is new york gov. mario cuomo
what may be understandable but nevertheless regrettable is that campaigning so far resembles a `political olympics' with a concentration on percentage points in pre-ballotting polls and in the results. this tends to obscure the issues, particularly in the reporting by the media.''
_ neil lurrssen, washington correspondent, the sunday star of johannesburg (english-language, independent: ``the united states is in for a roughhouse 1988 election season
it is going to be quite a spectacle. ... and the campaigning shows every indication of deteriorating into a bare-knuckle brawl, especially among the republicans where the two leading candidates . .. have already started slugging away at each other.''
none of the other candidates is likely to shake the bush-dole lead, though there could be a rude surprise for both of the leaders in some parts of the south where former television evangelist pat robertson has enthusiastic supporters. ... this could make mr. robertson _ who has sympathy for the south african government _ a significant factor at the party convention if there has to be horsetrading of delegates to find a presidential nominee.''
_ the independent of london (independent): ``it looked on occasion last year as if america's ... method of selecting presidential candidates was finally coming to pieces. there was speculation that nobody of any ability or self-respect would subject himself and his family to the intense strain and scrutinizing involved in the race for nomination
such questions no longer dominate the political agenda; suggestions that the system is unable to throw up a credible slate are rarely heard. the political silly season is, mercifully, past. ..
the main problem for the united states has turned out not to be the caliber of the leading candidates. it is, increasingly, the quality of government in the final months of a lame-duck administration
_ the times of london (independent): ``questioned on his defeat by vice president george bush (in new hampshire), sen. robert dole's first response was to rebut the `lies' put about by mr. bush that he wanted to raise taxes. evidently the last thing mr. dole wanted to be associated with was a responsible fiscal policy which he believed had cost him a significant number of votes at a crucial stage in the presidential race
for the rest of the world this is a disappointing comment on the nature of u.s. politics. but it hardly comes as a surprise. the shadow of the presidential election has for months hung over the struggle to rein back america's budget deficit. its influence can only increase as president reagan's term draws to a close.''
susan crosland, wife of the former labor party cabinet minister tony crosland, the sunday times of london (independent). writing in her weekly column on what she perceived as a backlash against dole because he accused bush of lying, she said raised the question with a washingtonian living in london:
q. ``why is bush's insincerity preferred to dole's frankness?''
a. ``if you speak from the heart and say that someone should have lost, you're seen as a dirty player. it's a matter of manners. as an example of american mores, when i say `how are you?' i don't really care how you are.''
as thousands roared approval, michael jackson moonwalked across the stage and declared, ``i'm bad,'' to open his first solo u.s. tour
jackson kicked off the 13-city tour tuesday at 16,900-seat kemper arena, where smoke machines, lasers, and 72 speakers highlighted the performance
ku klux klan leaflets were placed on numerous car in the parking lot, but the only arrest was of a person suspected of being under the influence of alcohol, police said
after another show here tonight, the pop singer moves to new york city's madison square garden in march
jackson sang 17 songs tuesday in a two-hour concert that opened with smoke machines churning and the audience bathed in brilliant white lights. an overhead video screen showed the image of jackson's legs moonwalking across it
flanked by four dancers, and backed by four singers and a seven-member band, jackson appeared and slid into non-stop gyrations to the throbbing beat of ``wanna be startin' somethin','' one of the hits from ``thriller,'' the 1983 blockbuster album that sold 40 million copies
many traveled for hours to get to the concert, but perhaps none farther than ivan herman, 32, and carla vanparys, 27, who came from their home in brussels, belgium. herman said he also attended the opening of the 1984 victory tour by jackson and members of his musical family
i've seen him six times,'' herman said. ``he's gotten more mature. he's more of a real person.''
some said they liked the idea of a solo tour
this time we get to focus on michael, just his talents,'' said alonzo washington, 20, of kansas city, kan. ``he's trying to prove he's a talent, and not just hype.''
during his rendition of ``bad,'' jackson was lifted on a platform over the heads of the audience. while suspended there, his coat and hair flapped in an artificial breeze as he sang, ``i'm bad, i'm bad.''
during ``thriller'' he was enveloped in smoke and threw a white hat to the crowd
tickets were $30 when the victory tour opened with a concert at arrowhead stadium, home of the kansas city chiefs football team. this tour, tickets at the much-smaller kemper arena were priced at $23, but scalpers reportedly were getting up to $200
a fan from tulsa, okla., who won a free ticket to tonight's show but can't ride a bus with other winners because of a disability was given an airline flight, limousine service and hotel accomodations by the tour's sponsor, pepsi-cola co
alan stephens, 18, won promotional tickets from tulsa radio station kmod, but cannot travel by bus because he suffers from lesch-nyhan sydrome, which causes him to strike himself and limits the use of his limbs
other stops on the tour are st. louis; pittsburgh; minneapolis; cleveland; denver; chapel hill, n.c.; indianapolis; cincinnati; houston; louisville, ky.; and birmingham, ala. other dates may be added, tour officials have said
rep. jack kemp, r-n.y., has joined the field for indiana's may 3 republican presidential primary
kemp campaign officials tuesday filed the required ballot petitions in the office of the secretary of state. bob poor of greencastle, kemp's indiana campaign chairman, said the petitions contained 6,300 signatures
indiana law requires a candidate to have 500 petitioners from each of the state's 10 congressional districts
kemp and sen. bob dole of kansas are the only gop candidates to file so far. the filing period ends march 4
state and democratic party officials say at least three democratic presidential contenders will not be running statewide on ohio's may 3 primary ballot because they failed to file slates of delegates in one or two of the state's 21 congressional districts
the secretary of state's office said tuesday that while official lists will be compiled by march 1, it appears former sen. gary hart of colorado, rep. richard gephardt of missouri and jesse jackson will not run statewide
all of the other major presidential candidates in both parties apparently fielded slates in all districts, although democrat bruce babbitt and republican pete dupont have abandoned their campaigns and their names apparently will be withdrawn
democrats whose statewide candidacies appeared assured include gov. michael dukakis of massachusetts, illinois sen. paul simon and sen. albert gore, tennessee. the republicans are sen. robert dole of kansas, vice president george bush, congressman jack kemp of new york and pat robertson
supporters of jesse jackson have become the first of the six announced democratic presidential candidates to file petitions for a spot on the crucial april 19 new york primary ballot
while the jackson camp showed up tuesday at the state board of election with more than six times the required number of signatures, state board spokesman steven lafever said they had been beaten to the ballot by ``uncommitted.''
lafever said supporters of uncommitted slates of delegates, put together by a group of elected democratic county clerks from across upstate new york, had filed petitions containing 18,816 signatures on monday
democratic candidates have until midnight tomorrow to file petitions containing at least 10,000 signatures with at least 100 coming from each of 17 of the state's 34 congressional districts. voters</head>
gov. michael s. dukakis enjoys a prohibitive lead among democratic presidential candidates in his home state and vice president george bush leads the republican field in the massachusetts primary on march 8, according to a new poll
the survey, commissioned by wcvb-tv in boston, weei radio and the boston globe, was conducted by the gallup organization among massachusetts voters last weekend
the survey said dukakis led the democratic field with 61 percent support, followed distantly by missouri rep. richard gephardt with 13 percent
in the republican race, bush _ a massachusetts native _ led with 49 percent, compared to 29 percent saying they support kansas sen. bob dole
the telephone survey of presidential preference involved 639 registered democrats with a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percent. the poll also reached 331 republicans, with a margin of error of plus or minus 6 percent
disabled americans express greater interest in politics than other citizens, but they register and vote at a rate considerably lower than the general public, according to a recently released survey
our findings suggest that barriers, either external or internal or both, prevent many disabled americans from converting their exceptionally high political interest into actual electoral activity,'' said humphrey taylor, president of louis harris and associates, which conducted the poll
the most common barrier cited for disabled people was lack of transportation and difficulty in getting to the polls, problems noted by 29 percent of the respondents. twenty-one percent said it was difficult to stand or walk
the telephone poll of 536 disabled people nationwide, conducted in june and july 1987, found that 53 percent said they follow government and public affairs most of the time
in comparison, only 26 percent of all u.s. adults pay attention to politics much of the time, according to a 1984 national election study by the university of michigan
the survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percent
a white man who admitted chasing two blacks with a baseball bat was ordered to perform 200 hours of community service for the naacp by a judge trying to help him overcome racial hatred
he has been taught to hate black people for some reason,'' said cook county circuit judge stuart nudelman. ``i'm trying to put him in an environment where he can perhaps do some good and learn something about the people he thinks he hates and perhaps learn that his feelings are misguided.''
james kalafut, a 21-year-old plumbing company laborer, pleaded guilty to aggravated assault and ethnic intimidation and could have been sentenced to a year in prison, the judge said after sentencing him tuesday
kalafut was charged in august after he and a group of other whites _ brandishing baseball bats, throwing bottles and shouting racial slurs _ chased two blacks from a transit stop in gage park, a predominantly white neighborhood on the southwest side
nudelman placed kalafut under his supervision for one year and ordered him to perform 200 hours of community service work for the national association for the advancement of colored people
details of when kalafut will serve the sentence are to be worked out in the next few days by his attorney, barry silver, the naacp and the judge
silver said before the sentencing that kalafut would accept the agreement to perform community service and no appeal would be attempted
i think it's a good sentence given the fact that he's basically pleaded guilty to hating a minority group,'' silver said
by being with black people, he will have a chance to learn they are no different than he is except that the color of their skin is different
i think that is an important lesson for anyone to learn, especially someone who has been involved in this kind of activity,'' silver said
the attorney said kalafut, who declined to be interviewed, was ``concerned about his own personal safety when he is in the neighborhood of the naacp,'' located on the south side
silver said kalafut also was concerned about being rejected by naacp officials and being ``made the scapegoat in a sort of reverse discrimination.''
but the civil rights organization plans to make sure that doesn't happen, said edward mcclellan, president of the south side branch
certainly we don't presume there are only white racists or what have you,'' said mcclellan, who wasn't sure what type of work kalafut would perform. ``racism can be engendered by anyone inclined to that sort of prejudice.''
nudelman said that trying to help kalafut overcome his prejudice against blacks made more sense than sentencing him to jail, ``where he won't learn anything except more hatred.''
but the judge warned, ``if he ... doesn't do what he's supposed to, he'll come back before me and i'll sentence him to jail.''
it's a lot more fun winning.'' _ sen. bob dole of kansas, after winning south dakota's republican primary and minnesota's gop caucuses
this is a war of citizens, women and children, to achieve a political aim. that's what's serious about it and against it we have to use force so that the violence would not prevail.'' _ israeli defense minister yitzhak rabin, on the riots by palestinians in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
as of this moment, all of the checks are stopped.'' _ west virginia treasurer a. james manchin, after the state supreme court ruled that the legislature unconstitutionally enacted a deficit budget
it's been a quarter century since betty friedan helped launch the women's movement with her book ``the feminine mystique,'' but a recent survey indicates women still do most of the cooking and grocery shopping
when most couldn't persuade the men they live with to help out, women of all income levels devised their own methods of easing the burden, mainly by cutting the time they spend in the kitchen, the new york times reported today
the times conducted telephone interviews with 1,870 people nationwide between oct. 29 and nov. 5 and found that while more women are in the work force and have less time at home, they remain the primary care-givers and the ones who pay attention to ``how, when, what and where their families eat.''
among married couples surveyed, only 18 percent of men said they do the family's main food shopping; 6 percent more said they share the responsibility with someone else at home
meanwhile, 91 percent of married women said they do the shopping, with 3 percent saying the chore is shared
working full time outside the home didn't seem to make much difference. the study found that 90 percent of married women who work full time said they do the principal family shopping
as for preparing meals, 90 percent of married women surveyed said they do most or all the cooking in their homes, compared with just 15 percent of married men
last month, a magazine survey reported that 77 percent of working mothers queried said they prepare dinner by themselves _ and 64 percent said they do the after-dinner cleanup alone, too
in its february issue, working mother magazine also reported that its survey found 92 percent of working-mother respondents do the laundry regularly in their households
according to that study, whereas husbands and children do the laundry regularly about 25 percent of the time, 27 percent of husbands never so much as throw a dirty sock into the washing machine
the magazine found that men in higher-income families were much more likely to pitch in than men in lower-income families
working mother published its questions in april and drew responses from 2,811 working mothers around the country
the outlook for u.s. wheat farmers has improved significantly, aided in part by huge subsidized sales to the soviet union
an additional sale of 700,000 metric tons to the soviets was announced tuesday by the agriculture department. overall, exports are expected to rise more than 50 percent from last year, reducing the u.s. wheat stockpile to the lowest level in six years
in a related analysis, the department's economic research service said the rising demand and shrinking inventories have boosted wheat prices well above last year's harvest lows of about $2.28 per bushel
over the entire wheat marketing year, which began last june 1, the national average farm price is expected to be in the range of $2.55 to $2.65 per bushel, up from $2.42 in 1986-87, the report said. that will be the first year-to-year increase since 1983-84
looking briefly at 1988 harvest prospects, the report noted that plantings of winter wheat last fall for this summer's harvest were the smallest in 10 years. spring wheat plantings may be up slightly if strong prices entice farmers away from the usda's 1988 acreage program
however, weather remains the leading determinate of 1988's wheat crop,'' the report said
the latest sale, equal to about 25.7 million bushels, was handled by continental grain co., 150,000 tons; tradigrain inc., 50,000; louis dreyfus corp., 250,000; cargill inc., 100,000; and peavey co., 150,000
at recent prices averaging $2.76 per bushel, the wheat would have a farm value of about $71 million. that is a five-day average price through feb. 19, adjusted to reflect prices received by farmers
more than 6.3 million tons of subsidized wheat have been sold to the soviet union under the department's export enhancement program, or eep, for delivery in the year that began last oct. 1
william l. davis, acting general sales manager for the department's foreign agricultural service, said an additional 500,200 tons of wheat are still available to the soviet union under current eep authorization
under eep, private exporters are given surplus commodities owned by the department's commodity credit corp. so they can sell a foreign buyer wheat or other authorized commodity at competitive world prices
the sales also are part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of a long-term agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans, or 39.4 bushels of corn
in addition, 1.67 million tons of u.s. corn, 800,000 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal have been bought by the soviets for delivery this year
agriculture department economists say consumers soon will see lower prices for lettuce
lettuce shipments and prices should return to normal this spring as harvesting moves north from california's imperial valley and spring brings improved weather,'' according to a report by the department's economic research service. ``both grower and retail lettuce prices likely will decline to more typical levels.''
last fall prices soared because ``unusual heat and pest problems reduced yields,'' the report said. in november and december, lettuce sold for $20 to $25 per carton at california shipping points, compared with $4 to $7 a year earlier. as of early february, prices were ranging between $3 and $12
prices remained higher than usual during the winter because cold weather and plant disease transmitted by the whitefly reduced midwinter shipments from the imperial valley,'' the report said. ``the valley usually supplies most of the domestic lettuce supply during midwinter.''
the recent death of donald l. houston, one of the agriculture department's senior career officials, was a tragic loss to the department and to the nation, agriculture secretary richard e. lyng said
houston, 53, died feb. 19 of cancer. he was named head of the department's animal and plant health inspection service last fall and previously was administrator of the food safety and inspection service for seven years
lyng said tuesday in a statement that he had known houston, a veterinarian, for more than 15 years. ``he truly epitomized what the american people want and expect in a public servant,'' lyng said
houston was born in east st. louis, ill., where he joined usda as a veterinary meat inspector in 1961. he moved to washington in 1965
the state department's second-ranking official caused a diplomatic and political dustup last week with his explanation, later partially disavowed, of why the administration wants to shut down its aid program for ireland
the remarks by deputy secretary john whitehead generated a stir in dublin, sent irish diplomats scurrying to find explanations, and produced expressions of dismay from the ``shamrock caucus'' in congress
in the end, the state department took the unusual step of issuing a clarification that effectively repudiated part of what whitehead said
at issue is u.s. participation in the international fund for ireland. american contributions have totaled $85 million over the past two years, and $35 million is slated for the current year. most of the money is aimed at promoting economic and social progress in northern ireland, now approaching two decades of sectarian strife
last thursday, whitehead went before reporters to explain the administration's foreign aid proposals for 1989, and he was asked why no money was programmed for ireland
he said ireland ``ranks down the list'' of foreign aid priorities, adding that the united states does not get a ``real return'' on its investment despite the emotional and ``maybe political appeal'' of aid to ireland
other needs appear to us to be more urgent,'' whitehead said
both the cutoff decision and the tone of whitehead's remarks were the talk of dublin late last week. and there were expressions of concern from two of the best known irish-americans in congress _ sen. edward m. kennedy and his nephew, rep. joseph p. kennedy ii, both massachusetts democrats
the chairman of the congressional friends of ireland, rep. brian donnelly, d-mass., said he was outraged
the state department came under pressure to clarify whitehead's remarks, and did so over the weekend. privately, one official said that whitehead misspoke but the problem was ``how to set the record straight'' without upsetting him
after a day's contemplation, the state department issued a statement expressing strong support for the international fund even though whitehead had said u.s. contributions to it had yielded few benefits
distancing itself still further from whitehead, the statement said, ``we have been very happy with the progress which the fund and its governing board have made.''
beyond that, it even implied that the administration would not be displeased if congress overrode the aid cutoff and earmarked more money for the program
of course, we will be ultimately guided by what congress authorizes and appropriates and what is signed into law by the president,'' the statement said
there is some dispute as to whether u.s. participation in the program was to be phased out. whitehead made no reference to any such limit, but the state department clarification does allude to a three-year time frame. irish diplomatic sources, meanwhile, said funding for additional years had never been ruled out
in any case, the statement appears to have calmed dublin, where there is a feeling that the congress won't cut the aid program adrift
contributing to the more relaxed mood was the statement by rep. kennedy: ``the fund has done good work and continues to do so,'' he said. ``i for one will be encouraging my colleagues to consider the economic and symbolic importance of continued american support for the international fund.''
kansas sen. bob dole, proclaiming ``we're winning again,'' was heading south hopeful his victories in minnesota and south dakota would help his republican presidential campaign in a region where vice president george bush is the front-runner
i've got a big hill to climb in the south,'' dole said tuesday night while celebrating his latest victories
dole scheduled four stops in south carolina, one in north carolina and then planned to head for florida
the kansas senator got some help in south carolina on monday when he was endorsed by sen. strom thurmond, the state's senior officeholder. but bush has the backing of gov. carroll campbell
with a republican primary on march 5, south carolina opens the southern phase of the 1988 campaign. three days later is super tuesday, when 20 states, the majority of them in the south, will hold primaries or caucuses
for the second time this busy campaign month, dole was heading out of the midwest with a decisive show of support
two weeks ago, he won the iowa caucuses and flew to new hampshire hoping to deliver a killing blow to bush. but new england proved to be bush territory and the vice president won the new hampshire primary and revived his status as gop front-runner
dole was in a black mood after his new hampshire defeat, but upon getting strong backing from voters in south dakota and minnesota, the senator said, ``it's a lot more fun winning.''
as for bush's showing _ second in south dakota and fourth in minnesota _ dole said, ``i really believe when the vice president of the united states gets 10 percent, or around that area _ the sitting vice president _ and only about 15 percent in south dakota, it's going to send a strong signal to small towns, to farmers, to businessmen and businesswomen.''
we're winning again,'' he said. ``we probably had our expectations too high in new hampshire and it probably hurt us some around the country. but now we're winning again.''
dole said he hoped the results ``send a message that bob dole has a message. that's what the election is all about. i haven't changed my message. i've talked about the future, i've talked about leadership, i've talked about party responsibilities, i've talked about the left out and the down-and-out in america, i've talked about the future of our young people.''
the returns from south dakota's presidential primary election were complete _ except for lincoln no. 51, a rural precinct near lemmon in extreme northwestern south dakota
fern brockel, perkins county auditor, said election workers in the precinct were supposed to fill in the vote totals for each candidate on the unofficial return sheet. but she said it was given to her with all the lines blank
the returns are in the official poll book, but under the rules, it cannot be opened until the official canvass this afternoon
without the missing precinct, perkins county residents cast 1,345 votes out of the nearly 165,000 votes cast in the election. and violent protest between other students and police. adds byline. no pickup. ^by barry renfrew</note>
five radical students armed with bombs and knives seized a u.s. information service office today and detonated two bombs and started a fire before police overpowered them
two of the students brandishing explosive devices and draped in south korean flags stood at shattered windows on the second floor yelling ``yankee go home'' as riot police ringed the building
u.s. embassy officials said they had no reports of injuries, but the attackers smashed windows and set a fire in a periodical storage room. thick smoke filled part of the building located in the heart of seoul
people inside the building at the time of the attack, including at least one american, were not detained by the radicals
the students, who said they were members of the ``young student suicide group'' claimed they had 18 bombs and screamed at surrounding police to stay away. they tossed down a statement charging the united states was attempting to make south korea a colony
yankees stay out of korea,'' the students yelled
a police officer said it was unclear how many of the explosive devices the attackers had. the bombs were crude chemical devices, possibly some kind of plastic explosive, he said
about 200 radical students hurling firebombs and rocks clashed with riot police about an hour later outside myungdong cathedral. police fired volleys of tear gas at the students who yelled slogans denouncing president-elect roh tae-woo, who is to be sworn in thursday
hundreds of protesters had gathered at the cathedral less than a mile from the u.s. information service office earlier in the afternoon for an anti-government protest. ``down with roh tae-woo,'' the students yelled
some of the attackers were reading in the office's library when there was a large explosion in a nearby roon and they suddenly pulled out bombs and started screaming slogans, eyewitnesses said. at least one of the attackers pulled out a knife and brandished it, they said
he was kind of crazy-eyed,'' said paul wadden, a visiting american teacher who was reading in the library at the time
the attackers smashed three windows overlooking the main street outside and two of them stood shouting slogans out into the street and brandishing bombs and cigaretee lighters. riot police stood on the sidewalk below with shields covering their heads and shattered glass covered the street
the students tossed at least one bomb into the street where it exploded harmlessly, eyewitnesses said. a second bomb was tossed out, but did not explode, they said
people caught in the library said the students did not attempt to detain them and they were able to leave after recovering from their initial shock. wadden said he and other people were prevented from leaving downstairs for up to 10 minutes by building guards
there were about 40 people in the library at the time, most of them koreans, eyewitnesses said
police who entered the building by the rear entrance overpowered the protesters about 30 minutes after the attack began. the students were taken out of the building in a bus with covered windows
u.s. embassy officials said south korean riot police entered the building at their request
japanese prime minister noboru takeshita arrived at the lotte hotel across the street from the u.s. information service office just as the incident ended, officials said. takeshita is in seoul for roh's inauguration
american diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they did not know why the students attacked the u.s. facility. ``we have no idea what the motivation was,'' an embassy official said
the united states is south korea's chief ally. washington has 40,000 troops in south korea under a mutual defense pact against communist north korea
the u.s. information service provides reading material and other materials on the united states and operates libraries and information centers around the world in conjunction with american embassies. the service office in seoul is located about half a mile from the american embassy
the same office was seized by 73 radical students for four days in may, 1985 as an anti-american protest. they ended the occupation peacefully and some later received prison sentences
u.s. embassy officials were unable to explain today how the attackers were able to bring weapons into the well-guarded building. visitors must pass a metal detector, present identification and have their bags searched and there are police guards inside and outside
the statement by the students denounced roh as a puppet who had been installed by the united states
south korean radicals have repeatedly charged the united states has kept a series of authoritarian governments in power in south korea. roh, a former general, won the first democratic elections in 16 years last december
snow squalls howled over western new york today as snow fell in six other states
a snow squall warning was in effect for the lake ontario shoreline, where as much as 6 inches of snow was expected to accumulate
snow also fell in north central new york, northwestern minnesota, michigan and central pennsylvania, and scattered snow fell in west virginia, indiana and central illinois
rain extended from southern new england across the central atlantic coast into eastern north carolina. patches of dense fog deveoped over the tennessee valley and across the florida keys
today's forecast called for scattered snow showers along the great lakes and over western new york state and northwest pennsylvania, and for scattered rain showers over florida
high temperatures were expected to be in the 40s and 50s across much of the nation; the teens across the upper mississippi valley and upper great lakes, with single digits over northeast minnesota; the 20s and 30s over the northern plains, the middle mississippi valley and lower great lakes to northern new england; the 60s from the central and southern pacific coast across the southern rockies, central and southern texas, the gulf coast and northern florida; the 70s across the desert southwest and central florida and the lower 80s across southern florida
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 3 degrees below zero at international falls, minn., to 73 degrees at homestead, fla
other reports:
