a retired lawyer who reads dictionaries for fun says too many people are put off by big words
because so many people suffer from sesquipedalophobia, a fear or hatred of big words, 80-year-old norman schur has written eight books on the subject
this has gone from a hobby with me to a vocation and finally to a matter of sociological and political concern,'' schur said tuesday
schur has just published his latest book, ``1000 most challenging words.'' in the next one, ``1000 most obscure words,'' he plans brief essays on each word's origins and meaning. he believes if a person becomes familiar with a word, he or she will use it
schur, who received his high school diploma at age 11 and graduated from harvard university at age 17, does not blame weak vocabularies on the educational system
there are some well-educated people who do not like you to use big words,'' he said. ``if you use a word that's unfamiliar to them they resent it and this intimidates a lot of people.''
for people who want to improve their vocabulary, schur suggests they jot down every new word in a notebook, master it and then use it
i find reading dictionaries fascinating, but that's not the menu for most people,'' he said
grammy goose met granny goose in court, but the legal fight is not a family feud
granny goose foods inc., the nation's third largest potato chip manufacturer, has accused grammy goose baby boutique in nearby petaluma of creating confusion over the food firm's name and logo by using a similar name
granny has asked for a preliminary injunction against grammy
the name and logo ``represent the most valuable asset my client owns,'' granny attorney kate spellman told sonoma county superior court judge lloyd von der mehden on tuesday. ``where there is confusion, dilution has occurred.''
sandy gotelli, the petaluma grandmother who owns the baby shop, said she'll be forced out of business if the injunction is granted. she said she picked the name by combining her liking for geese with her granddaughter's nickname for her
ms. spellman said the company offered to help grammy goose design a new sign, phase out printed paper goods and find a new name that retains part of the current name
we understand she is a small business and we would like to mitigate the harm to her,'' ms. spellman said. ``we mean her no harm; she is so inflexible.''
mrs. gotelli's attorney said the shop owner had made a counter offer to the chip maker: to promise the grammy goose name would never be sold to anyone else and would never be used outside of sonoma county
the judge gave mrs. gotelli one week to respond in writing to the granny goose offer. granny goose's attorneys then will have five days to respond
the judge said he would then issue a ruling.  jeopardy to three.</head>
three presidential candidates faced the prospect of losing future federal matching funds after failing to win at least 10 percent of the vote in the south dakota primary
democrats jesse jackson, albert gore jr. and gary hart were in jeopardy of losing their eligibility under an election-law stipulation that starts the clock on dropping a candidate from the matching-funds category if he receives less than 10 percent in two successive primaries
in south dakota, gore had 8 percent and hart and jackson each had 5 percent. all three also finished in the single digits in new hampshire last week, in the first primary of the campaign season
failing to get 10 percent in south dakota does not mean an immediate cutoff because the law stays such action for 30 days after the primary. and candidates can qualify anew by getting 20 percent of the vote in a future primary
that means jackson and gore, who are expected to do well in the super tuesday primaries on march 8, are likely to score the strong finishes they need before the 30-day stay expires
in 1984, jackson lost his eligiblity because he fell below the 10 percent threshhold in nebraska and oregon. but before the money was actually stopped, he had regained certification by winning 23.6 percent in new jersey
regardless of whether candidates have been disqualified from receiving matching funds to continue their campaigns, they can continue to receive matching payments to retire campaign debts that were incurred before the date of ineligibility, said spokesman fred eiland of the federal election commission
matching funds from the federal treasury have become the manna of presidential campaigns, with the amount distributed to each candidate dependent on how much he raises privately
the federal election commission so far this year has handed out close to $40 million to 14 candidates. three of those candidates have already dropped out of the race _ democrat bruce babbitt and republicans alexander haig and pete du pont
the fund matches each contribution of $250 or less that a candidate raises privately. the fund is supported by the $1 checkoff on individual income tax forms under the public financing system set up in the mid-1970s by congress
the six-member federal election commission votes on candidate certification following a review of the campaign's finances by the fec audit and legal staff
to be certified, a candidate must raise $100,000 across 20 states in contributions of $250 or less
vice president george bush and robertson have received the most matching funds for this year's election, each with more than $6.5 million
jackson has received $621,828, gore nearly $2 million, and hart $1.1 million
at a recent fec meeting, commissioner joan aikens attacked what she described as an inequity in the law that allows an unopposed third-party candidate, or a candidate who chooses not to compete in every state, to continue receiving federal matching funds while others who place their names on every primary ballot face the risk of cutoff
a candidate whose name is not on the ballot is not covered by the 10 percent rule
china's latest activist in the campaign against high-living officials is a cook who overturned a banquet table in disgust over their feasting
the official china daily said today the unidentified woman cook was applauded by residents in linshu county, one of the poorest in the coastal province of shandong
it said she was angry at the county communist party secretary, who together with other officials last december gathered for a meeting which in actuality was a 14-dish banquet
the party said county officials were already under fire for investing $378,000 to build a guest house for vips and budgeting $59,000 for banquets last year at the county government guesthouse
china's state council, or cabinet, last year ordered all party and government officials to cut back on banqueting and gift-giving
a judge committed suicide today by jumping from the 16th floor of a high-rise building housing court offices in tokyo, police said
an official of the tokyo metropolitan police department identified the man as akira takayama, 55, a judge at the tokyo high court
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said police were investigating the reason for the suicide
according to an official of the tokyo high court's public relations division, takayama had been suffering from depression since last year
takayama, a native of tokyo, was appointed to the tokyo high court in april 1986 following service with several local courts, the court official said
the death toll in a monthlong outbreak of whooping cough reached 12 with the death of an infant girl, health authorities said
the 2-year-old girl died friday in the maria ludovica children's hospital in buenos aires despite a campaign by public health authorities to innoculate children in the buenos aires-la plata area
whooping cough normally is not a common health risk in argentina
officials have noted each of 12 fatalities were malnourished, came from low-income families and had not been innoculated against whooping cough
a tiny porcelain tea bowl painted by a french artist in 1749 was bought for $34,850 at sotheby's, the auction house said
the artist, louis denis armand the elder, who worked at the vincennes factory near paris, painted 46 patches of enamel colors on the bowl to guide him in selecting colors, which often changed drastically in the firing process
some colors were also very expensive. one pound of one color cost nine times armand's annual salary
the bowl, 1} inches high, was bought and sold anonymously on tuesday. only one similar tea bowl from vincennes is known to exist, and it is in a museum at sevres, the other famous french porcelain center
here are excerpts of the government's new regulations banning political activity by major opposition groups. the rules were imposed today in the form of an order
if the minister (of law and order) is of the opinion that it is necessary for the safety of the public, the maintenance of public order or the termination of the state of emergency, he may, without prior notice to any person or without hearing any person, issue an order ... prohibiting an organization ... from carrying on:
_any activities or acts whatsoever
_activities or acts of a nature, class or kind specified in the order
(the order says an affected organization will not be barred from:)
_preserving its assets
_keeping up to date its books and records and performing administrative functions in connection therewith
_complying with an obligation imposed on it by or under any law or court
_taking legal advice or judicial steps
_carrying on such activities or performing such acts as the minister may have consented to
no consent ... shall be granted by the minister unless he is convinced that the granting of such consent will not result in the safety of the public or the maintenance of public order being threatened
(the organizations affected by the new restrictions are:)
azanian people's organization, azanian youth organization, cradock residents association, detainees parents support committee, detainees support committee, national education crisis committee, national education union of south africa, port elizabeth black civic organization, release mandela committee, soweto civic association, soweto youth congress, south african national student congress, south african youth congress, united democratic front, vaal civil association, western cape civic association
taiwan residents made nearly 90,000 trips to china in 1987, an official report said. it was a huge increase from the previous year and was brought about by taiwan's lifting of a ban on such travel
china's domestic china news service, in a report appearing in hong kong today, said ``taiwan compatriots'' traveled to the chinese mainland more than 89,000 times last year, a 180 percent increase from 1986. the statistics were provided by a public security bureau spokesman, the report said
the nationalist chinese government on taiwan in october lifted a 38-year old ban on travel to mainland china to allow family reunions. thousands of taiwan residents secretly traveled to china before the ban was lifted
a couple who claimed they were waging a holy war have been sentenced in the latest of three slayings in which they regarded the victims as witches or vampires
michael carson was sentenced to prison for 27 years to life in the 1982 slaying of clark stephens near garberville. his wife, suzan, was sentenced to 25 years to life
the sentences will follow earlier terms, deputy district attorney max cardoza said tuesday. the carsons were convicted in may of shooting stephens, 26, and burning his body before burying it
carson, 36, was given an additional two years for using a firearm. the two were sentenced monday by humboldt county superior court judge william ferroggiaro
the carsons previously were given consecutive sentences of 25 years to life for two other slayings
they were convicted in the 1981 murder in san francisco of a woman mrs. carson told investigators was a ``psychic vampire'' who was draining her of her beauty
they also were convicted of the 1983 killing of a man in sonoma county who picked up the hitchhiking couple, only to be declared a witch by the wife
in a lengthy statement taped by police, the two said they were on a holy war ordered by allah
defense attorneys contended carson shot stephens to death because he had sexually attacked mrs. carson, an action that amounted to self-defense in keeping with the couple's beliefs as fundamentalist moslems
eric sevareid says news on television ``has become part of the daily entertainment of a rather bored society.''
the former chief washington correspondent of cbs news, at a seminar tuesday at the museum of broadcasting, expressed misgivings about the rise of features-oriented tv magazine shows
underlying this whole development in the way news is presented now is ... the nature and psychology of american society at this moment in history (after) years of essential peace and essential prosperity for most people
we have news about entertainment now; you're going to have a news magazine on the business side of sports; you have a game called `trivial pursuit.'''
audiences don't get very excited about policy issues and don't want to follow what appears to be 30 years of the same pictures coming from the middle east, he said
if you had another great war or great depression, that would change matters, but that would be too high a price,'' sevareid said
sevareid also said he watched ``with some astonishment'' the on-air battle between cbs anchorman dan rather and vice president george bush
i'd never seen brother dan lose his cool before,'' sevareid said. ``i'm sorry it happened. i don't think a cbs hard news show should become controverted. ... neutrality should be preserved
i don't think mr. bush answered much,'' he added. cq</note>
former miss america bess myerson, who was indicted last year for conspiring to influence the judge in the divorce settlement of her boyfriend, has been called to testify in a hearing today over a property dispute between the estranged couple
nancy capasso sought the hearing after her ex-husband, carl ``andy'' capasso, allegedly removed property from the house she had won as part of the divorce settlement, said raoul felder, mrs. capasso's attorney
felder said that he had subpoenaed the 63-year-old miss myerson, a former city cultural affairs commissioner, and characterized her as ``a key witness'' in the proceeding in state supreme court in manhattan
miss myerson stayed in the long island house last summer after capasso went to jail in june after being convicted of tax evasion in an unrelated case
mrs. capasso, who won the house as part of her $6.4 million divorce settlement, seeks to have capasso held in contempt, felder said
felder said he could not elaborate on details because a gag order was in effect
mrs. capasso has said all the living room furniture was taken, some artwork, a collection of antique quilts, some decoy ducks and sets of china and flatware
miss myerson was indicted last october for allegedly attempting to influence the rulings of former state supreme court justice hortense gabel in the capassos' divorce by giving the judge's daughter, sukreet gabel, a city job
miss myerson, capasso and mrs. gabel have pleaded innocent to five counts each of federal conspiracy, mail fraud and bribe-related charges. they each face up to five years in prison, if convicted. miss myerson faces an additional five years if convicted of obstruction of justice. germany</head>
the soviet union will start removing its shorter-range nuclear missiles from czechoslovakia in the next few days, the communist party daily newspaper rude pravo said today
also today, east germany said the soviets will begin the early withdrawal of its shorter-range missiles from the communist german nation this week
the missiles in both countries are included in an arms control agreement signed by the united states and the soviet union last december in washington under which all intermediate-range nuclear weapons in europe will be scrapped
the rude pravo newspaper stressed that the missiles are being taken out of czechoslovakia before the treaty is ratified by the u.s. congress
word that soviet missiles will be removed from czechoslovakia coincided with national celebrations of the 40th anniversary of the communist takeover in prague. the planned removal of the missiles was described by rude pravo as a significant gesture by the kremlin
a further expression of good will, similar to (others) made by the soviet union ... is that according to an agreement with czechoslovakia and east germany, it will begin in the next few days to pull out from the territory of both states the missile units equipped with otr-22 missiles,'' rude pravo said. otr-22 is the warsaw pact name for the shorter-range missiles nato calls ss-12. czechoslovakia has never said how many soviet missiles were installed on its territory. the only location ever given for the weapons was a military base near hranice, 180 miles southeast of prague
in 1983, nato began installing u.s. cruise and pershing 2 missiles in western europe to counteract soviet missiles pointed at the west. the kremlin responded by moving some ss-12 missiles from their bases in the soviet union to east germany and czechoslovakia, to put them within striking range of the west
meanwhile, the east german mission in bonn said today in a brief statement: ``withdrawal of the soviet shorter-range missiles from the german democratic republic will begin'' thursday. the statement said missiles would be removed that day from two east german sites _ bischofswerda and waren
east germany announced last week that ss-12s had been dismantled, put into crates and were ready for transport back to the soviet union. but it did not announced until today when the missiles would be taken out of the country
east german leader erich honecker in january indicated that soviet nuclear missiles in europe could be removed ahead of schedule
according to figures released after the superpower arms treaty was signed, there are 54 ss-12s in east germany
the dollar was mixed in dull european trading today as dealers waited for new factors to get the market out of the doldrums
gold prices fell in london following a large sell order from the middle east, which had a big impact because the market was so thin, dealers said
traders said last friday's remark by swiss national bank president pierre languetin that the dollar was poised to move lower again had put a very tight lid on any upward movement of the u.s. currency
dealers said tuesday's congressional testimony in washington by u.s. federal reserve chairman alan greenspan failed to give the market new directions and they didn't expect his repeat performance for the senate banking committee today to have much more impact
the release later today of fourth-quarter u.s. trade figures isn't likely to have a major impact on the market either because the figures are already known, dealers said
i honestly don't know what could help the dollar move,'' said one senior trader in milan. but another dealer said thursday's report of the first revision of u.s. fourth-quarter gross domestic product growth could possibly have an effect on the dollar
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar rose 0.25 yen to a closing 128.75. later, in london, it was quoted slightly higher at 128.85 yen
