a bus driver was arrested after allegedly beating a passenger who boarded his bus without exact change, police said
the name of the driver, a 43-year-old detroit man, was withheld pending issuance of a warrant on a charge of felonious assault, city police lt. philip foster said tuesday
jonathan perkins, 30, of detroit boarded the detroit department of transportation bus about 9:15 a.m. monday without the proper change, police said
the driver was absolutely belligerent,'' an unidentified bus rider told the detroit free press
perkins placed some coins in the fare box, then asked other passengers for change for a $20 bill to pay the balance of the $1 fare, the rider said
the driver yelled at perkins for about a mile, then shoved him off the bus, the passenger said
he literally threw him on the ground, pulled a knife on him and the next thing i know, he's on the guy's face,'' the passenger said. ``he started kicking him in the head and then shoved him into the intersection and left the scene.''
perkins was treated at detroit receiving hospital for minor bruises and cuts, police said
a woman who answered the phone at the department of transportation office said robert polk, director of the agency, was not available for comment tuesday. speeding</head>
panamanian police detained more than two dozen u.s. servicemen without charges after the son-in-law of panama's military strongman was held for speeding at a u.s. military installation
two u.s. military personnel were stopped and briefly held tuesday, a pentagon official said in washington. on monday, panamanian police detained 25 u.s. servicemen for two hours before releasing them without filing charges, said a u.s. embassy spokesman in panama city
the servicemen were picked up while driving to u.s. military installations inside the former panama canal zone
the state department planned to protest the detentions, said the pentagon official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the official said the detentions came a day after gen. manuel antonio noriega's son-in-law was stopped in the canal zone. he declined to give the son-in-law's name, but said noriega's daughter and two other passengers were in the car when it was stopped sunday night for speeding and passing in a no-passing zone at the albrook air force station, outside of panama city
the son-in-law allegedly became abusive with the air force security policeman who stopped him. he could not produce identification, the source said. at that point, the policeman ``restrained'' him, put him in handcuffs and took him to the air force police station for processing, the source said. the son-in-law was released about an hour after being stopped, he said
on monday, the u.s. embassy spokesman told the associated press police stopped 25 servicemen. the spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said most were driving motorcycles to installations inside the former canal zone, but two were driving cars and one was walking
col. leonidas macias, chief of police for the panamanian defense forces, denied police detained the servicemen. he said officers merely stopped them to check for drivers' licenses and remind them that u.s. personnel are forbidden to wear uniforms outside of the former canal zone
the detentions marked the latest sign of deteriorating relations between the united states and panama since last june, when demonstrations broke out in panama demanding the resignation of noriega, the armed forces chief
the reagan administration has publicly called for noriega to step down following his indictment on drug trafficking charges this month by a federal grand jury in miami. county</head>
the california coastal commission has approved a $2.5 billion plan for three offshore oil platforms in the santa barbara channel, a plan first proposed by exxon in 1981
on an 8-2 vote, with one commissioner abstaining, the commission approved exxon's plans for the platforms, a marine terminal and onshore facility in las flores canyon
but the plan, which would more than double the state's oil production, requires major changes in exxon's production methods. the company must dismantle an offshore treatment and storage ship now in use, commission spokesman jack liebster said tuesday
we're talking about state-of-the-art air pollution control to reduce the current levels,'' he said. ``even with the expansion, this will result in a reduction of emissions.''
a 1987 agreement on air pollution controls was instrumental in breaking a political deadlock over exxon's plan, commission chairman michael wornum said
the company is producing up to 40,000 barrels a day on platform hondo, located between coastal santa barbara county and the channel islands. it processes the oil on an offshore vessel, a converted oil tanker moored in federal waters 3.1 miles offshore
in 1984 the oil company sued the commission, and later sued santa barbara county, over its demands that exxon stop using the converted tanker. in 1986 it renewed its lawsuit and issued an appeal to the interior department
commission approval was the result of compromises reached on all sides, including environmentalists, who agreed with tuesday's decision, said ralph faust, another commission spokesman
following the vote, terry c. leftgoff, spokesman for the environmental group get oil out, said the exxon project is ``the best that we could hope for in a regulatory environment.''
honduran death squads linked to the military have stepped up their campaign of terror, targeting opposition leaders, human rights activists, students and peasants, amnesty international said today
serious human rights violations, including arbitrary arrests, torture and ill-treatment are widespread in honduras and show no signs of diminishing,'' the london-based human rights organization said in a report
the group said many of the abuses arose during strikes, disputes over farm land or army operations against leftist guerrillas. the group also said it remains concerned about the government's failure to investigate reports of more than 100 people who disappeared between 1980 and 1984
in the report, titled ``honduras: civilian authority, military power,'' amnesty based its findings on interviews with senior government and military officials and non-government sources during two visits to honduras last year
the group said recent abuses include bombings, arbitrary detentions, death threats and harassment of critics of the government of president jose azcona hoyo. despite a civilian government, the 17,500-man army wields great power
victims include human rights figures, opposition leaders, members of labor organizations, students and peasants, amnesty said. the victims described severe beatings, electric shocks and sexual abuse
the group said patterns of abuse changed since the early 1980s, when it said abductions and executions were carried out systematically by order of the armed forces
the alleged abuses fell off after 1984, but the death squads have apparently begun a new campaign of intimidation in the last two years, the report said. death squads were believed to have been involved in three killings last month, it said
two people shot to death in january were to have testified against the government in a human rights case before the inter-american court of human rights in costa rica
amnesty blamed most of the recent alleged human rights abuses on the national investigations division, which amnesty said is part of the police but actually is controlled by the military
the report quoted a former member of battalion 3-16, which it said was a secret military intelligence unit, as saying he and other members of the group were secretly trained by the u.s. military in 1981
the unidentified man was quoted as saying that the u.s. officials discouraged torture but had trained the unit in methods of physical coercion
since 1981, the reagan administration has made honduras a key ally for policy aimed at containing the leftist sandinista government in neighboring nicaragua
a series of joint military exercises have been held, almost continously, for the past five years. a permanent american military presence is maintained at palmerola air base near tegucigalpa and at other facilities, totaling more than 1,000 u.s. troops
the u.s. military aid program grew from $8.9 million in 1981 to $88.8 million for 1986
a tugboat captain was wounded early today when shots fired from the brooklyn shoreline shattered the cabin's glass windshield, police said
more than a dozen such shootings have occurred since 2,800 union tugboat and barge workers went on strike over wage cuts feb. 16, said an officer from the police department's harbor unit who declined to give his name
early today, the tugboat odin was headed south in the east river, just off newtown creek, when a gunman fired four shots. newton creek divides brooklyn and queens
capt. les wallin suffered cuts on the left side of his face and glass in his eye when the windshield broke, but refused medical aid when the tugboat docked at staten island, the officer said
the captain and non-union crew members declined to discuss the shooting, police said
no other details were immediately available
acting gov. rose mofford may be able to run for governor in a may 17 recall election without giving up her position as secretary of state, the state's attorney general said
attorney general bob corbin, in a non-binding opinion issued tuesday, said that if mrs. mofford is drafted instead of declaring herself a candidate, she would not have to resign as secretary of state
mrs. mofford, who became acting governor following the impeachment of gov. evan mecham on feb. 5, has not said whether she is interested in running, and had no comment tuesday on the possibility of a draft
as governor, mecham would automatically be on the recall ballot, but his status is clouded by his impeachment and impending trial before the senate, and a criminal trial scheduled for march
democrat carolyn warner, who lost to mecham in a three-way race in 1968, and republican john rhodes have indicated they will be candidates in the recall election
mecham, a republican, faces a senate trial monday on charges that he hid a $350,000 campaign loan, misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership, and tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
a criminal trial is scheduled for march 22 on felony charges of concealing the $350,000 loan
arizona's resign-to-run law requires officeholders who run for another position to resign unless they are in the last year of their current term
rep. cindy resnick, a democrat, had asked corbin whether a draft of an officeholder as a gubernatorial candidate would require that person to resign
ms. resnick said she expects a draft-mofford movement to be started, but said she did not plan to be involved
meanwhile, rhodes announced tuesday that former sen. barry goldwater would be his honorary campaign chairman. goldwater endorsed mecham in the 1986 campaign, but now says that was a mistake
in accepting the position, goldwater said: ``you look back over all the governors that we've had in this state. we've had some darn good ones and we've had some mediocre ones, but it took us a long time to get a really bad one.''
the concert pianist solomon, hailed as one of the century's most distinguished pianists but forced to cut short his career because of a stroke, has died at age 85, his family said
solomon, born solomon cutner but known professionally by his first name only, died feb. 2, his family announced tuesday. no cause of death was given
solomon was born aug. 9, 1902, one of seven children in a family in london's rough east end. at age 7 he began studying music. one of his fellow students became the queen mother, mother of queen elizabeth ii
solomon made his concert hall debut when he was 8 years old, playing playing mozart's b flat concerto and the slow movement of tchaikovsky's first concerto at the queen's hall in london
he later appeared again at the queen's hall, under conductor sir henry wood, playing beethoven's third concerto and liszt's hungarian fantasy, and in 1911 undertook his first british tour. the same year he played to the royal family at buckingham palace, and his career as a child prodigy was established
solomon appeared with many of the world's most famous conductors and orchestras, but by the time he was 16, he had tired of the concert hall circuit and temporarily quit to resume his musical studies
wood wrote in his autobiography that the young solomon told him he had ``no boy's interests, no games,'' because of his career
as he said, it had been piano, piano, and nothing but piano,'' wrote wood
solomon resumed his concert hall career in 1921, made his american debut in 1926, and was one of the world's most sought-after pianists until suffering a debilitating stroke in 1956
the times of london wrote: ``he developed his technical virtuosity to the highest pitch, but his outstanding quality was the intellectual insight and poetry of feeling which he brought to the keyboard repertory, from mozart to debussy.''
another london paper, the daily telegraph, wrote: ``solomon's clarity of articulation, his warm, soft-grained tone, musical accuracy and honesty of purpose shone through all his performances, and his virtuosity was so formidable as to be unnoticeable.''
solomon is survived by his wife, gwendoline byrne, who was one of his former pupils
retired maj. gen. harry m. arthur, who spent two years as the ranking american officer with the chinese army during world war ii, has died. he was 88
arthur, also a prominent upstate banker, died tuesday in wallace thomson hospital
a 1921 graduate of the citadel, arthur was called to active duty during world war ii, where he served in the chinese combat command, rising to the rank of colonel
after his release from active duty, he organized the 218th infantry regiment and was its commander until 1952, when he was promoted to brigadier general and took command of the 51st division artillery
arthur, who retired as a major general in 1959, was president and chairman of arthur state bank, which he and his family founded in 1933. he also was a former president of the american bankers association and south carolina bankers association and state commander of the american legion
he was survived by his wife, daughter and three grandchildren
apple computer inc. is developing a laptop computer which it hopes to introduce next year, according to a computer magazine which printed details of the secret project
the article in this week's edition of macintosh today details the size, appearance and technical specifications of apple's laguna laptop model. the san francisco examiner reported tuesday that the article was based on a confidential document given to a free-lance writer by an apple employee
we don't comment on rumors of products which may or may not come to market,'' said barbara krause, spokeswoman for apple computer inc
the magazine article describes a 12-pound laptop with a flat-panel monitor called an active matrix screen and a central processor that can run macintosh software using only a fraction of the power used by most desktop models
the magazine said the system will come with 1 megabyte of internal memory, the same as the macintosh se. it will be powered by a five-pound lead-acid battery that will last up to 10 hours before recharging
the laguna is not expected to join the $1 billion laptop market until next year. will be 6th president sted 13th.</note>
president-elect roh tae-woo will be sworn in thursday in the first peaceful transfer of power in south korea's turbulent history with a promise to end authoritarian rule and usher in full democracy
roh will take the oath of office as the 6th president at a heavily-guarded ceremony at the national assembly with no general public participation. outgoing president chun doo-hwan and other leaders will attend the ceremony
the inauguration also will mark the start of the sixth republic as the country adopts a new constitution that provides for greater political and individiual freedoms. roh has promised the republic will be ``the great era of the common man.''
the charismatic roh, 55, is committed to ending the nation's long tradition of authoritarian rule that strictly limited political activity and ruthlessly cracked down on opposition. he also has pledged to end the country's confrontational politics and violent regional divisions and to redress social and economic inequality
roh on monday called for a government that ``is loved by the people and run in accordance with democratic principles to suit a new era.''
the new president faces the challenge of ending authoritarian rule in a nation that has never had a peaceful transfer of power. the nation has been dominated by civilian and military strongmen since its creation in 1948 and its politics are turbulent and often violent
police were on alert in seoul and other cities today after reports that radical students and dissidents may attempt to stage anti-roh protests. radical groups have refused to recognize roh's election and contend he is intent on continuing authoritarian rule
radical groups called for anti-government protests in seoul and other cities today and thursday. detachments of riot police were seen guarding key points in some areas of seoul and police officials said reserves were on alert
more than 200 student and dissident leaders were being watched in case they attempted to organize protests, officials said. police also were guarding festive arches erected in seoul for the inauguration in case dissidents attempted to wreck them
chun warned at a farewell dinner in seoul tonight that political stability and continued expansion were vital. he warned against political unrest
i am convinced that there must not, and will not, be any repeat of political chaos that imperils the country or social chaos that threatens national survival,'' he said
chun, who took power with military backing in 1980 when he and roh were senior generals, is to head a presidential advisory board. he was to leave office in a separate ceremony thursday
a low-key inaugural ceremony was planned for thursday with roh scheduled to take the oath of office in the square in front of the national assembly building. but attendance was by invitation only and there were no plans for celebrations or public attendance
factory workers, street cleaners and other ordinary people were invited to attend the ceremony along with officials, academics, and other representatives of korean society, officials said
envoys from 88 nations, including prime minister noboru takeshita of japan and the premiers of sri lanka and fiji, were to attend the inauguration. the united states was to be represented by treasury secretary james baker
roh won the country's first democratic presidential election in 16 years on dec. 16 with 36.6 percent of the vote. he defeated rival opposition candidates kim young-sam and kim dae-jung, who split the opposition vote
roh, a former general, is identified with the military-backed governments that have ruled the country since 1961 and many koreans are doubtful if he can achieve massive democratic change
opposition parties contend roh's inauguration will simply signal a change of figurehead and the government will continue to be run by the armed forces and an entrenched elite of government officials and business leaders
thousands of leftist demonstrators marched on a military camp today and accused the government of betraying the revolution that swept president corazon aquino to power two years ago
about 200 policemen blocked the road leading to camp crame as helicopters patrolled overhead. but the crowd, estimated at 20,000 people by police, was peaceful
the rally was held on a boulevard between camp crame and camp aguinaldo. two years ago, hundreds of thousands of filipinos flocked there and prevented troops loyal to then-president ferdinand marcos from attacking rebellious soldiers holed up in crame. the four-day standoff ended with marcos' depature from the philippines
today's marchers included students, workers, farmers, nuns and priests. they chanted ``dismantle the u.s.-aquino regime'' and carried effigies of mrs. aquino and uncle sam
red banners said, ``advance the people's genuine revolution,'' and one poster read: ``cory _ closet dictator.''
the protesters denounced what they said was mrs. aquino's failure to put in place the sweeping economic and political reforms she had promised during the 1986 presidential election
we had high hopes when cory aquino said she would be the exact opposite of marcos. but after two years, we have no more hope that she will fulfill her promises,'' crispin beltran, head of the militant may 1st movement labor organization, told the rally
some of the protesters distributed leaflets of the outlawed national democratic front, an umbrella organization of 12 marxist groups, including the communist party of the philippines and its armed wing, the new people's army
the aquino government has betrayed the filipino people's hope for fundamental changes in society after ousting marcos...,'' a leaflet said. it accused the government of incompetence and ``subservience to the u.s.''
the crowd dispersed without incident after about three hours
u.s. ambassador nicholas platt, however, congratulated the aquino government today on molding a democratic government
what we have seen happen in this period is impressive,'' platt said in a statement. ``a constitution has been written and ratified by an overwhelming margin... a new congress has been freely elected and is vigorously functioning. local elections have been held in every province, city and town throughout the philippine archipelago
in these and mnay other ways democracy has been restored in the philippines,'' he said
in other developments, mrs. aquino defended her embattled defense secretary, gen. fidel ramos, and credited him with blocking attempts by renegade military officers to topple her government
she said ``as far as i'm concerned, general (fidel) ramos has proven himself not only now but in the past, especially in his abiding by the constitution. he has not been any part of any coup attempt.''
mrs. aquino made the remark to reporters one day after the wife of a navy captain linked to at least two coup attempts and the assassination of a leftist labor leader hinted that ramos was involved in a november 1986 conspiracy
ramos said that he, in fact, exposed the coup attempt
an unusually well-preserved fossil skull stumbled upon by a graduate student belongs to one of the smallest baleen whales ever known, scientists said
the skull and other parts of the 15-foot whale, believed to be 12 million to 14 million years old and possibly related to modern toothless whales, were found embedded in a sandstone bluff on ano nuevo island, about 19 miles northwest of santa cruz
the 35-pound skull is a ``beautiful specimen,'' said kenneth s. norris, a professor of natural history at the university of california-santa cruz
(it's) one of the best i know of,'' norris, a world authority on whales, said at a news conference tuesday
brian fadley, 26, a uc-santa cruz graduate student, said he spotted the skull as an irregularity in a rock formation last may while visiting ano nuevo island with a group studying elephant seals. a closer look revealed that it was a whale skull
since i didn't have the usual tools of a paleontologist, i modified a rusty pipe to excavate the fossil,'' fadley said
norris said it was unusual to find a cetacean skull with the delicate earbones intact. those tiny bones could help researchers learn how whales and other marine mammals developed their exceptionally acute hearing, he said
the animal itself, 15 feet long and weighing 1,500 pounds, apparently was an adult pygmy baleen whale ``with close linkage to the modern california gray whale,'' norris said. california grays can be as long as 40 feet long and weigh 40 tons
baleen whales, which include the 100-foot blue whale, have no teeth but eat by filtering plankton and tiny crustaceans from seawater with bristly baleen plates attached to their upper jaw. convenes</head> anglo-irish meeting under way. picks up 13th graf pvs, `o fiaich ...</note>
an 18-year-old british soldier was charged today with unlawfully killing an unarmed roman catholic civilian in a case that has further strained tense anglo-irish relations
the soldier, david jonathan holden, appeared at cookstown magistrates court, 25 miles west of belfast, as british and irish leaders met across the border in dublin to discuss the deterioration in relations
in addition to the holden case, tensions have increased because of the disclosure tuesday that another british soldier jailed for murdering an unarmed roman catholic civilian was freed on parole after serving three years
magistrate robert porter ordered holden held in police custody until a court appearance in belfast on march 9. the defense said it would appeal to the high court for bail to be set
holden's attorney said the soldier will plead innocent to the charge of unlawfully killing aidan mcanespie, 23, an election worker for sinn fein, the legal political arm of the outlawed irish republican army
the british army said mcanespie was killed sunday by a ricocheting bullet after a machine gun was fired accidentally from an army observation post at a checkpoint near aughnacloy, half a mile from the border in county tyrone
prime minister margaret thatcher on tuesday rebuked irish prime minister charles haughey's government for ordering its own investigation into the shooting. british officials said they already were investigating
northern ireland secretary tom king paid a courtesy call on haughey in dublin before he joined irish foreign minister brian lenihan and justice minister gerry collins today for a meeting of the anglo-irish conference
the main item on the agenda was proposed british legislation aimed at guaranteeing a fair division of employment between roman catholics and protestants in protestant-dominated northern ireland
before entering the meeting, king said: ``we will be talking about all matters of concern to us both and we shall be having very frank and valuable discussions. this is the value of the anglo-irish agreement. it means we can meet to discuss very difficult issues.''
the anglo-irish agreement, signed in november 1985, gives the irish government a consultative role in the running of northern ireland
the conference was set up as a forum for irish and british ministers to discuss problems in the province, where the ira is fighting to end british rule
on tuesday, security forces ringed aughnacloy for mcanespie's funeral
cardinal tomas o fiaich, roman catholic primate of ireland who broke off a trip to san francisco to attend the funeral, told the congregation mcanespie had been murdered. mcanespie was buried across the border in the irish republic
o fiaich said he has never hesitated to condemn ira killings as murder, adding: ``how can i now avoid using this term `murder' to describe the killing in broad daylight of one of the best known and most highly respected men in this parish?''
anglo-irish relations have been severely strained recently by a series of disputes, principally britain's refusal after a long inquiry to prosecute northern ireland policemen who shot and killed six unarmed catholics in 1982
news that a british soldier sentenced to life in prison for murdering an unarmed roman catholic civilian, thomas reilly, 22, in belfast in 1983 was freed on parole after serving only three years has added to that tension
the british army in a statement tuesday confirmed irish news reports that pvt. ian richard thain, who was jailed for murdering reilly during rioting in belfast on aug. 9, 1983, had been freed on parole in february 1987
thain, 21, said at his trial he thought reilly, road manager of the pop group bananarama, was reaching for a gun, but the judge dismissed his claim
upon hearing of thain's release, reilly's father, james reilly, said: ``it is unbelievable. people talk about british justice but where is it today? our son was never involved in anything. he was murdered.''
eleven men were given prison terms ranging from three years to life for killing two giant pandas, the official xinhua news agency said today
the report said a court in northwest sichuan province, one of the last natural habitats of the endangered species, found the men guilty in two separate incidents of killing the pandas and selling their pelts
it did not say how many of the men were given life terms
in december, another court in sichuan sentenced 26 men to prison terms ranging from two years to life for killing six pandas and selling their skins
only about 1,000 giant pandas still survive in the wild, all in sichuan and neighboring southwest china provinces
although the chinese government has banned panda hunting, the pandas' numbers are believed to have decreased as a result of their low fertility rate, a shortage of the wild bamboo on which they feed and human predators
the meter has expired on penny parking in this western massachusetts town, where selectmen voted to eliminate one-cent meters on two downtown streets to raise more money
selectmen voted tuesday to boost the parking rates on main and federal streets, the two busiest streets in the downtown commercial district, to five cents for 15 minutes, 10 cents for 30 minutes and 20 cents for an hour. motorists will still be able to park on side streets for a penny and a nickel
the new meter heads will also have quarter slots, but 25 cents will still get you only an hour's parking, selectman joseph laurie said
an advisory committee urged the town in january to boost the rates, maintaining it was costing the town of 19,100 people more to collect the pennies than it was getting in meter revenue
the new meters, which officials said should be installed in about two months, are expected to generate an additional $36,000 in revenue annually. the town now gets about $70,000 from its parking meters
programs aimed at helping california's preschool children resist sexual abuse are ineffective and should be phased out, a federally funded study said
the programs are beyond the understanding of such young children, may frighten them away from normal affection and unjustly make them responsible for the behavior of others, researchers said tuesday
the central idea of training the children bears rethinking,'' said neil gilbert, professor of social welfare at the university of california at berkeley
we should not make 4-year-olds responsible for defending themselves,'' said gilbert, who conducted the two-year study for uc-berkeley's family welfare research group
programs that try to train preschool children to recognize and resist sexual abuse reach 42,000 younsters throughout the state
the study of 118 preschoolers in seven counties found that attempts to teach very young children the difference between a ``good touch'' and a ``bad touch'' may confuse them
defining a ``bad touch'' as anything that ``feels bad'' results in children resisting any contact they do not like at the moment, such as grandma's ``yucky'' kiss, uncle ed's scratchy cheek and the tight hug from a well-meaning relative, gilbert said
thus, in the most inclusive view of `bad touch,' children are taught that virtually a pat on the head could be cause for reporting to the authorities,'' the report said
the report also said responsibility for protecting children lies with adults and not with the youngsters themselves
teaching 4-year-olds they must ``take charge to control the outside world ... is an abdication of family and social responsibility'' and a ``sorry message of these times,'' researchers said
however, teaching parents alone will not make children safe from sexual abuse, said pnina tobin, executive director of the san francisco-based children's self-help project, one of the programs studied
it does no good just to (educate) the adults around the child,'' she said. ``what if that adult is the offender? the child is not protected. they must know there are others they can talk to.''
a man who stole a courthouse bailiff's gold bracelet left behind a clue to his identity _ his subpoena in a theft case
police say miguel garcia approached a bailiff at an information booth in the dade county courthouse to explain he could not show up at a thursday hearing on a theft case because he had a conflicting court date on another theft charge
as the bailiff, elisa yepe, leaned over to examine the subpoena, her $525 gold bracelet fell to the floor
garcia picked it up and ran, leaving behind his subpoena, police said
one minute he's asking her for a new trial date, the next minute he pulls this,'' metro-dade officer rick conover said monday. ``either this guy has guts or he's not wrapped too tight.''
police hope to arrest garcia when he shows up for one of his thursday court dates
a sorority formed by lesbians has been officially recognized by ucla, reportedly the first such recognition extended by any u.s. university
the decision allows the nine-member lambda delta lambda to meet on campus and apply for student funds, but university rules forbid exclusion of heterosexual members
it was very validating for us,'' sorority president allison adler said of last week's recognition by the office of fraternity and sorority relations at the university of california, los angeles
although other social and political organizations for homosexual students exist at ucla and other campuses, gay activists said they knew of no other gay-oriented sorority or fraternity that has formal approval from an american college or university to be part of a regulated greek letter system
i think it's fantastic,'' said vernon strickland, a leader of the washington, d.c.-based gay fraternity delta lambda phi. ``i think that means the gentlemen will have no problems getting recognition.''
delta lambda phi is trying to organize chapters at ucla and four other universities. its washington chapter isn't affiliated with any school
i never felt any sentimental attachment to ucla before. but i now feel proud to be a student here,'' lambda delta lambda member julie leverence said this week. ``lambda delta lambda gives me a supportive atmosphere and a connection to the school.''
all nine women members said they are lesbians and said they feel excluded at existing sororities
we are not starting this sorority so we can meet new people to sleep with,'' marci kay said. ``we are starting it because we feel excluded from the greek system now, and that is a network system for friendship and professional careers.''
lambda delta lambda is planning ways to raise money and attract new members, and it is also considering applying for membership in the panhellenic council, which coordinates many inter-sorority events
we don't just want to be separate but equal,'' adler said. ``we want to be equal.''
the chief cuban delegate to the u.n. human rights commission today accused the chief u.s. delegate, a former cuban political prisoner, of lying about his 22 years in custody
raul roa kouri, cuba's deputy foreign minister, called a news conference to answer the allegations of armando valladares, who said he was tortured and temporarily crippled while imprisoned in cuba
he was never beaten, he was never tortured,'' roa said. ``this doesn't happen in cuba.'' he said he called the press conference because ``the credibility of the commission is at stake.''
roa distributed copies of documents that included a purported confidential u.s. state department memo on valladares and cuban arguments against points made in the memo
valladares, named late last year to head the u.s. delegation to the 43-nation human rights commission, has been a u.s. citizen since january 1987. in january 1961, valladares was sentenced to 30 years in prison in cuba. he was freed after 22 years following the intervention of president francois mitterrand of france
valladares gained international attention during his incarceration by writing poetry that he managed to smuggle out of prison
in a book he wrote about his prison years, titled ``against all hope,'' valladares says he was arrested and jailed because he voiced his opposition to communism under cuban leader fidel castro
roa said, ``the book is full of lies, and it is boring.''
roa repeated cuban allegations that valladares was jailed because he belonged to a group that was planning terrorist activities to overthrow the government
he read from what he said was the record of valladares' trial, saying valladares was convicted of ``planning to take up arms with the purpose of overthrowing through violent means the powers of the state.''
the state department says valladares was not charged with terrorism at his trial and that such allegations only arose later
roa alleged that valladares had been a police officer under the government of dictator fulgencio batista, who was ousted in 1959 by castro loyalists, but he said valladares was never penalized for this. he denied that the cubans had charged valladares belonged to batista's secret police
however, a reproduction of an article in the french newspaper le monde in 1983, included in the package of documents distributed by the cuban delegation, quotes castro as saying valladares was a member of the ``gestapo of batista.'' a u.s. spokesman, bill lawrence, said roa was ``lying'' when he said valladares had been a policeman
they keep altering their story every year, trying to make it more acceptable,'' he told the associated press. he said cuba had also at one time accused valladares of being a torturer but that the country now denies having said that. ...'; inserts 1 graf after 13th graf, `solyom reported ...' with mother reportedly goading son into suicide attempt; deletes last 2 grafs to conform to editing changes.</note>
with one lucky rifle shot, a young man troubled by a compulsion to take four-hour showers and wash his hands up to 50 times a day cured his affliction
the man, identified as george, failed in a suicide attempt, but the .22-caliber bullet he fired into his mouth lodged in the lower part of his brain's left frontal lobe, a region believed related to so-called obsessive-compulsive disorder
if it had gone to the center, it would have killed him,'' his psychiatrist, leslie solyom, said tuesday. ``if it had gone to the right, it would have had no effect.''
victims of obsessive-compulsive disorder, like george, suffer from extreme hesitation and doubtfulness, solyom said. ``they hesitate so much that after closing the door they are not really certain they closed the door, so they have to go back again and again.''
george was nearly 18 when he fired the bullet into his brain. ``he was found lying on his face, blood oozing from his nostrils,'' said solyom, who practices at shaughnessy hospital in vancouver, british columbia
george recovered from the shooting in three weeks. ``we started on behavior therapy,'' solyom said. ``but he was no longer obsessive.''
it was the only change that solyom could find
his i.q. did not change. there was no change personality-wise. he did not become an automaton. his symptoms are gone,'' solyom said
before the suicide attempt, george washed his hands as often as 50 times a day. he would take four-hour showers, and would check and re-check to see whether doors and windows were locked and whether he had enough money in his wallet
when he pulled the trigger, george may have in effect given himself a lobotomy
or, more precisely, a leukotomy _ a severing of the links between the frontal lobes and other parts of the brain, rather than a removal of brain tissue as in a lobotomy
in the '40s and '50s, psychosurgeons would get these patients and have reasonably good results cutting the pathway between the front part of the brain and a part called the striatum,'' said dr. thomas insel, a psychiatrist at the national institute of mental health in bethesda, md. such surgery has fallen out of favor as effective drugs have been found
insel, who has specialized in this disorder, said sophisticated brain images called pet scans show that the frontal lobes are more active in obsessive-compulsive patients than in normal people. that suggests that the source of the disorder lies at least partly in the frontal lobes, he said
solyom reported george's case in the december issue of the british journal of psychiatry. a short report of that study appears this week in a newsletter for doctors called physician's weekly, which describes the suicide attempt as ``successful radical surgery.''
solyom said george was goaded into the suicide attempt several years ago by his mother. ``she said, `so look george, if your life is so wretched, just go and shoot yourself,''' solyom said
dr. judith rapoport, also of the national institute of mental health, said that george's accident is reminiscent of the incident early in this century that led to the discovery of the frontal lobotomy
a massachusetts railroad worker named phineas gage suffered an accident in which a piece of a crowbar became lodged in his head, she said. the crowbar was removed. ``amazingly he survived,'' she said
in those days, the risk of infection was high. what was remarkable was his personality change. he became a happy-go-lucky bum who sang for his supper and wandered. and somebody studied this.'' gage had had the first lobotomy
some 20,000 customers have asked southwestern bell telephone to block access to 976 phone numbers, including 8,000 who called bell in one day requesting the free service
the 976 system has drawn criticism from parents and citizen groups because some 976 lines offer sexually explicit messages. in some cases, children have made numerous calls to the services, racking up large phone bills for their parents. businesses also face problems with employees making calls and billing the company
eight thousand calls were received tuesday, the first day southwestern bell offered to block access to dial 976 for free, company spokesman dave lopez said. the other calls were made before bell began running notices in local newspapers, he said
the 20,000 requests represent less than 1 percent of the 3.5 million phone lines in four cities where 976 service is availble _ dallas, fort worth, houston and san antonio, lopez said
the public service commission authorized bell to block the calls for free last week following hearings in austin
the chairman of president reagan's aids commission called today for spending an additional $2 billion to fight the disease among drug abusers
retired navy adm. james d. watkins proposed that half of the money should be in federal funds with the rest coming from state and local sources
the additional $1 billion in federal spending called for in the chairman's recommendations to the full 13-member commission would nearly double the total $1.3 billion reagan requested for all aids education and research in the budget he submitted last week
but watkins told reporters only 15 percent of the nation's estimated 1.3 million intravenous drug abusers are in treatment plans, with long waiting lists in many cities for people seeking help in kicking drugs
anyone crying for help should get help on demand,'' watkins said
moreover, he said, the sharply higher spending on drug treatment must be a ``sustained emphasis. you cannot just throw in some money one year and drop it out next year.''
although male homosexuals still make up the largest percentage of people with aids, health officials have determined that the disease is spreading most rapidly now among intravenous drug abusers and their sexual partners
watkins' recommendations go to the full commission for action monday; the panel expects to present an interim report to the president the following week
the former chief of naval operations acknowledged that his recommendation for sharply higher spending on drug treatment programs might spark controversy by opening the way for criticism of the administration for not doing more in that area
but he expessed confidence the full commission would adopt that and most of his other recommendations for an interim report and said, ``it is not in our charter to worry about the political impact.''
asked his reaction to the likelihood that presidential candidates, particularly democrats, would use his recommendations to ``zing the white house,'' watkins replied:
how do you avoid politicizing something in an election year. if they all adopt this and say `let's get on with it,' that's the kind of politization i like.''
watkins' proposal on drug treatment calls specifically for adding 32,000 drug abuse treatment specialists and said 3,300 new treatment facilities may have to be added
in other areas, watkins called for more financial support for the food and drug administration to double the number of scientists reviewing aids-related products and a program of direct grants to community-based drug testing programs
he also made a number of recommendations in the health care area, including more training for doctors
many physicians are severely lacking in knowledge about aids and there are signs that medical schools have not yet built up a curriculum to educate doctors about aids treatment,'' watkins said
the interim report will not include any recommendations on the controversial areas of aids testing, discrimination against people testing positive for the virus and other social and legal aspects
to try to adopt recommendations in those areas would result in the commission's being ``at loggerheads with ourselves'' at this time
but he said hearings on those topics are scheduled next month in nashville and promised the panel would not shy away from addressing them in its final report june 24. abortion sketchy; picks up 8th graf, `rentz, a ...'; insert 2 grafs after 18th graf, ``according to ...'' with suspect having set up family counseling service.</note>
a woman apparently kidnapped a 5-week-old baby because she had an abortion recently, authorities said after they returned the infant to her ecstatic mother
maritza rentz, a 38-year-old psychotherapist arrested tuesday, was being held today on $8,000 bond for investigation of second-degree kidnapping in the abduction of 5-week-old rachael ann white, police said
rachael ann was found at mrs. rentz' home a day after the girl's mother issued a nationwide plea for the baby's safe return
rachael ann had been kidnapped from her home friday by a woman answering a babysitting ad, police said
it appears it was a replacement baby,'' said police lt. joe vernier
mrs. rentz gave a statement to police saying she told her husband when he came home from work friday that she had had a baby that day by caesarian section, said police capt. vic morris
investigators said they did not know how long mrs. rentz was pregnant when the abortion was performed on oct. 27 for medical reasons. details were sketchy, but apparently doctors decided she couldn't bring the baby to term, police said
police also have not determined whether air force capt. paul rentz was aware his wife's pregnancy was terminated
rentz, a 36-year-old clinical psychologist and behavioral science instructor at the air force academy, was being questioned, authorities said
rachael ann's mother, cora abbott, was elated after being reunited with her baby
i thought i loved her all i could until this happened, but now i know i love her even more,'' said abbott, who was at work at a pizza parlor when the abduction occurred
of mrs. rentz, she said: ``i feel very sorry for her, that she'd have to do something like this. but i'm angry. i still don't understand it.''
the woman who kidnapped the baby matched mrs. rentz's description ``like a mirror,'' said deputy police chief pat mcelderry
the woman was applying for a babysitting position at the home of rachael's ann's grandmother, ethel reed. reed gave the child to the woman while she went to answer the telephone; when she returned, the woman had fled with the child, authorities said
a tip led police to the rentzes, morris said. air force maj. bruce yeager, a neighbor in the subdivision where the rentzes moved last summer, said he became suspicous after he and his wife saw the baby and thought it did not look newborn. he said he contacted air force academy police
investigators went to the home tuesday as rentz was leaving for work in a car that matched a description of the car police were seeking in the abduction, authorities said
police found the baby in a crib and were shown a false birth certificate with ``penrose hospital'' handwritten on a gold seal, police said
but after an fbi agent looked at the child's navel and noticed the umbilical cord knot was gone _ an indication the baby was older than four days _ mrs. rentz was arrested, authorities said
mrs. rentz came into her office at about 9 a.m. friday, but stayed only about 30 minutes, said receptionist meda frye
according to police documents, friends were told mrs. rentz had given birth at 9:42 that morning. she said her baby was named aurora helen rentz
on oct. 31, shortly after she lost her own baby, mrs. rentz put an ad in a newspaper offering her services as a counselor. her business cards referred to her as a psychotherapist offering ``parent-child consultations,'' said the colorado springs gazette telegraph
a month later, on dec. 1, she set up a family counseling practice, the newspaper said
dr. john mcdonald, a university of colorado criminal psychiatrist, said women who kidnap babies often have lost a child of their own
the need to have a baby is so great, they don't really face up to what they are doing, or they convince themselves that what they are doing is right,'' he said
a claim that fallout from the chernobyl nuclear accident may have caused deaths in the united states is highly unlikely and based on an erroneous statistical analysis, scientists say
a researcher, jay gould, said he found an unexplained jump in the nation's deaths in the months following the chernobyl accident
however, the amount of radiation that reached the united states is so small that the notion is ``not credible,'' harvard radiation expert edward webster said tuesday
webster, who serves on a united nations committee studying health effects of chernobyl, called the hypothesis ``a mechanism which most knowledgeable radiobiologists would throw out because of the very low doses involved.''
a federal health statistics official says no mysterious increase in deaths occurred
gould said he will present his work thursday at a meeting on radiation and the immune system in west germany
gould, a fellow of the institute for policy studies in washington, says federal statistics show an unexplained jump of maybe 20,000 to 40,000 deaths in the nation for may through august of 1986, following the soviet accident in april
radioactive fallout from chernobyl is ``the only explanation we've been able to develop,'' gould said in a recent interview
the hypothesis, which he stressed was not proven, is that fallout reaching the united states encouraged formation of ``free radicals,'' chemically reactive molecules that can damage cells. these molecules, the hypothesis continues, may have weakened the immune systems of some people enough to make them vulnerable to fatal diseases
gould said slightly more than 33 percent of all 1986 deaths occurred in may through august, up from the average of about 32 percent for the three prior years and the highest percentage since 1900
increases appeared among people older than 65 and those who suffered from infectious diseases, including pneumonia, he said
the study also looked at peak concentrations of iodine-131, a radioactive component of fallout, reported in milk during the summer of 1986. gould said that among the nation's nine census regions, higher concentrations were associated with greater increases in mortality for the summer of 1986 compared to the previous summer
the study's data on deaths came from the national center for health statistics. but harry rosenberg, chief of the center's mortality statistics branch, said tuesday his analysis found no inexplicable jump in deaths
we didn't see anything that departs from the historic pattern,'' he said
his numbers are not consistent with the numbers that are adjusted to represent the united states as a whole.''
rosenberg also said 1986 had the lowest death rate ever recorded for the nation, when the population's changing age composition is taken into account
neal nelson, a radiation biologist for the u.s. environmental protection agency, said he was skeptical of the chernobyl hypothesis after starting to study information gould sent him
the maximum dose of chernobyl radiation in the united states was only about 1 percent of the normal background exposure, he said
people eat radioactive material constantly, from natural and man-made sources, so ``there is nothing unique'' about swallowing the tiny amounts of radioactive iodine from chernobyl fallout, he said
the supreme court today expanded the power of communities to impose rent controls, ruling that hardships to tenants may be considered when landlords seek rent increases
by a 6-2 vote, the justices upheld a san jose, calif., ordinance that has been attacked as a ``robin hood'' law that steals from the rich to pay the poor
while some 200 cities nationwide have rent control laws, the san jose hardship provision appears to be unique. landlord groups have said other communities now may adopt similar laws
chief justice william h. rehnquist, in his opinion for the court, said landlords failed to prove that the ordinance deprived them of the value of their property without just compensation
he rejected the landlords' claim that the city unlawfully is seeking to alleviate hardships for tenants by imposing financial burdens on the property owners
we have long recognized that a legitimate and rational goal of price or rate regulation is the protection of consumer welfare,'' rehnquist said. the ordinance ``represents a rational attempt to accommodate the conflicting interests of protecting tenants from burdensome rent increases while at the same time ensuring that landlords are guaranteed a fair return of their investment.''
today's decision does not rule out all challenges to such oridinances. but rehnquist said to win their case landlords at least must show actual losses suffered because communities lowered rents to lessen tenants' hardships
there was no such evidence in the san jose case, rehnquist said
rehnquist also noted that rent controls are based on the idea that without them housing shortages would permit landlords to gouge renters
the impact of the san jose ordinance has been muted, at least temporarily, because vacancy rates have been around 8 percent with the downturn in the local high-technology economy. that has made it less likely that landlords, concerned about losing tenants, will increase rents sufficiently to prompt challenges based on hardship
justices antonin scalia and sandra day o'connor dissented today
scalia, writing for both, said the tenant hardship provision takes private property without just compensation in violation of the constitution
scalia denounced ``the unfairness of making one citizen pay, in some fashion other than taxes, to remedy a social problem that is none of his creation.''
the san jose law generally permits annual rent increases of 8 percent on residential property. but if the landlord seeks more than that, it opens the way for challenge by ``hardship'' tenants who are defined as earning less than 80 percent of the median income for the area
the landlords said that means individuals making $34,000 a year can qualify as hardship cases
the ordinance, passed in 1979, provides a hearing before a city officer to determine if a challenged rent increase is too great
the increase can be rolled back even below 8 percent for hardship tenants if the hearing officer decides a smaller increase is justified. the landlord still would receive an increase of 5 percent plus enough to cover capital improvements and increased rehabilitation, maintenance and other costs
no landlord in san jose alleged that the law actually has been implemented to deprive owners of their property's full value
landlords challenged the law's constitutionality shortly after it was adopted. they said the ordinance, in effect, is a robin hood statute that requires them to assume the public burden of subsidizing low-income tenants
the california supreme court, reversing rulings by lower courts, upheld the ordinance by a 4-3 vote in 1986
justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the u.s. supreme court last thursday, did not take part in today's decision
the case is pennell vs. san jose, 86-753
a civic panel recommending policy guidelines to the president called on the government to apologize for the military's bloody suppression of a civil uprising in the city of kwangju, members said today
the committee for the promotion of democracy and national reconciliation also said the government should compensate victims of the 1980 revolt, said panel members
by official count, at least 191 people were killed and more than 800 were wounded in the nine-day uprising in the southern city of kwangju. dissident sources say the casualty figure was much higher
president-elect roh tae-woo set up the 56-member committee after winning the dec. 16 presidential elections, saying he needed ``policy guidelines'' reflecting the opinions of broad sections of the society
the committee called on the roh government, to be inaugurated thursday, to make an open apology for the kwangju incident and compensate its victims
the committee also urged roh to declare a human rights charter in a bid to show his determination to support civil rights
the committee said a government apology is needed because harsh military suppression was partly blamed for the anti-government uprising, the worst in modern korean history
the kwangju incident is a touchy political issue involving roh and his predecessor, chun doo-hwan, who seized power with military backing in 1980. they are known to have played a key part in the military suppression of the uprising
the united states has also been criticized for its alleged part in the military suppression of the kwangju uprising. government critics have alleged that the top u.s. commander in seoul permitted some south korean army units under his operational control to help crush the kwangju revolt
the united states has denied the allegations
