a triumphant bob dole headed for southern campaign territory today with two republican midwest victories in hand, proclaiming ``it's a lot more fun winning.'' george bush dismissed his losses, saying ``you can't win them all.''
dole racked up solid victories in minnesota's presidential caucuses and south dakota's primary while bush finished third in south dakota and last in minnesota
in portland, maine, bush said his poor showings were ``somewhat anticipated.''
you can't go everywhere,'' he told reporters. ``... you can't win them all.''
jack kemp, with dismal finishes in both states, took solace in bush's equally poor showings
i think last night proved the race is wide open. that's all i really needed,'' kemp said in beaufort, s.c. ``i needed to break up the idea that this is a bush-dole race.''
dole was campaigning today in south carolina, which holds its primary march 5, three days before the 20-state super tuesday contest
a week ago, dole lost the new hampshire primary to bush. a week before that, bush lost the iowa caucuses to dole, finishing behind former television evangelist pat robertson
robertson, who ran second to dole in minnesota and south dakota, said he was ``simply delighted'' with his showing in south dakota. but he conceded he had hoped for a victory in minnesota, where he built a strong organization
this helps me enormously as i go into the super tuesday states,'' robertson said today in atlanta. ``i am very pleased with what i'm seeing. i believe that coming out of super tuesday i will be the acknowledged front-runner of the republican party with delegates.''
bush, who had bypassed campaigning in the two states, went to bed in kentucky without commenting to reporters on the returns. dole, for his part, was anything but silent
i hope we send a message that bob dole has a message,'' the kansas senator told cheering backers at a victory celebration in minneapolis. ``that's what the election is all about. i haven't changed my message. i'm talking about the future, i've talked about leadership, i've talked about party responsibility, i've talked about the left-outs, the down-and-outs in america.''
returns from all but one precinct in south dakota gave dole 55 percent, robertson 20 percent, bush 19 percent and kemp 5 percent
in minnesota, with returns in from 80 percent of the precincts, dole had 42 percent, robertson 28 percent, kemp 15 and bush 11
kemp was in a do-or-die effort to make a competitive showing in one of the midwest states. on the last weekend of the campaign, kemp inundated south dakota with biographical television commercials that emphasized family values and he spent most of the weekend campaigning in minnesota. but he spent the election night in south carolina, unavailable to reporters
in minnesota, the first order of business in the gop caucuses was a non-binding straw poll of presidential preference
robertson startled party regulars in the iowa caucuses with a strong second-place finish, well ahead of bush. the former evangelist saw minnesota as a similar situation and he hoped to repeat his iowa performance
barb sykora, chairman of the minnesota republican party, had predicted a lot of people would attend caucuses for the first time
i think there are going to be a lot of people coming for pat robertson and for bob dole,'' she said
where is george bush?'' taunted dole during campaign appearances in south dakota and minnesota
why vote for someone who doesn't come to the state?'' the kansas senator asked an audience in minneapolis, on the final full day of campaigning
as usual, party officials were unable to project the turnout for robertson because so many of his supporters were newcomers to republican politics
kemp's best showing so far in the race going into tuesday's contests was third place in the new hampshire primary, well behind bush and dole. the new york congressman hoped a strong showing in minnesota would give his campaign renewed energy
