honolulu advertiser on withdrawal of bruce babbitt and pete du pont:
both (bruce) babbitt and (pete) du pont bowed out before most voters could really assess them
but either is probably in a good position for a cabinet post or the like, depending on whose party wins in november
and they deserve credit for bringing up issues that expanded the scope of the campaign in its early period
sen. paul simon, battered in the early democratic contests, said today he is bypassing the march 8 super tuesday primaries and caucuses because he does ``not have the resources for winning'' them
but the illinois democrat said he was not dropping out of the race and would continue to campaign to win his home state primary on march 15 and the contests in the states that follow
the campaign will begin anew after super tuesday, starting in illinois,'' simon told a news conference
simon was dealt a crippling blow tuesday when he finished far behind massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and was trailing jesse jackson in minnesota's caucuses. he came in a distant fourth in the south dakota primary behind rep. richard gephardt of missouri, dukakis and albert gore jr
last week after coming in third in the new hampshire primary, simon said he would withdraw if he did not finish first in either minnesota or south dakota. he later backed off that statement
faced with primaries and caucuses in 20 states and american samoa on march 8, simon said he cannot raise the money to match the big warchests of dukakis and gore in the region
there is no sense in my fooling myself,'' the illinois democrat said. ``we just don't have the money.''
his campaign plunged into debt before the new hampshire primary, but he has been talking of close to half a million dollars gathered in the past two weeks
we have had record-breaking fund-raising,'' simon declared. ``monday, for example, $137,000 came in. we never had a day like that before. but you take $137,000 and then look at 20 states and what it would cost for a media buy, and you're talking about something that is nowhere near adequate.''
simon also said he had made the judgment that march 8 will not settle the race and that the battle for the 1988 democratic presidential nomination will go to the convention in atlanta in july
super tuesday is likely to result in a very mixed picture,'' he said. ``phase one of the selection process ends on march 8. ... but we do not have the resources for winning in the super tuesday states.''
phase two of the selection process begins march 15. i shall use phase two to deliver the message that we must become a nation with leadership characterized by compassion and vision and common sense. it is on to atlanta with that message.''
simon is on the ballot in all the super tuesday primaries, but he said he will do little or no campaigning in those states _ except for the nationally televised debates that are a major feature of the next two weeks
i'm not writing off the south. i want my friends there to vote for me,'' he said. ``i'm realistic about resources. i simply cannot do everything.''
dukakis and gephardt have split the four major democratic contests so far. and simon said he had concluded the party will not have a certain winner going into the atlanta convention
he cited ``growing evidence that for the first time in recent history there will be no first-ballot winner at the democratic convention.''
simon's best day so far was in iowa on feb. 8, where he finished a very close second to gephardt. he was third in new hampshire
he talked to reporters after a speech to the united auto workers at a washington hotel
the kremlin's attempt to bring 100 nationalities under one communist umbrella has been difficult in the southern caucasus mountain region, where dozens of ethnic groups strive to assert their identity far from the seat of soviet power
about 50 different nationalities have been identified in the caucasus area, some represented only by a few thousand individuals largely isolated amid the remote mountain valleys. the main peoples of the region are the azeris, georgians and armenians, all of whom have their own soviet republics
armenians drew attention this week because of demonstrations in their capital, yerevan, and in a small adjoining area that is part of azerbaidzhan. thousands of demonstrators in yerevan demanded that the area, the nagorno-karabakh region, be made part of armenia
nagorno-karabakh is a microcosm of the inconsistencies of soviet nationality policy. its population of 157,000 was 81 percent armenian and just 18 percent azeri, but the region was made part of azerbaidzhan in 1923 after having been deeded to armenia when it became part of the soviet union in 1920
the caucasus residents tend to be fiercely independent, bristling at attempts by the soviet union's dominant ethnic group, the russians, to interfere with their languages, customs and religions
in armenia, the most bitter fuel to nationalist passions occurred while turkey controlled western armenia in 1915. more than a million armenians are believed to have died or been massacred when turkey deported the local population
other armenian nationalism stems from religious beliefs, which are discouraged by the communist party government. patriarch vazgen i of the armenian church said in an interview at church headquarters in etchmiadzin last year that the majority of armenians are believers and that more than half of newborns are christened
the region's turmoil has led many armenians to leave their homeland, settling principally either in other parts of the soviet union or in the united states. armenian emigration to the united states approaches 1,000 per month
to the north, georgians say they have been more successful than their caucasus neighbors at resisting ``russification'' because they tend to stick close to home, limiting assimilation. but georgian students protested by the thousands in 1979 when the republic's government tried to change the official language to russian
georgians' spirit of independence is reflected in their business dealings. they are known for doing a brisk business growing produce in georgia's mediterranean-like climate and selling them in areas where supply is scare
azerbaidzhan's wealth traditionally was the oil found in its capital, baku, on the caspian sea. but oil production has dropped, causing economic problems in the republic
ethnic tensions have surfaced in areas of azerbaidzhan with large populations of armenians. in addition to nagorno-karabakh, demonstrators have also asserted armenian national rights in the village of chardakhlu. the village was the scene in october of a clash between native azeris and long-time armenian residents
there also is a sizable moslem population in azerbaidzhan, which is officially tolerated by the kremlin but serves as yet another wedge between the republic's people and the russian-dominated moscow government
given the choice, more than one out of every four west german women would ditch their husband before giving up their best friend, a magazine survey said wednesday
a survey by the journal for women magazine also reported that 86.5 percent of the women asked said they willingly accepted criticisms from their best female friends
according to the magazine, 26 percent of the women surveyed said they would give up their husbands before their best female friends
but in the end the men won out, with 71 percent of the women saying they would give up their best friends to keep their husbands, while three percent were undecided, the magazine said
the hamburg-based magazine did not say how many women took part in the survey. student body.</note>
about 100 hampshire college students occupied a dormitory office for a second day in a protest over racism and marched across campus today to present a list of 12 demands to the college president
the group then withdrew to the dakin house office they seized tuesday morning and said they did not plan to meet again with president adele simmons until 9 a.m. thursday
the protesters deliberately delayed negotiations, said penny predmas, a junior from new york city
we are building our sense of our community, so we can feel invincible,'' she said
the protesters were escorted across campus by about 100 students, who snaked through a classroom building and a building housing administrative offices chanting, ``one, two, three, four. racism has got to go.''
among the protesters' demands were additional library materials dealing with third world nations, establishment of a college policy on racial harassment, a full-time adviser for minority students, a permanent meeting place for non-white students, a minority recruitment week each semester, and no retaliatory actions against the protesters
about a dozen white supporters pitched tents and staged an overnight vigil outside dakin house, and students from nearby amherst, mount holyoke and smith colleges as well as the university of massachusetts joined the demonstraters this morning
a week ago about 125 minority students at the university of massachusetts began a six-day occupation at a building there
the problems are the same, although the sizes of the minority communities are different,'' said hampshire freshman anita fearman of los angeles
there's a general feeling here that we've been more or less pushed under the rug,'' said ms. fearman, who is black
although there have been racial attacks at the university of massachusetts, there have been none at hampshire, which lists 100 minority students among its 1,100 undergraduates. but minorities complained of verbal harassment and a lack of attention to third world issues
we have been to the administration several times over the past three years with our demands and concerns and nothing has been done,'' premdas said. ``it's been all lip service. it seemed this was the only way to get something done.''
here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken wednesday by the supreme court

falwell-hustler

the court overturned a $200,000 award won by evangelist jerry falwell against hustler magazine and its publisher larry flynt, extending the legal protections for parody and satire, even when they are pornographic
the court unanimously ruled that even pornographic spoofs about a public figure enjoy the free-speech protections of the constitution's first amendment if those spoofs could not reasonably have been interpreted as stating actual facts about the person
the case is hustler vs. falwell, 86-1278

rent controls

the court expanded the power of communities to impose rent controls, ruling that hardships to tenants may be considered when landlords seek rent increases
by a 6-2 vote, the justices upheld a san jose, calif., ordinance that has been attacked as a ``robin hood'' law that steals from the rich to pay the poor
the case is pennell vs. san jose, 86-753

entrapment

the court broadened protection for criminal defendants who claim they were enticed by law enforcement officials into committing a crime
by a 6-2 vote, the justices overturned a bribery conviction against frederick mathews of milwaukee, wis., a former small business administration official
the case is mathews vs. u.s., 86-6109

defendant's testimony

the court made it a bit easier for prosecutors to talk to criminal trial juries about a defendant's failure to testify
in splintered voting, the court reinstated the mail fraud conviction of a man who prosecutors say set his tennessee home afire so he could file a false insurance claim
the case is u.s. vs. robinson, 86-937

default judgment

the court bolstered the right default-judgment losers have to challenge a judgment entered after they fail to respond to a lawsuit
the justices unanimously ruled for a houston businessman in his challenge of a default judgment awarded against him six years ago for a $5,000 debt owed to a medical center
the case is peralta vs. heights medical center, 86-1430

lawyers fees

the court ruled that federal judges lack authority to order the government to pay fees to lawyers who successfully obtain overdue federal welfare for poor people who are aged, blin or disabled
the 8-0 ruling in a case from arkansas held that federal officials are not required by law to withhold a portion of a recipient's benefits to pay the attorney
the case is bowen vs. galbreath, 86-1146. ``security sources...'' edits to trim and conform.</note>
angry palestinians today lynched an arab who they apparently suspected of collaborating with the israelis, stringing him up on a utility pole after he went on a shooting spree that killed a 4-year-old boy and wounded 13 other people, security sources said
israel radio called the incident in a west bank village ``a serious escalation'' of the unrest in the occupied territories and linked it to the palestine liberation organization's calls to deal with collaborators
the dead man's identity was not immediately known
details were sketchy concerning the incident in qabatiye, near jenin, 60 miles north of jerusalem. however, israel radio said the violence began when hundreds of residents marched to the man's house, threw firebombs and setting it afire
security sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the man shot into the crowd, which apparently suspected him of collaborating with israeli authorities, killing the boy and wounding the others
israel radio said the crowd then dragged the man away and hanged him. security sources confirmed the report
an army spokesman said soldiers arrived after the hanging. according to the united nations, 63 arabs have been killed, most by soldiers, since the wave of unrest began dec. 8 in the occupied territories
a general strike gripped the west bank and gaza strip today as businesses shut down and arab workers stayed home in response to a call for stepped up protests before secretary of state george p. shultz arrives
also today, the army reported what it said may be the first armed attack against the military in the past 2{ months of unrest in the territories seized by israel in the 1967 middle east war
an army spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a bomb exploded on a road near gaza as a vehicle was passing tuesday night and shots were fired. there were no injuries
extra-tight security arrangements went into effect today at ben gurion airport in advance of shultz's arrival thursday. airport police said riot police units were called in and will stay on duty through tuesday as shultz conducts his shuttle mission in the middle east
in the gaza strip today, few people were on the streets and only one or two cars were seen moving. most arab laborers stayed away from their jobs in israel, there was little public transport, and there were reports of a few scattered tire-burning and stone-throwing incidents
much of the west bank was dusted white with a thin layer of snow that fell overnight and some arab youths in a jerusalem neighborhood threw snowballs at passing cars, a relief from the stone-throwing of previous days
business was at a standstill today. there was little traffic and few workers left home, according to army radio
the underground national leadership of the uprising, in leaflets distributed throughout the territories, called for a general strike today and thursday
shultz is coming to israel to launch a new peace initiative he hopes will put an end to the violence of past weeks, bring the arabs and israelis to the negotiating table and eventually achieve an overall solution to the mideast conflict
the secretary of state has acknowledged he has only a slim chance of accomplishing that goal during his visit. the shultz initiative, which includes trading territory for peace, is likely to encounter opposition from prime minister yitzhak shamir's likud bloc
deputy prime minister david levy, interviewed on army radio, said on tuesday the new initiative contradicts the 10-year-old camp david agreement
there is confusion in it and an attempt to sell it to israel as camp david and to sell it to the arabs that will give them almost all of the west bank and gaza,'' he said
the plo has prohibited local palestinians from meeting shultz. fayez abu rahme, a gaza lawyer who was among a group of arabs who met with a u.s. official on saturday, said: ``as far as we are concerned there won't be a meeting.''
david good, spokesman for the u.s. consulate in jerusalem, said he did not know if palestinians will meet with shultz
informed u.s. sources said shultz would not meet with palestinians outside jerusalem. ``we're not taking directions from the plo on how to meet with palestinians,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity
president reagan's proposed cuts in programs to help the poor keep warm in the winter and cool in the summer will cause ``pain, stress and homelessness,'' a congressional report said wednesday
a proposed $518.3 million cut in federal energy assistance for the poor in reagan's fiscal 1989 budget would drop to 13 percent the eligible heating and cooling expenses covered by the program, which provides assistance to 6.7 million households, rep. howard wolpe, d-mich., said in releasing the study by the northeast midwest institute
in 1981, the year reagan took office, federal energy assistance for the poor covered nearly 25 percent of eligible heating and cooling expenses, wolpe said
the considerable erosion of federal support is all the more shocking considering the fact that `eligible costs' represent only about 40 percent of a recipient's energy bill,'' wolpe said
the declining funding for the program, an outgrowth of the oil crises of the 1970s, comes amid a background of rising energy costs, the study said
in 1981 the nation spent $7.47 billion on heating and cooling, and in 1988 the cost likely will be $9.67 billion, the study said
many poor families in this country are threatened with the loss of their home heating and other basic utility services because they cannot afford to pay their bills,'' the study said. ``as a visible result, the nation's poor experience a high level of pain, stress and homelessness.''
the program ``is grossly and tragically underfunded,'' said sen. john heinz, r-pa., the co-chairman of the coalition. ``both the administration and the congress are to blame _ the administration for failing to honor its long-stated commitment to the safety net, and congress for acquiescing.''
heinz and wolpe said they oped to stave off further cuts in the program and to roll back last year's 16 percent reduction in funding
the institute is a policy group formed by senators and representatives from the northeast and midwest
mayor tom young is asking a federal judge to order former mayor lee alexander and the people who bribed him to pay $1.5 million in restitution to the city
in a letter to u.s. district judge thomas a. mcavoy and u.s. probation officer frank waterson, young asked that the city be named a victim of alexander's extortion-kickback scheme in the pre-sentence report now being prepared
if that request is rejected, the city may sue alexander and five or more local businessmen who paid bribes for city contracts, young said tuesday
if your household was robbed of cash and valuable jewels and the thieves were found, along with some of the loot they stole, who'd receive the stolen cash and jewels? obviously the owner of the home,'' young said
i'm head of the household. we're requesting that what's been stolen from this household be returned to it.''
waterson declined to comment specifically about the alexander case, but he said consideration of restitution to the victim of any crime is a matter commonly brought up during sentencing
alexander and nine others who pleaded guilty to federal charges of racketeering, tax evasion and conspiracy will be sentenced march 10 and 11. the charges stemmed from a probe by the fbi and internal revenue service into corruption during alexander's tenure as mayor from 1970 to 1986
the administration believes the city was a victim, and we're doing the best we can to recover as much of the assets as possible,'' said syracuse corporation counsel frank harrigan
the city is asking for a portion of the money alexander has returned to the federal government, as well as restitution from the ex-mayor and his associates, harrigan said
alexander already has surrendered $1.4 million in cash, bonds and coins to the federal government
the ex-mayor could be sentenced up to 30 years in prison, but the u.s. attorney will recommend a term of 10 years
federal authorities have said they will administer a lie detector test to alexander next week to determine if he is withholding any other illegally gained assets
the nation's record trade deficit began to shrink in the final three months of 1987 as u.s. exports climbed 6 percent to record levels, the commerce department said wednesday
while narrowing just $200 million from the summer, the decline of the trade deficit to $40.2 billion on a balance-of-payments basis marked the first quarterly improvement since the spring of 1986
we have a genuine export boom going on and i think a lot of people are are pleasantly surprised,'' said robert ortner, undersecretary of commerce for economic affairs
ortner said further improvements were likely in the months ahead at present levels of the dollar, which he said appears to have stabilized in foreign exchange markets
still, the year finished with a record $159.3 billion balance-of-payments trade deficit for all of 1987, the report said
in terms of volume alone, the trade deficit actually showed a 5 percent improvement from 1986 to 1987. the fact that import prices rose more rapidly than export prices helped mask this improvement, commerce department analysts said
the new figures confirmed an end-of-year narrowing of the trade shortfall that already had shown up in the department's monthly merchandise trade reports. the earlier figures showed a $43 billion deficit for the fourth quarter and a $171.2 shortfall for all of 1987
wednesday's figures were smaller because they subtracted factors such as the cost of shipping, insurance and military sales from the monthly numbers. the balance-of-payments deficit is also adjusted for seasonal variations; the monthly figures are not
the october-december deficit was down from the $40.4 billion deficit sustained in the third quarter. that figure was revised upward from the $38.9 billion originally reported
exports, buoyed by a weakening exchange value of the dollar, increased $3.9 billion, or 6 percent, to a record $69.1 billion
imports also rose to a record $109.2 billion in the fourth quarter, but the increase of 4 percent or $3.8 billion was smaller than that for exports
the report was cited by analysts as further evidence that exchange-rate changes since 1985 finally are helping to trim the trade deficit
the dollar is worth just 50 percent of its mid-l985 value against japanese and key european currencies, a devaluation that is making imports more expensive to u.s. consumers while making american goods cheaper and more competitive abroad
the trend has changed. exports will continue to grow and i think you will see a major decline in imports in the first, second and third quarters of this year. the biggest surprise of 1988 will be the narrowing of the trade deficit,'' said jay goldinger, chief economist for capital insight, a los angeles bond brokerage
during the fourth quarter, the trade deficit with japan increased $1.3 billion to $15 billion; the deficit with western europe was up $1.5 billion to $8.2 billion, and the shortfall with canada rose $100 million to $1.8 billion
in the same period, the deficit with the newly industrialized countries in the far east _ taiwan, south korea, hong kong and singapore _ fell $2 billion to $8.1 billion
non-petroleum imports increased $5.3 billion, or 6 percent, to $98.1 billion in the fourth quarter. passenger cars from canada were up 52 percent, a $1 billion increase. auto imports from all other countries, including japan, fell by 7 percent, or $700 million
petroleum imports decreased $1.5 billion, or 12 percent, to $11.1 billion. both prices and volume were down
on exports, non-agricultural shipments of u.s. products increased $4.5 billion, or 8 percent, to $61.3 billion. among the largest increases were machinery, up $2.1 billion or 12 percent, and automotive products to canada, up $1 billion or 21 percent
however, agricultural exports fell during the quarter by $600 million, or 7 percent, to $7.7 billion
if ``constant'' dollars were used, subtracting the effects of inflation since 1982, the trade deficit would show a $1.2 billion decline in the fourth quarter, to $41.4 billion. for the year, the deficit would have shown a decline to $168.6 billon, from a hypothetical $177.4 billion constant-dollar deficit in 1986
the commerce department will use the figures to calculate an even broader measure of trade, the current account deficit, which measures not only trade between countries in merchandise, but also in services, primarily investment earnings and transfer payments such as foreign aid
the state department of motor vehicles today revoked the driver's license of a man who was driving the car that killed a black man in the howard beach racial assault case
dmv officials said the order against dominic blum's license would take effect march 10. blum would be eligible to apply to have the license reinstated after 30 days, said dmv spokesman r. bryan jackson
blum's lawyer, william breuer, said the order would be appealed to the dmv's administrative review board and then to the courts, if necessary
this is an aberration,'' breuer said of the dmv's action. ``there's no evidence to support this.''
three white men were convicted of manslaughter in connection with michael griffith being chased onto the belt parkway in queens where he was struck on the night of dec. 20, 1986, by blum's car
blum, a court officer and son of a new york city policeman, was not charged in connection with the case
in revoking blum's license, dmv officials said blum was guilty of leaving the scene of a personal injury accident, operating a motor vehicle at a speed greater than is reasonable and prudent, and following too closely
seven of eight accused members of the westies gang were found guilty today of various crimes including murder conspiracy, extortion and drug dealing
the federal jury that convicted them will receive further instructions and resume deliberations on the most significant charges, racketeering and racketeering conspiracy
in its eighth day of deliberations, the sequestered jury in manhattan's federal court returned a finding that the westies gang was a racketeering enterprise and that seven of the eight defendants were involved with the gang
the jury of 10 women and two men also found that all but one of the defendants had each committed at least two of the 28 criminal acts listed in the racketeering charges, including murders, kidnappings, extortion, loansharking and drug dealing
but unlike other racketeering trials, u.s. district judge whitman knapp will give jurors additional instructions before sending them back to determine if those acts were committed as part of a racketeering enterprise
one defendant, john halo, was acquitted on all charges
convicted on various other charges were: reputed westies leader james coonan; his wife, edna; james ``jimmy mack'' mcelroy; richard ``muggsy'' ritter; william ``indian'' bokun; thomas collins; and collins' wife florence. oil spill</head>
reports that toxic chemicals may have been dumped into the ohio river while the water was fouled with diesel fuel have been turned over to environmental protection agency criminal investigators, an epa official said wednesday
robert boodey, head of the epa region iii criminal unit in philadelphia, declined, however, to say whether his office has opened a formal investigation. he said agency policy forbids commenting on criminal investigations
all i can tell you is we passed the information along,'' said thomas voltaggio, superfund chief for region iii. ``once we send the reports over to them we are really out of it. we want to separate any criminal activity from regulatory activity.''
epa officials received the toxic dumping reports in mid-january, several weeks after the jan. 2 collapse of an ashland oil inc. tank near pittsburgh fouled the monongahela and ohio rivers with an estimated 730,000 gallons of diesel fuel
sen. arlen specter, r-pa., on tuesday asked epa to investigate the reports
traces of chloroform and methylene chloride, which both cause cancer, and another industrial solvent, 1,1,1-trichloroethane, were found in water samples by the west virginia department of natural resources, according to officials in that department
they found no hard evidence, however, that the toxins were deliberately dumped to take advantage of the ashland pollution crisis, said ron sandy, branch head of field opertions for the natural resources department
the pittsburgh press reported sunday that the toxic chemicals were found in a 15-mile stretch of the river between wheeling and moundsville
the concentrations exceeded the levels set by epa as cancer risks, but probably had no effect on public health, said peter tennant, water quality program manager for the ohio river valley sanitation commission
the intakes of all the water companies were shut down as the spill passed,'' tennant said. ``also, those compounds ... are easily removed by the carbon filtration systems water companies use.''
the tank collapse cut tap water service to about 23,000 suburban pittsburgh residents and threatened to do the same for an estimated 1 million others. water companies along the ohio, which is formed by the monongahela and allegheny in pittsburgh, closed their intakes and relied on reserves and emergency supplies until the diesel fuel passed
the pennsylvania emergency management agency has helped process 70 claims against ashland from municipal governments seeking a total of about $1 million, karen critchfield, pema disaster assistance officer, said tuesday at a meeting of federal, state and local officials involved in the spill. everest</head>
the son of one of first two men to conquer mount everest has set his own sights on the mighty mountain, joining a team that hopes to scale the world's highest peak to mark the 35th anniversary of the feat
tenzing norbu, a connecticut travel agent and the son of tenzing norgay, said he joined the expedition to honor his late father, the sherpa guide who joined new zealander edmund hillary at the top of the world in 1953
for me, it is a pilgrimage to a mountain which has reshaped the lives of my family and my people,'' tenzing, 25, said at a news conference wednesday.``it will allow me to pay homage to my late father.''
the young tenzing, a university of new hampshire graduate who works for a travel agency in westport, conn., only will go as far as the base camp, about 17,000 feet, on the chinese tibetan side of the mountain that straddles the nepal-china border
the final assault on the summit of the 29,028-feet peak, the world's highest, will be made by an international team of mountaineers led by robert anderson, 30, a denver native now living in auckland, new zealand
anderson, joined by two other americans and a british climber, will attempt to reach the peak without oxygen by an untried route along the eastern side of the mountain
like the nepalese tenzing and hillary in 1953, the ``everest '88'' expedition will be supported by the united nations. miklos pinther, chief cartographer of the u.n. secretariat, will travel to the base camp and the climbers will have a u.n. flag to plant on the summit
the group leaves beijing on thursday for lhasa, the capital of tibet. from there, they will begin a five-day journey accompanied by 45 yaks to a site where they will set up their base camp
anderson, who came within 800 feet of the summit in a 1985 expedition to everest, said the team hopes to put a man at the peak by the end of april
he said the climbers will forgo oxygen to relive some of the challenge of the original assault, much of which has been diminished by technological advances in climbing equipment. tenzing and hillary used oxygen in their climb
the young tenzing said he will give the summit assault team objects similar to those his father took up the mountain, including a wooden black cat, a broken pencil and candy to pay respect to the mountain gods
tenzing and hillary reached the summit on may 29, 1953. since then, 209 people have conquered the mountain, but only about 15 without oxygen, according to anderson
tenzing norgay, the ``tiger of the snows,'' died in may 1986 at the age of 72 in darjeeling, india, where he set up a climbing school. hillary, now sir edmund, is new zealand's ambassador to india. the two men kept their vow never to reveal which first set foot on the majestic pinnacle. details on other plants; no pickup; adds byline.</note>
general motors corp. said today it has boosted its production plans for 1988 by 175,000 cars and trucks, will recall 8,600 laid-off workers and reopen a temporarily closed assembly plant
the strengthening demand for gm vehicles reflects the ongoing product quality improvements resulting from plant modernization and employee involvement programs,'' gm president robert stempel said in a statement
this combined with very competitive retail incentive programs has increased the value of gm products,'' he said
gm will increase production by running some plants, particularly for trucks, on overtime; restoring second shifts at two u.s. plants and one in canada; and reopening its closed framingham, mass., assembly plant
at the three plants where gm had dropped the second shift, workers from both shifts were sharing jobs by alternating between two weeks on layoff and two weeks on the job, gm said
the framingham assembly plant, which gm closed abruptly nov. 30, will reopen may 9 on one shift with 2,000 of its 3,700 workers. the plant will build the oldsmobile cutlass cierra, but will not resume production of the chevrolet celebrity, gm spokeswoman kathy tanner said
the second shift at gm's 4,200-worker van nuys, calif., assembly plant will be restored march 14, bringing 1,900 employees back full time. the plant, which gm's only chevrolet camaro and pontiac firebird source, dropped the second shift last week
gm also will restore the second shift at its oshawa no. 1 plant in oshawa, ontario, bringing back 2,700 laid-off workers on march 21. the plant builds the oldsmobile cierra and pontiac 6000. against delaying the trial again, prosecutors asking for contempt sanctions against mecham attorney. pickup 4th graf, `leonard said...' adds 5 grafs at end with details of request for contempt sanctions.</note>
gov. evan mecham's new attorney says he will seek a postponement of the impeachment trial before the arizona senate, which is set to start monday
we will be requesting ... that the trial be postponed,'' jerris leonard said in an interview late tuesday night. he said he would meet today with state supreme court chief justice frank gordon, who is presiding over the trial, and with senate president carl kunasek
senate majority leader bob usdane, a republican, noted today that the trial already has been delayed a week and added, ``my inclination is to not give them another minute of delay. ... i think it's a tactic. i think they've known all along what they were going to be doing.''
meanwhile, the state house's impeachment prosecutors today asked that contempt sanctions be imposed against mecham attorney murray miller for refusing to provide a list of planned witnesses before the senate trial begins. prosecutors william french and paul eckstein accused miller of ``patent, blatant disregard and disobedience'' of a deadline set by gordon
leonard, who headed the law enforcement assistance administration in the nixon administration, also said he planned to meet with miller
leonard said he was retained by mecham monday night
i am certainly very enthusiastic to take the case,'' leonard said
we're going to put together a very strong defense in his behalf, a very forceful, fruitful, responsible defense and hope that the members will be persuaded by it,'' leonard said
roy dunton, former mohave county republican party chairman and founder of the mecham legal defense fund, said tuesday that leonard was hired as the lead defense counsel
edith richardson, chief spokeswoman for mecham's recall election campaign, said tuesday night that leonard had been added to the defense team, ``but i'm not sure of the terminology, whether he is the lead attorney.''
she said she believed that miller and michael scott, the attorney for mecham's brother, willard, would handle the criminal defense
in addition to the impeachment trial, mecham and his brother face felony charges stemming from mecham's alleged failure to properly report a $350,000 campaign loan
leonard ran unsuccessfully for the u.s. senate from wisconsin in 1968 and in 1969 was named director of the law enforcement assistance administration by president nixon. he also served as an assistant u.s. attorney general in washington
he joined the washington law firm of manatt, phelps, rothenberg, tunney &amp; evan in may 1986
french and eckstein, in their motion for contempt sanctions, said mecham's defense should not be permitted to call any witnesses during the trial unless they meet today's 5 p.m. deadline to provide a list
the prosecution submitted a list of 41 possible witnesses monday
miller said in a letter monday he did not want to disclose his planned witnesses because he thought it was unfair to hold mecham's impeachment trial before his criminal trial is over
gordon also had set a 9 a.m. deadline today for miller to file any objections to the impeachment counts, but no documents were filed by that time
usdane said he thought the deadlines set by gordon appeared to be more of a request than an order, and questioned whether sanctions could be imposed if there was no direct order involved
evangelist jimmy swaggart, who is said to have confessed an obsession with pornography, once wrote a newspaper column saying pornography is as addictive as drugs
swaggart faces disciplinary action by his denomination, the assemblies of god, for sexual misconduct. he was reportedly observed and photographed while visiting a prostitute in new orleans
the rev. glen cole of sacramento, calif., one of 13 members of the assemblies of god's ruling executive presbytery, said swaggart had confessed last week to having an obsession with pornography dating back to his youth
james hammill of memphis, tenn., a member of the denomination's general counsel, said monday night that the panel had been given pictures of swaggart going in and out of a new orleans motel room with a woman
in a july 1986 column for the baton rouge sunday advocate, swaggart wrote:
pornography is now considered as addictive as drugs, leading, as with any addiction, to a need for escalated `doses' and intensity. that, in turn, breeds desensitization, which leads to the acting out of roles that have been at the heart of the nation's most sensational serial murder and serial rape cases
women and children, portrayed as nothing more than debased objects on screen and in print, pay a particularly high price when fantasy turns into reality.''
swaggart called those who make their living from pornography ``wretched, disgusting and dangerous.''
in another column, swaggart wrote: ``most of today's sex, i'm afraid, is a consequence of lust, and that has absolutely nothing to do with love
you see, the laws of god cannot be abrogated with impunity. yes, we can do it, we are free moral agents. to do so, however, means that we `pay the piper,' and we're now starting to do so.''
the december issue of swaggart's magazine, the evangelist, was critical of mercer university, a baptist school that did not take disciplinary action against six women who posed for playboy magazine
it seems to us that if the standards set forth in the word of god were truly being taught, neither the girls nor the university would find themselves in this embarrassing circumstance,'' the magazine said
portuguese prime minister anibal cavaco silva, disappointed in american aid levels, said today his nation wants to review a 1983 u.s.-portugal defense agreement giving the united states access to a key air base
cavaco silva, emerging from a two-hour meeting at the white house with president reagan, said he told the president that cuts in american aid have posed difficulties ``particularly at a time when we are committed to the re-equipment of our armed forces and trying to modernize the country.''
i stated to president reagan that the portuguese government intended to request that consultations be held under the terms of the agreement,'' cavaco silva said
reagan reiterated u.s. desire to help portugal, but he said ``the efforts remain firm, even within the context of the harsh budger realities that we all face. the task of leadership is to rise to the challenge.''
the portuguese leader is using his first official visit to washington to register disappointment that the united states is providing barely more than half the $205 million that portugal wants in aid each year for u.s. rights at lajes air base in the azores, a vital refueling point in the atlantic
the u.s. deficit-reduction program is responsible for the cuts, not just in aid to portugal but to the philippines, greece, and turkey _ other base-rights countries with struggling economies
a senior u.s. official, briefing reporters in advance of cavaco silva's meeting at the white house with president reagan today, said ``we're going to have a foreign policy job to do in convincing them why we're doing it and why we have to share the pain together.''
cavaco silva arrived on tuesday for three days of talks
portugal is disappointed in the aid levels, which have dipped to $117 million this year after hitting a high of $205 million in 1984, one year after the current base agreement was signed
in his budget proposal last week, reagan asked congress for $163 million for the fiscal year beginning oct. 1
the u.s. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he doubted the prime minister wanted a ``confrontation'' during his visit to washington
rather, we'll look for ways we can figure out _ at least in the short run _ some of our problems,'' the official said
earlier this month, defense secretary frank c. carlucci appeared to have soothed portuguese feelings enough to head off a request for a formal review of the u.s.-portugal defense agreement. he received permission from cavaco silva's government to send over surplus u.s. military equipment to make up part of the shortfall in financial assistance
experts from both defense departments are to meet soon to figure out what portugal can use from u.s. stocks
in the past two weeks, however, portuguese foreign minister joao de deus pinheiro and president mario soares have expressed reservations about the plan
nevertheless, the u.s. official said, ``i think what he (cavaco silva) told frank carlucci at the beginning of february, we expect, holds
obviously the portuguese are disappointed with the levels of assistance. so are we,'' the official said. ``invariably we've requested more money out of congress and in recent years have not done very well. as the budget crunch is being faced by all agencies, obviously security assistance is one of those areas hit
we're probably going to face it in a great amount of countries, particularly countries that feel they have a commitment for a certain level of military assistance and believe that they have been good allies.''
