voting unanimously, the cabinet urged air force secretary edward c. aldridge not to pursue a proposal for low-level, high-speed jet fighter missions over the national park
park superintendent michael finley agreed with the cabinet and said the park already is stressed by south florida's expanding population
to add one more type of stress to everglades national park could be the nail in the coffin,'' said finley. ``at some point ... the everglades will be to south florida what central park is to new york city.''
gov. bob martinez was on a trade mission in europe and did not participate in the cabinet vote
lt. tom barth, deputy for public affairs at homestead air force base, said the training missions still were in the planning stage and might not be carried out over the park. a second site is being examined southwest of lake okeechobee, north of alligator alley
the training missions would not use live ammunition or bombs, he said
air force officials say the south florida missions would be cheaper than continuing to send figters to other bases for combat training
homestead, once solely a training base, has been converted to an active fighter base. the base is home to two wings, the 31st and 482nd. in october, it will have three squadrons of f-16s and f-4s. ``west.''</note>
a crisis over an unconstitutional state budget blew over wednesday almost as quickly as it developed after west virginia officials agreed to continue government as usual until they hear more from the state supreme court
the high court issued a 3-2 opinion on tuesday calling the budget unconstitutional because it contains a $26 million deficit. but the court granted a 60-day grace period during which the order would be suspended while a rehearing is requested
check-writing officials were thrown into a panic initially, with treasurer a. james manchin saying he would not process any more state bills. but manchin reversed himself overnight and said wednesday he would process the checks as usual
he called the high court's ruling a ``whimper in the wind'' and said it carried enough delays to put off any final action until the new fiscal year that starts on july 1
manchin released a number of checks for hospital workers on wednesday. manchin's reversal also apparently clears the way for the state payroll to be distributed on monday as scheduled
gov. arch moore already has scheduled a special session of the legislature for april 12 to look at education matters, and the budget problem presumably could be considered at that time
the governor has a possible safety valve. on tuesday, he received a bill that would allow him to borrow up to $50 million from the state's pension and workers' compensation trust fund, said gubernatorial press secretary john price
if he signs the bill, it might be possible to solve the crisis by simply dumping $26 million into the current budget
auditor glen gainer, who also signs the state's checks, said he questions whether the loan is legal but said he would not contest it in court
a lawsuit filed last fall by the west virginia education association challenging $13.5 million in cuts in education this year sparked the high court decision
the unprecedented ruling comes as lawmakers grapple with bills that gainer estimates will be $170 million by the june 30 end of the fiscal year. in addition, lawmakers are trying to write a budget for the next fiscal year
tax collections are $35.7 million behind predictions this year, and a national investment firm issued a national bond rating warning against west virginia on dec. 15 because of the financial crisis facing the state
house finance chairman george farley suggested his colleagues simply ignore the high court decision and continue to work on the budget for next year
artist clayton lefevre has sulked for a couple of years because prince charles refused to sign a portrait, so he has taken his revenge with a window display depicting the queen of england and the duchess of york as derelicts
lefevre installed the display at his studio this week, anticipating the arrival on friday of the duke and duchess of york, also known as prince andrew and the former sarah ferguson. the couple is coming to participate in uk-la, a celebration of british art and culture
lefevre started his ``100 club'' celebrity collection in houston, where he lived until four months ago
he has completed 105 of the acrylic portraits, including frank sinatra, nancy reagan, eddie murphy, muhammad ali and dolly parton
working from photographs, he did two portraits of the prince. he sent both to charles, asking that one be signed and returned and the other be kept as a gift
prince charles is the only one of the 105 who has refused,'' said lefevre, who offered the portrats to prince charles and princess diana when they visited houston in 1986
they took the two paintings back to buckingham palace. they told me if i wanted the (one) painting back, they would send it unsigned, otherwise they would give it to charity
i was just happy to get my copy back,'' he said
angus mackay, public affairs officer for the british consulate in los angeles, said no insult was intended to lefevre by the royal family. they never sign autographs for anyone
i think it's unfortunate he interprets what is a general ground rule as a specific slight to him apparently,'' mackay said
