the city of baytown, banking that city hall may be sitting on a pool of oil, is looking in its own back yard for more income
the city council has approved a plan for trace oil and gas to drill a shallow 5,000-6,000-foot well near the entrance to the 30-acre, wooded city hall complex. the city would receive a 20 percent royalty on any petroleum uncovered under the agreement
we're keeping our fingers crossed,'' said emmett hutto, mayor of this town of 57,000 people about 30 miles east of houston. ``if the well brings in $100,000 a year, we could knock a half-cent off our tax rate.''
jim bob jackson, a geologist and co-owner of trace oil in houston, projects the company has a 50-50 chance of hitting oil
we feel confident. we drilled a well 500 feet south of there on maryland avenue last year and got the smell of oil,'' he said
after careful calculations, his research indicated an oil pool could be trapped beside a fault under the lush complex, he said
the company has permission to drill about 2,000 feet from the city buildings. an 80-foot derrick will be erected and the drilling will continue around the clock for five to six days, jackson said. if oil is discovered, a fence will be erected around the site and landscaping will be used to disguise the oil pumping operations, he said
we made stipulations in the lease so that it won't be a messy operation,'' hutto said
the company will spend about $150,000 on the prospecting venture
we expect it could bring in anywhere from $500 to $15,000 per day in revenue, which is a minor find,'' jackson said
the prospect of oil under the building is not outlandish, said assistant city manager bobby rountree
after all, this is an oil town,'' agreed jackson. ``exxon, one of the world's largest refineries, made baytown what it is today.'' falwell</head>
the supreme court expanded significantly the legal protections for parody and satire wednesday as it overturned a $200,000 award evangelist jerry falwell had won against hustler magazine and publisher larry flynt
the justices ruled unanimously that ``emotional distress'' lawsuits filed by public figures targeted by such spoofs should be as difficult to win as libel suits
and the court unanimously said that even pornographic spoofs enjoy the free-speech protection of the constitution's first amendment
the hustler material was a phony ad purportedly quoting falwell discussing an incestual encounter with his mother in a virginia outhouse and his habit of getting drunk before giving sermons
small print at the bottom of the page said the ad was ``not to be taken seriously.''
led by chief justice william h. rehnquist, the court rejected falwell's arguments _ and a federal appeals court's ruling _ that some parodies are so outrageous they do not deserve legal protection
outrageousness in the area of political and social discourse has an inherent subjectiveness about it which would allow a jury to impose liability on the basis of the jurors' tastes or views,'' rehnquist said, adding that such results are constitutionally impermissible
the decision was praised by news organizations
it's easy to stand up for nice talk from nice people but the first amendment protects all speech, even the outrageous,'' said paul mcmasters of the society for professional journalists
editorial cartoons have been a particular target of lawsuits lately,'' mcmasters said. ``the court was right to speak up so forcefully on behalf of ... tools editorial cartoonists wield so well.''
but falwell, a baptist minister and founder of an organization called the moral majority, disagreed. ``no sleaze merchant like larry flynt should be able to use the first amendment as an excuse for maliciously and dishonestly attacking public figures,'' he said after learning of his defeat. ``i'm sure the justices were holding their noses while making the ruling.''
flynt said he was ``absolutely delighted'' by the ruling
even though the suit had no merit in the beginning, i still spent over $1 million in attorney's fees. ... it's what you call paying to defend the first amendment,'' flynt said by telephone from los angeles
he said he was concerned about small newspapers and house organs and others unable to afford to fight such a battle
they just go out of business,'' flynt said
rehnquist's opinion drew a distinction between the hustler ad and more traditional forms of parody such as editorial cartoons, calling the falwell spoof ``a distant cousin of the political cartoon, and a rather poor relation at that.''
following publication of the parody in november 1983 and march 1984, falwell sued hustler, a sexually explicit magazine, and its publisher for $45 million in damages for libel, invasion of privacy and the intentional infliction of emotional distress. he won on the emotional-distress allegations only and a federal jury in roanoke, va., awarded him $200,000 in damages in late 1984. the 4th u.s. circuit court of appeals upheld the award
but the high court said the same tough standard of proof falwell faced in trying to prove he was libeled should have applied as well to his emotional-distress allegations
the supreme court since 1964 has required that free-speech considerations be taken into account in libel cases. but those considerations never before have been required in emotional-distress cases
in order to win a libel suit, a public figure must prove that the allegedly libelous statement was false and was made with ``actual malice'' _ knowledge or reckless disregard of its falsity
until wednesday, winning an emotional-distress suit was easier for public figures. they only had to prove that the defendant intended to cause the distress, that the defendant's conduct was extreme and that emotional distress actually was suffered
now, if public figures sue over some spoof _ whether alleging libel or emotional distress _ they must meet the actual-malice standard of proof. and in proving falsity, they must show that the spoof reasonably could have been interpreted as stating actual facts
the court's vote was 8-0. justice anthony m. kennedy, who joined the court thursday, did not participate in the decision
in other decisions, the court:
_expanded by a 6-2 vote the power of communities to impose rent controls, ruling in a case from san jose, calif., that tenant hardships may be considered when regulating the increases sought by landlords
_ruled unanimously in an arkansas case that federal judges may not order the government to pay fees to lawyers who successfully obtain overdue federal welfare benefits for the aged, blind or disabled
_made it a bit easier for prosecutors to talk to criminal trial juries about a defendant's failure to testify as it reinstated a man's tennessee mail fraud conviction
_broadened protections for criminal defendants who claim they were enticed by law enforcement officials into committing a crime by overturning, 6-2, on entrapment grounds a milwaukee man's bribery conviction
democrat paul simon, admitting ``there is no sense in my fooling myself,'' said wednesday his battered presidential campaign is skipping the super tuesday primaries and caucuses to try to recover from four straight defeats
republican also-ran jack kemp vowed he, too, would press on despite an 0-5 record. unlike simon, the new york congressman said he would take his chances in the clump of primaries in the south and elsewhere on march 8
i'm in this all the way to new orleans'' and the gop convention in august, said kemp in beaufort, s.c
it is on to atlanta'' and the democratic convention in july, echoed simon at a washington news conference
simon, the illinois senator, has yet to win a democratic event, watching massachusetts michael dukakis and missouri rep. richard gephardt split the early contests. so he said he will skip the south and focus on his home state primary on march 15, one week after super tuesday
the campaign will begin anew after super tuesday, starting in illinois,'' simon said
money is the problem simon sees in the south
there is no sense in my fooling myself,'' the illinois democrat said. ``we just don't have the money.''
simon's campaign plunged into debt before the new hampshire primary, but he has collected close to half a million dollars in the past two weeks
we have had record-breaking fund-raising,'' simon said. ``monday, for example, $137,000 came in. we never had a day like that before. but you take $137,000 and then look at 20 states and what it would cost for a media buy, and you're talking about something that is nowhere near adequate.''
i'm not writing off the south. i want my friends there to vote for me,'' simon added. ``i'm realistic about resources. i simply cannot do everything.''
on the republican side, kemp said he was outspent in the tuesday contests in south dakota and minnesota, but that would not happen in the south. senate gop leader bob dole won both contests, with former evangelist pat robertson coming in second. vice president george bush trailed
we beat bush in minnesota. ... i was outspent 8-to-1 by dole and probably 10-to-1 by robertson. we're going to match them dollar-for-dollar in the south and in south carolina,'' kemp said
kemp's hopes have been badly shaken by robertson's strong showing in the early caucus states. and robertson has said that he will win the south carolina primary on march 5, the door-opener to the super tuesday primaries
i think last night proved the race is wide open. that's all i really needed. i needed to break up the idea that this is a bush-dole race. this is no longer a bush-dole race,'' kemp added
kemp finished second in michigan, third in new hampshire and minnesota and fourth in iowa and south dakota
among the democrats, simon said he has concluded that the super tuesday contests will continue the early pattern of confusing results with no clear front-runner emerging _ leading to a brokered convention in atlanta
super tuesday is likely to result in a very mixed picture,'' he said. ``phase one of the selection process ends on march 8. ... but we do not have the resources for winning in the super tuesday states.''
phase two of the selection process begins march 15. i shall use phase two to deliver the message that we must become a nation with leadership characterized by compassion and vision and common sense. it is on to atlanta with that message.''
he cited ``growing evidence that for the first time in recent history there will be no first-ballot winner at the democratic convention.''
simon claimed he was in second place in the delegate count, but the ap count places simon in third place with 33 delegates, behind dukakis with 44.5 and gephardt with 39. simon aides said he is claiming delegates out of minnesota, even though the returns allocating the delegates there will not be known until march 8
simon is on the ballot in all the super tuesday primaries, but he said he will do little or no campaigning in those states _ except for the nationally televised debates that are a major feature of the next two weeks
simon's best day so far was in iowa on feb. 8, where he finished a very close second to gephardt. he was third in new hampshire and then fourth in the tuesday contests
two of the networks have decided that the super tuesday primary is so unlikely to produce a clear winner in the presidential nominating races that they are cutting back on their planned prime-time coverage
cbs had planned to pre-empt its entire prime-time schedule for super tuesday coverage on march 8, but decided tuesday to cut back to two hours. nbc, which had planned a two-hour special, cut it to one hour
the reasoning is that after iowa and new hampshire, we determined that super tuesday was not going to be as conclusive as previously thought,'' said nbc news spokesman bill mcandrew. ``in planning coverage, we protectively booked two hours and decided we could cover it comprehensively in one.''
gene f. jankowski, president of the cbs broadcast group, said the network decided the public wasn't interested enough in the primary results to spend more than two hours
what we did was took a look at the public's attitude in iowa, what the public's reaction to the coverage in new hampshire was and did a reevaluation of what the reaction was going to be to the primaries that take place on march 8 and said to ourselves, from an editorial point of view and journalistic point of view, can we really fill three hours in a meaningful way that the audience would want to watch?'' he said
abc was sticking to its plan to have two hours of coverage, despite the fact that tuesday is its highest-rated night of prime-time programming. cnn will have comprehensive coverage throughout the evening, beginning at 6 p.m. est
on pbs, ``the macneil-lehrer newshour'' will wait until wednesday to assess the results
because we're not stupid, we're going to avoid projecting or predicting what may happen,'' said associate editor jim lehrer. ``it is so diverse and diffused down there, who knows what all of these many, many results are going to add up to when it's all said and done.''
this is the first year for super tuesday, when 20 states, most of them in the south, will select delegates to the two presidential nominating conventions. coverage of the event, stretching from massachusetts to american samoa, has confounded the networks, who are additionally hampered by budget cutbacks in the news divisions
before the presidential campaign began, the networks believed super tuesday would likely clinch the race in one or both parties. but after the iowa caucuses and the new hampshire primary failed to produce clear frontrunners, the networks decided super tuesday was less likely to be decisive
the networks are backing and filling. they're less sure than they were that we'll actually know who the nominee will be,'' said abc correspondent jeff greenfield. ``you have to assume at present it's going to be an extremely diffuse result. we may come out of this not knowing a thing.''
president reagan on wednesday sent congress the ``truth in federal spending act'' aimed at attacking budget deficits with a pay-as-you-go approach to new programs
the legislative proposal is part of the ``economic bill of rights'' reagan announced last july. it would force the executive and legislative branches to spell out the costs of programs and legislation
reagan said the bill ``will help us carry out the important goals'' reflected in the deficit-reduction accord reached in the aftermath of the oct. 19 wall street crash
faced with indications of growing investor uneasiness with red-ink budgets, reagan and leading lawmakers signed the nov. 20 agreement calling for a two-year, $76 billion reduction program
that accord also provided for $9 billion in tax increases in fiscal 1988, which began oct. 1, and $14 billion in fiscal 1989
in asking for enactment of the truth-in-spending bill, reagan said the agreement with congressional leaders ``reflects a strong consensus that federal spending must be brought under control.''
protecting the federal budget from special interest, budget-busting legislation requires a continued, ongoing commitment,'' he said in a message to congress. ``despite recent encouraging efforts to bring the federal budget deficit under control, major problems persist.''
the truth-in-spending proposal was among several reagan unveiled last july 3 in a speech at the jefferson memorial here
other components of the so-called ``economic bill of rights'' included a balanced budget amendment and line-item veto authority for presidents. it also contained a proposal to require a ``super-majority'' vote, rather than a simple majority, for enactment of tax hikes
the truth-in-spending legislation would require executive agencies and the congress to submit legislation and programs that are ``revenue neutral.''
each piece of legislation would have to be accompanied by a financial impact statement showing how much it would cost, and proposing concurrent cuts in other programs, or increases in federal revenues, to cover the costs
reagan said in his message he wanted to make it clear that there is no intent in the legislation ``simply to shift'' the costs of legislation from the federal to state and local governments
in another development, reagan budget director james c. miller iii said the president will not propose legislation to rescind pork-barrel spending as he promised in his state of the union address
it will not be in the form of a package of rescissions, but a list'' for congress to review, he told the senate appropriations committee. the president will be ``leaving it up to you, members of congress,'' he said
if the president proposed rescissions, those accounts would be frozen for 45 days while congress decided whether to make the cuts permanent in a process with procedural advantages. the list, however, would have no force of law
sen. mark o. hatfield, r-ore., criticized the administration for focusing so much attention on small items that ``really add up to a hill of beans'' compared to the huge budget deficit problems. ``every dollar counts,'' he said, ``but keep matters in perspective.''
hatfield also complained that the administration touts its own initiatives _ such as buying new leather flight jackets for the military _ as good government while congressional priorities become ``pork barrel.''
former colorado gov. richard lamm says the next president of the united states could end up in history books like herbert hoover, who was the nation's leader during the great depression
i think there is a four-out-of-10 chance that it's 1929 over again,'' lamm said tuesday in an address to journalism students at the university of denver
lamm, who practices law, also teaches at the university
i think there is a six-out-of-10 chance that it's a very severe recession that's going to cause lots of trouble,'' he said
lamm said he's not sure if any of the current presidential candidates are willing to take the tough steps he thinks are needed to deal with the nation's economic problems, including massive cutbacks in the federal budget
he was asked by one student if he ever considered himself presidential timber
would i like to run for president of the united states?'' lamm said. ``i not only would not like to run for president of the united states, but if the good fairy godmother would come down tomorrow and offer me the presidency of the united states for the next four years, i would say `no.'''
the chairmen of both major political parties are supporting a national student-parent mock election scheduled for nov. 3, five days before the real election that will determine the next president
two million students and parents took part in the 1984 mock election, picking president reagan as did the general electorate
the organizers, based in tucson, ariz., have the support of 46 national civic, religious and educational organizations, and former presidents ford and carter are honorary chairmen
both frank j. fahrenkopf, jr., chairman of the republican national committee, and paul kirk, chairman of the democratic national committee, joined in a statement urging educators to support the mock election
it is open to students of all ages, from kindergarten through college. participants will meet at local, state and national ``election headquarters'' on the thursday before election day to cast votes for federal offices and to make recommendations on key national issues
the party chairmen said it was one way to help overcome youth apathy about voting
four out of five eligible voters under age 30 never bothered to go to the polls in the last election, kirk said
a political activist peddled one of the most popular pins at last weekend's state republican convention: ``nixon in 88.''
mary stanley of fresno, calif., said she had sold more than 600 of them at other political events around the nation this year
the pins are popular with conservatives ``who wish he was doing our negotiating with the russians instead of the people we have now,'' said stanley, who made news in 1984 when she resigned from the state republican central committee to support democrat geraldine ferraro for vice president
she said many people also buy the nixon buttons for fun or because they can't decide which of this year's crop of republican presidential candidates to support
it's a fun thing,'' she said. ``with this button, they know they aren't going to get in trouble.''
a moslem guerrilla leader said wednesday that the united states has struck a secret deal with moscow to betray the insurgents fighting to overthrow afghanistan's soviet-backed government
gulbaddin hekmatyar, head of the extremist islamic party guerrilla group, reiterated his vow to keep fighting in afghanistan until peace is forged on the insurgents' terms
speaking to reporters and diplomats, he said evidence of washington's alleged betrayal was its acceptance of soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's offer to begin removing red army troops from afghanistan on may 15 if a u.n.-sponsored peace accord is signed next month
soviet troops intervened in afghanistan in december 1979, and by western estimates 115,000 are still there
hekmatyar said the soviet pullout would leave the country in the hands of the communist kabul government, making it impossible for the nearly 5 million afghan refugees in pakistan and iran to return home
i don't think gorbachev (made the offer) without making a deal with the americans,'' he said
pakistan recently has insisted that any u.n. accord on foreign intervention in the afghan conflict include an agreement that an interim government would be installed in kabul during the withdrawal
asked why he thought the united states would betray the guerrillas after supporting them throughout the war, hekmatyar said, ``that's an impertinent question.''
asked whether his group would continue to accept u.s. military aid, he said, ``nobody can buy us or sell us out.''
the mujahedeen alliance, comprising the seven political factions of the insurgents, this week announced its own blueprint for a government to replace the soviet-backed one in kabul
it envisons a joint executive committee composed of all seven guerrilla leaders to preside over a 28-member cabinet composed of mujahedeen, afghan refugees and ``moslems presently living in kabul.''
the plan says the head of the cabinet would also be head of state but it did not suggest who would have that post
hekmatyar's said that if pakistan, the mujahedeen's headquarters, signed a u.n. accord without the guerrillas' approval, they might change their external operating base to iran
the next round of peace talks is scheduled to begin march 2 in geneva. islamabad, the capital of pakistan, and kabul have been the principal negotiators in the talks
pakistan has indicated it might not sign any agreement until a new government is installed in kabul. exporters</head>
president reagan said wednesday the decline in the value of the dollar has opened opportunities for u.s. exporters but they could be undermined by protectionist legislation being considered in congress
the fact that the dollar's exchange rate is at a far more realistic level is of great significance'' to the market for u.s. exports, the president told members of export now, a public-private group organized by the commmerce department
new opportunities are emerging because of the adjustment in the value of the dollar,'' he said. ``at the current exchange rates many american companies can now quote a lower price to customers in hamburg, antwerp or osaka than their competitors and still make a higher profit than on sales in the domestic market.''
in addition, he said, ``in the last few years, american industry has been going through an unprecedented period of renovation, computerization and modernization.''
what we don't need now, however, is protectionisn that undermines all the progress we've made,'' the president said
i strongly urge congress to send me a trade bill that does not imperil our ability to export by causing other countries to close their markets,'' he said. ``we shouldn't shoot ourselves in the foot after we have worked so hard and are in a position to win the race.''
the president said legislation being considered by a house-senate conference committee contains provisions that encourage exports ``and we don't want to lose those.''
but he said other provisions would violate the general agreement on trade and tariffs and make u.s. business less competitive
we ask for your support to ensure that we don't end up with an economy-killing, protectionist bill,'' reagan told the group
secretary of commerce william verity introduced reagan, saying he was to ``make introductory remarks and wave the flag.''
verity said the president had told him ``in no uncertain terms'' that the comemrce department would lead an effort to expand sale of u.s. goods overseas. the commerce secretary said there ``has been a tremendous improvement in the climate for exporting.'' he attributed that to an exchange rate that favors the united states and to an administration in washington ``that cares and would like to do more'' to stimulate u.s. sales abroad. floor</head> comments; subs pvs 3rd graf, bgng: it was, to correct times; subs pvs 4th graf, bgng: giugni found, to correct precedent; subs pvs 19th graf, bgng: democrats and, to correct to 52 co-sponsors sted 56; adds 2 grafs to give arrest precedent</note>
washington _ republicans angrily complained of ``banana republic'' tactics wednesday after armed capitol police broke into gop sen. bob packwood's locked office, arrested him and hauled him feet-first into the senate chamber during an all-night filibuster over democratic campaign finance legislation
on a motion by senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., sergeant at arms henry k. giugni was handed warrants for the arrest of absent republican senators, thus forcing them to answer a quorum call and keep the filibuster alive
it was after midnight, more than 10 hours after the filibuster began, when giugni and five armed plainclothes capitol policemen began stalking senate hideaways and senators' suites in nearby office buildings
giugni found several senators' offices empty but saw sen. steve symms, r-idaho, running down a hallway to escape arrest. then in an extraordinary incident that the senate historian said had not occurred since 1942, giugni used a passkey to unlock packwood's office door
bob witeck, a spokesman for the oregon republican, said packwood resisted and somehow jammed a finger he had broken two weeks ago in a fall. ``he tried to hold the door closed with his shoulder, but they were able to push it open,'' witeck said
i had to shove in the door to get into his office,'' said giugni, a stocky army veteran of world war ii and former vice squad policeman in honolulu. ``i think he hurt his finger. he was very courteous.''
packwood walked with giugni and his police escort a block or so from the russell senate office building to the senate wing of the capitol but refused to ``walk on the floor willingly,'' witeck said
at that point, three policemen grabbed packwood by his ankles and both arms and carried him bodily into the senate chamber, feet first. packwood later went to a hospital, where x-rays showed that his left hand _ enclosed in a cast _ had not been reinjured during the scuffle with giugni
i rather enjoyed it,'' packwood told reporters later. ``i instructed four of my staff to bring a sedan chair. but except for the honor of it, i'd rather walk.''
packwood said he bolt-locked his main office door after his staff reported that giugni would try to arrest him
the senator said ``it sounded like a battering ram'' at the door, with his shoulder pushing from inside against three shoulders on the other side. ``their mass beat my mass,'' packwood said, adding that he suffered only swollen knuckles
giugni served the arrest warrant signed by the presiding officer, sen. brock adams, d-wash., after 1 a.m
on a more serious note, packwood said the campaign spending bill has no chance of becoming law, because senate republicans have more than enough votes to sustain a certain veto by president reagan, and that byrd succeeded only in alienating his gop colleagues
packwood's arrest provoked angry clashes between democrats and republicans. sen. arlen specter, r-pa., said the incident brought to mind the police-state measures of ``nazi germany and communist russia.'' he protested that packwood was hustled into the senate chamber like a ``common criminal.''
sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, complained of ``banana republic'' tactics, and said packwood's arrest ``flaunted the constitution of the united states.'' he proposed a change in the senate rules to forbid any future arrest of absentee senators
sen. john kerry, d-mass., responded that republican senators had engaged in a ``shameful display'' of fleeing the chamber to avoid a quorum call, requiring giugni to search them down like a ``headmaster chasing schoolchildren.''
senators went off in a dead sprint,'' said sen. dale bumpers, d-ark. ``they should have been in calgary in one of the olympic events.''
the incident was prompted by a walkout by republican senators from the filibuster that they had started in opposition to the democratic proposal to impose voluntary spending limits in general election campaigns for the senate
the republicans charge that the bill was a democratic attempt to discriminate against them in states with a heavy democratic edge in registered voters. they began a filibuster early tuesday afternoon to prevent the democratic majority from bringing the bill to a floor vote they are virtually certain to win
but when the gop senators failed to answer repeated quorum calls requiring the presence of a majority of no fewer than 51 senators, byrd invoked a parliamentary rule that requires every senator to attend floor sessions unless excused. after a series of roll calls failed to lure republicans back to the floor, byrd moved to have the sergeant at arms arrest the absentees and escort them to the chamber
his motion was approved, 45-3, with dissenting votes cast by democrats howell heflin and richard shelby of alabama and dennis deconcini of arizona. the arrest warrants were signed by adams, who was presiding over the senate at the time
byrd said later he had no choice but to resort to the arrest tactic because only 50 senators _ one short of a majority _ had answered the last quorum call and three democrats were unavoidably absent. he appealed for an end to the republicans' ``guerrilla warfare'' against the bill
the senate rules provide that the sergeant at arms can be ordered to ``request'' or ``compel'' the attendance of absentees. if that doesn't work, the senate can ``direct the sergeant at arms or his deputies to arrest absent senators and bring them to the bar of the senate.''
democrats and republicans have been at loggerheads for nearly a year over the democratic proposal, which has 52 co-sponsors, to impose voluntary senate campaign spending limits of $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a state's population
under the bill, a candidate who observes the voluntary spending limit would get campaign funds from the treasury if an opponent exceeded the limit or an independent group spent large amounts of money in opposition
senate historian richard baker said the last time something similar to the packwood incident ocurred was on nov. 23, 1942, when a deputy sergeant at arms carried a subpoena to the mayflower hotel and escorted sen. kenneth mckellar, d-tenn., to the senate floor for a vote on poll tax legislation
u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz will find israel deeply divided over how best to approach peace negotiations with the arabs
shultz's mission will take him to neighboring arab states, but he will also have to shuttle between conservative prime minister yitzhak shamir and his liberal foreign minister shimon peres
it may be difficult to wring concessions from shamir. many in his likud bloc are grumbling about the american timing, worried that any change of position will create the impression that israel is giving in to arab rioters
the country is in a very defiant mood,'' said a shamir adviser, adding that any hint of u.s. pressure would likely backfire
the shamir aide said he doubted an agreement on starting negotiations with the arabs was not possible in the five days shultz has set aside for his trip
a more upbeat assessment came from yossi beilin, director-general of the foreign ministry
we are welcoming the initiative. we are welcoming the timing. we understand, all of us, that there is no military solution for the uprising in the territories but only a peaceful solution,'' beilin said
i am far from thinking that it is an impossible mission,'' he added
the main difference between peres and shamir is over whether israel should exchange territory captured in the 1967 middle east war for peace with the arabs. the two also disagree over whether israel should participate in an international peace conference
peres favors the return of some land and has agreed to jordanian king hussein's demand for an international conference
shamir opposes returning land and argues an international conference would be a biased forum and would give the soviet union too great a say
shultz has tried to find middle ground in one disagreement by proposing that arab-israeli talks be launched at an ``international event.''
shamir, who has accepted the idea of soviet-american auspices, has not closed the door to shultz's proposal but asked the secretary for clarification on what kind of format he has in mind
to satisfy the arabs, shultz needs israeli approval for a land-for-peace trade
but his mention of this formula in a recent speech irritated shamir and prompted him to send emissaries to washington to stress that no pledge to give up land would be made in advance
shamir hinted at the possibility that he was ready to negotiate territory. we are ready to negotiate on the territorial issue, but that doesn't mean we are ready to agree in advance to withdraw (from occupied lands),'' said yossi olmert, a legislator shamir sent to talk with shultz
a senior israel official who demanded anonymity said shultz would try to hammer out guidelines for arab-israeli talks on both a temporary and a permament solution in the west bank and gaza strip
the first obstacle he faces in this quest is a u.s.-proposed, yearlong timetable designed to get the process moving before u.s. and israeli elections in november
according to his schedule, an international conference would convene in april. elections for a palestinian self-rule council would follow in october, and in december, talks would begin on a final settlement
shultz's formula is designed to overcome arab suspicions that negotiations would never move beyond the limited autonomy idea, a concept rejected by the palestinians since it was first proposed in the 1978 camp david accords
the palestinians seek an independent state, which is opposed by israelis on both the right and left
shamir has demanded a confidence-building period of several years to set the stage for talks on a final disposition of the west bank and gaza strip
not even the most optimistic israelis are predicting shultz will iron out the final guidelines for talks during his visit. the best they hope for is an ``initial breakthrough'' that will set the stage for further trips by shultz or other u.s. officials
shultz was dealt an early setback when palestinian moderates were banned by yasser arafat's palestine liberation organization from meeting with the secretary in jerusalem
without palestinian participation, the new u.s. peace initiative is unlikely to have the desired calming effect on rioting in the occupied lands
in fact, his visit may have the opposite effect. responding to leaflets calling for anti-shultz protests, a general strike was launched on the eve of shultz's visit and israeli security officials are preparing for an escalation of violence
nicolas b. tatro, bureau chief in jerusalem, has been based in israel since 1983 and served in cairo, beirut and tehran since 1977
a man who allegedly made a false report that he was in the wreckage of a plane crash was indicted on a federal charge wednesday
u.s. attorney richard wiebusch said mark blair, 29, would face up to five years in prison and a fine if convicted on the charge of making a false statement to a federal government agency
blair is accused of talking by radio for four hours with an airborne navy plane on jan. 8, saying that he was aboard a small jet that crashed near meredith, killing one and injuring three. the navy plane also detected intermittent beeping from an emergency locator transmitter
officials said as many as 100 people, 15 planes, five helicopters, six police agencies, a snowmobile club and search dogs joined in the search for the aircraft. harold buker, state aeronautics director, said the search may have cost as much as $50,000
blair, who was arrested blair at his apartment four days after the hoax, already faces a state misdemeanor charge
the later life of josephine baker, the american entertainer known as ``the darling of paris'' in the jazz age, is documented in a collection of personal papers, photographs and clippings acquired by the yale university library
the collection was assembled by harry harford janes of england, who died last year before he could complete a biography of her. yale's beinecke rare book and manuscript library bout the collection at auction in london in december
i knew that she was of ongoing interest,'' patricia willis, beinecke curator of american literature, said wednesday
baker, who died in 1975 at age 69, was known for her opulent costumes, singing and exotic dancing in the folies bergere in the 1920s
the st. louis native first dazzled french audiences in 1925 in her performance in the revue negre, or the black review, when she dressed in scarlet ostrich plumes and danced on a mirrored drum
that role, along with her love of the exotic, illustrated by a daily stroll down the champs elysees with her leashed pet leopard, earned her another nickname _ ``siren of the tropics.''
she was the first to have highly unusual costumes and to work with a chorus that was extravagantly beautiful, making a whole image of the stage,'' willis said
the yale collection, acquired in december, focuses on the second half of her life, beginning with her work entertaining allied troops during world war ii, willis said
the collection includes letters from princess grace of monaco, and photographs and articles from the french and british press
baker and her husband, jo bouillion, adopted 12 children whom they dubbed their ``rainbow tribe.'' one picture shows baker with the entire clan by a swimming pool at les milandes, their home in southern france
willis said she did not know if a collection of papers documenting baker's earlier life exists, and she said she did now know of any major biography of her
the papers have become part of the beinecke's james weldon johnson collection of negro arts and letters in the library's american literature collection. est.</note>
a test of a redesigned nozzle-to-case joint for the space shuttle booster rocket was set for wednesday despite computer problems which forced a delay
the six-second test, the fourth of six nozzle joint environment simulator experiments and one of hundreds of tests of booster rocket components, was rescheduled for 3 p.m. mst at the wasatch operations plant of morton thiokol inc., 25 miles west of here
the joint was deliberately flawed to allow hot gases to blow past bonded adhesive insulation and one of three o-rings to reach the craft's main seal, or primary o-ring, said company spokesman rocky raab
he said the test was designed to evaluate the main seal's ability to contain any gases that might leak through the insulation and a ``wiper'' o-ring during a launch
the test had been scheduled for 1 p.m. but was delayed because of unspecified problems with a ground computer, raab said
engineers concluded after the third test of the joint on oct. 8 that the o-ring system withstood gas pressure after a deliberate flaw was built into the joint, which connects the nozzle to the body of the segmented booster rocket
however, during a full-scale test on dec. 23, a ``blow hole'' was detected in the joint's adhesive sealant _ a defect nasa had not built into the test but one which officials described as ``very benign.''
for wednesday's test, engineers created a quarter-inch by five-hundredths-inch hole through the bonded insulation and damaged the wiper o-ring _ two flaws aligned to assure a gas path in the joint up to the primary seal
raab said the double defects would subject the joint to ``a little bit more severe'' conditions than previous tests
again, it's another step in the process of ensuring that this is a fail-safe and fault-tolerant design,'' raab said. ``it builds our experience base on the behavior of the joint, and it also serves as a precursor for the april full-size motor firing, which will have similar flaws,'' raab said
blow holes can occur during assembly of the 126-foot rocket, ``so it happens here at the factory, if it happens,'' he said
raab said the test simulates ``the most difficult portion of the environment for the o-rings, that is the first one second'' of launch
the solid-fuel rocket booster was redesigned following the jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the shuttle challenger. the disaster, which killed the craft's seven-member crew, was blamed on a faulty seal in a booster joint that allowed hot gases to escape and ignite the shuttle's external fuel tank
while the blow hole detected in december was not considered a major problem, the failure of a nozzle boot ring during the same test prompted national aeronautics and space administration officials to push back the june 2 target date for resuming shuttle flights
the launch of discovery is now planned sometime in august
in addition to the final two njes tests scheduled before shuttle flights resume, nasa and morton thiokol will conduct several more joint environment simulator tests of the booster rocket and three more full-scale horizontal tests, the first one tentatively set for early april, raab said
up to 1 million taxpayers will receive federal refunds as much as three weeks earlier this year by having a professional file their tax returns directly into the irs computer
already this year, 119,494 returns have been filed electronically _ compared with 77,612 for the entire filing season in 1987. if the taxpayers choose, their refunds will be deposited directly into their bank account
although the number of electronic returns are up considerably this year, the volume of ordinary, paper returns filed so far is 6.7 percent below last year's pace. however, the gap _ which officials blame partially on the new tax law _ is closing each week
through feb. 19, the internal revenue service said wednesday, 23.55 million returns had been filed, compared with 25.24 million a year ago. the irs has processed 9.74 million of this year's returns, up slightly from 9.72 million last year
the inventory of unprocessed return totaled 13.8 million last week, compared with 15.5 million a year ago
the number of returns qualifying for refunds is down 14.4 percent, a decline that irs officials cannot explain. through last week, 3.8 million refunds had been certified; the figure was almost 4.5 million at this time last year
the average refund is bigger this year: $782 compared with $727. by the time all 107 million individual returns are filed this year, the irs estimates, nearly 80 percent will qualify for refunds averaging about $1,000
it is taking the irs about five weeks to process a return and certify a refund check this year. but those taxpayers who file electronically are getting refunds within two or three weeks
this is the third year of electronic filing, and within three or four more years, says richard f. moran, who manages the project, about 35 million returns will be filed annually by computer
electronic returns save the irs considerable time, said moran, and these returns generally have fewer errors that would delay a refund. the irs estimates electronic filing could save $200 million in processing and storage costs over the next 10 years
and if a taxpayer who files electronically chooses to have the refund deposited directly into a bank account, that saves the treasury 23 cents that would have been spent to issue and mail a paper check
so far, electronic filing is available only to taxpayers in 10 states and parts of four others who are due refunds and who pay any of about 2,000 professional preparers to fill out their returns. although the preparer sends the completed return directly into the irs computer by telephone line, the taxpayer must sign a signature form which is mailed to the irs
electronic filing is avaible in alabama, arizona, indiana, kentucky, nebraska, north carolina, utah, virginia, washington and wisconsin and in the albany and buffalo areas of new york, the sacramento and san jose areas of california and the cincinnati and dallas areas
all electronic returns are processed to irs centers in ogden, utah, or cincinnati
an anesthesiologist performed experiments on a comatose patient, his superior said wednesday after france's health minister suspended the doctor for experiments on another comatose patient
on tuesday, a professor of medicine testified in a criminal trial in the western city of poitiers that a doctor he did not identify had placed a deeply comatose patient, considered legally dead, on sabotaged medical equipoment
professor jean lassner said the experiment was carried out to see if the effects were the same in the case on trial, in which a young woman died, possibly from medical sabotage
maurice peria, director of the regional hospital center of amiens, said wednesday that the experiment was carried out by dr. alain milhaud on 24-year-old man who had been in a deep coma since late january. he said the man's family had been notified and the patient survived the experiment
the experiment was videotaped and sent to dr. lassner so he could use it at the trial,'' peria said. he said milhaud proceeded without the consent of the hospital
lassner gave his testimony in the trial of three doctors charged in the 1984 death of nicole berneron after her operation for a benign tumor at jean bernard hospital in poitiers
mrs. berneron, then 33 and the mother of two children, apparently received nitrous oxide instead of oxygen after the operation and died of asphyxiation. an investigation showed that the tubes had been switched
milhaud was condemned by the medical community after he admitted experimenting in 1985 on a 20-year-old comatose man
health minister michele barzach on wednesday ordered milhaud suspended from his duties in amiens, north of paris, and asked the state prosecutor to investigate to find out who had carried out the latest experiment
the minister, a doctor, said she was ``indignant and revolted that in this country one can carry out experiments on humans, obviously without their consent, given their state.''
in comments during the 1985 controversy, milhaud called patients in a prolonged, chronic vegetative state ``almost perfect human models, who constitute intermediaries between animal and man.''
in the 1985 experiment, he injected in two minutes a quart of blood into the patient's bone marrow to try to show this was a viable treatment for patients in shock. the man, comatose for three years, died within months but no link between the experiment and the death was established
president francois mitterrand condemned human experimentation
human beings are not instruments,'' he said. ``neither the search for truth nor scientific progress must distance us from this certitude, this value of civilization.''
the nation must double its spending on public works projects ranging from highways to waste disposal plants to keep them from falling into ruin, a government-appointed commission said wednesday
but in an era of high budget deficits and a push to reduce spending, not increase it, there are few signs that either congress or the white house is prepared to embrace the call for spending billions of additional dollars for such programs
sen. daniel patrick moynihan, d-n.y., said he was introducing legislation calling for an additional $5 billion a year in public works spending, but aides acknowledged there is little chance the bill would go far this election year
the white house gave little notice to the report by the national council on public works improvement, although it appointed three of its five members. the administration recently sent a proposed fiscal 1989 budget to congress calling for reduced highway and mass transit spending
the special government council, created four years ago to examine the nation's public works needs, concluded that ``the quality of america's infrastructure is barely adequate to meet current requirements and insufficient to meet the demands of future economic growth'' without sharply increased spending
for america's public works, the yellow light is flashing. the danger sign is apparent. there is serious and very real cause for alarm,'' joseph giglio, the council's chairman and a wall street investment banker
if we do not act to shore up our nation's infrastructure, we could very soon be faced with enormous problems that imperil future economic growth,'' giglio said at a news conference
the report called for all levels of government and the private sector to double their capital spending on public works projects from an annual level of $45 billion to $90 billion by the end of the century
the council criticized the federal government for hoarding funds in various public works trust funds _ a cash balance of $24 billion in 1987, according to the report _ but said additional revenue must also be obtained
it suggested possible sources of new money ranging from higher federal fuel taxes to local ``impact fees'' on developers
in most cases we cannot rely simply on wiser spending. we also must generate additional sources of funding,'' the council declared
the five council members acknowledged that the call for billions of dollars of increased spending for public works comes as a variety of social programs, the military and other government needs are competing for limited funds
to throw one more urgent monetary request into the pot may seem foolhardy,'' said panel member freeman holmer, president of eugene, ore., city council. ``it is anything but. ignoring our infrastructure, the foundation of our economy, will be even more costly in the long run.''
the study also included a ``report card'' on progress made in dealing with each major type of public works
the panel gave no failing grades. however, it raised serious concerns about efforts to deal with toxic wastes, which received a grade of d, as well as attempts to grapple with mass transit, solid waste disposal and waste water treatment needs. all three areas received a c or c-minus grade
highway programs did a little better with a c-plus. programs to manage water resources was given a b, the best grade, followed by b-minuses for aviation and water supply management
as a whole, this is a report card that would make most parents weep,'' said council member peter goldmark jr., a vice president of the times mirror co. of los angeles
discussing hazardous wastes, the council said that while spending to clean up contaminated sites has increased fivefold in the last two years, ``only a small fraction of the 2 tons of waste per capita produced in america each year is being treated safely.''
on water quality, the council suggested that governments at all levels have been fighting a losing battle. ``despite (a) $44 billion federal investment in sewage treatment since 1972, water quality has not improved significantly. ... due in part to uncontrolled sources of pollution ...,'' it said
the report said overall spending on public works has declined from 3.6 percent of the gross national product in 1960 to 2.6 percent in 1985. money for public works programs accounted for 20 percent of total government spending in 1950, but only 7 percent in 1984, it said
in effect, we're drawing down past investments without making commensurate investments of our own,'' the report said. ``failure to reverse this decline will exact a high price for the nation in the future both in the cost of deferred investment and in reduced economic competitiveness.''
other members of the council are lowell b. jackson, an engineering consultant from aurora, colo., and freida k. wallison, a washington, d.c., lawyer
the arrest warrant used by the senate to bring sen. bob packwood to the floor early wednesday left no question about what sergeant-at-arms henry giugni had to do
i had to take him in. i knew he was not going under his own power,'' giugni told reporters
the warrants given to giugni listed missing republican senators individually by name:
to henry k. giugni, sergeant-at-arms, united states senate:
the undersigned, presiding officer of the senate, by virtue of the power vested in me, hereby command you in pursuance of the order of the senate, this day made, to forthwith arrest and take into custody and bring to the bar of the senate, bob packwood, who is absent without leave
hereof fail not and make due return of this warrant.''
the order was signed by the presiding officer, who at the time was sen. brock adams, d-wash
packwood, r-ore., was physically carried onto the floor after giugni and five detectives shoved their way into his office
packwood later quipped to reporters, ``real men don't get arrested by brock adams.''
here is a look at the major differences between prime minister yitzhak shamir and foreign minister shimon peres on peacemaking strategy and the plan by u.s. secretary of state george shultz:
international conference _ peres has agreed to jordan's demand that the five permament members of the u.n. security council meet to start peace talks
shamir opposes the idea, arguing such a forum would be weighted against israel and would give the soviet union too much of a say
land-for-peace _ peres favors territorial compromise, returning some of the land captured in the 1967 middle east war for peace agreements with jordan, syria and other arab states
shamir says he is willing to negotiate the territorial issue, but he will not pledge in advance that israel will return any land. his party views the west bank and gaza strip as essential to israel's security
both leaders agree to giving palestinians some form of autonomy as a temporary solution in the occupied lands
shultz plan _ shamir has expressed reservations, especially over u.s. proposals to start talks by the end of the year on a final disposition of the occupied lands. he insists the five-year interim period called for in the camp david accords is needed to build trust between the palestinians and israelis
peres has not objected to any elements publicly
soviet involvement _ peres has argued the soviets are already involved in the region. he conditions soviet participation on a significant change in the number of jews allowed to come to israel. he has placed less emphasis on a demand for full diplomatic relations
shamir opposes any opening that will increase soviet influence and has insisted on full diplomatic relations and free emigration for soviet jews as conditions for any soviet role
plo _ peres leaves open the possibility of talking to plo chairman yasser arafat if the palestine liberation organization ends all forms of violence against israel and accepts the right of the jewish state to exist
shamir rules out any dealings with plo leaders
three democratic presidential candidates could lose future federal matching funds based on poor showings in the south dakota primary but they have 30 days to turn that around before the money is cut off
democrats jesse jackson, sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee and former colorado sen. gary hart became ineligible for matching funds by attaining less than 10 percent of the vote in two successive primaries _ south dakota on tuesday and new hampshire a week earlier
but election law stays the actual cut-off of money for 30 days after the second primary, giving the candidates a chance to re-establish their matching fund status by doing better in a subsequent primary
during the 30 days, the candidates can continue to receive federal matching funds for every contribution of $250 or less that they raise privately
there is absolutely no harm done to the campaign by this,'' said gore spokesman paul risley. he added that gore, by focusing his campaign on the south, had never expected to do well in new hampshire or south dakota but anticipated better results before the 30-day period ended
the candidates can regain eligibility by achieving a 20 percent or better showing in a successive primary
that means they have a chance to redeem themselves on march 8 when the super tuesday series of 20 primaries occurs. most of the states are in the south, where both jackson and gore have strong support
jackson's campaign manager, gerald austin, said he anticipates no problem in keeping matching-fund eligibility. he said that since jackson's respectable showing in iowa's caucuses on feb. 8, when he came in fourth, the campaign has raised $400,000
hart's possibilities are weaker. his campaign organization is tiny and he raised only $70,000 during january
the matching money is distributed from an u.s. treasury account that is supported by the voluntary $1 checkoff on individual income tax forms
gop contender pat robertson dropped below the 10 percent threshhold in new hampshire, but he redeemed himself with a 20 percent showing in south dakota
to be declared eligible initially by the fec, a candidate must raise $100,000 across 20 states in contributions of $250 or less
prince charles said tuesday he has banned the use of aerosols in his household because of concern that they damage the environment, and so far the only problem has been finding an alternative to hair spray
aerosols contain chlorofluorocarbons (cfcs) which float into the stratosphere and attack the ozone layer, a 20-mile-deep belt of protective gas around the earth
we are always told that it is not scientifically proved,'' charles said
but i, personally, as i have become older and more autocratic, have banned the use of aerosols in my household.''
in a light-hearted reference to his wife, princess diana, the 39-year-old heir to the british throne added:
trouble still remains with finding adequate and good enough alternatives to hair spray _ as i am sure all husbands here will find.''
he spoke to representatives of businesses which won awards for improving the environment under a program organized by the royal society of arts
he said the award-winners had found solutions to environmental problems, ``so if anybody can come up with a really good answer, an alternative to hair sprays, then for god's sake do so and i will come and give the award next year.''
the environmental group friends of the earth welcomed the prince's action, but said he did not have to ban sprays completely from his household
there are environmentally safe alternatives for every single kind of spray, including hair spray,'' said charles secrett, a spokesman for the group
holes in the ozone layer allow the sun's ultraviolet rays to reach the earth, causing skin cancer and threatening to damage crops and alter weather patterns
the supreme court was told wednesday that police should be allowed to pursue someone who starts running at the sight of them without having any other reason to suspect a crime has been committed
the alternative is for the police to shrug their shoulders and let a crime occur,'' said andrea l. solak, an assistant state prosecutor from detroit
but carole m. stanyar, representing a man who started running when he spotted a police cruiser on a detroit street, said, ``people run from the police for a variety of reasons.'' she said some people fear harassment, that they will be falsely accused of a crime or ``they may not like the police.''
the justices, hearing arguments in a case that could expand police power to stop people on the street, reacted skeptically to ms. stanyar's assrtions
don't you think sound law enforcement would want (the police) to see what's up?'' asked justice antonin scalia
justice thurgood marshall suggested that ms. stanyar's client, michael mose chesternut, initiated the chase. ``could it be he had a guilty conscience?'' marshall said
michigan authorities are seeking to reinstate as evidence drugs dropped by chesternut, who was standing on a detroit street corner talking to another man a little after midnight on dec. 19, 1984, when he saw the cruiser
police said chesternut immediately started running away and they followed him in the car. after turning a corner and as the cruiser drew alongside of him, chesternut threw a number of packets to the ground and then stopped
the officers said they picked up the packets, which appeared to contain narcotics, and they then arrested chesternut. he was charged with possessing heroin, codeine and diazapan
a judge in detroit threw the case out on grounds police lacked a reasonable suspicion to pursue chesternut and therefore seized the evidence unlawfully
michigan law enforcement officials said the judge may have dismissed the case out of a concern for innocent joggers
mrs. solak argued wednesday that the show of police authority which apparently prompted chesternut to drop the packets and stop did not amount to an illegal search and seizure barred by the constitution's fourth amendment
she also said that when chesternut dropped the packets he abandoned any right of privacy he had to protect them from a police search
ms. stanyar countered that chesternut reasonably believed he was being seized when police chased him and acted in ``an aggressive and confrontational'' manner
under the circumstances, a reasonable person would feel he was not free to leave,'' she said. he was prevented from asserting ``his right to go on his way,'' she said
the supreme court previously has held that police must have a reasonable suspicion of wrongdoing before stopping and questioning someone in a public place. the court also has said police must have more specific probable cause to believe a crime has been committed when arresting or detaining someone
a ruling in the case argued wednesday is expected by july
the case is michigan vs. chesternut, 86-1824
vice president george bush, saying ``you can't win them all,'' said wednesday he was disappointed but not surprised by finishing third in south dakota's republican presidential primary and fourth in minnesota's gop caucuses
i think the result was somewhat anticipated,'' he told reporters, but ``you can't go everywhere.''
in south dakota on tuesday, bush finished behind sen. bob dole of kansas and pat robertson, while bush trailed dole, robertson and rep. jack kemp of new york in minnesota
bush won the new hampshire primary feb. 16 after coming in third in iowa's gop caucuses feb. 8 behind dole and robertson
we've done well out there,'' bush said. ``we've won in michigan (at the convention jan. 29-30) and in nevada (in a non-binding straw poll at caucuses feb. 18). so you can't win them all,'' he added
bush is favored in maine's republican town caucuses this weekend. bush said that ``i think we have to do our best. the same is true for all these southern states'' in the march 8 super tuesday balloting, which also includes primaries in massachusetts and rhode island
state sen. pamela cahill, a leader of dole's maine campaign, said he is ``still optimistic'' but she did not expect him to win; instead, she said, at best, dole will finish second or third in maine
meanwhile, in burlington, vt., on wednesday, bush asked robertson to apologize or provide proof for suggestions that political motivations were behind the timing of reports of sexual misconduct by television evangelist jimmy swaggart
robertson, a former tv evangelist, provided no evidence to support his accusation on the timing, and declined to say who might be behind any such effort. but he claimed bush's campaign was the only one in the gop engaging in ``dirty tricks.'' robertson said it was odd that swaggart's tearful confession of sin came just two weeks before super tuesday
by sundown in the old south, i'd like to see him stand up like a southern gentleman with a little evidence,'' bush said. ``i'd like to see an apology or proof.''
bush was in vermont to meet with supporters, and shook hands with about 100 backers at burlington airport. he said he was looking for a victory in vermont, which holds a non-binding presidential primary next tuesday
asked whether he would support a regional approach to federal dairy policy, a key issue in vermont, bush said he has not taken a firm stand on the matter. attack</head>
the bechtel group inc. offered in 1985 to sell oil to israel at a discount of at least $650 million for 10 years if it promised not to bomb a proposed iraqi pipeline, a foreign ministry official said wednesday
but then-prime minister shimon peres said the offer from bruce rappaport, a partner in the san francisco-based construction and engineering company, was ``unimportant,'' the senior official told the associated press
peres, now foreign minister, never discussed the offer with other government ministers, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the comments marked the first time israel has acknowledged any offer was made for assurances not to bomb the planned $1 billion pipeline, which was to have run near israel's border with jordan. the pipeline was never built
in san francisco, tom flynn, vice president for public relations for the bechtel group, said the company did not make any offer to peres but that rappaport, a swiss financier, made it without bechtel's knowledge or consent
another bechtel spokesman, al donner, said bechtel ``at no point'' in development of the pipeline project had anything to do with the handling of the oil. he said proposals submitted by the company ``did not include any specific arrangements for the handling of the oil or for the disposal of the oil once it reached the terminal.''
asked about bechtel's disclaimers after they were made in san francisco, the israeli foreign ministry official said peres believed rappaport made the offer for the company
rappaport came to peres as a representative of bechtel and said he was speaking on behalf of bechtel,'' the official said. ``if he was not, he misrepresented himself.''
the jerusalem post on wednesday quoted sources close to peres as saying that according to rappaport, bechtel had said the oil sales would have to be conducted through a third party to keep the sales secret from iraq and jordan
the foreign ministry official said peres did not take the offer seriously
this is a man who sees 10 people every day,'' he said. ``thirty percent of them come with crazy ideas. he just says, `yes, yes. we'll think about it.' that's how things work in israel.''
the offer appeared to be the one mentioned in a september 1985 memo to attorney general edwin meese iii. the memo referred to an arrangement between peres and rappaport ``to the effect that israel will receive somewhere between $65 million and $70 million a year for 10 years.''
the memo from meese friend e. robert wallach, rappaport's attorney, also states, ``what was also indicated to me, and which would be denied everywhere, is that a portion of those funds will go directly to labor,'' a reference to the political party peres leads
the wallach memo has become the focus of an investigation into whether meese knew of a possibly improper payment. peres has denied any wrongdoing and has denounced the memo as ``complete nonsense.''
the israeli official said rappaport, a native of israel and a close friend of peres, relayed the offer to peres earlier in september
peres thought the offer was unimportant. for him, the most important thing was to have an iraqi oil port near israel's border,'' the official said
the thinking was that this would put iraq in a position where it would not be able to wage war with israel, out of concern for its pipeline.''
a person answering the telephone at rappaport's swiss residence said he was out of town and could not be reached for comment
sailors from an american guided-missile cruiser risked their lives in a three-hour operation to free a 30-ton sperm whale tangled in fishing nets in the arabian sea, u.s. officials said tuesday
at one point, lt.j.g. james m. syvertsen of wading river, n.y., rode the back of the 40-foot mammal like ``something out of a rodeo'' while cutting the nylon cords, according to a navy news release issued in manama
he was one of four divers who went into the water to cut the nets loose in the dangerous operation sunday
in the end, the female whale was freed and swam off, with one last piece of line dangling ``like dental floss'' between its teeth, according to capt. clinton j. coneway, skipper of the cruiser truxtun.
through the ordeal the whale made no attempts to harm the swimmers. it seemed that she knew they were trying to help,'' said coneway. ``all in all it was a most unusual and rewarding way to spend a sunday afternoon. jacques cousteau would be proud.''
the rescue occurred after crewmen aboard a helicopter from the nuclear-powered carrier enterprise spotted the whale floating listlessly. the helicopter was on a routine patrol and the crew dropped smoke flares to mark the spot for the truxtun, which was 30 miles away
the two ships are part of a u.s. battle group that arrived in the arabian sea earlier this month to support naval operations in the persian gulf
the helicopter crewmen said they thought the whale was dead until they ``saw water spouting from its blowhole,'' according to petty officer james cox, a rescue specialist aboard the helicopter
rear adm. guy zeller, commander of the enterprise's escort group, ordered the truxtun to the scene
its crew used grappling hooks to snag the net and pull the tired animal next to the ship where they worked to remove the net. the navy said the nylon net was a type used by fishermen in the area, but it was ``of unknown orgin.''
curtis michitsch of reno, nev., was lowered in a sling to cut the nets
when he became exhausted, he was replaced by seaman gerald samples of wilbur, neb
although they appeared to have nearly freed the whale, which swam a short distance away, coneway said he feared the animal still might not survive because of the the remaining nets and he dispatched a whaleboat to overtake it
syvertsen, one of two volunteers, became entangled in the net for about 15 minutes, and finally was relieved by seaman adam webber, a rescue swimmer from portland, maine, who finished the task
coneway said he doubted at first his sailors would be able to free the whale from the ``tangled mess,'' but ``i completely underestimated the ingenuity, perseverance and courage of truxtun's swimmers and deck force.''
about 5,000 lawyers marched on parliament on wednesday to demand the ouster of india's top policewoman, and they vowed to continue a strike that began because police handcuffed a lawyer who allegedly rifled a woman's purse
the lawyers voted by show of hands to keep up their paralyzing boycott of new delhi's district courts and india's supreme court, which has been shut since feb. 15
the dispute also closed courts around the country monday when an estimated 500,000 lawyers struck in sympathy for their new delhi colleagues. that strike also continues
the object of their ire is kiran bedi, a deputy police commissioner who has a reputation for stepping on toes. she made headlines last year by arresting a member of parliament for violating curfew laws
the continuance of ms. kiran bedi in her official position is detrimental to the interests of justice,'' the lawyers said in a petition to the government
she has struck a blow at the independence of the judiciary, which we will not allow, '' protest leader gobinda mukhoty told the lawyers' demonstration
home minister buta singh on wednesday rejected demands to suspend ms. bedi, 38
the controversy began jan. 4 when students at a college caught a man who allegedly rifled a female student's purse
he was handed over to police and taken in handcuffs to district court, where he identified himself as rajesh agnihotri, a new delhi lawyer
angry district court lawyers went on strike the following day to protest the handcuffing of a colleague and demanded the suspension of the police officers involved
on jan. 21, striking lawyers picketed the office of ms. bedi, who has jurisdiction over the agnihotri district, where the arrest took place
police charged the corridors with bamboo clubs to disperse the barristers, injuring 13 lawyers. the following day, the high court bar association joined the strike, and the supreme court lawyers followed suit on feb. 15
the lawyers say that ms. bedi was responsible for ordering police to charge them with clubs. but they underestimated her public support. more than 1,000 people demonstrated in her favor on feb. 17
ms. bedi was the first female member of the indian police service, the training ground for senior officers
in the past, she has booked several senior officials and politicians for traffic violations in the indian capital, where such minor indiscretions by the powerful are routinely ignored
ms. bedi has been uncharacteristically silent on the lawyers' strike and her office has refused to comment. she met with lawyers on the eve of the national strike in an unsuccessful pitch to call it off
lawyer ram jethmalani said the issue goes beyond the recent handcuffing incident
we are against this officer because she represents an evil principle, the arrogance of the executive,'' he said
jethmalani, considered one of india's best criminal lawyer, said the strike would cause difficulties to litigants
i want the people to suffer a little inconvenience. this show of solidarity will help us serve the people better,'' he said
but new delhi's largest daily newspaper, the hindustan times, rendered a different verdict
the lawyers must plead guilty to the charge of having ignored their obligation to the clients and the society at large,'' it said
margaret thatcher rebuked ireland on tuesday for conducting its own investigation of the death of a man killed by a gunshot from a british army observation post just inside northern ireland
the prime minister said she did ``not think it right or possible'' under the 1985 anglo-irish agreement for the irish republic to investigate the shooting sunday of aidan mcanespie, 23, in the british province
during the house of commons question-and-answer period, she declared: ``the irish government can inquire into anything they wish, but not of course into matters north of the border.'' the anglo-irish accord gives ireland an advisory role in the northern ireland affairs in an effort to redress grievances of roman catholics in the protestant-dominated province
mrs. thatcher's remarks appeared likely to worsen relations, already strained by disputes that include britain's refusal to prosecute police officers involved in the shooting deaths of six unarmed catholics in 1982
the british army also disclosed tuesday that a soldier given life in prison for the shooting death of a catholic in belfast had been freed and returned to his regiment after serving three years
reports that pvt. ian richard thain was back in uniform, although not in northern ireland, provoked sharp responses from leaders of the province's catholic minority
thain was convicted of fatally shooting thomas reilly, road manager of the pop group bananarama, on aug. 9, 1983. he claimed in court that he fired because riots were going on and he believed reilly was about to pull a gun
the judge found him ``deliberately untruthful.'' thain was the first soldier sentenced to life in prison for actions in northern ireland
an army statement said thain was 18 at the time and, ``while the army in no way condones his action, we consider the incident to have been a tragic error of judgment made by a young man in very difficult circumstances.''
the home office said thain was released on a life license, a form of parole under which he can be returned to prison ``should his behavior give rise to concern.''
a security cordon ringed the town of aughnacloy for mcanespie's funeral tuesday. he was buried across the border in the irish republic
the irish government sent eugene crowley, deputy police commissioner, to the border town of monaghan to investigation mcanespie's death. protestant politicans called the irish inquiry unwarranted interference by a foreign government in northern ireland's affairs
mcanespie supported sinn fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed irish republican army. he was killed by a bullet from a british army observation tower at a checkpoint near aughnacloy in county tyrone, half a mile from the border
relatives said he was walking to a weekly gaelic football game and had passed through the checkpoint
press association, the british domestic news agency, said the soldier told interrogators the shooting was an accident. he was in military custody tuesday. and tighten; restores ap logo. picks up 14th graf pvs, ``jay naidoo ...''</note>
the government on wednesday banned political activity by 18 opposition groups, including the nation's largest anti-apartheid organization and its biggest union federation, in the most sweeping crackdown in a decade
anglican archbishop desmond tutu said the move would be seen by many government opponents as a ``declaration of war.''
law and order minister adriaan vlok, however, said the regulations ``will contribute to a climate of stability, peaceful coexistence, and good neighborliness among all population groups.''
vlok's order prohibits the united democratic front, which represents more than 2 million members, from any activity except bookkeeping and court action. the same order was applied to 16 other groups, covering most of the large militant black political groups in south africa
it gives vlok the power to prohibit any organization ``from carrying on or performing any activites or acts whatsover.''
security police notified at least nine udf members of restrictions on their activities, which included being confined to home and prohibited from speaking publicly
udf co-president archie gumede was prohibited from participating in any udf activities and banned from speaking to journalists
albertina sisulu, the other co-president, was ordered confined to her home from 6 p.m. to 5 a.m., prohibited from participating in activities of the udf and other organizations, and barred from addressing meetings of more than 10 people
we are all peaceful organizations trying to unite the people. ... is this the way of reform? ... we dare say the government is declaring war on the people of south africa,'' mrs. sisulu told reporters. she said she wasn't sure if she was prohibited from speaking to the press
the 750,000-member congress of south african trade unions was ordered to stick to labor issues and barred from political activities, such as advocating holidays with special meaning to blacks and calling for the release of detained union members
anti-apartheid activists had anticipated a crackdown this year, suggesting that president p.w. botha's national party government would seek to blunt criticism from the extreme right in advance of parliamentary by-elections next week
the union and several of the affected organizations said they would consider legal action to challenge the regulations
the government's idea of reform is to smash all effective possible political opposition in the country, no matter how peaceful and lawful, and to rule with a jackboot,'' said tutu, who won the nobel peace prize in 1984 for his fight against south africa's system of racial segregation
tutu appealed to the united states and other western countries to intensify economic pressure on south africa, saying that if they do not act, ``then god help us.''
in washington, state department spokesman charles redman said the government was ``appalled'' at the restrictive measures
this is a giant step backward for south africa,'' redman told reporters
jay naidoo, general-secretary of the trade union federation, said, ``the closing of the avenues of democratic expression will possibly lead to an escalation of civil conflict and violence. there cannot be a peaceful resolution of south africa's crisis without freedom of expression and association, and without credible organizations which can articulate the needs and interests of the majority
vlok said the groups being acted against had encouraged civil disobedience and rebellion, advocated alternative structures to replace official ones, and waged campaigns of intimidation
all the groups denied wrongdoing
in addition to the udf, groups affected by the ban include:
_ the azanian people's organization, the largest group espousing the black consciousness philosophy pioneered by steve biko, the activist who died in police custody in 1977
_ the national education crisis committee, which has promoted a ``people's education'' philosphy in which black communities would exercise greater control over their schools
_ the detainees parents support committee, which monitors detentions and provides support for relatives of people detained without charge
_ the soweto civic association, the main anti-apartheid community group in the country's largest black township and a key factor behind the rent boycott that has persisted there for nearly two years
others included regional and national youth and community organizations and the release mandela committee, a group campaigning for the release from prison of african national congress leader nelson mandela
the outlawed anc is the main group fighting to oust south africa's white-led government. under the government's system of apartheid, the nation's 26 million blacks have no voice in national affairs, and the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate schools and districts
it must be friday because the disney channel is looking for youngsters who look like the original mousketeers for a movie about the start of ``the mickey mouse club'' in 1955
on the syndicated show, which lasted until 1959, friday was ``talent roundup day.''
the producers are looking for kids who look like annette funicello, darlene gillespie, tommy cole and all the other original mousketeers
the search begins friday in dallas, goes to radio city music hall in new york on march 5, to chicago on march 19 and los angeles on march 26. parents can also send their children's photos to mousketeer casting, disney studios, 500 s. buena vista, burbank, calif., 91521
