bulgaria and turkey signed a protocol on good neighborly relations tuesday in an apparent effort to resolve their bitter dispute over bulgaria's estimated 1 million ethnic turks
the text of the protocol, as released by the yugoslav state news agency tanjug, was a clear indication that the two feuding neighbors are determined to normalize relations after years of discord
the signing averted a clash between the two countries at the balkan foreign ministers' meeting opening here wednesday
earlier, sources said the turkish delegation was planning to raise the issue of the ethnic turks, who were forced by bulgarian authorities to adopt bulgarian names. the sources spoke on condition of anonymity
the ``bulgarization campaign'' began in 1984 and reportedly led to violent clashes between the turkish population and bulgarian police. it was first reported by turkish newspapers and was later confirmed by western diplomats and amnesty international
foreign ministers peter mladenov of bulgaria and mesut yilmaz of turkey signed the protocol at a meeting in a belgrade hotel, said tanjug
mladenov and yilmaz arrived in belgrade on tuesday for the first meeting of foreign ministers from six balkan countries. the other participants come from albania, greece, romania and yugoslavia
neither the protocol nor the two ministers in news statements mentioned bulgaria's turkish minority, whose existence has so far not been acknowledged by bulgarian officials in public
the protocol we have just signed does not solve the problems, but i am convinced that it will serve as a sound basis for seeking positive solutions to the existing problems,'' mladenov was quoted as saying
tanjug quoted yilmaz as saying the protocol ``makes it possible for us to develop and settle a number of issues of our bilateral relations.''
the protocol, as reported by tanjug, provides for a joint working group ``with a view to finding a solution to the existing problems in bilateral relations, the area of humanitarian cooperation included.''
it said, ``another high-level working group shall be established to determine specific measures to speed up cooperation ... in the field of economics, trade, tourism, technology, transport, communications and culture.''
under the protocol, the two countries' foreign ministers are to make periodic visits to the other country and ``review the activities'' of the two working groups with regular political consultations between the two foreign ministries
a similar protocol between the two countries was signed in 1975
spanish officials and leaders of the basque separatist organization eta established preliminary contacts in algeria tuesday that could lead to a cease-fire, spain's national efe news agency reported
it said the resumption of talks between the government and eta leaders living in exile in algeria might bring an end to 20 years of violence that has convulsed the three basque provinces in northern spain and spilled over into the rest of the country
last friday, government spokesman javier solana told reporters socialist prime minister felipe gonzalez was willing to resume the talks, broken off after a dec. 11 car bombing at a civil guard barracks in zaragoza that killed 11 people
he said the eta appeared to be respecting a 60-day truce it offered jan. 28 in return for a resumption of the talks
efe, citing unnamed algerian sources, said chief negotiators at the talks in algeria were eugenio etxebeste, an eta leader, and julen elgorriaga representing the government
the government made no comment on the efe report. solana said last week the news media ``should not expect daily updates'' on the progress of any future talks
eta is an acronym in the basque language that stands for homeland and liberty
since taking up arms in 1968, the group has claimed responsibility for killing more than 600 people in its campaign for independence for the basque area. most of the victims were police and military officers
gonzalez acknowledged in august that his government had made contacts with eta leaders in algeria in an attempt to secure a cease-fire as a basis for future talks
the government has said it is prepared to discuss when, where and how eta guerrillas will lay down their arms and possible pardons for jailed eta members not directly involved in attacks
according to various reports, eta still seeks greater political autonomy for the basque region that would include predominantly basque parts of neighboring navarre province
the el pais newspaper said gonzalez was expected to discuss the contacts with eta in his annual state-of-the-nation address to parliament wednesday
but it reported government sources said gonzalez probably would warn there could be breakdowns during arduous negotiations and no guarantee of success
police stormed a social welfare department office in a cloud of tear gas wednesday and rescued eight hostages who had been held nine hours by a man with a cleaver
one policeman was slightly injured but the eight hostages were unharmed. the hostage-taker, identified only as shum, 44, was hospitalized with head injuries
reports from the scene said shum was homeless and had applied to the office for public assistance. he went there tuesday afternoon armed with a cleaver and two knives and demanded to see the person handling his application, police reported
when he was told the person was not in, shum argued with the staff, who called the police. he locked himself and the employees inside the office until police broke the door down
robert yiu, a police spokesman, said officers made their assault at about 1:45 a.m
sen. bob dole, the gop winner of the south dakota primary and minnesota caucuses, now has 60 delegates to the republican national convention, one fewer than vice president george bush
the kansas senator got all 18 of the national convention delegates from south dakota by winning 55 percent of the vote. dole was the only candidate to win more than 20 percent of the vote, the minimum necessary under state gop rules to win any delegates
former television evangelist pat robertson came close, but with 99 percent of the precincts reporting, he finished at 19.6 percent, just shy of the threshold
the democratic primary in south dakota, which missouri rep. richard gephardt won with 44 percent of the vote, was non-binding
party leaders in the state say they feel an obligation to honor the voters' wishes. nevertheless, the results must first be ratified by a statewide caucus on march 12 to have any effect on how south dakota's 15 pledged delegates to the democratic national convention will be awarded
if the caucus accepts the results of the primary, gephardt would gain nine delegates, and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis would win six. none of the other democratic candidates on the ballot received at least 15 percent of the vote, the minimum needed under party rules to claim any delegates
following bush and dole on the republican list so far is rep. jack kemp of new york with 35 delegates and robertson with eight. ten are uncommitted. those totals include delegates allocated in michigan, kansas, pennsylvania, new hampshire, guam and south dakota
in all, 2,277 delegates will attend the gop national convention in new orleans next august, and 1,139 are needed to win the nomination
in minnesota, dole won a straw poll taken in the republican caucuses, but that has no binding effect on how the state's 31 gop national convention delegates will be allocated among the candidates. that will not be decided until minnesota republicans pick 24 national convention delegates at congressional district conventions in mid-april and choose the remaining 7 delegates at the state convention in mid-june
minnesota democrats will have to sort their way through a mountain of paper ballots that will come in from tuesday's precinct caucuses before the allocation of their national convention delegates can be calculated
the figures from the tuesday night caucuses represented an informal poll of the presidential preferences of the delegates elected to attend the county conventions. that poll had no binding effect, and the county convention delegates will be expected to follow the results tallied from the separate paper ballots
state party leaders do not plan to count those ballots before march 8, under an agreement worked out with the national party, which had objected to minnesota democrats holding their caucuses so early in the season
democratic national delegate totals remain unchanged by tuesday's events
dukakis has 44.5, gephardt has 39, simon has 33, gore has 10.55, jackson has 9.8, and 278.4 are uncommitted. those totals include delegates allocated in iowa and new hampshire, as well as the results of an associated press survey of party leaders who automatically will hold seats as convention delegates
in all, the democratic national convention next july in atlanta will include 4,162 delegates, and 2,082 are needed to win the nomination
about 80,000 people joined hands to form a 42-mile link through the industrial ruhr valley tuesday to protest the loss of jobs in the steel industry, union organizers said
after spending hours forming their line, the demonstrators joined hands for about 15 minutes, according to the ig metall labor union
thousands of people held flares and banners calling for aid to unemployed steelworkers, while church bells pealed throughout the area
police said they could not confirm that the human chain ran unbroken for 42 miles and they did not provide a crowd estimate
traffic was disrupted on main roads during much of the evening
the demonstrators formed their line from the krupp steel works in duisburg-rheinhausen in the western ruhr region to the hoesch-westfalen steel works in dortmund
tens of thousands of steel workers are scheduled to be laid off, retrained or retired early because of the expected closure of steel plants
an italian newspaper said tuesday that the chief of afghanistan's diplomatic mission in italy, reported missing since last week, defected to the west with american help
the foreign ministry confirmed that the afghan embassy reported last thursday that charge d'affaires mohamed nazir fedaiy, 43, had ``disappeared.''
but a ministry spokesman declined comment on the front-page report in the turin newspaper la stampa that the diplomat defected with his wife and was flown to another european country with the help of u.s. intelligence agents
the state-run rai-tv, without giving attribution, said the envoy was probably being held under the protection of american agents, possibly in the united states
a spokeswoman for the u.s. embassy said she had no comment on the case
the officials spoke on the condition of anonymity
la stampa said fedaiy had sought to defect for some time and a few weeks ago met with a representative of the former king of afghanistan and offered him information on his country
former king mohammad zaher shah, deposed 14 years ago while vacationing in italy, has been mentioned as possibly playing a role in a peace settlement in afghanistan. he lives in exile in rome
