injected sedatives hastened the death of an 83-year-old woman whose severed head was frozen in hopes she could someday be restored to life with a new body, officials said wednesday in classifying the case as a homicide
the riverside county coroner's office, after reviewing the results of extensive toxological tests on the tissues of dora kent's headless body, said she was given a lethal dose of a barbiturate shortly before her death in early december
the coroner has classified the death as the result of a homicide due to the administration of medicinal drugs which assisted kent's death,'' supervising deputy coroner dan cupido said wednesday
those involved in the attempt to preserve mrs. kent's head for eventual resurrection denied the coroner's office charge, saying the drug was administered after she died as part of their effort to preserve the brain
the coroner's office amended its death certificate tuesday, referring the case to the riverside county district attorney's office, where it is now under investigation. the original death certificate did not state a cause of death pending further tests
deputy district attorney curt hinman said the tests indicated mrs. kent was alive when the drugs were administered. the sedatives pentobarbital and secobarbital were found throughout the woman's system, including her liver, kidneys and bone marrow, and investigators concluded her body had metabolized the drugs, he said
we think they gave it (the drug) to her before she was dead,'' hinman said
but mrs. kent's son, saul, 48, said wednesday the allegations of homicide were ``smear tactics'' to discredit the alcor life extension foundation, a cryonics lab here
kent is a strong supporter of the cryonics movement, which believes bodies or heads may be stored at subfreezing temperatures and then brought back to life through future advances in science
mrs. kent had been living in a riverside nursing home, but on dec. 9, her physician, dr. steve harris, determined that she was gravely ill. based on that information, kent moved her from the home to alcor
kent said his mother was maintained there briefly on a respirator before dying dec. 11. her head was surgically removed soon afterward
alcor spokesman carlos mondragon said the drug nembutol was given to mrs. kent after the death. her son explained barbiturates are given immediately after death to slow damage to the brain from lack of oxygen. and another alcor official, michael darwin, said cardiopulmonary resuscitation was also given after death to distribute the drugs throughout her system
kent said the foundation had previously explained those methods and the use of drugs in its notes regarding his mother's preservation
now suddenly to come up and say that they think it's homicide is kind of absurd,'' he said. ``i was there and she died of natural causes and then the procedure was started.''
but cupido said the drugs ``expedited dora kent's death.''
the death certificate amendment states mrs. kent died between dec. 9 and dec. 11, cupido said
mrs. kent's death has been under investigation since the coroner's office learned of it. she died at alcor's lab in riverside, where a body and six other heads are frozen in liquid nitrogen
no doctor was present when she died, which prompted the coroner's office to investigate her death. the location of her head has been kept secret by her son and alcor officials, despite a coroner's request to examine it
a judge earlier this month blocked the coroner from disturbing any of the frozen remains at alcor. rally; picks up 21st graf, ``street demonstrations ...''</note>
the kremlin on wednesday installed an armenian as the communist party chief of a disputed territory in an apparent effort to end ethnic protests in soviet armenia that a dissident said involved 200,000 people
soviet authorities also ordered an end to the unrest
protesters in yerevan, the armenian capital, want the nagorno-karabakh region in neighboring azerbaidzhan turned over to armenia, smallest of the soviet union's 15 republics
in another apparent concession, moscow radio said armenian party leaders would ask the central committee in moscow to discuss nagorno-karabakh in a meeting on nationality policy. no such meeting has been scheduled, but soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev proposed one last week
yerevan was the scene tuesday and wednesday of industrial strikes, school boycotts and public demonstrations said to be the largest in the soviet union's 70-year history
in the baltic republic of estonia on wednesday, there was a rally on an national anniversary day, with demonstrators shouting ``get the russians out!'' according to a dissident
the demonstrations were the latest in a recent burst of ethnic conflicts in a huge nation that stretches from europe through asia and encompasses more than 100 nationalities, under a central government dominated by ethnic russians
paruyr ayrikyan, an armenian activist who spent 17 years in labor camps and internal exile for national activities, said 200,000 people gathered in the central square of yerevan
he said in a telephone interview that they chanted ``we want a session!'' _ demanding that a special session of the republic's legislature decide whether nagorno-karabakh should become armenian
western reporters could not travel to yerevan immediately, and telephone contact was not always possible
about 150,000 people, most of them armenians, live in nagorno-karabakh, the disputed autonomous region in the caucasus mountains whose 1,760 square miles make it smaller than delaware. annexation would increase armenia's area by 14 percent and its population, about 3.4 million, by 4 percent
last fall, armenian sources said more than 2,000 ethnic armenians marched in the region, just north of turkey, to protest mistreatment by azeris, the dominant ethnic group in azerbaidzhan
the party central committee has declared nagorno-karabakh should remain part of azerbaidzhan, which caused armenian protests and began an argument about whether the party has the right to decide such issues
in a dispatch wednesday night, the official news agency tass said the regional party organization named a 56-year-old armenian, genrikh pogosyan, party leader in nagorno-karabakh
while tass said pogosyan was armenian and born in nagorno-karabakh, it did not give the nationality of his predecessor. the surname of the former leader, boris kevorkov, indicates he is russian or azeri
the agency also referred to a ``passive, wait-and-see attitude of the autonomous region's party and government bodies whose leadership had displayed a superficial approach to evaluating the . .. situation and the existing sentiments
tass said party leaders plan to take all necessary steps to restore order in yerevan, effectively declaring an end to the dispute
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov confirmed there were mass demonstrations in yerevan. he described them as peaceful and said he did not know the number of protesters
arikyan, the armenian activist, said protesters were angered by central committee interference in a territorial question, which he said the soviet constitution defines as a matter for the government, not the party
in a telephone interview from yerevan, he said major industries were crippled by strikes wednesday and virtually all students at colleges and technical institutes boycotted classes
ethnic tensions have arisen with increasing frequency over the past year as soviets embrace gorbachev's call for ``glasnost,'' or more openness about some social problems
another national demonstration was reported in tallinn, the capital of estonia. wednesday was the 70th anniversary of the establishment of an independent estonia, which was annexed by the soviet union in 1940
alexander podrabinek, a moscow-based dissident, said 2,500-3,000 people gathered at a tallinn landmark and shouted ``independence to estonia!'' and ``get the russians out!''
plainclothes agents photographed the demonstrators and militia surrounded them, bringing in a bus with a loudspeaker that blared music and propaganda to drown out the demonstrators. no one was detained and the demonstrators dispersed after about three hours, he said
podrabinek said he received his information from a correspondent in tallinn for the underground journal express chronicle, which podrabinek edits
earlier, tass reported there was an official rally in tallinn to protest what they considered u.s. provocation of nationalist activists
street demonstrations occurred last summer in estonia and its neighbors latvia and lithuania, which were annexed at the same time
in the central asian republic of kazakhstan, at least 3,000 people rioted dec. 17-18, 1986, in the capital, alma ata, to protest appointment of an ethnic rusian to replace a kazakh as the republic's party leader
in a tass report tuesday, the government acknowledged the unrest in armenia and said it was not in the public interest
gerasimov said the government believes ``things should remain as they are now'' in terms of which republic governs nagorno-karabakh. he said he had spoken with officials in armenia by telephone, but had no more information than that contained in media reports
izvestia, the government newspaper, recommended more public discussion of the dispute. it acknowledged a ``mass meeting'' of protesters in yerevan, student boycotts and involvement of national party figures in seeking a solution
wednesday's edition of the communist party newspaper pravda carried the tass report, but no commentary on the events
ayrikyan, who said he spoke from an apartment 100 yards from the protest site, said wednesday: ``there are at least 200,000 people in front of the opera house. i've never seen anything like it
he said two members of the central committee secretariat, vladimir i. dolgikh and anatoly i. lukyanov, arrived in yerevan on tuesday ``to calm the people'' in the city 1,100 miles south of moscow
dolgikh addressed the protesters tuesday, the armenian activist said
on wednesday, lukyanov and dolgikh asked the demonstrators to send a small delegation to party headquarters in yerevan to discuss the dispute, ayrikyan said
rep. richard gephardt echoed a george wallace refrain on wednesday, saying there is ``hardly a dime's worth of difference'' between his chief democratic presidential rivals on economic issues. republican sen. bob dole sought to slice into vice president george bush's southern support
gephardt blistered gov. michael dukakis and sen. albert gore jr., while a fourth democrat announced he would not compete in the delegate-rich round of primaries known as super tuesday on march 8. illinois sen. paul simon, reeling after a spate of poor finishes, insisted he would remain in the race but conceded he lacked the money to compete across the south
among the republicans, former television evangelist pat robertson said his christian broadcasting network once knew the whereabouts of the american hostages in lebanon and suggested they could have been rescued
the assertion drew a tart response from the white house, where spokesman marlin fitzwater said, ``why didn't he tell us where they were?''
it was the second startling comment in as many days from robertson. he suggested on tuesday that bush's campaign aides were behind the recent public disclosure of television evangelist jimmy swaggert's sexual misconduct, and said they timed the disclosure to make life difficult for another television evangelist running for president
bush denied that charge anew, saying, ``i'd like to see an apology or proof.''
the vice president shrugged off dole's solid victories tuesday night in the south dakota primary and minnesota caucuses, saying, ``you can't win them all.'' he made a flying tour through new england, where he hopes to win the maine caucuses over the weekend and the vermont primary next tuesday
but those events _ one in a state where the vice president owns a home and the other that has no bearing on the hunt for convention delegates _ drew little attention from the rest of the field
instead, other eyes turned to dixie, which is hosting most of the 20 democratic and 17 republican contests that will be held on a single day on march 8
dole campaigned in south carolina with sen. strom thurmond at his side, and said he supports legislation on textile imports that is popular in the state
i recognize that i've got to catch up,'' he said. ``but we believe there is some momentum'' after his twin wins in south dakota and minnesota
even so, a fresh poll showed just how far dole has to go
the denver post survey of southern voters showed bush favored by 54 percent of republicans most likely to vote on march 8, with dole favored by 33 percent. and the dole forces said their prospects were particularly bleak in texas, which offers the biggest single cache of super tuesday delegates
dukakis was a narrower favorite in the democratic survey, at 26 percent, with gore at 18 percent, jesse jackson at 16 percent, and gephardt at 12 percent. the poll was conducted feb. 19-21 among 759 registered voters in 13 southern states
but if gephardt's speech in waco, texas, was any indication, the fight for the region's hundreds of delegates will be intense
he said gore and dukakis seem committed to ``nothing more than redecorating the facade of the status quo.'' he charged that the approach both men have taken to the federal deficit problem ``invites a post-election round of income tax increases and federal cuts in medicare and social security.''
on the central economic issues of this campaign, there is hardly a dime's worth of difference between gov. dukakis and sen. gore,'' said gephardt
he also ridiculed dukakis's foreign policy experience, saying it consists ``almost entirely of negotiating with the governor of new hampshire over the issue of nuclear power.''
the ``dime's worth of difference'' phrase was a reminder of former alabama gov. wallace's third party campaign theme of 1968, when he used it to sneer at the major party nominees
dukakis' initial response was made by campaign aide leslie dach
we welcome a comparison of the candidates' records but first we need to know which of dick gephardt's records he's talking about,'' he said
mike dukakis is the only candidate in this race who's balanced budgets, put people back to work and lowered taxes five times in five years.''
there was no immediate response from gore, who ridiculed dukakis and gephardt as ``two peas in a pod... i don't see either one of them to stand out as a principal challenger.'' gore has based his candidacy on making a strong showing in his native south
simon announced his scaled-back campaign at a news conference in washington, saying, ``there's no sense in fooling myself'' about his chances for success in the south
simon said he would concentrate on the primary in his home state of illinois on march 15 and the states that follow. but without prospects for delegates from the super tuesday states, his chance of winning the nomination appeared non-existent
republican also-ran jack kemp vowed he would stay the course, despite two more disappointing finishes in minnesota and south dakota
kemp's campaign has been victimized by robertson's emergence as a strong contender in the early caucus states. ``i needed to break up the idea that this is a bush-dole race,'' he said. ``this is no longer a bush-dole race.''
the world's largest black religious organization will begin construction in march on its world center headquarters, church officials announced wednesday
the $9.2 million development for the national baptist convention u.s.a. inc. is expected to be completed in april 1989, said t.j. jemison, president of the organization
more than 40,000 convention members are expected to attend dedication ceremonies two months later, he said
with 7.7 million members, the national baptist convention has grown to the point where the leadership decided we need a central headquarters from which to manage our many missions,'' jemison said
the six boards which now comprise the convention are currently located throughout the country, and to bring them all under one roof will result in a fundamental restructuring of our entire organization from which we should reap tremendous benefits,'' he said
the 75,000-square-foot building, containing a 2,000-seat chapel and crowned by a 225-foot spire, will be built on 12.5 acres near the seminary of the national baptist convention and the southern baptist convention in downtown nashville. higgins' role with defense department; picks up 5th graf pvs: ``the pro-iranian...''</note>
heavy rain on wednesday slowed the search for a kidnapped u.s. marine and forced a top u.n. official to postpone a helicopter flight to beirut to press for his release
the rain flooded citrus groves in south lebanon, where amal, the largest shiite moslem militia faction, and united nations peacekeepers have searched since lt. col. william r. higgins was abducted feb.17 near tyre, 50 miles south of beirut
an amal spokesman confirmed a report the militia captured gunmen involved in the kidnapping of higgins, a onetime aide to former u.s. defense secretary caspar weinberger and leader of a u.n. observers' group in lebanon
defense secretary frank c. carlucci, weinberger's successor, said wednesday in washington that too much was being made of higgins' role with the defense secretary's office
carlucci, responding to a question, said: ``let me point out that lt. col. higgins was a lower-ranking officer in the office of the secretary of defense, which has about 38 people in it. my principal military aide is a major general.''
lt. col. higgins' functions were mainly administrative. i think overly much is being made of this in the press and if i may say, i'd prefer to limit by comments to that because i think any further comment tends to encourage undesirable and unwise press speculation.''
the amal spokesman said the detainees had not been able to provide information on the whereabouts of higgins or the abduction's mastermind, who escaped
the pro-iranian organization of the oppressed on earth has claimed it abducted higgins and alleged he was a cia spy. u.s. and u.n. officials denied the accusation
on monday, the group released a videotaped message in which the captive recited conditions for his release _ israeli withdrawal from south lebanon, release of palestinian and lebanese detainees held by israel and suspension of u.s. diplomatic activity in the middle east
security sources in tyre said the amal search for higgins, 43, of danville, ky., was continuing
the weather has generally been against the search campaign,'' said one source, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``heavy rains and storms hamper the search by amal.''
the amal spokesman said the group arrested in the tyre region three gunmen ``who seized col. higgins and forced him into the first getaway car and three men who had monitored higgins' movements before the abduction.''
amal also captured ``the man who was supposed to transport higgins to beirut,'' he said
the seven detainees are among 42 members of the fundamentalist hezbollah, or party of god, arrested by amal in the past week
hezbollah, which is backed by iran, has supported higgins' abduction, calling him a ``filthy american.'' it claimed amal has abducted 150 of its members
hezbollah is believed to be an umbrella group for smaller factions involved in the kidnapping of 24 other foreigners missing in lebanon. the kidnapped include eight other americans
the longest-held foreign hostage is terry anderson, 40, of lorain, ohio. anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, was abducted march 16, 1985
hezbollah and amal have been vying for control of south lebanon
the amal spokesman said the group was ``coordinating efforts'' with the united nations interim force in lebanon. ``we keep unifil informed on all developments.''
the amal spokesman said his militia group, which is headed by justice minister nabih berri and backed by syria, ``supports unifil and will not permit such acts to reflect negatively on the peacekeeping force.''
higgins headed a 76-man u.n. team of observers that monitored violations of a 1949 lebanese-israeli armistice agreement along the border. the observers were attached to the u.n. forces when the nine-nation, 5,800-man force deployed in south lebanon in 1978 after an israeli intervention
the u.n. commander, lt. gen. gustav hagglund of finland, told reporters tuesday that further kidnappings of u.n. personnel would ``endanger the future'' of the peacekeeping forces. he said swedish soldiers have been ordered ``not to leave their posts or move around south lebanon alone.''
hagglund met in naqoura on wednesday with u.n. undersecretary-general marrack goulding, a u.n. source said. goulding had flown to unifil headquarters by helicopter from israel, hoping to fly on to beirut
he later returned to israel, said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity
unifil's chief spokesman, timur goksel, said only that ``mr. goulding's helicopter flight to beirut has been postponed due to bad weather conditions.''
an acquaintance of abbas hamadi testified tuesday he could not link the defendant to explosives that were smuggled into west germany
the lebanese-born hamadi is on trial of charges of masterminding the kidnapping of two west german businessmen in beirut in january 1987 in a bid to force the release of his brother, mohammed hamadi, held as a twa hijacker
abbas hamadi is also charged with smuggling liquid explosives into west germany from lebanon for possible use in terrorist attacks
rashid hage, an acquaintance of abbas hamadi's, testified that he and his three sons helped the defendant pick up suitcases from a train station in the town of merzig in mid-january 1987. but he said he did not know what was in the suitcases, nor what hamadi later did with them
on jan. 20, hage's son, ali, told the court he helped hamadi pick up the suitcases and that he suspected the luggage contained explosives
police found explosives buried in a field near merzig on jan. 27, 1987, and said hamadi had left them there
the 47-year-old hage on tuesday repeatedly denied any knowledge of hamadi's activities
in earlier testimony, hamadi was linked to the beirut kidnappings by a west german government official and by transcripts of wiretapped telephone conversations with his friends and acquaintainces in west germany
in january 1987, west german businessmen rudolf cordes and alfred schmidt were abducted separately in beirut
the abductions followed the jan. 13, 1987 arrest of mohammed hamadi at the frankfurt airport
mohammed hamadi is charged with air piracy and murder in connection with the june 1985 hijacking of a twa airliner, in which 39 people were held hostage 17 days and a u.s. navy diver was killed
schimidt was released in september, but cordes remains a hostage. another west german, ralph rudolf schray, was kidnapped in beirut jan. 27 and is still being held. authorities saying both hostages were lawyers, sted one a judge. no pickup. adds byline.</note>
a disgruntled workers' compensation recipient, waving a .38 caliber handgun, held two attorneys hostage for nearly three hours in a brooklyn office building wednesday afternoon before quietly surrendering
no one was injured in the incident, which started at the workers' compensation board around 1:15 p.m., police said. the man pulled a gun in a hearing room and grabbed the two hostages, said detective joseph mcconville, a police spokesman
the man was holed up inside the room with his two hostages until about 3:45 p.m., when he released one of them. fifteen minutes later, he turned the second attorney loose and surrendered to police, said police spokesman lt. thomas fahey
earlier, he had demanded that john johnson, a local television news reporter, come to the scene and had aired his grievances about his case to johnson. and workers' compensation board chariman barbara patton agreed to review the case, which involved a 1984 car accident that led to a settlement in december, authorities said
the two lawyers were identified as richard kelman and richard wolf. initially, police had said one of the two lawyers was an administrative law judge
one of the attorneys had represented the gunman in his workers' compensation case, said alice mcgillion, deputy police commissioner for public information
apparently, his grief is with the workmen's compensation board,'' mcgillion had said during the incident. ``we'll wait it out.''
the gunman's only demand was to meet with johnson, mcconville said. the television newsman arrived shortly before 2:30 p.m., riding in a police car with its sirens and lights on and cheered by workers in the six-story office building
the gunman complained to johnson that he was being harassed over the $20,000 settlement in his case
thirty-four oil rig workers arrived safely on land tuesday after their platform sank into the gulf of mexico, forcing them to flee in watertight capsules
the workers on the rig e-302, owned by keyes offshore inc. of sugar land, were evacuated monday night from the rig, 82 miles south of galveston, then transferred to a workboat for the trip back to galveston, said bill keyes, president of keyes offshore
the vessel radioed the u.s. coast guard about 1:15 a.m. that it had picked up the workers, said coast guard duty officer don merwin
about three hours earlier, a distress call had been relayed to the coast guard from the rig, merwin said. coast guard rescue ships were dispatched from houston, corpus christi and sabine
the accident occurred when one of the 396-foot legs of the triangular, jack-up rig punched through the gulf floor, keyes said
it resulted in bending the three legs on the rig,'' he said. ``the rig was about five feet above the water because we had not jacked up all the way.''
workers had been at the site about three hours before the accident, which happened in seconds, he said
southwesterly winds at 30 knots, causing 7- to 10-foot waves, may have contributed to the collapse, merwin said
that kind of wind, though, shouldn't have been enough to sink a rig like that,'' merwin said. the rig was capable of drilling 20,000 feet, he said
the coast guard marine safety office would investigate, he said
company spokesman bill flores said the rig appeared to be salvageable
the soviet union has bought 350,000 metric tons of u.s. corn for delivery this year under a long-term agreement between the two countries, the agriculture department said wednesday
it was the first u.s. corn sale to the soviet union since last fall, although moscow has been buying huge quantities of wheat at subsidized prices under the department's export enhancement program (eep). corn is not eligible for the subsidy
jean nollmeyer of the department's foreign agricultural service said it was the first substantial sale of corn to the soviets since last oct. 23 when u.s. exporters reported 600,000 tons. some small quantities were sold after that, she said
no selling prices or other information about the corn sale were disclosed. when subsidies are involved, the exporting firms, quantities and amounts of eep payments are shown, but not when straight cash deals are involved
under eep, private exporters are given surplus commodities owned by the department's commodity credit corp. so they can sell a foreign buyer wheat or other authorized commodity at competitive world prices
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. the 350,000 tons of corn would be about 13.8 million bushels
corn prices recently have been averaging about $1.82 per bushel at the farm level, meaning that the sale could have a farm value of around $25 million
the corn is part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
with the latest purchases, the soviets now have bought a little more than 2 million tons of corn, or just half of the minimum amount specified by the agreement
by comparison, the soviet union has bought more than 6.3 million tons of wheat at subsidized prices, plus 800,000 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal for delivery this year
panamanian president eric arturo delvalle has indicated to associates that he may be ready to break his close links to military strongman manuel antonio noriega, according to u.s. officials
the officials, in interviews this week, said any such move would narrow further noriega's base of support and possibly hasten his demise as panama's dominant political force
the reagan administration looks upon noriega as the principal obstacle blocking its goal of an eventual transition to elected, civilian-led rule in panama
the officials, who asked not to be identified, said delvalle has privately expressed his intention for many weeks to distance himself from noriega, but they recognize that such a step would require considerable courage
we get information from all sorts of sources, including friends and relatives, that he is about to do something along these lines,'' one official said. congressional sources, also insisting on anonymity, said they have heard the same reports
since last summer, the administration has been publicly encouraging panama's military officers to withdraw from politics as a means of promoting a return to rule by civilians. in the meantime, much of the u.s. aid program to panama has been suspended and panama has expelled all american aid personnel
two federal indictments against noriega on drug trafficking charge added a new dimension to the already strained relationship. the indictments, handed down in florida earlier this month, portrayed noriega as a key member of an international drug-smuggling conspiracy. in congress, opposition to noriega spans the political spectrum
delvalle assumed the presidency in 1985 under circumstances that strongly suggested noriega had forced his predecessor, nicolas ardito barletta, from office
it was a constitutional succession, but delvalle has been widely perceived as no more than panama's titular head
noriega has maintained that executive authority rests with delvalle and that panama has achieved a full transition to democracy. noriega says his u.s. critics are campaigning against him for the purpose of annulling the panama canal treaties, under which the waterway reverts to panamanian control at the end of 1999
attempts to obtain comment from the panamanian embassy on delvalle's purported intentions were unsuccessful
for the united states, the stakes in panama are extraordinarily high. the administration believes that a democratic, politically stable panama offers the best assurance for the continued efficient operation of the canal
the u.s. officials noted that challenging noriega would not be an easy step for delvalle. they said the president's extensive business interests and his family could be threatened if he breaks with noriega. in addition, delvalle's health is said to be tenuous because of a heart operation
however, the officials said delvalle has become increasingly disturbed by his ties to noriega and that some of his friends have rebuffed him because of that association
delvalle also may be tempted to act because of panama's growing financial crisis. ``the country is falling apart all around him,'' said one source
lawrence chewning fabrega, a panamanian diplomat who resigned recently in protest over noriega's rule, said in an interview this week that the country's financial problems are so severe the government may not be able to meet its payroll next month
assemblies of god leaders, swamped with protests that the penalty recommended for television evangelist jimmy swaggart's moral lapses was too mild, indicated wednesday it may be stiffened
a torrent of complaining telephone calls has poured into the denomination's headquarters here, more than 3,000 of them in the past two days
there's a strong sense of moral outrage at the leniency applied in this case,'' said the rev. howard cummings of aurora, colo., who said he got that assessment from two of the denomination's top executives
a special meeting was called for thursday of the church's 13-member executive presbytery, which rules on such matters, to examine the louisiana state presbytery's recommendation that swaggart be suspended from preaching for three months and undergo two years' rehabilitation
swaggart, known for his harsh denunciations of sexual lapses in his worldwide tv preaching, was charged with such an offense himself, although details have not been specified
photographs showing swaggart with a prostitute reportedly were given to church officials by rival evangelist marvin gorman, who filed a $90 million suit charging swaggart with unjustly accusing him of numerous sexual affairs
an unidentified new orleans prostitute said on abc-tv tuesday night that she had had sex with swaggart, while other reports described the case as involving ``pornographic'' activity
a suburban new orleans sheriff said wednesday that a tattooed prostitute with an arrest record in louisiana, florida and tennessee is believed to be the woman photographed with swaggart last october
jefferson parish sheriff harry lee told the state-times that the 28-year-old woman was rumored to be in florida on thursday. he said he has a warrant for her arrest for failure to show up for a dec. 9 hearing on a soliciting for prostitution charge
the likelihood that swaggart's penalty may be extended came in official word that the issue was expected to be turned back to the louisiana district, which had proposed the penalty, for reconsideration
that is the prescribed procedure under church bylaws for getting a punishment revised if it is deemed inadequate
if the matter is returned to the state district, a final decision may not come for several weeks, said juleen turnage, the denomination's information officer
church sources also said the louisiana district, in announcing its decision tuesday, had violated a church bylaw that such recommendations are not to be disclosed until approved by top officials
it created tremendous pressures, appearing that the louisiana district was trying to dictate its judgment,'' cummings said
it was learned that some members of swaggart's board are on the louisiana district council, and did not abstain from participating in the case
asked whether the $12 million that swaggart contributes annually to the denomination might have been a factor in the louisiana handling of case, ms. turnage said, ``it won't affect the decision here.''
the church's final verdict, when it comes, will be in accord with ``the seriousness of the offense,'' ms. turnage said
an unwritten church precedent is that those involved in sexual offenses are barred from preaching for at least a year. ``it's never been less than a year,'' she said
ms. turlage said a ``high percentage'' of those calling the church about the louisiana district's proposal ``were not pleased.''
a lot of people are unhappy with the initial recommendation,'' said the rev. richard champion, editor of the denomination's weekly, pentecostal evangel. but he added, ``many thought it too light. some thought it too severe.''
cummings, pastor of 2,000-member first assemblies of god church in aurora and former district presbyter, said protests at the lightness of the sentence had come from overseas as well as across the united states
pastors and leaders are deeply concerned about the adverse effects on young people and church efforts to teach them moral principles,'' he said, as well as on the ``image of the church and american christianity'' generally
most pastors take their marriages seriously,'' he said, and to ``give approval to this sentence is to say we're soft on sin.''
he said some overseas leaders have demanded immediate cutting off of swaggart's overseas broadcasts
the denomination has 2 million members nationally, and about 16 million in autonomous assemblies churches overseas
nobody is out for blood, or after swaggart's hide,'' cummings said. he said most want the case handled not only with compassion and forgiveness, but ``with a sense of accountability'' for conduct
a communist official who monitors religious affairs indirectly attacked thursday a group of roman catholics who organized a petition to the government signed by more than 300,000 believers
deputy culture minister frantisek jelinek said ``so-called activities we have witnessed in recent days not only do not explain accurately (church problems), but essentially damage'' their solution
jelinek oversees church affairs in the czech republic
the 31-point petition, said by knowledgeable religious activists to have garnered 243,000 signatures in slovakia and about 100,000 in the czech lands, demands separation of church and state, more religious education and permission for priests and bishops to fill vacant positions in 10 dioceses
it gained support from cardinal frantisek tomasek and was signed by far more people than any other document of its kind in 40 years of communist rule in czechoslovakia
authorities were slow to comment on the petition, which has circulated since late december. an article in the communist party daily rude pravo last saturday, however, attacked some points as unconstitutional, while admitting that some demands, such as the one for more bishops, were ``natural.''
in reporting jelinek's remarks, the state news agency ctk did not quote him as mentioning the petition. but the comments appeared directed at petition organizers, who have been attacked in the state-run media
jelinek was speaking in the moravian capital of brno to leaders of the government-sponsored pacem in terris group, a priests' organization not recognized by the vatican
in prague, an official at the state office for church affairs said talks between the communist authorities and the vatican on filling vacant sees will not resume for at least one month. the two sides met last month but did not report progress
the official spoke on condition of anonymity
the government favors pacem in terris candidates to fill the vacant sees. the vatican wants other candidates. no new bishops have been named in czechoslovakia since 1973
no official statistics are kept on the number of believers in czechoslovakia, but church sources estimate the roman catholics make up about 60 percent of the 15.5 million population
interest in roman catholicism and other religions in czechoslovakia has revived in recent years, particularly among young people
in an article feb. 13, the north bohemian communist party daily pruboj attributed this to what it described as the low morals of society and suggested the new believers could not be condemned for turning to religious faith
a public show of the strength of religous belief is expected march 6 in prague during a mass for the blessed agnes, a 13th-century czech princess who became abbess of a prague convent. she is to be made a saint later this year
czechoslovakia is a federal socialist republic consisting of two nations, the czech socialist republic and the slovak socialist republic
former navy secretary james h. webb never approached defense secretary frank c. carlucci to complain about proposed navy budget cuts before webb quit in anger, carlucci told congress on wednesday
carlucci said he had heard that webb was unhappy but said webb ``never elected to come and talk to me about it.''
webb abruptly resigned monday with a public blast at carlucci for rejecting webb's proposals on the navy budget, which was reduced along with budgets for the other services to meet lowered military spending totals approved by congress and president reagan
webb will be replaced by william l. ball iii, a veteran capitol hill lobbyist for the administration
carlucci appeared before the house armed services committee to defend reagan's military budget, unveiled last week, and carlucci's decisions about how to reduce defense spending by the $33 billion total approved by reagan and congress late last year
to meet the lowered spending goals, carlucci said, he ordered reductions in ships, helicopters and other hardware and chose to retain spending for pay raises and training
carlucci pronounced himself committed to the 600-ship navy, the fleet size set by reagan shortly after he took office in 1981 when the navy had about 450 ships
carlucci ordered 16 aging frigates mothballed, which will mean that the navy will have 580 ships at the end of the current fiscal year. but carlucci also pointed out that the navy would be authorized to build 17 ships in reagan's proposed budget
as most people who've worked with me know, i function with an open door,'' said carlucci, a veteran of numerous top government jobs
he said webb ``never came to me with any protest over the budget cuts nor was i aware of his intention to resign until the letter actually landed on my desk (monday).''
carlucci was generally praised wednesday by legislators who noted that he had a difficult job, taking office late last year at about the same time the $33 billion cut was ordered. because of that reduction, the proposed pentagon budget for the next fiscal year will be $299 billion
rep. william dickinson, r-ala., ranking republican on the panel, referred to webb and noted, ``i don't understand where this fit of pique comes from...if anybody's living in fat city, it's the navy the past few years. we've worked toward a 600-ship navy, that's fine, but there's nothing magic about that.''
he criticized webb for what dickinson said was ``ill grace.''
adm. william j. crowe jr., chairman of the joint chiefs of stafff, also disputed webb's statements that the joint chiefs had opposed carlucci's plan to mothball the 16 frigates. webb said the ships should have instead been transferred to the reserves, where they could later be returned to the active fleet
crowe said didn't support putting the ships into the reserve fleet
both crowe and carlucci reiterated their warnings that u.s. security might be damaged if defense budgets are not increased
the budget ``reflects significant force structure reductions _ fewer ships, fewer aircraft, fewer weapons systems _ that have long-term implications for our national security,'' said carlucci
he added: ``we must weigh carefully our future decisions on defense budgets and programs if we are not to reverse the substantial achievements in our military forces realized at great cost over the last seven years.''
a new ``condom for females'' pioneered in europe will be tested this spring in the united states, and its developers predicted wednesday it would be a major weapon in the fight against aids and other sexually transmitted diseases
the new disposable contraceptive, made of polyurethane, resembles a condom but is worn by women, researchers said wednesday as they unveiled the device
it takes the advantages of both the male condom and the female diaphragm and gets rid of significant disadvantages,'' said mary ann leeper, head of the research team developing the device for wisconsin pharmacal co., which will market it in the united states and canada
but dr. gerald zatuchni, a gynecologist with 25 years experience in researching and developing new contraceptives, said he saw the potential for ``real problems'' with the device
i have not seen the device nor have there been any published studies that would indicate its acceptability to couples, the effectiveness of the device in preventing pregnancy or any side-effects from using the device,'' zatuchni said
the device, known in europe as a ``fem-shield'' or vaginal shield, isn't sold anywhere yet, but testing has begun in europe and is scheduled to start in the united states in march, officials said
the contraceptive consists of a soft, loose-fitting polyurethane sheath and two flexible polyurethane rings, ms. leeper said
one of the rings lies inside the sheath and serves as an insertion mechanism and internal anchor, fitting against the woman's cervix much like a diaphragm, she said. the other ring forms the outer edge of the sheath and remains outside the vagina
it is no more difficult to insert than a tampon,'' said dr. paul salmon, who helped organize tests of the device at london's middlesex hospital
the company, based in jackson, wis., said the device would provide more protection than the male condom, in part because the material is stronger than most condoms and covers a larger physical area, reducing chances of infection or exposure to body fluids
from a medical perspective, this product is likely to offer additional protection against sexually transmitted diseases,'' salmon said
it also is more convenient to use than a diaphragm, ms. leeper said, because it doesn't have to be initially fitted by a doctor and can be inserted up ``six hours before the sex act or six minutes before.''
zatuchni, a gynecology and obstetrics professor at northwestern university medical school in chicago, said the idea of a ``one-size-fits-all'' condom for women ``would be sort of ridiculous because women's anatomy varies so much.''
it would be hard to envision such a device staying on during the act of intercourse,'' he said
ms. leeper said secure and proper fitting actually would occur during intercourse
she said the company had no estimate on how much the device would cost consumers
the ``female condom'' was developed by an group of gynecologists and obstetricians headed by danish gynecologist dr. erik gregersen and his wife, bente
the device has been tested so far on 80 couples in the united kingdom, denmark and sweden, and clinical trials are continuing in europe, ms. leeper said
the world health organization also plans to conduct clinical trials in 15 countries, including brazil, thailand, singapore and african nations battling the spread of aids
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is believed to be spread mainly through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants at or before birth
researchers won't have statistics on how effective the device is in preventing pregnancy or the spread of diseases like aids until additional studies are completed, salmon said
the company hopes to apply to the u.s. food and drug administration sometime this summer for permission to begin marketing the device commercially in the united states
if everything goes as planned,'' ms. leeper said, ``this product will be available to the consumer by the end of the year.'' loans</head>
a house panel voted unanimously wednesday to approve legislation requiring additional disclosures for increasingly popular home equity loans
the measure received the full support of the eight-member house banking consumer affairs subcommittee, chaired by rep. frank annunzio, d-ill., including rep. fernand j. st germain, d-r.i., chairman of the house banking committee
similar legislation is expected to be introduced in the senate in the near future. sen. christopher j. dodd, d-conn., chairman of the senate banking consumer subcommittee, held hearings last year on the general subject of home equity loans, in which a home owner borrows money against the equity in his or her home
according to u.s. housing markets, a research survey published by lomas &amp; nettleton, the dallas mortgage banking and financial services firm, the value of new second mortgages and home equity loans were to increase to more than $150 billion by the end of 1987
home equity loans totaled $30 billion in 1981, according to the report, but topped $50 billion in 1984. the popularity of such loans began mushrooming when a new tax law took effect in january 1987 that limited the deductibility of interest on most consumer loans, but preserved deductions for home loans
the house bill, introduced by annunzio and rep. david price, d-n.c., would, among other things, put limits on a creditor's ability to terminate a home equity credit line and demand full and immediate repayment of the balance due
the measure also prohibits the creditor from unilaterally changing the terms of the home equity credit line agreement and allows states leeway to provide for additional requirements
the consumer bankers association, a group representing retail banks, savings and loans and credit unions, supported the subcommittee's action
two major consumers organizations, consumers union and the u.s. public interest research group, applauded annunzio for moving the bill out of the subcommittee but criticized the panel ``for failing to correct major abuses in the hel (home equity loan) market.''
the organizations said panel members promised to work toward changing the bill when it is considered by the full banking committee
michelle meier, counsel for government affairs with consumers union, said the present bill ``doesn't do enough to protect consumers. it doesn't prohibit some fundamentally unfair contract terms. it only makes the lenders tell you about them.'' investigation of kidnapping, quotes from officer, mother on reunion, other detail, and to correct spelling of name to vernier, sted venier. no pickup.</note>
police found 5-week-old rachael ann white on tuesday, four days after she was kidnapped by a woman answering a baby-sitter ad. the baby appeared to be in good condition, police said
we found found her, and we reunited her with her parents at 11:42 a.m. at the detective bureau,'' said lt. joe vernier. ``there were many smiles and tears throughout the investigations bureau here.''
acting on a tip through police at the air force academy, police found rachel ann abbott at a home on the north side of the city, vernier said
when i saw (rachael ann) come through the door, nothing could have made me more happy in my life _ nothing,'' said the child's mother, cora abbott, 27. officers appaluded as she and the baby were reunited
abbott had issued a nationwide plea monday for the safe return of her baby
police said maritza rentz, a psychologist, was arrested for investigation of kidnapping
it appears it was a replacement baby,'' said vernier. the suspect had a pregnancy that terminated in october, he said. he didn't say how the pregnancy ended
the child was taken from abbott's home friday morning by a woman who had come to the house in response to an ad for a baby sitter
the child's grandmother, evelyn reed, 52, asked the woman to hold the child while she answered a telephone in another room. when the grandmother returned, the child and the woman were gone
rentz's husband, capt. paul rentz, is an instructor in the air force academy's behavioral sciences department, police said
authorities said that he was being questioned but that it was not known if he was involved in the abduction
jesse jackson's campaign manager on wednesday heralded his second-place finish in the minnesota caucuses as a ``rainbow coalition'' victory and proof that the so-called electability issue is dying off
jackson got 20 percent of the vote in a state with a voting-age black population of 1 percent, proof that his appeal went far beyond the his traditionally strong base among blacks, said gerald austin
we're thrilled about what happened yesterday,'' he said
observers said there was evidence that jackson's targeting of the hard-pressed, blue collar workers may be paying off, although there were no exit polls to confirm that
austin predicted that as voting occurs in more states, people will stop talking about whether the fact that jackson is black means he can't be elected
i haven't heard it in a couple of weeks,'' he said of the electability issue
opinion polls tend to support the notion that jackson has made some strides in his effort to reach out out to whites, although this early in the election season it is not yet clear how much of that will translate into votes across the country
overall, i think he has made a slight inroad into the white vote. i do not think there's any evidence so far that it has been substantial,'' said polling associate john brennan of abc-tv's polling operation
pollster geoffrey garin of peter hart research associates said the firm's polling has consistently found ``that we're looking at very different jesse jackson than in 1984.''
the sense of polarization that was there four years ago really isn't there this time. there are obviously some white voters who are not open to jesse jackson, but the negatives and the degree of antagonism ... has really worn out over four years.''
for whites who are either strongly liberal or sort of feel ignored by the establishment, there is a real sense of sympathy for the things that jackson's been saying.''
jackson himself makes a particular point of chiding white voters who think along the lines of ``i like jackson, i like what he's saying _ but ...''
he told a ballroom full of receptive united auto workers members this week that those people ``should move from `but' to `therefore.'''
jackson edged out sen. paul simon for second place after the illinois senator had banked heavily on a good showing there
jackson also had targeted the state _ where he got only 2.4 percent of the vote in his 1984 race _ but had spent only four days campaigning there this time around, and put only about $45,000 into the state, said austin. he credited much of the success to organizing by a devoted crew of volunteers
minnesota political analyst d.j. leary said jackson's support appeared strong among liberal whites and blue collar workers. jackson has gone after union worker support across the country, travelling to many strike locations to back them, including the hormel strike in austin, minn
he was doing very well among working people,'' leary said. he said he attended a minneapolis caucus where 44 of the 134 participants supported jackson, and only one of those 44 was black
austin said jackson also got strong support from gays in minnesota. jackson had drawn a capacity crowd during a campaign appearance last week at a minneapolis church led by a lesbian pastor
in the super tuesday primaries on march 8, jackson expects also to expand his large base of black supporters into the gay community and trade union groups, austin said
nationwide, polls show jackson has his work cut out for him among white voters. a cbs-new york times poll taken last week showed jackson was the choice of 3 percent of the white voters, and 13 percent overall
in a mid-january poll, he did better, getting 6 percent among the whites polled, said cbs news director of surveys kathleen frankovic
however she noted the polls have also shown that he gets ``a clear measure of respect'' from whites, admiration for his leadership qualities, and a feeling that he cares strongly about their problems
in jackson's adoptive home state, a chicago tribune poll in mid-january showed that among 507 democratic voters, 39 percent picked him as their first or second presidential choice. the electorate is 26 percent black
among the whites, 35 said they had a impression of him, and 37 percent reported a negative impression
her mother wanted her to come home to massachusetts, but 17-year-old lenora rolle wanted to stretch her vacation in new york by just one day. it turned out to be her last
i begged and pleaded with her to come home,'' coralie rolle said after learning that her daughter had been shot to death at a party in brooklyn. ``i missed her. i wanted her back. i didn't like her being there too long. i begged her to be careful.''
it was a lack of care _ or a surfeit of trust _ that led to miss rolle's death tuesday morning, according to accounts by police
miss rolle, a senior at rindge and latin high school in cambridge, had used the money she earned as a cashier at warburton's pastry shop in harvard square to finance the trip to new york, where she stayed with aunts in the bronx
detectives say she was at the port authority bus terminal in manhattan on monday night with a 15-year-old friend, bianca, when the two were lured away from their boston-bound bus by a peddler of exotic fragrances
the man, who may have known bianca, urged the girls to come to a party at his mother's house in the brownsville section of brooklyn, and promised to pay their bus fare home
she was a good girl, but she liked to party,'' her mother said. she also said that lenora was not very streetwise
the party was in a two-bedroom apartment on the second floor of a four-story apartment building. police sgt. arthur stoecker, who is investigating the case, said at least seven people were at the party; one of those in attendance told new york newsday that there were about 15. stoecker said a few empty crack vials were found in the apartment afterward
after miss rolle arrived, police and witnesses say, she was approached by a man who demanded to have sex with her
is she for me? is this one for me?'' the man asked, according to a witness quoted by the new york post
when miss rolle refused, the man pulled out a 9mm hand-held machine gun and fired two shots into the floor, authorities said. he then forced her to undress and, as she screamed in protest, dragged her into a bedroom
the other partygoers fled in terror. ``they were fearful for their own lives,'' stoecker said
he said the witnesses tried to telephone police, but were unable to get into an apartment building across the street. a street phone was out of order, they said
after about a half-hour, they saw the gunman, still clutching his pistol, leave the building. when they entered, they found miss rolle dead
an autopsy wednesday determined that she had been shot in the back, the right thigh and the left arm, according to a spokeswoman for the city medical examiner's office, ellen borakove. fluid samples were sent to a lab to determine if miss rolle had been raped
stoecker said police were searching wednesday for michael mays, 20, a convicted felon. ``he's a suspect,'' stoecker said, although he added that ``there hasn't been an official warrant yet.''
mays served about two weeks in rikers island in 1986 on a misdemeanor sexual misconduct conviction, according to a spokeswoman for the city correction department, ruby ryles. last june he was sentenced to three to nine years in state prison after pleading guilty to attempted robbery, according to glenn goldberg, a spokesman for the brooklyn district attorney's office
criminal court records indicate the sentencing was imposed in absentia. in any case, mays never served the time. a spokesman for the state correctional services department, james flateau, said the prison system had no record of mays. goldberg said the prosecutor's records end with mays' sentencing. ms. ryles said mays never served time in city jail on the attempted robbery charge
richard gephardt opened fire wednesday on michael dukakis and albert gore, rivals in the race for the democratic presidential nomination, saying their vague positions invite a round of income tax increases and cuts in medicare and social security after the election
echoing the rhetoric of former alabama gov. george wallace in past presidential campaigns, gephardt called dukakis and gore the favorites of ``editorialists and elites'' with ``hardly a dime's worth of difference'' between them on economic issues
with the crucial super tuesday primaries and caucuses less than two weeks away, gephardt, a missouri congressman, leveled his charges at dukakis, governor of massachusetts, and gore, a senator from tennessee, who are the two he must beat march 8 to become the democratic front-runner. gephardt generally trails both in the polls in the super tuesday states
on foreign policy, gephardt said dukakis' experience ``consists almost entirely of negotiating with the governor of new hampshire over the issue of nuclear power.''
on the economy, gephardt said gore ``has talked more about what is wrong with the iowa caucus than what is wrong with the national economy.''
he accused gore of having ``no budget solution at all'' and dukakis of being off the mark by as much as $95 billion with his claim of the return on more aggressive pursuit of tax cheats
on the central economic issues of this campaign, there is hardly a dime's worth of difference between governor dukakis and senator gore,'' gephardt said in a speech. ``the gore-dukakis approach is to distract the voters from those fundamental questions _ to divert the campaign to tactics or drown it in generalities
the gore-dukakis approach is worse than an evasion. it invites a post-election round of income tax increases and federal cuts in medicare and social security _ which is the standard prescription of too many editorialists and elites,'' gephardt said
i am not their candidate. i have not been a favorite of the establishment editorialists. michael dukakis is. i have not been endorsed by the neo-liberals of the new republic. they have endorsed albert gore.''
on farm policy, trade and the idea of an oil import fee, gephardt contended: ``governor dukakis talks competence; senator gore talks strength _ but there is nothing competent or strong (about their policies).''
dukakis and gore were on the road campaigning wednesday and did not have an immediate response to gephardt's blast
but dukakis aide leslie dach said: ``we welcome a comparison of the candidates' records but first we need to know which of dick gephardt's records he's talking about.''
dach said that ``mike dukakis is the only candidate in this race who has balanced budgets, put people back to work and lowered taxes five times in five years.''
gore has ridiculed dukakis and gephardt as ``two peas in a pod. ... i don't see either one of them to stand out as a principal challenger.''
gephardt has been hitting dukakis with ads accusing him of raising taxes in massachusetts and of making ridiculous suggestions to farmers that they should diversify with crops such as blueberries and belgian endive
gephardt and dukakis have split early democratic tests, while gore has focused on super tuesday when 20 states and american samoa hold primaries and caucuses _ many of them in the south
polls across the south generally put gephardt third or fourth in the field. jesse jackson has usually been the leader in the southern surveys, but a new gallup poll conducted last week gave dukakis the lead
dukakis and gore have big campaign warchests for march 8, while gephardt's campaign has been on a slimmer budget
in austin, texas, gephardt, who won tuesday's south dakota primary, said he doesn't think gore will have much impact on the march 8 elections
albert gore has not run and won anything in any of these races (so far),'' gephardt said. ``he pulled out of iowa. he ran hard in new hampshire and got not many votes. he was very active in south dakota, probably spent more than i did and did not get many votes. i don't see this as a gephardt-gore race, i think it's a gephardt-dukakis race.''
the house ethics committee has decided to hold off introducing a resolution calling for the expulsion of 10-term rep. mario biaggi because he is involved in litigation, according to a letter released wednesday
the committee on standards of official conduct will not bring the matter berfore the house for a vote until ``an appropriate time can be established with congressman biaggi in order to allow for his particiaption in the floor proceedings,'' the letter said
biaggi, d-n.y., is appealing his conviction on charges of accepting illegal paid vacations from an old political friend and ally. he is also due to be tried on bribery and racketeering charges in the wedtech case starting march 7 in u.s. district court in new york
the ethics committee announced last week it would recommend that biaggi be expelled for violating the house code of conduct by accepting the vacations and not reporting them on his financial disclosure forms; obstructing justice; and illegally crossing state lines to accept the free trips
in a 148-page report explaining why it was recommending its most severe punishment, the 12-member committee said, ``the offenses for which representative biaggi was convicted involved criminal conduct of a most serious nature going to the heart of his representational responsibilities.''
biaggi has vowed to fight the expulsion resolution on the house floor, but his spokesman, bob blancato, said the congressman needs time to prepare his defense. he declined to say how much time
a resolution to expel must pass by a two-thirds vote of the 435-member house
the last member of congress to be expelled was rep. michael myers, d-pa., in 1980, who had been captured on videotape accepting a $50,000 bribe in the abscam sting
biaggi was convicted sept. 22 of illegally accepting a paid florida vacation from meade esposito, the former brooklyn, n.y., democratic leader. esposito was seeking government help for coastal dry dock and repair corp., a financially troubled brooklyn shipyard which owed $280,000 in premiums to esposito's insurance brokerage firm
biaggi was sentenced to 2{ years in prison and a $500,000 fine. he is free pending appeal. nagorno-karabakh and subs 4th pvs: `georgia _ a ...' to correct spelling of tbilisi. also subs 7th graf `lithuania _ five ...' to correct to vilnius sted riga</note>
here is a look at recent unrest involving some of the soviet union's more than 100 national groups:
armenia _ police broke up a demonstration in the capital, yerevan, on oct. 18, 1987, by at least 1,000 people supporting armenian national rights in the village of chardakhlu in neighboring azerbaidzhan, according to moscow dissidents. as many as 200,000 armenians demonstrated in yerevan this week to demand annexation of an area of the neighboring republic of azerbaidzhan called nagorno-karabakh, witnesses report
azerbaidzhan _ a clash between azeris, the natives of azerbaidzhan, and long-time armenian residents occurred in october in chardakhlu, according to moscow dissidents
georgia _ thousands of georgians staged an unsanctioned rally in 1979 in the capital, tblisi, to protest the omission from the republic's constitution of a phrase acknowledging georgian as the state language. about 100 people demonstrated in 1983 in the capital, tbilisi, after the arrest of two nationalist students
kazakzhstan _ up to 3,000 people rioted dec. 17-18, 1986, in the capital, alma ata, to protest the appointment of an ethnic russian to replace an ethnic kazakh as the republic's party chief. two people are killed, 200 injured and dozens arrested
crimean tatars _ members of this national group flocked to moscow in july 1987 and demonstrated in red square for the right to return to their historic homeland along the black sea. this month, the government endorsed steps to promote the culture of the crimean tatars but indicated they won't be given privileges in their homeland, from which they were expelled in 1944
lithuania _ five-hundred people gathered outside a church in the capital, vilnius, on aug. 23, 1987, to protest on the anniversary of the 1939 german-soviet pact that allowed soviet takeover of lithuania and the other formerly independent baltic states. moscow-based dissidents report that police and soldiers beat hundreds of lithuanians in vilnius as they gathered feb. 16 to mark their homeland's brief independence. a soviet spokesman denied the reports
estonia _ a group of estonian nationalists gathered in the capital, tallinn, on aug. 23, 1987, to protest the german-soviet pact. dissidents were denied permission to stage demonstrations wednesday to mark the days when their homeland declared independence from soviet russia
latvia _ five-thousand people assembled at a world war ii memorial in the capital, riga, on june 14, 1987, to mark the 47th anniversary of ``deportation day,'' when josef v. stalin sent thousands of baltic residents into exile at the time of the soviet takeover of their homelands. up to 7,000 people gathered aug. 23, 1987, at the memorial to protest the german-soviet accord, witnesses said. describing weapon. picks up 10th graf pvs, an army ... with minor editing to trim</note>
west bank villagers burned the home of a fellow arab accused of helping the israelis and lynched him after he fired on a crowd wednesday with a submachine gun, killing a 4-year-old boy and wounding 13 people, security sources said
israel radio called the event ``a serious escalation'' of 11 weeks of violence in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, and linked it to calls by the palestine liberation organization for harsh action against collaborators
a reporter for the arabic-language jerusalem newspaper al quds said residents of qabatiya village accused the man of collaborating with israeli authorities. the reporter, who spoke on condition of anonymity, identified the man as mohammed al ayad
palestinians began a general strike in the occupied territories wednesday and the army reported the first attack on israeli soldiers with explosives and firearms since riots began dec. 8
the army said a bomb exploded on a road near gaza as a military vehicle passed at about 11 p.m. tuesday and shots were fired at the soldiers, but no one was injured
secretary of state george p. shultz arrives in jerusalem on thursday to discuss a new u.s. plan for ending the unrest and reviving negotiations for middle east peace
israel radio said hundreds of residents marched to the suspected collaborator's house in qabatiya, near jenin, 60 miles north of jerusalem, and destroyed it with firebombs
security sources said the man killed the boy and wounded the others when he fired from the house at the attackers
the national itim news agency said ayad fired an uzi submachine gun and that after the shooting, people dragged him away and hanged him. security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed the report, saying the man was strung up on a utility pole
the arab-run palestine press service identified the slain boy as mohammed qassem abu zeid kmeil
an army spokesman called it a fight among arabs and said soldiers arrived later
at least 63 arabs have been killed by israelis since the violence began, according to u.n. figures. about 1.5 million palestinians live in the west bank and gaza, which israel captured from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
three arabs were shot and wounded wednesday during disturbances at the nuserat refugee camp in the gaza strip, including a 9-year-old girl, hospital officials said. several other confrontations were reported between soldiers and young arabs throwing stones and burning tires in the streets
jerusalem's police force has been strengthened for the shultz visit by 1,500 officers, to at least twice its normal size
the military also provided extra manpower at the request of jerusalem police, an army spokesman said
no details were available on the attack on the military vehicle
palestinian protesters have avoided using firearms in what they call ``the uprising'' against israel, confining themselves to throwing stones, bottles, and occasionally firebombs. several knife attacks have been reported
plo chief yasser arafat has said arms would not be used at this stage, but did not rule out using guns and explosives later
escalation of the violence could prompt an even harsher military response and might cost the arabs much of the sympathy they have won abroad
in jerusalem, police said about 20 arabs were arrested in recent days on suspicion of taking part in disturbances. all palestinians leaving silwan, an arab village inside the jerusalem city limits, were checked and searched wednesday
a senior police officer at the scene said: ``we are throwing the book at them: traffic violations, drug trafficking, not paying taxes. the people in silwan for the last two months thought they belonged to palestine. we are now teaching them they live in israel, and they will never forget it.''
amnesty international, the human rights organization based in london, urged israel to conduct a thorough investigation of human rights violations
sometimes soldiers have found themselves in the immediate context where some force was necessary, or maybe even gunfire was necessary, but in our view the step toward firing a combat rifle at people who are not themselves armed with firearms is a very big step to make,'' clayton yeo, head of research for amnesty, said on israel radio
the general strike, called for wednesday and thursday by the underground ``united national leadership of the uprising,'' appeared to be almost total
few people were on the streets in the gaza strip. in the west bank, business was at a standstill
shultz is likely to meet resistance in jerusalem, particularly from prime minister yitzhak shamir, whose right-wing likud bloc opposes the secretary's idea of trading land for peace
it also appeared shultz will not be able to meet with palestinians during his mideast shuttle between jerusalem and arab capitals. those invited say they will not confer with him because the plo has forbidden such a meeting in jerusalem
a meeting with palestinians is considered critical to the peace effort
ucla's lambda delta lambda is believed to be the nation's first sorority founded by lesbians, but the group's nine charter members say they started out to make friends, not history
when you meet someone from a sorority it's almost like a built-in friendship,'' marci kaye, one of the group's founders, said wednesday. ``we just wanted something like that that we could have, kind of a way for people to meet other people.''
officials of the sprawling university of california, los angeles, campus in westwood formally recognized lambda delta lambda as a campus organization last week
it was very validating for us,'' said sorority president allison adler, a junior creative writing major
university regulations forbid exclusion of heterosexuals who may want to join, and krisi burk, the group's spokeswoman, said lambda delta lambda hopes to sign up some heterosexual women during sorority rush week next month
if they're comfortable with us, then we're comfortable with them,'' said the 20-year-old junior political science major
she said several heterosexual women have inquired about joining, and the group hopes to at least double its membership next month
i hope people don't think our non-discriminatory policy is a paper policy because it's not,'' she said. ``i have a lot of straight friends and i'd like to see them all join.''
several lambda delta lambda members said they considered pledging traditional greek sororities before forming their own. they said they were frightened away by stories of lesbian members who had been ostracized after their sexual preferences became known
maybe i'm just paranoid, but i don't always feel comfortable about traditional sororities,'' ms. burk said
now that she's a member of her own group, she spoke excitedly as she outlined some of lambda delta lambda's plans for the weeks ahead, including participation in rush week, the spring mardi gras carnival, homecoming and other campus activities
also high on the agenda will be raising the money to rent a sorority house. the group now meets on campus
ms. burk said the sorority hopes to get more involved in political issues than most traditional greek letter organizations, including efforts on behalf of women, gays and minorities
she said the group can also serve as a support network for its gay members
we've all had family problems or at least tense moments,'' she said. ``we can help each other.''
in her case, after the group went public she decided to tell her grandparents she was a lesbian ``because i was afraid someone might ... send them a letter.'' she said they took the news well
thus far, members said, reaction to the sorority has been generally positive
yesterday in one of my classes someone approached me and said he thought it was very courageous what we were doing,'' said ms. kaye, a 25-year-old senior english major
ms. burk noted that one person did complain in a letter to the editor of the campus newspaper, the daily bruin, that if lesbians were allowed to share a sorority house it would be the same as allowing men and women to share sorority and fraternity houses. she dismissed the argument with a chuckle
it's not just a sexual thing, which of course everybody thinks it is,'' she said of the sorority. ``it's no more sexual than any collection of human beings.''
richard a. oppel, editor of the charlotte observer, and ted turner, chairman of the turner broadcasting system, were honored wednesday night with the national press foundation's awards for journalistic achievements in 1987
oppel received the george d. beveridge jr. editor of the year award for directing the observer's ``aggressive yet careful'' coverage of the jim and tammy bakker-ptl story
turner was presented the sol taishoff award for excellence in broadcast journalism for inaugurating cnn as the first 24-hour television news network
in addition, fred w. friendly, an educator, media critic and former president of cbs news, received the foundation's award for distinguished contributions to journalism
friendly's selection was based on his contributions to the quality of american broadcast journalism over more than two decades
the national press foundation is an independent, non-profit organization devoted to the support and improvement of journalism. it offers in-career training and other programs to print and broadcast journalists
the 159-nation general assembly will convene monday on the dispute between the united states and the united nations over the fate of the palestine liberation organization mission, u.n. officials said
congress passed an anti-terrorism law ordering the plo observer mission closed by march 22, despite a 1947 treaty in which the united states agreed to let official delegations function in new york, the u.n. headquarters
the legislation is really an assault on the independence of the united nations and on its integrity,'' said former u.s. attorney general ramsey clark, who has been providing legal advice to the plo
state department and u.n. officials also said closing the mission would violate the treaty under which the united states became u.n. headquarters
but attorney general edwin meese iii has reportedly said he intends to enforce the measure
what plan of action the general assembly might advance at the special session is not clear. it has already passed a resolution calling on the united states to leave the mission alone
the plo and the 21-nation arab league say the assembly may ask the international court of justice in holland for a ruling. the plo and the league have also said they may ask the assembly to move from new york to geneva if the united states closes the mission
clark said binding arbitration, as called for in the treaty, is the best way to resolve the dipute. he said the plo would bring suit in a u.s. court ``only as a last resort.''
the plo was given official observer status 13 years ago. its mission is a manhattan townhouse with a staff of three political officers and two secretaries. heptachlor</head>
a federal judge on wednesday gave the environmental protection agency until april 15 to ban the sale and commercial use of products containing an anti-termite pesticide believed to cause cancer
u.s. district judge louis oberdorfer ruled that the epa had acted illegally by allowing 197 holders of federal pesticide licenses to sell existing stocks of products containing the pesticides chlordane and heptachlor
oberdorfer said epa failed to take into account whether continued sale or use of the products ``would pose any unreasonable risk to man or the environment.''
epa scientists have concluded that chlordane causes cancer and excessive residues remain in homes even after proper application of the chemical, which is usually injected into soil around the foundations of houses
last year, velsicol chemical corp., the nation's only manufacturer of chlordane and heptachlor, agreed to stop selling the chemical while it tries to find an acceptable method of applying the pesticide
but the epa's agreement with velsicol did not cover products containing chlordane made by other companies for the retail market
epa separately agreed to allow 197 companies that hold federal pesticide licenses to sell existing stocks of their chlordane products if they surrendered their licenses
the agency estimates these companies have 1,700 pounds of chlordane products in their stocks compared with the 110,000 pounds in velsicol's inventory
the judge found that epa's decision to permit continued sale of the products ``is arbitrary, capricious and an abuse of discretion'' and violates the federal insecticide, fungicide and rodenticide act
epa spokesman albert heier said the judge's decision ``has really tied our hands on this one because it will actually result in the product returning to the market.''
if we go ahead and ban these products, they can appeal the ban,'' heier said. ``under the law, the registrants can appeal, and while it's under appeal they can manufacture and sell'' the chemicals
that 's the reason we went on the voluntary route,'' heier said. ``it will take two years to get rid of them. we thought we could get rid of them faster this way.''
jay feldman, a spokesman for the national coalition against the misuse of pesticides, one of the plaintiffs in the lawsuit against the epa, said the agency can always use its emergency powers to suspend use of chlordane
they have assumed they have no authority to use their emergency powers, and that is certainly incorrect,'' feldman said
they have simply misused their discretionary authority in this case and refused to consider emergency suspsnsion,'' feldman said
if epa believes that application of the regulatory standards in fifra results in extended product life and the only way to protect public health and the environment is to circumvent fiftra, they should be seeking statutory changes,'' feldman said
besides the coalition, the lawsuit was brought by 10 other environmental groups and two labor unions
doctors who believe any humanitarian aid to nicaraguans must help both sides in the conflict said wednesday they are seeking $20 million to set up an american hospital in the war-torn country
they want the money from congress, which is voting on a democrat-sponsored aid package thursday, but say they'll try to raise it elsewhere if necessary. the hospital proposal has been sent to congressional leaders but is not included in the democrats' plan
dr. william burman of the newly formed pan american trauma association said he and swiss dr. hansjurg holdener would be willing to work for one year in nicaragua to set up the facility which they said should include three airplanes, 10 ambulances and a 150-bed hospital to treat sandinista, contra and civilian victims
burman described the proposal as an unprecedented offer by american doctors to help the united states provide humanitarian aid to central america. he provided a list a dozen doctors supporting the project and said u.s. doctors would work in nicaragua for a salary of no more than $20,000 a year
there is no way to consider food and clothing for an army engaged in a war as humanitarian,'' said chris orsinger of the council on hemispheric affairs, which sponsored a news conference with the doctors and endorsed their project. the council describes itself as a nonpartisan supporter of democratic political processes in the western hemisphere
burman said he resigned as an assistant professor of orthopedic surgery at the state university of new york to work full-time on the nicaraguan proposal. he and holdener said they met last november with medical officials in nicaragua and toured the area where the hospital would be set up
burman said east germany, cuba and czechoslovakia all have hospitals in nicaragua, which he said are apparently open to all victims of the conflict
he said the u.s. hospital proposal was intended to ``put the united states' best foot forward in the region and express the highest ideals of medical ethics.''
wilson morris, an aide to house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said congressional leaders had seen the doctors' proposal, but funding for it it was not included in the democrats' $30.5 million contra aid measure which wright said he is confident will pass. the house narrowly defeated president reagan's proposal for $36.2 million in military and other aid to the contras three weeks ago
the democrats propose to give $14.6 million for food, clothing, medicine and shelter for the rebels and about the same amount for medical aid to nicaraguan children who are victims of the conflict. an additional $1.4 million would go for aid to miskito indians, who ended their resistance to the sandinista government earlier this month
the quintessential chanteusse, liliane montevecchi, has brought the songs, the movements, and all the atmosphere of the cosiest french cabaret to the off-broadway kaufman theater
the petite singer, with gamin face and haircut, wins the audience before she sings a note. she wears a long-sleeve, high-neck, black minidress which almost covers her black leotard, revealing slim, shapely legs in black hose and spike heels
when she sings, her voice proves even more winning. and her jolie, unflappable air delights
draping herself across the top of joel silberman's upright piano to sing what she calls ``new frangles tango,'' she says: ``this song, i have not done it yet once perfectly.'' she flubs the first line; everybody laughs, and she starts over
miss montevecchi's show, ``on the boulevard,'' which opened monday night, wisely varies its mood. she dips into bittersweet regret, a mood which fits a french singer so well _ but only does it a couple of times. and she throws herself entirely into songs, but again not too often, fervently raising temperature and volume
she has a light touch with humor and exquisite timing. introducing cole porter's ``you don't know paree,'' her voice is as beautifully inflected as any dramatic actress conveying emotion as she says, ``i have friends there. some are still there and some are gone.''
miss montevecchi's french-accented english singing has been heard here before, in ``nine'' on broadway. here, she often moves directly from one song to the next, so the audience doesn't break its french enchantement with applause
lighting by jeffrey schissler is subtle and effective. martin r. kaufman, who owns the tiny theater, with seats on two sides of the stage, is the presenter in association with jean-claude baker
the house on wednesday unanimously condemned north korea for the bombing last year of a south korean airliner that killed 115 people aboard
on a 396-0 vote the house approved the resolution, which urges ``other countries, particularly with close relations with north korea,'' to adopt sanctions and other measures against the pyongyang government
the bombing was one of the most outrageous acts of terrorism perpetrated since the end of the second world war,'' said rep. stephen solarz, d-n.y., chairman of the house subcommittee on asian affairs
kim hyun-hee, a surviving member of an alleged two-agent north korean team, confessed on south korean television that she helped plant a time bomb on korean air lines flight 858 before leaving the plane in abu dhabi. the plane exploded off burma
solarz said the united states has ``fairly persuasive'' independent evidence of north korean responsility for the bombing
britain and japan have been asked to participate in a program that would allow their subjects to visit the united states for up to 90 days without a visa, a state department spokeswoman said wednesday
a 1986 immigration law authorized the state department and immigration and naturalization service to approach up to eight countries to see if they were interested in participating in a pilot project to determine if visa requirements could be waived in some cases
britain announced earlier this week that it is interested in taking part in the program, and u.s. spokeswoman ruth van heuven confirmed that japan also has been asked to participate
current rules require all visitors, except canadians, bahamians and some mexicans, to obtain a visa to come to the united states. the normal process is for u.s. embassies to rule on visa applications and check the names against lists of people barred from entry
visitors from some nations are required to prove they have the means and the intention to go home again
the pilot program would allow tourists and business people from the two countries to come to the united states for 90 days or less without going through that process
among those for whom visas are required, britons and japanese top the list of visitors to the united states. last year, the state department issued nearly 1.2 million visas to citizens of japan and 496,000 visas to britons
those two countries also are high up on the list of countries where visa applications are rarely rejected
van heuven said the program would not go into effect until the immigration and naturalization service completes the installation of an automated arrival and departure system that would permit authorities to monitor people coming and going from the united states. a completion date for the system has not been announced
under the 1986 law, the program would permit entry by people with round-trip, non-transferable tickets, valid for a year or less and not refundable in the united states
carriers also would be required to certify that they will provide return transportation for the visitors
participating countries also would have to waive visa requirements for u.s. visitors. britain does not require visas for americans, but japan does
her mother wanted her to return home to massachusetts, but 17-year-old lenora rolle wanted to stretch her vacation in new york by just one day. it turned out to be her last
i begged and pleaded with her to come home,'' coralie rolle said after learning that her daughter had been shot to death at a party in brooklyn. ``i missed her. i wanted her back. i didn't like her being there too long. i begged her to be careful.''
miss rolle, a high school senior in cambridge, mass., had used the money she earned as a cashier at warburton's pastry shop in harvard square to finance the trip to new york, where she stayed with aunts in the bronx
detectives say she was at the port authority bus terminal in manhattan on monday night with a 15-year-old friend, identified only as bianca, when the two were lured away from their boston-bound bus by a peddler of exotic fragrances
the man, who may have known bianca, urged the girls to go to a party at his mother's house in brooklyn, and promised to pay their bus fare home
she was a good girl, but she liked to party,'' her mother said. she also said that lenora was not very streetwise
police sgt. arthur stoecker, who is investigating the case, said at least seven people were at the party; one of those in attendance told new york newsday that there were about 15. stoecker said a few empty crack vials were found in the apartment afterward
after miss rolle arrived, police and witnesses say, she was approached by a man who demanded to have sex with her
is she for me? is this one for me?'' the man asked, according to a witness quoted by the new york post
when miss rolle refused, the man pulled out a 9mm hand-held machine gun and fired two shots into the floor, authorities said. he then forced her to undress and, as she screamed in protest, dragged her into a bedroom
the other partygoers fled in terror. ``they were fearful for their own lives,'' stoecker said
he said the witnesses tried to telephone police, but were unable to get into an apartment building across the street. a street phone was out of order, they said
after about a half-hour, they saw the gunman, still clutching his pistol, leave the building. when they entered, they found miss rolle dead
an autopsy wednesday determined that she had been shot in the back, the right thigh and the left arm, according to a spokeswoman for the city medical examiner's office, ellen borakove. samples were sent to a lab to determine if miss rolle had been raped
stoecker said police were searching wednesday for a 20-year-old man with a previous felony conviction, but no official warrant had been issued
the man spent two weeks in jail in 1986 on a misdemeanor sexual misconduct conviction, then was sentenced to three to nine years after pleading guilty to attempted robbery, officials said
criminal court records indicate the sentencing was imposed in absentia, and prison officials said there was no record that he had served the time
at warburton's pastry shop, which serves soups and pastries to a clientele heavily weighted with harvard students and professors, manager ed buschard recalled lenora rolle as ``a very desirable employee.''
i thought that she was a good worker,'' buschard said. ``she came in on days when i was shorthanded. if i needed someone to work, she would work. ... she probably was a very popular girl in school, because she got along with everybody here at work. she seemed like a very outgoing girl
everybody's pretty shaken up. it's a shock to everybody.'' millar is not a defendant; subs graf 8 with one graf to clarify that some defendants face possible life sentences; picks up graf 9 pvs, the government.</note>
a key prosecution witness in the sedition trial of members of a white supremacist group testified under cross-examination from a defendant that he receives direct guidance from god
after the government used jim ellison's testimony to implicate many of the 10 men accused of plotting the violent overthrow of the government, defendant louis ray beam jr. questioned ellison on his religious beliefs
ellison testified tuesday ``a prophet of god'' led him to settle in arkansas, where he was annointed ``king of the ozarks'' by robert millar, leader of a religious group in oklahoma
ellison also said he has the gift of prophecy and is a descendant of the biblical king david
has anyone ever suggested to you before today that you, sir, might be paranoid?'' beam asked
before today, i've heard it,'' ellison said
beam and nine others, including aryan nations leader richard butler, are accused of seditious conspiracy. the 10, and four others on trial, espouse white supremacist goals or belong to white supremacist groups, the government alleges
those four, and one of the accused conspirators, are charged with plotting to kill a federal judge and an fbi agent. two also are accused of interstate transportation of stolen money. those charged with conspiring to overthrow the government face maximum sentences of 20 years in prison and $20,000 fines if convicted, while the charge of plotting to kill federal officials carries a maximum life sentence
the government contends the conspiracy involved actions to kill jews, who were seen by the white supremacists as in charge of the united states government
ellison has testified that in 1983, members of an arkansas-based religious-military group he led had participated in a murder, robberies and attempts to blow up utility facilities
ellison is serving 20 years for racketeering and weapons violations committed when he led the group, called the covenant, the sword and the arm of the lord. he was arrested in 1985 after a four-day standoff
richard wayne snell, a member of ellison's group, is on death row in arkansas for the 1983 murder of texarkana pawn broker william stumpp
ellison testified that snell, one of the 14 on trial here, decided to kill the pawn broker because he considered him to be ``an evil man, he was a jew, and that he just needed to die.''
snell also is serving a sentence of life without parole for the 1984 slaying of state trooper louis bryant
ellison said beam and others agreed in 1983 at hayden lake, idaho, to step up activities to bring down the government and replace it with an all-white state in the northwest
ellison also has testified that defendant robert miles, 63, of cohoctah, mich., gave him a 30-gallon barrel of cyanide to poison the water supplies of new york or washington, d.c., to create civil unrest
butler, 69, of the aryan nations group, gave approval for the csa to provide sanctuary to members of the order when they were ``in trouble with the law,'' ellison said
at a trial in seattle, more than 20 people, many of them members of the order, were convicted of racketeering for robberies of banks and armored cars. some of the defendants in the fort smith case were sentenced in the seattle case
overweight people often get that way because their bodies burn calories more sparingly than normal-size folks', and this difference between the fat and the lean can be seen in the first months of life, two new studies show
together, the studies demonstrate that whether people are chubby or svelte may depend as much on how efficiently their bodies use energy as it does on what they eat
in one of the studies, researchers found that fat babies _ all of whom had overweight mothers _ were already expending less energy than other infants when they were just 3 months old
low energy expenditure in infants seems to be making them become overweight,'' said dr. susan b. roberts of massachusetts institute of technology, who directed the study
the other report found that some grownups have lower metabolic rates, or energy expenditure, than others. they need less food to keep going, and they gain weight more quickly
it all boils down to how much you eat and how much you expend. some people are just unlucky enough that they can't eat too much,'' said a co-author of the adult study, dr. clifton bogardus of the national institutes of health in phoenix, ariz
other studies have shown that fat people often use up relatively low amounts of calories when resting. but a crucial question remained: is their metabolism low because they are fat, or are they fat because their metabolism is low?
by following people over time, the new studies conclude that people get fat because their bodies are especially fuel efficient, although overeating also aggravates this problem. but when two people the same height and sex eat the same amount, it appears that one may stay trim while the other gets chubby, solely because of this difference in metabolism
what's being shown here is that there is some broad pattern of vulnerability to weight gain,'' commented dr. william i. bennett of harvard medical school. ``they are starting to get awfully close to showing that there is a set of genes'' that controls obesity
the two latest studies were published in thursday's issue of the new england journal of medicine
in the infant study, doctors studied six babies who were born to lean mothers and 12 who were born to overweight women. they used a newly developed urine test called the doubly labeled water method to measure the infants' energy expenditure while living at home
at age 3 months, all of the babies were normal sized. but by age 1, six of the fat mothers' babies had become overweight. total energy expenditure at 3 months was 21 percent lower in the infants who later became fat
the researchers theorize that these babies have an inherited tendency to be fat. their bodies have a high ``set point,'' or weight goal. they try to reach this point by taking in more energy or using up less
roberts said she believes that the fat babies ate no more than the normal ones. so they put on weight to reach their set point by being less active
that would be a logical thing to do in small infants, because their food intake is largely controlled by their mothers, so they didn't have the option of going to the fridge and having another sandwich,'' she said. ``but in adults, who have the option of going to the fridge, high food intake may also contribute to the maintenance of being overweight.''
the phoenix study was conducted on pima indians, who have a high rate of obesity. researchers measured their energy expenditure while resting and while living for 24 hours in a small room
they found that those whose 24-hour energy expenditure was low were four times more likely than those with high metabolisms to gain over 17 pounds during the following two years. they also found that low and high metabolisms tend to run in families
it means that some people have to eat less than others to maintain their weight. it's like they always said, but nobody ever believed,'' said bogardus
he said he hopes the research will help convince doctors that ``everyone who is fat isn't that way just because they are gluttonous slobs. they have something wrong.''
estonian nationalists shouted ``get the russians out!'' in the streets of tallinn on wednesday to commemorate the small baltic nation's brief generation of independence from the soviet union, which ended in 1940
tass noted the demonstration, the latest expression of unrest among the nation's more than 100 nationalities. the official news agency did not say how many people took part, but a moscow dissident in touch with an estonian journalist put the number at 2,500 to 3,000
the associated press could not get a telephone call through to tallinn, the estonian capital, to verify the reports
wednesday was the anniversary of estonia's declaration of independence in 1918. the soviets took it back in 1940 under a secret agreement with nazi germany
nationalists in estonia had asked official permission for a demonstration wednesday but were refused
alexander podrabinek, the moscow dissident, gave this account of the day's events in tallinn:
about 1,000 people gathered in the downtown area late in the afternoon for an official rally intended as a protest of what the government called u.s. provocation of estonian nationalists
nationalists rallied in a tallinn square wednesday night at a monument to estonian writer antonu-hansenu tammsaare, laying flowers on it as militiamen watched. plainclothes police photographed the protesters
an elderly man began speaking to the crowd about estonian independence and militiamen tried to take him away, but other demonstrators intervened. the militiamen backed off and remained at a distance for the rest of the three-hour rally
speakers shouted ``independence to estonia!'' and ``get the russians out!''
authorities brought in a bus with a loudspeaker blaring music and official propaganda. demonstrators were invited to hold their discussion in the warmth of nearby buildings, but most refused
no one was detained and the people remaining outside dispersed on their own
tass quoted tallinn's mayor, harry lumi, as saying people gathered at the monument to discuss ``the actual problems of modernity and the historic past of estonia.''
lumi said the demonstrators were invited to go inside buildings to continue their discussion because it was cold and windy, tass said, and quoted him as saying:
there occurred an improvised meeting with leading scientists of the republic, deputies of the city council. problems of the economic development of estonia, national relations, ecology and the democratization of society were discussed.''
podrabinek said his information came from a correspondent in tallinn for the underground weekly ``express chronicle,'' which podrabinek edits
nationalists in tallinn also demonstrated on aug. 23 against the german-soviet pact under which the soviets annexed estonia
snow fell wednesday across much of the great lakes region, the upper ohio valley and the central appalachians, and light rain fell in southern florida, while most of the rest of the nation had dry weather
winds gusting to 35 mph caused ``whiteout'' snow squalls in eastern upper michigan, particularly west of sault ste. marie
up to 8 inches of snow were forecast for the erie, pa., lakeshore, which receives ``lake-effect'' snow brought by cold air blowing across the great lakes
a snow squall warning was posted in upstate new york. up to 6 inches of snow were reported at boonville, n.y., overnight
snow advisories went up across northwestern pennsylvania and extreme northeastern ohio. three to 7 inches of snow fell in astabula county, ohio, early wednesday
heavier snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 3 inches at erie, pa., and 1 inch at grand rapids, mich
clear to partly cloudy skies prevailed elsewhere across the nation. rainfall was largely limited to a few light showers in southern florida
northwesterly winds of 15 to 25 mph with a few gusts to around 30 mph were common across the midwest. the wind, combined with midday temperatures in the teens and 20s, produced subzero wind-chill readings across the upper midwest
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 8 degrees at international falls, minn., to 80 degrees at homestead, fla., and fort myers, fla. the early-morning low for the nation was 17 below zero at gunnison, colo
the forecast for thursday called for scattered snow in upper michigan, the lower great lakes region and the central appalachians, and rain in southwestern california
highs were forecast in the 20s and 30s from the dakotas across the northeastern quarter of the nation, except from eastern minnesota across upper michigan, where highs in the teens were forecast. highs in the low 60s were forecast for parts of southwestern oregon, louisiana and southern mississippi, and in the 60s and 70s from california through much of texas and in florida. the rest of the nation will generally have highs in the 40s or 50s
communist party leader milos jakes pledged to implement reform in czechoslovakia wednesday, while at the same time denouncing the ``prague spring'' reforms crushed by warsaw pact forces 20 years ago
jakes spoke at a celebration marking the 40th anniversary of communist rule here, on the same day that czechoslovakia and east germany announced the imminent removal of soviet nuclear missiles
czechoslovakia was the last country in eastern europe to turn communist, setting the seal on kremlin domination of the region
the 65-year-old jakes gave little indication he is about to plunge into economic and political reforms now being enacted in the soviet union, poland, hungary and bulgaria
jakes took over party leadership last december from gustav husak, now 75. his hourlong speech to about 500 communists in the resplendent white and gold spanish hall of prague's hradcany castle displayed the same cautious conservatism that characterized husak's leadership for 18 years
he had harsh words for the communists who, under the leadership of alexander dubcek, tried in 1968 to introduce some of the reforms soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev advocates today
as head of the party's chief disciplinary body from 1968-77, jakes was responsible for purging almost half a million people from the communist party after soviet-led warsaw pact tanks crushed the 1968 reforms
on wednesday, jakes denied there is any need to reassess the official view of 1968 and rejected any comparison between dubcek's reforms and gorbachev's perestroika, or restructuring, of communist society
without mentioning dubcek by name, jakes said czechoslovaks were hopeful and supportive when dubcek was made party leader in january 1968, but that anti-socialist forces ``frustrated the great opportunity that occurred for the solution of important problems.''
the healthy forces in the party and society saw this growing danger and conducted a difficult and complicated struggle against it,'' jakes said
he said dubcek failed to ally with these forces, and a ``tragic development'' was averted only ``thanks to the international assistance of our friends.'' public reference to the warsaw pact invasion has been rare over the past year
jakes went on to praise husak, who presided over the ceremonial meeting, the first official event to mark the communist takeover in february 1948
the communists got almost 40 percent of the vote in elections in 1946, but assumed sole power only after a series of political maneuvers during street demonstrations from feb.20-25, 1948
it was no communist coup, as it's always described by hostile propaganda,'' jakes said of the 1948 takeover. ``it was the will of the people.''
jakes' speech set off celebrations that will include a mass rally thursday in prague's old town square, scene of a triumphant speech by then communist party leader klement gottwald on feb. 21, 1948
jakes' speech signaled that his leadership is likely to be conservative, despite official talk of economic reform
czechoslovakia's communists adopted the rhetoric of reform a year ago, but a much-delayed blueprint for economic changes will be published only later this week and reforms are not to be finally be implemented until 1991
political change is scarcely mentioned. jakes made clear it will not _ as in hungary, poland and even the soviet union _ lead to a dialogue between communists and unofficial opposition groups
the broadening of democratization in no case means the creation of space for the legalization of political opposition which, as all experiences to date show, cannot be other than anti-socialist,'' he said
in announcing the imminent removal of soviet missiles, east germany and czechoslovakia hailed the move as a goodwill gesture before the u.s. congress votes on ratification of the superpower arms treaty
east germany said removal of shorter-range ss-12 missiles from its territory would begin thursday. czechoslovakia's communist party daily newspaper rude pravo said withdrawal of ss-12s deployed here would begin in ``the next few days.''
neither country specified how many rockets will be removed, nor how long the process will take
the announcements came one day after u.s. secretary of state george shultz ended a moscow visit and talks with soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze
east germany said last week that ss-12s there had been dismantled and were ready for removal, but did not say then when withdrawal would begin
under the arms control agreement signed by the united states and the soviet union last december in washington, all intermediate and shorter-range nuclear weapons in europe will be scrapped within three years. correct spelling of acetaminophen.</note>
st. joseph's aspirin for children, once a leader in over-the-counter pain relief for youngsters, is slowly disappearing from medicine cabinets
the manufacture of the chewable orange tablets ended in december 1986 as shering plough corp. of madison focuses on chewable low-dosage aspirin products for adults concerned about preventing heart disease
aspirin-free pain relievers and name-brand aspirin products competed with each other until the american academy of pediatrics, in a report in 1982, said giving aspirin to children suffering from chicken pox and influenza increased the risk of contracting reye's syndrome
the illness is fatal in about 20 percent to 30 percent of the cases, and some survivors suffer permanent brain damage. the government in 1986 ordered warning labels on all aspirin bottles about the risk to children and teen-agers of contracting reye's syndrome
the market ``dropped considerably from 1980 with the reye's syndrome business,'' said terry kelly, a spokesman for sterling drug inc. of new york, which still manufactures bayer's aspirin for children
we feel there are certain patients for whom children's aspirin is appropriate,'' kelly said
st. joseph's aspirin for children, first marketed in 1949, was replaced with aspirin-free tablets called st. joseph's aspirin-free fever reducer
jim saberton, a consultant with kline &amp; co. inc. in fairfield, said wednesday that the children's aspirin market has become relatively small with sales of about $15 million in 1986 compared with sales of about $115 million for the non-aspirin pain reliever acetominophen that same year
the risk and work involved in making aspirin is unattractive, especially since there's acetominophen,'' he said
st. joseph's aspirin for children and bayer children's aspirin each had about $5 million in sales in 1986, with the balance of sales taken up by generic brands, he said
he also said johnson &amp; johnson's tylenol products, which use acetominophen, cut heavily into sales of st. joseph's, which once held 50 percent of the children's pain-reliever market while bayer had the other half
lewis nolan, a schering plough spokesman, said, however, that his company disputes the link of aspirin to reye's syndrome
it's been our position that there's been no scientific valid evidence to link aspirin and reye's syndrome,'' he said
st. joseph's low dose adult aspirin was introduced last month, although the company makes no claim in relation to aspirin's effectiveness against heart disease. the low dose aspirin product label advises it not be given to young children, he said
kelly said his company showed higher sales of bayer children's aspirin during 1987, although he could not say if it was due to shering plough leaving the market
i think the first increase you saw was ours last year. i cannot analyze why that is,'' he said
czechoslovakia and east germany said they will start removing shorter-range soviet nuclear missiles from their territory thursday
dmitri t. yazov, the soviet defense minister, said monday while secretary of state george p. shultz was in moscow that withdrawal of the ss-12s would begin this month as a ``display of goodwill.''
the weapons must be eliminated under the u.s.-soviet treaty on intermediate-range nuclear arms signed in december, which has yet to be ratified
dusan rovensky, spokesman for the czechoslovak foreign ministry, said wednesday: ``under an agreement between the czechoslovak and soviet governments, the withdrawal of soviet army rocket units armed with operational-tactical missiles from czechoslovak territory will start on feb. 25.''
ctk, the official news agency, said the defense ministry confirmed the announcement
a brief announcement by the east german diplomatic mission in bonn, west germany, said: ``withdrawal of the soviet shorter-range missiles from the german democratic republic will begin on febrary 25 (thursday), 1988.''
east germany announced last week that soviet ss-12s stationed at waren had been dismantled, crated and prepared for return to the soviet union
according to figures released after the treaty was signed, there are 54 ss-12s in east germany. czechoslovakia has not said how many soviet missiles were installed on its territory, but western analysts put the number at 39
the intermediate-range treaty requires elimination of nuclear weapons with ranges between 300 and 3,000 miles
east germany said missiles would be removed thursday from waren and another site at bischofswerda. the only location ever given for the weapons in czechoslovakia was a military base near hranice, 180 miles southeast of prague
in 1983, nato began installing u.s.-built cruise and pershing 2 missiles in western europe to counteract soviet ss-20s pointed at the west. the kremlin responded by moving some ss-12s from bases in the soviet union to east germany and czechoslovakia
foreign ministers from six balkan nations meet in belgrade wednesday to discuss ways of ending conflicts in the area, long troubled by regional disputes
the three-day session will be the first such conference since world war ii
military, ethnic, environmental and political disputes mar relations among the six
ministers from nato allies greece and turkey, warsaw pact members bulgaria and romania and non-aligned yugoslavia and albania arrived in belgrade tuesday
at a meeting in sofia, bulgaria, on monday, prime minister andreas papandreou of greece and bulgarian leader todor zhivkov said the balkan conference should be a forum for cooperation
we hope that this meeting will turn into an institution,'' the official bulgarian news agency bta quoted papandreou as saying in a dinner speech. he suggested that such meetings be held every two years
bta quoted zhivkov as saying the conference first ``should discuss the questions that unite us
we do not underestimate the contradictions and the difficulties between the balkan states, but they must continue to be discussed on a bilateral and multilateral basis.''
although the conference is expected to focus largely on economic, scientific and cultural cooperation, festering issues are expected to be raised
bulgaria and greece are likely to raise the possibility of establishing a nuclear-free zone in the balkans, a proposal opposed by turkey
turkish and greek diplomats, however, have said they won't raise the dispute over cyprus, which is divided by forces loyal to each nation
the yugoslav state news agency tanjug has reported that bulgaria plans to propose a special balkan conference on environmental issues, apparently to take romania to task for pollution on the bulgarian-romanian border area
one potential problem apparently was resolved tuesday when bulgaria and turkey signed a protocol on good neighborly relations
a turkish diplomat had said earlier his delegation planned to raise the issue of bulgaria's ethnic turkish minority at the conference. bulgaria's estimated 1 million ethnic turks were forced by the government to adopt bulgarian names as part of a ``bulgarization campaign.''
the protocol was seen as a clear indication that the two neighbors seek to normalize relations after years of discord
ethnic tensions also strain relations between albania and yugoslavia, which has a large albanian minority in the southern province of kosovo
there are many problems that we must review, concerning both bilateral cooperation and cooperation among the balkan countries in general, in order to create an atmosphere of confidence,'' albanian foreign minister reis malile said in a television interview upon his arrival in belgrade
malile is the highest-ranking albanian to visit yugoslavia in 40 years. albania strongly condemned yugoslavia's decision in 1948 to break with the soviet loc, but 20 years later albania followed suit
alexei magarik, a jewish cellist imprisoned in the soviet union on charges of drug possession, arrived in israel on wednesday after a five-year struggle for an exit visa
magarik, 28, was accompanied by his wife natasha, 26, and their 2-year-old son chaim
magarik, a poet and songwriter, was active in jewish musical groups in moscow. he first applied for an exit visa in 1983
in march 1986, magarik was arrested on his way back to moscow from tbilisi on a domestic flight when airport authorities searched his luggage and reported finding a cigarette pack containing drugs
magarik said he never saw the pack before, and a blood test revealed no trace of drugs
but he was sentenced in 1986 to three years in prison on charges of drug trafficking and possession. a year later he was released after soviet authorities reviewed his case
magarik's release was attributed to the policy of greater political openness initiated by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
when i was released from prison i was told that i was the last of the prisoners of zion. but in this great and terrible country, the soviet union, you never can tell who is still being held in jail,'' magarik told dozens of friends at ben gurion airport in tel aviv. workers</head>
the federal government will seek supreme court review of a ruling that overturned mandatory drug and alcohol testing for railroad workers, the justice department said wednesday
in a 2-1 decision, a federal appeals court in california declared on feb. 11 that such testing violates the constitutional protection against unreasonable search and seizure
justice department spokeswoman amy brown said the government planned to seek high court review within the next several weeks
brown also said the justice department will notify the court that the government no longer opposes supreme court review of another drug testing case, involving the u.s. customs service
the 5th u.s. circuit court of appeals in new orleans last year supported a drug testing program for customs workers in sensitive positions such as those involved in drug interdiction. the appeals court overturned a u.s. district court decision which had held the testing to be unconstitutional
the justice department originally had opposed supreme court review of the customs service case because at that time there were no conflicting decisions from other appeals court circuits
the national treasury employees union, which brought the suit challenging the customs program, went to the supreme court last summer seeking review
energy secretary john herrington was asked wednesday to halt rail shipments of radioactive waste from the three mile island nuclear plant until a new study can be made of the route by which they are transported
sen. john danforth, r-mo., ranking minority member of the senate commerce, science and transportation committee, made the request in the wake of an incident involving a tmi train in the st. louis area earlier this month
herrington took the senator's request under consideration, a danforth aide said
the federal railroad administration confirmed on wednesday it is investigating a rail car switching incident on feb. 9 just before a tmi train passed through st. louis. the agency is determining whether there were violations of rail regulations, which could draw civil penalties of up to $10,000
the train was carrying casks of radioactive wastes from the damaged tmi plant in pennsylvania to a government laboratory in idaho
bill loftus, an fra spokesman, said the possible violations involve mislabeling of a covered hopper car, which was added to the tmi train in a railyard in east st. louis, ill
the car carried a placard stating that it contained a flammable material, but later was found not to be carrying the dangerous cargo
loftus said the investigation is looking at possible violations by the rail switching yard, the union pacific railroad which operated the train after it left the yard and a lime company that was shipping the car
federal rail regulations, loftus said, require shippers to properly label goods being moved by rail. regulations also prohibit switching yards from offering mislabeled cars for addition to a train and railroads from transporting any improperly labeled freight
herrington met on wednesday with danforth and several other senators from states along the tmi rail route. the missourian wants the energy department to halt the waste shipments until the transportation department can study the rail route used by the energy department to move the materials to the laboratory in idaho falls, idaho
since the shipments began in 1986, missouri officials have complained that the government's route takes the radioactive materials through densely populated cities such as st. louis
amtrak has begun installing smoke detectors in crew cars as a result of a weekend fire that killed an employee, a spokeswoman said wednesday
the installation of smoke detectors began monday in the 15 or so double-decker cars that serve as crew sleeping quarters on long-distance trips, debbie marciniak said in a telephone interview from chicago
the move came after a 70-year-old amtrak employee died of smoke inhalation from a fire that began early saturday in the crew car of a westbound california zephyr. nineteen people suffered minor injuries
the fire was discovered as the train pulled into hastings, about 150 miles west of here, for a scheduled stop
some passengers complained that they were not warned about the fire, and questioned why there were no smoke detectors on the train
marciniak said the train crew's first priority was to rescue those in the employee car and evacuate those in a passenger sleeper
amtrak officials said the passengers were in no danger because the burning crew car and the passenger sleeper were detached from the coach section of the train
amtrak spokesman john jacobsen had said commercial smoke detectors were too sensitive and that the vibration of the trains would set them off. he said train fires were rare, but that amtrak had been looking for a reliable smoke detector
marciniak said wednesday that the newly installed smoke detectors may go off as a result of cigarette smoke or dust, but that the false alarms would be preferable to not having any alarms
the railroad also is considering installing smoke detectors in passenger sleepers, she said
amtrak has been trying to develop a fire and smoke alarm system for several years, and during the last six months has asked vendors for assistance, marciniak said
four companies appear to have a concept that may work and amtrak is working with them, she said
the state fire marshal's office has blamed the fire on an electrical short in the crew car
marciniak said amtrak officials believe the fire may have begun when boxes of pillows placed next to a heating element in the luggage storage compartment of the crew car ignited. however, amtrak officials are continuing to investigate, she said
in the meantime, marciniak said amtrak had disconnected all heating elements in the luggage storage compartments in similar crew cars. in addition, emergency windows in the dormitory section of the cars are being expanded, she said
a girl was shot and killed tuesday and three other people were wounded during an anti-government demonstration in the town of azua, radio commercial reported
it identified the slain girl as mary ramirez, 17, and said she was shot in the head when protesters clashed with police and soldiers in azua, 75 miles west of santo domingo, the capital. the brodadcast said another youth, who was not identified, and two policemen hit by rocks were treated at hospitals
demonstrators had started their protest monday, stoning cars and businesses to demand the government build more public works projects in the town
demonstrations also were reported tuesday in two other towns, both involving claims of pollution by the government-owned rosario gold mine north of santo domingo
in cotui, 60 miles north of the capital, 500 farmers joined the rev. carlos guerra in a protest at the town's roman catholic church, according to radio popular. it said the rally was held at the end of a 72-hour general strike by cotui residents
a protest demonstration also was held in bonao, 50 miles north of the capital, according to local news reports, but no details were given
president joaquin balaguer declined comment on the latest demonstrations. he said sunday the disturbances were organized by political opponents, but no oposition party has identified itself with the protests
an inmate who had called eight killers to the stand as character witnesses was sentenced a second time wednesday to die in the electric chair for the rape-murder of his 13-year-old stepniece
judge gary formet said the convicts' statements on behalf of 31-year-old james hitchcock were believable ``but fall short of convincing this court'' to spare his life
testifying last week under extraordinary security, the eight death row inmates from florida state prison had portrayed hitchcock as a model prisoner, a peacemaker, teacher and generous person who should be spared execution
a jury late saturday recommended by a 7-5 vote that the judge impose the death penalty
formet was free to set aside the recommendation but cited hitchcock's confession, which he later recanted, and agreed with the prosecution that the 1976 slaying of cynthia driggers was ``heinous, atrocious and cruel.''
hitchcock's original death sentence was overturned in april by the u.s. supreme court, which ruled the original jury in 1977 had not considered mitigating evidence of the defendant's character and background
prosecutors steve wallace and belvin perry had denigrated the testimony of the ``eight despicable criminals.''
all these murderers stated their opposition to the death penalty while seeming oblivious to the fact that each had himself imposed that ultimate penalty upon innocent victims,'' the prosecutors said. observers saying majority backs roh. no pickup</note>
president roh tae-woo was sworn into office thursday and promised to end decades of harsh authoritarian rule and form a ``people's government.''
it was the first peaceful transfer of power in south korea's violent 40-year history
roh said human rights abuses and government repression would not be tolerated under the new sixth republic and his administration would swiftly carry out democratic and social reforms
the day when freedoms and human rights could be slighted in the name of economic growth and national security has ended. the day when repressive force and torture in secret chambers were tolerated is over,'' the 55-year-old roh said in a tough speech
but roh also warned opposition groups to work with his government and end the country's long tradition of confrontational and violent politics. he said he would not tolerate disorder
outgoing president chun doo-hwan, whose authoritarian government crushed opposition and imprisoned and beat dissidents, listened impassively as roh criticized past abuses of power and said south korea could accept nothing less than full democracy
roh was chun's hand-picked successor
there is a strong wind of change blowing over the country,'' roh said to applause at the heavily guarded ceremony
roh said the new government would ensure full democracy along with social and economic reforms to aid the poor and other disadvantaged groups
i declare that the new administration will be a government of the people. it will open an era of democracy in which each citizen can reach his full potential,'' he said
then, in a warning to the opposition, he said, ``the day when confusion was irresponsibly created on the pretext of freedom and participation must also come to an end.''
thousands of radical students staged demonstrations wednesday to protest roh's inauguration and protesters hurling firebombs and rocks battled police in seoul and two other cities
it was massive demonstrations led by students last summer that prompted chun to agree to democratic reforms. he accepted the changes after roh publicly urged him to do so
but roh, a former general, is identified with the military-backed governments that ruled the country since 1960 and many koreans are doubtful he can achieve widespread democratic change
in washington, an international observer team said wednesday that roh's election appears credible despite some government abuses during nationwide voting last dec. 16. the observers, co-sponsored by the washington-based international human rights law group, said ``it appears that the vast majority of the korean people have accepted'' roh's victory
thousands of riot police and security agents guarded thursday's ceremony attended by 25,000 invited guests in the square in front of the national assembly building under a hazy late winter sky. the general public was not admitted and the 120,000-man national police force was on nationwide alert
army and navy bands played, trumpeters blew fanfares and a traditional korean folk orchestra in red robes and black horsehair hats performed
detachments of riot police stood guard in side streets as roh rode to the inauguration ceremony
about 150 protesters remained thursday in the compound of the roman catholic myongdong cathedral in seoul after battling riot police in the surrounding streets during the night
five students armed with bombs and knives briefly seized a u.s. government building in seoul and detonated two bombs wednesday before being overpowered by police. nobody was hurt or taken hostage in the hourlong incident
main streets of seoul were decorated with the white, red and blue south korean national flags and thursday was declared a national holiday. pink and blue arches proclaimed the founding of the new republic that comes into being with the adoption of a new constitution
roh told this nation of 41 million people, ``let us here and now bury regional antagonism, partisan and factional egoism and personal resentment.'' roh won the country's first democratic presidential election in 16 years on dec. 16 with 36.6 percent of the vote. he defeated rival opposition candidates kim young-sam and kim dae-jung, who split the opposition vote
opposition parties contend the government will continue to be run by the armed forces and an entrenched elite of government officials and business leaders
many koreans reacted with dismay last week when roh announced a new cabinet that included seven holdovers from the chun government. top security posts went to right-wing hardliners
other koreans argue roh must be given time to meet his promises for major reforms
roh has emphasized the need for political stability and continued economic expansion as well as democratic reforms. he has stressed that security must be sufficient to ensure the 1988 olympic games are carried out successfully in september
chun stepped down at the end of a seven-year term. africa. top 7 grafs new to update with reagan comments; picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``by acting ...''</note>
president reagan said wednesday the u.s. government was constrained from helping black south africans fighting the government partly because of divisions among them
reagan was asked at a news conference whether he had considered aiding the african national congress or other groups opposing the pretoria government since his administration has aided guerrillas fighting oppression in other countries
no, we have not involved ourselves in that, other than things such as the sanctions and so forth,'' reagan said. ``we have tried our best to be persuasive in this very difficult problem.''
he was asked what the difference was between south africa and other countries where the united states is supporting ``freedom fighters.''
the difference is that we don't have an armed insurrection going as we have in some other countries and we have a great division even among the people who are being oppressed,'' he said. ``it's a tribal policy more than it is a racial policy and that is one of the most difficult parts here.''
reagan noted that the state department had contacted the south african government earlier wednesday to object to the government's banning of anti-apartheid organizations
they should be working toward a multiracial democracy and not oppressing political organizations there, and we've made our feelings clear about that,'' he said
the state department had said it was ``appalled'' by south africa's decision to ban political activity by the nation's largest anti-apartheid group and 17 other opposition organizations
by acting to outlaw non-violent political activity of these organizations, the south african government has dealt a severe blow to efforts to achieve a a peaceful solution to south africa's problems,'' state department spokesman charles redman said
he said the affected organizations represent the aspirations of a broad cross section of the black community
we are appalled by the announcement from the south african government today that it is effectively outlawing the activities of a large number of organizations,'' redman said, adding: ``this is a giant step backward for south africa.''
redman said assistant secretary of state chester crocker had summoned south africa's ambassador to the state department to register ``shock and distress'' over the crackdown
a federal appeals court wednesday night granted a stay of execution to a man scheduled to die early thursday for a murder committed at age 17
a three-judge panel of the 5th u.s. circuit of appeals in new orleans, in granting the indefinite stay, said it needed more time to study the case of 24-year-old gary graham. earlier wednesday, a federal judge in houston denied a stay
the stay came hours before graham was scheduled to die by injection for the 1981 shooting death of bobby grant lambert, 53, of tucson, ariz., in a houston grocery store parking lot
lambert was robbed of less than $100, although police said the victim had $6,000 on him
defense attorney doug o'brien had asked for a stay pending a decision by the u.s. supreme court in an oklahoma case contending that people who commit crimes when under the age of 18 should not be executed
his appeal also was based on a texas case contending jurors should be allowed to hear mitigating circumstances when considering punishment. arguments in that case are scheduled before the u.s. supreme court on march 1
five other texas death row inmates have execution dates this year
twenty-seven people have been executed in texas, more than in any other state, since the supreme court allowed states to resume use of the death penalty in 1976. anniversary of marcos ouster. no pickup.</note>
church bells rang thursday and thousands of filipinos joined hands in a ``chain for peace'' to mark the second anniversary of the ouster of ferdinand marcos
president corazon aquino clasped the hands of defense secretary fidel ramos and chief of staff gen. renato de villa on epifanio de los santos avenue
it was along the broad avenue, known popularly as edsa, that hundreds of thousands of civilians rallied to support military mutineers in the uprising that forced the former president from the country on feb. 25, 1986
as church bells pealed thursday, a philippine air force t-28 swooped low over the crowd dragging a banner reading ``people power.'' police estimated that by 8:30 a.m. (7:30 p.m. wednesday est) about 20,000 people had packed the avenue for the all-day celebrations
leftists scheduled their own rallies thursday at which they planned to accuse mrs. aquino of abandoning the reformist goals of the 1986 revolution. on wednesday, about 20,000 people marched along the boulevard and burned an effigy of mrs. aquino
during celebrations thursday, armored personnel carriers carried images of the virgin mary in a procession along epifanio avenue. officials said the images were the ones carried by priests and nuns during the 1986 revolt
roman catholic cardinal jaime l. sin, archbishop of manila, said in a radio broadcast that the celebrations showed ``we want brotherhood and not bloodshed.''
in 1986, sin called on filipinos to fill the streets to support mutineers led by ramos and former defense minister juan ponce enrile
they had broken with marcos, charging him with fraud in the feb. 7, 1986, presidential election in which he ran against mrs. aquino. the rebels' action galvanized the opposition that began after the 1983 assassination of opposition leader benigno aquino, mrs. aquino's husband
marcos fled to hawaii
during a leftist protest wednesday, about 200 police officers blocked the road leading to the military's camp crame in suburban quezon city as helicopters hovered above. the crowd of students, workers, farmers and roman catholic clergy dispersed without incident after three hours of anti-government speeches
the leftist protesters chanted ``dismantle the u.s.-aquino regime'' and burned effigies of mrs. aquino. red banners said ``advance the people's genuine revolution'' and one poster read: ``cory _ closet dictator.''
we had high hopes when cory aquino said she would be the exact opposite of marcos. but after two years, we have no more hope that she will fulfill her promises,'' crispin beltran, head of the militant may first movement labor organization, told the rally
people distributed leaflets of the outlawed national democractic front, the umbrella organization of 12 marxist groups including the communist party and its armed wing, the new people's army
the aquino government has betrayed the filipino people's hope for fundamental changes in society after ousting marcos...,'' the democratic front statement said
also wednesday, mrs. aquino denied charges by the wife of a discredited navy officer that ramos was involved in a november 1986 coup attempt
as far as i'm concerned, general ramos has proven himself not only now but in the past, especially in his abiding by the constitution,'' she told reporters. ``he has not been any part of any coup attempt.''
ramos also denied the charges by marilyn robles, wife of capt. rex robles
the plot involved killing leftist officials, installing a military junta and reducing mrs. aquino to the role of a figurehead
foreign ministers of eight latin american countries opened a conference wednesday at which they will consider calling for the readmission of cuba to the organization of american states
the foreign ministers of peru, panama, brazil, colombia, mexico, uruguay, venezuela and argentina are scheduled to meet for three days in the colombian port city of cartagena
also on the agenda are peace efforts in central america, british naval drills near the falklands, the region's $400 billion foreign debt and increased policing of drug trafficking, said esther lozano de rey, chief secretary for the colombian foreign ministry
the ministers make up what is called the group of eight, organized last year mainly to monitor the situation in central america
mrs. lozano de rey told the associated press that a preliminary agenda for the group of eight meeting, drawn up by assistants to the foreign ministers, included a proposal to support cuba's re-entry into the oas
cuba was expelled from the organization in 1962, three years after fidel castro came to power
in a meeting of the eight latin american countries' presidents last november in acapulco, mexico, president jose sarney of brazil told reporters that the leaders had agreed that the communist nation should be readmitted to the oas. however, such a statement was not included in a final document from the meeting
the u.s. state department has said the united states can not support the readmission of cuba to the oas until that country stops trying to subvert democratic rule in the hemisphere
at the cartagena meeting, the latin american ministers are considering calling for an end to the british naval maneuvers that have taken place around the falklands islands in the south atlantic since the 1982 war between argentina and britain, according to ms. lozano de rey
argentina invaded the islands, which it calls the malvinas, but later surrendered to the british
the ministers planned to discuss a statement urging wealthy countries to fight consumption of cocaine and calling on the eight latin american countries to work to cut production of the drug
colombia, peru and bolivia are south america's three biggest cocaine-producing countries
panama's foreign minister, jorge abadia, said wednesday his government is not discounting the possibility of u.s. military intervention in panama because of the indictment on drug trafficking charges of gen. manuel antonio noriega, head of panama's armed forces
if there is an invasion, ``we won't have the capacity to stop it,'' abadia said
the reagan administration publicly called for noriega to step down following his indictment this month by a federal grand jury in miami
abadia said the charges do not constitute an attack on noriega but on the panamanian military. he claimed the charges are an attempt to break the treaty under which the united states has promised to turn the panama canal to panama by the year 2000
when the meeting ends, the eight foreign ministers will head for hamburg, west germany for a series of meetings with central american officials on the situation in their region. freed'</head> spokesman</note>
republican presidential candidate pat robertson said wednesday his christian broadcasting network once knew the whereabouts of american hostages in lebanon ``and they could have been freed'' but president reagan said if that were so ``he kept it to himself.''
robertson's comments came at an atlanta news conference during which he complained that u.s. intelligence in the middle east is inadequate and declared that action must be quick when americans are taken hostage
a robertson aide said later that the former television evangelist was referring to passengers who had been taken hostage by hijackers of a twa flight in the middle east
we identified in our news department at cbn the location of those hostages in lebanon very shortly after they were taken, and they were in a position where they could have been rescued,'' robertson said
they were in beirut, and they could have been freed.''
robertson did not provide specifics and did not say which hostages were involved
reagan, at a nationally broadcast news conference, responded to robertson's claim
it'd be very strange if he actually did have information as to the location of those hostages,'' said the president. ``isn't it strange that no one in our administration was ever apprised of that?''
if he thought that he knew,'' the president said of robertson, ``he kept it to himself.''
reagan added that ``we have tried our best and through every kind of channel to establish their (the hostages') whereabouts because that's the beginning of efforts to try and get them free.''
it's very frustrating to try and establish a location,'' reagan said. ``but we've never let up, and we never will, in trying to obtain the freedom of all the hostages.''
after reagan spoke, robertson's deputy press secretary, scott hatch, said: ``i think what pat said was accurate.''
benton miller, spokesman for cbn, based in virginia beach, va., later issued a synopsis of the news report to which robertson referred. he said it involved hostages who had been taken from twa flight 847
the synopsis said that in response to a question from robertson, a cbn middle east correspondent, who was not named, said the hostages, ``are in several locations in and around lebanon and we have also learned that maybe at least one of them, and we do not know which one, but we have been told by intelligence sources in lebanon, that at least one may be being held in tehran.''
the suspicion concerning the hostage thought to be held in tehran was later reported as incorrect in a subsequent news report on robertson's ``700 club'' talk show, miller said
asked whether he had told the reagan administration what he knew, the former television evangelist said, ``i broadcast it on national television; they monitor our programs virtually every day.''
later, in an interview on atlanta radio station wgst, robertson said the information about the hostages was obtained by a cbn-affiliated tv station in lebanon. ``my reporters in lebanon had information, initially, on where these hostages were taken,'' he said
robertson said that was ``several years ago, when the first hostages were taken.''
rival republican candidate jack kemp called robertson's statements irresponsible and said he should ``apologize to the families of the hostages whom he has needlessly hurt in an attempt to gain publicity.''
vice president george bush, campaigning in boston, was asked about robertson's statements. ``my question would be, how come he didn't get hold of the proper authorities in the united states government that were working day and night, trying to figure out how they could get these people out?''
in his news conference, robertson said action to rescue hostages ``has to be quick and it has to be a surprise, that once the situation has hardened, six months have gone by, eight months, a year, it's virtually impossible to get any movement because the hostages are dispersed and the captors are more or less dug in.''
robertson aide gary lane told the associated press that in 1985, ``during the twa flight 847 crisis,'' cbn beirut bureau chief gus hashem ``had information from sources where the hostages were being held in west beirut and who was holding them.''
lane said the state department contacted cbn for information at that time, but he said he did not know exactly who made the contact
a state department terrorism expert said he was puzzled by the contention
the official, who commented only on condition of remaining anonymous, said he was unaware that cbn ever broadcast the precise locations of any hostages. he also said knowledge of hostages' whereabouts in terms of a particular city or even a section of a city wouldn't be enough to mount a rescue mission
nine americans are in captivity in lebanon, including marine lt. col. william r. higgins, who was captured last week. terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, is the longest-held captive, having been kidnapped on march 16, 1985
robertson's comments on the hostages marked the second time in two weeks that his statements on international matters have sparked controversy. during a republican presidential debate on feb. 14, he alleged that the soviets have nuclear missiles in cuba, pointing to the united states. the reagan administration denied it
in yet another controversy, bush asked robertson to apologize or provide proof to back up his suggestion on tuesday that anti-robertson political motivations were behind the timing of public allegations of sexual misconduct against television evangelist jimmy swaggart
by sundown in the old south, i'd like to see him stand up like a southern gentleman with a little evidence,'' bush said. ``i'd like to see an apology or proof.''
federal agents wednesday arrested 17 people, most of them in virginia, and were looking for seven more in the windup of a four-year sting operation aimed at illegal bear hunting
nineteen search warrants were executed in 12 states and trophies and animal parts were seized at some locations. five airplanes were seized at anchorage, alaska, but no arrests were made there
clark r. bavin, chief of law enforcement for the fish and wildlife service, said at a news conference, ``we may have 30 to 35 people charged eventually.''
arrest warrants were obtained for two people in maryland, one in montana, four in north carolina, four in west virginia and 11 in virginia, a total of 22. twelve people in fact were arrested in virginia and an additional suspect was being sought, but officials in washington did not immediately know where
agents established a kind of hunters' brokerage in purcellville, va., about 50 miles from washington, that arranged hunts for customers, bringing guides and hunters together
bavin said the company, abrams creek outfitters, spent a year establishing its cover through advertisments, attendance of employees at conventions and visits to guides
the investigation began with a focus on out-of-season and airborne hunting of caribou and brown bears in alaska, but grew to include illegal killing of black bears, frequently in and near shenandoah national park in virginia, and sale of bear parts
bavin displayed a mounted, stuffed bear he said was taken in alaska by a two-plane party that landed the hunters at a makeshift camp to kill the bear as it was driven toward them by the other airplane
this is totally illegal,'' he said
appearing with federal officials at the news conference, gerald simmons, chief of law enforcement for the virginia game and inland fisheries commission, said, ``virginia was delighted to take part'' because it appeared that as many as 200 black bears were killed illegally last year out of a population of 2,000 to 2,500. in legal hunting, 557 bears were killed in the state
simmons and bavin displayed about a dozen bear gall bladders, wrapped in plastic bags, that had been seized in one arrest earlier in the day. these organs are considered valuable medicine in the far east and may bring $300 each
in addition, hides brought up to $250 each
the forest-dwelling black bear was found in 49 states 200 years ago, but practically decimated by the early part of this century. conservation programs have restored the bear to 30 states, and hunting is often permitted
federal law makes it a crime to transport across state lines widlife taken in violation of state law. that statute says violations can bring a year in prison and a $10,000 fine unless a sale across state lines is involved, in which case the term may be five years and the fine $20,000. under a 1984 law, the fine may be multiplied to $250,000
a 1971 law makes it a federal crime to shoot or harass wildlife from aircraft, with penalties specified as a possible yearlong prison term and fine of $5,000. the 1984 statute makes it possible to multiply the fine to $100,000. include reagan slips; should stand for ams</note>
president reagan said wednesday night ``we've never let up and we never will'' in efforts to free the american hostages in lebanon, adding that if republican presidential candidate pat robertson knew of their whereabouts, it was ``very strange'' that ``he kept it to himself.''
in his first full-dress news conference in four months, reagan also said he thought outside terrorists had been at work stirring up the middle east violence on the west bank that has prompted an israeli military crackdown
the president said he had ``every confidence'' in the personal integrity of embattled attorney general edwin meese iii. but said he could not comment on reports of the investigation of meese's role in a proposed middle east oil pipeline
as is his custom, reagan opened the nationally televised session in the white house east room with a quip. ``on the networks at last,'' he said in a wry reference to the refusal by cbs, nbc and abc to carry his prime-time feb. 2 speech on the eve of a house vote on aid to the contra rebels in nicaragua
the news conference blended international affairs with the domestic presidential campaign swirling outside the white house gates, and reagan showed his zest for political combat with a few jabs at the field of democratic contenders
to hear them, he said, ``we're in an economic slump'' suffering from a variety of ills. ``at the moment none of those things are true,'' he said
so i just think, you know, the kids will play,'' he said as laughter filled the room
the president also confirmed anew that vice president george bush expressed reservations during the iran-contra affair. but he refused to say precisely what bush had told him
on other topics, reagan:
_said secretary of state george shultz had given him an ``encouraging'' report on his just-completed trip to the soviet union. during the talks in moscow, shultz and soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze set a one-month deadline for arms negotiators to complete drafts on key elements of a new treaty to curb strategic nuclear weapons
_noted that shultz was embarking on a fresh peace-seeking mission to the middle east, and said he hoped israelis and arabs would ``rid themselves of old ideas and stances that cannot work'' and begin serious negotiations
_issued a fresh condemnation of the leftist sandinista government of nicaragua, and said the soviet union had doubled military assistance to the nation in the first two months of this year over 1987 levels. he provided no figures
_said he had not decided whether to tell congress that aid should be resumed to panama. he has to certify that panama is helping in anti-drug efforts, but gen. manuel noriega, panama's military leader, has been indicted on u.s. drug-trafficking charges
reagan passed up several invitations to criticize israeli action against arab protesters on the occipied west bank and gaza strip
we don't support that sort of thing,'' was as strong a statement as the president would make, but he added quickly that there was evidence that the riots that provoked an israeli military crackdown were not ``spontaneous.''
asked to elaborate, he said, ``we have had information that there have been certain people suspected of being terrorists, outsiders coming in and stirring up the trouble in those areas.''
he ducked a request for more information, replying that to say more would ``get into areas that violate security.''
the subject of associated press correspondent terry anderson _ nearly three years in captivity _ and the other american hostages in lebanon arose early in the 30-minute nationally televised question-and-answer session
we've never let up and we never will in trying to bring freedom for all our hostages,'' reagan said
asked about gop candidate robertson's claim that his christian broadcasting network had once known the location of some of the hostages and the administration may have missed a chance for a rescue, the president said:
i can only say this. it would be very strange if he did have information ... isn't it strange that no one in our administration was apprised of it.''
reagan said he didn't want to become involved in the campaign to succeed him in the white house, but he said, ``if he felt that he (robertson) knew he kept it to himself.''
the president's statement on the contras seemed to be a soft appeal for support in congress for fresh aid to the rebels. he noted with regret that the democratic-run house had rejected his call for $36.2 million in fresh aid to the contra, including some money for weapons
house leaders have scheduled a vote for next week on an alternative support calling for humanitarian aid
reagan was unclear on a number of points. for example, he said that soviet membershin||nt on tariffs and trade, is under review but he failed to point out that the united states strenuously opposes soviet participation
he also said that secretary of state george shultz and former defense secretary caspar weinberger did not object to the secret sale of arms to iran on grounds that it was a trade of arms for hostages. however, the secretaries have said otherwise, and the iran-contra report issued by two congressional committees said shultz and weinberger ``called it a straight arms-for-hostages deal that was contrary to u.s. public policy.''
reagan jockeyed a busy round of talks on foreign policy problems wednesday with last-minute preparations for the news conference, the 42nd in his seven years as president but his first since last oct. 22
his first appointment wednesday was with shultz, who returned from moscow on tuesday night after talks on arms control and the likelihood of a soviet pullout of military forces from afghanistan
shultz headed out again wednesday night, this time to the middle east to try to spark arab-israeli peace talks. shultz said in advance he had only a slim chance of succeeding, and that the two sides would have to moderate their ``extreme positions.''
during the talks in moscow, shultz and soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze set a one-month deadline for arms negotiators to complete drafts on key elements of a new treaty to curb strategic nuclear weapons
the roman catholic prelate of guatemala offered wednesday to mediate peace talks between the government of president vinicio cerezo and leftist guerrillas who have waged a sporadic war since 1960
monsignor prospero penados del barrio told reporters he accepted a request to act as mediator from the general command of the guatemalan national revolutionary union, which is made up of three leftist armies
there was no immediate comment from the president's office
the archbishop told at a news conference, ``we would carry out our mediation at any place, whether it be proposed by the guerrillas or by the government, since the important thing is to end the fratricidal fight that ... has served to blind useful lives.''
he said the first round of talks should be held before holy week at the end of march
the talks would be held in accordance with a central american peace plan signed last august by the presidents of guatemala, nicaragua, el salvador, honduras and costa rica
asked about the talks, defense minister gen. hector alejandro gramajo morales said the army ``is very close to achieving a total victory'' over the rebels
in a very short time,'' he said, ``the subversive activity in the country will be ended.''
he said the guerrillas number 500 to 700
last october, representatives of the government and the guerrillas met for the first time since the rebels took to the hills in 1960 after a failed coup attempt. their four-day talks were held in madrid, spain
the talks foundered over the role of the army, how to interpret the term ``cease-fire,'' and rebel concern over whether the government can control rightist death squads
foreign minister alfonso cabrera said then that further peace talks would be pointless and called on the rebels to ``become part of the country's political and productive framework once again.''
the request to the archbishop to negotiate new talks was made by leaders of the three rebel armies in the revolutionary union _ rolando moran of the guerrilla army of the poor; gaspar ilom, a pseudonym for rodrigo asturias, of the organization of people in arms and pablo monsanto of the rebel armed forces
in ads in local newspapers, the guerrillas said a dialogue with the government ``is the only way to avoid death and suffering.''
gramajo morales, the defense minister, said the rebels should put down their arms and rejoin public life before any talks are undertaken. he said guatemala was complying fully with the new peace plan
the plan calls for cease-fire talks between the government and rebels in el salvador, guatemala and nicaragua as a first step toward democratic elections. it also urges political amnesties and a ban on all outside military assistance to rebel groups
right-wing death squads have operated for the past decade in guatemala, kidnapping and killing labor leaders, suspected communist leaders and human rights activists. details. picks up 13th graf pvs, earlier wednesday ...</note>
an ira bomb exploded in central belfast late wednesday night, killing two part-time soldiers of the ulster defense regiment and wounding two others and a civilian pedestrian, police said
the irish republican army claimed responsibility in a telephoned statement to belfast news organizations
belfast police headquarters said in a statement that the explosion occurred at security gates in royal avenue
the british broadcasting corp. said the blast was heard more than 12 miles away. police estimated the size of the bomb at 150 pounds. the explosion shattered shop and office windows hundreds of yards away
the police statement said the four soldiers were on patrol in a land rover. it said police believe the bomb was hidden behind an advertising billboard fronting a building site
police earlier said they believed the bomb was thrown by hand but later amended this, saying they thought the bombers detonated it from some distance away using a control wire
the vehicle was stationary at the time. one soldier died almost instantly. the other died later in belfast city hospital, police said
they said a 57-year-old pedestrian passing by was slightly hurt. the army said the two wounded soldiers received only minor injuries
chief inspector jim boyd of belfast police said the attack occurred about 11 p.m. when few people were around
the locally recruited ulster defense regiment is part of the british army
wednesday's death brings to at least 2,628 northern ireland's overall toll since sectarian and political violence flared in 1969
the mainly roman catholic ira wants to drive the british from northern ireland and unite the predominantly protestant province with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic under socialist rule
earlier wednesday, police charged an 18-year-old british soldier with unlawfully killing an unarmed roman catholic civilian
a magistrate in cookstown, 25 miles west of belfast, ordered pvt. david jonathan holden held in police custody until his appearance at a belfast court on march 9
the defense said holden will plead innocent to the charge of unlawfully killing aidan mcanespie, 23. he was hit sunday by a bullet fired from an army observation post at a checkpoint near auchnacloy, half a mile from the irish republic's border
the irish government angered britain by launching its own police investigation
anglo-irish relations have also been strained by britain's refusal to prosecute police officers involved in shooting to death six unarmed catholics in 1982
british and irish leaders wednesday held their first meeting since october under the auspices of the 1985 anglo-irish agreement, which gave ireland an advisory role in northern ireland affairs in an effort to redress grievances of the catholic minority
ireland's foreign affairs minister, brian lenihan, met with northern ireland secretary tom king, the top british official in the province. after the meeting, king said they had arranged for their police chiefs to meet next month to discuss security cooperation along the border
but the irish government later denied that the two sides agreed on such a meeting
a joint communique issued after wednesday's talks focused on proposed british legislation aimed at guaranteeing a fair division of employment between catholics and protestants in northern ireland
meanwhile, police in dublin said they had uncovered a cache of weapons, including 30 soviet-made kalashnikov semi-automatic rifles, in a makeshift bunker beaneath a shed at malahide in the city's northern outskirts
police, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the weapons apparently were destined for the ira and may have been part of four shipments they believe were smuggled from libya into ireland over the last three years
the cache included a dozen rocket warheads, 64 hand grenades, 30,000 bullets and 500 pounds of explosives. additional comments; trims last 7 grafs for length</note>
president reagan said wednesday night the administration has information that suspected terrorists from the outside have been stirring up trouble in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip
reagan made his statement in a nationally televised news conference as secretary of state george p. shultz headed for the middle east with admittedly little chance of setting up arab-israeli negotiations
reporting on shultz' mission, reagan said, ``in the middle east, it's time for all parties to rid themselves of old ideas and stances that cannot work and to begin a serious process of negotiation and reconciliation.''
he was not specific, however, and he passed up several invitations to criticize israeli action against arab protesters in the occupied territories
we have spoken to the government there and we have also spoken to the palestinian leadership because there is every evidence that these riots are not just spontaneous and home grown,'' the president said
asked about the israeli actions against palestinian protesters, reagan said, ``we don't support that sort of thing and we are trying to persuade all the participants to try to arrive at a solution representing justice for all.''
when he was asked to whom he was referring in his statement about the riots not being ``home grown,'' the president responded, ``we have had information that there have been certain people suspected of being terrorists, outsiders coming in, not only with weapons, but stirring up and encouraging the trouble in those areas.''
now, that isn't something you can go out and say we absolutely know, but certainly the violence is both ways,'' the president said
he said he could not be more specific ``because i get into areas there that would be violating security rules, and i don't think i should.''
on a related subject, reagan was asked about reports out of geneva that palestinian liberation organization leader yasser arafat might be willing to accept two united nations resolutions, which he has scorned in the past and which are the cornerstone of u.s. policy in the mideast
well, i know that this is one other thing we're pursuing,'' the president said. ``if he really is, and if he is willing to acknowledge the right of israel to exist as a nation ... i'm sure that the secretary of state will be _ is apprised of that fact, and will see what we can do there.''
reagan said his administration would continue to seek ways to alleviate israeli-arab conflict
that's a goal that i think would ... be one of the greatest achievements of this administration, if before i leave, we could bring about a peace in the middle east,'' he said
before departing for jerusalem, shultz added syria to his itinerary despite u.s. sanctions against a country the state department has condemned as a supporter of terrorism
when we have an issue to address we're going to address it in the most effective way we can,'' department spokesman charles e. redman said. he called syria ``one of the key players in the region.''
sources in damascus said shultz would visit on saturday. redman refused to provide a specific itinerary, saying only that shultz would make stops in israel, jordan, egypt and syria, and that he ``was ready to meet with palestinians.''
he will remain in the region until next tuesday when he flies to london to see king hussein of jordan, who is in the british capital for dental work, and then to brussels for a summit meeting of the north atlantic treaty organization
shultz is leaving his schedule open for a return to the middle east next thursday for a few more days of diplomacy before returning to washington on march 6
shultz rates his chances of setting up negotiations as slim, and said succcess would depend on the israelis and arabs moderating their ``extree positions.''
at a news conference tuesday in brussels, he said ``it's just possible attitudes have shifted enough.''
looking forward to it?'' shultz joshed. ``it's going to be tough.''
the u.s. goal is to find a way for israel and a mixed delegation of jordanians and palestinians to hold negotiations to lower tensions on the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza
temporary self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who live under israeli control is the short-term aim. negotiations by december that leave open the option of a state linked to jordan is the projected second step
this would mean israel's surrendering most of the territory it gained from jordan and egypt in the 1967 six-day war. israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir and his likud bloc do not accept the state department's concept of ``trading territory for peace,'' while hussein refuses to commit himself to negotiations with an uncertain outcome
the palestinians, meanwhile, are divided about their objectives and unable to agree on who would represent them in negotiations
i don't think many people give me much chance,'' shultz said in brussels. he said he found ``intense skepticism'' even among the nato allies
however,'' he said, ``we do have a few ideas. the engagement of the united states on an intense basis is welcomed. i believe that even if the chances are small it's worthwhile trying, and you can't be too afraid of failing.''
shultz will have some good news for mubarak. a u.s. official said wednesday the state department will notify congress it plans to go ahead with a $2 billion, 10-year project to produce m-1 tanks jointly with egypt
the official, who demanded anonymity, said the project would involve the first foreign purchase of the top-of-the-line u.s. tanks. it will be financed from the $1.3 billion in grants that egypt receives annually from the united states
shultz returned to washington tuesday night to report to president reagan on his two days of talks in moscow. he also met with visiting portugese prime minister anibal cavaco silva and spoke to a meeting of the business council
ten years ago, the united states, israel and egypt produced the camp david agreements. this led in 1979 to a peace treaty between israel and egypt and to unsuccessful negotiations over palestinian ``autonomy,'' or limited self-rule
as shultz weighed a trip to the region this month, many arab countries led by egypt and jordan informed the united states that they firmly rejected another interim negotiation based on camp david
