the supreme court expanded significantly the legal protections for parody and satire wednesday as it overturned a $200,000 award evangelist jerry falwell had won against hustler magazine and publisher larry flynt
the justices ruled unanimously that ``emotional distress'' lawsuits filed by public figures targeted by such spoofs should be as difficult to win as libel suits. and the court unanimously said that even pornographic spoofs enjoy the free-speech protection of the constitution's first amendment
republican presidential candidate pat robertson said wednesday that his christian broadcasting network once knew the whereabouts of american hostages in lebanon ``and they could have been freed.''
told of robertson's statement, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater asked, ``why didn't he tell us where they were?''
robertson's comments came at an atlanta news conference during which he complained that u.s. intelligence in the middle east is inadequate and declared that action must be quick when americans are taken hostage
we identified in our news department at cbn the location of those hostages in lebanon very shortly after they were taken, and they were in a position where they could have been rescued. they were in beirut, and they could have been freed,'' said robertson, who did not provide specifics and did not say which hostages were involved
the kremlin on wednesday installed an armenian as the communist party chief of a disputed territory in an apparent effort to end ethnic protests in soviet armenia that a dissident said involved 200,000 people
soviet authorities also ordered an end to the unrest
protesters in yerevan, the armenian capital, want the nagorno-karabakh region in neighboring azerbaidzhan turned over to armenia, smallest of the soviet union's 15 republics
yerevan was the scene tuesday and wednesday of industrial strikes, school boycotts and public demonstrations said to be the largest in the soviet union's 70-year history
the chairman of a white house commission recommended wednesday that federal and local governments spend an additional $20 billion over the next decade to fight aids among drug abusers
retired navy adm. james d. watkins, head of the aids commission appointed by president reagan last summer, acknowledged that the call for such massive spending on drug addicts might prove controversial
but he said 200 hours of testimony from 350 witnesses has left the panel convinced that the deadly disease is spreading most rapidly among the nation's estimated 1.3 million intravenous drug abusers and their sexual partners
as many as 460 americans may get aids infections each year from transfusions of tainted blood that slip through blood-bank screening programs, according to a new federal estimate
a study by the u.s. centers for disease control concludes that there is ``a remote but real risk'' of infection with the aids virus when people get transfusions of blood that has been checked for the virus
the researchers calculate that the odds are about 1 in 40,000 that a blood transfusion will contain the aids virus
a lively pentecostal denomination, shattered by the successive shaming of its two most dazzling tv evangelists, this week was in a state of trauma
some of its leaders were questioning the propriety of television preaching itself
there's a great deal of sadness, shock and grief over the whole situation,'' said juleen turnage, communications officer for the assemblies of god, based in springfield, mo
we're back in the shades of 1987,'' she added, referring to when the sexual lapses struck in the case of ex-tv star jim bakker, and now had hit fiery tv preacher jimmy swaggart
it's a tremendous shock, so totally out of character with what he preached,'' said the rev. robert spence, president of the denomination's evangel college
it's going to have a very, very serious effect on those ministries that are still on television. the element of suspicion of it is going to become even more acute.''
some think that may be a good idea. clinical psychologist larry bass, a denominational member, says there is ``something corrupting about the power'' of dominating huge crowds
there's a kind of narcissistic evil that attracts people to that kind of work, all the self-aggrandizement it gives them. tv gives it even larger magnitude.''
he suggests local congregations should teach people to be more critical in viewing tv preachers and particularly to guard against these dangerous tendencies:
_``putting anyone up on a pedestal, or believing they're virtually the voice of god
_``ministers who put down other religions and people and who are extremely judgmental about the faults of others.''
he said swaggart seemed to fit these categories, almost mesmerizing crowds with his sizzling, emotional fervor and his blistering attacks on other religions and on other people's sexual flaws
nobody has all the answers, and for anyone to act as if they do is a big danger sign,'' bass said. noting that swaggart sometimes said anyone who disagreed with him was wrong, bass added:
anyone who sets himself up with that kind of authority, that he's always absolutely correct, is a dangerous thing, and hardly to be trusted.''
however, he said ``it's unfortunately true'' that the typical kind of followers swaggart attracts ``are the most gullible.''
religion professor stanley m. burgess, an assemblies scholar of southwestern missouri state university in springfield, said the fall of such high-powered evangelists as swaggart serves this clear warning:
we must be careful not to label as gold everything that glitters.''
such celebrated preachers ``still have feet of clay,'' burgess said. ``people have to show greater discernment about them, recognizing that we're not dealing with god here but humans who can fall.''
even in the scandals, he said, ``i would hope people will not drool over it, but learn from it, and look for a silver lining.''
for one thing, he added, ``people who have supported tv ministries may now put their support back in local churches and synagogues, where it has been missing in many cases.''
a noted church communications expert, the rev. william f. fore, maintains that religion, when it buys into television, is co-opted by it and becomes a victim to its focus on self-gratification and quick-fix answers
it ``maximizes self-interest,'' he said in his recent book, ``television and religion,'' grossly twisting the biblical emphasis on selfless service
this corruption of the fundamental biblical concept of conscience into self-interest is perhaps the most serious of all the electronic church's distortions.''
spence said there is ``nothing wrong'' with the medium of television itself, but that it does involve detachment from the local congregation, ``where there is a greater degree of accountability.''
in television, there's not that closeness, of a minister living among his people,'' spence said
furthermore, he added, other aspects of tv raise the ``posibility of distortion,'' such as tv's continual concern of ``what it will look like,'' and how a ``program will go over'' with a mass, theologically uninformed audience
he said that when someone in that situation has been very successful, there's a tendency ``to live in an unreal world, filled only with people who are saying what they think he wants to hear
it's an artificial environment that distorts the whole perspective and can lead to a point of assuming you're stronger than you really are ... that `what might bother other people does not affect me'.''
but despite the deflecting aspects, he said, ``a person has to be of the compromising type to cross over the line'' in his morals, something swaggart was ``definitely not'' in his words. his conduct turned out to be something else
that, spence said, ``is part of the tremendous shock.''
the rev. richard champion, editor of the denomination's weekly, pentecostal evangel, said church leaders ``are going through a personal trauma. here was this brother in christ, and suddenly this happens, and we have to deal with the fallout.''
a noted church growth specialist says the ``prognosis for the sunday school in america is not good,'' with enrollment falling from 40.5 million in 1970 to 26.6 million in 1986
win arn, head of the institute for american church growth, says that in 1970, only 10 percent of the adult population said they received no religious training as a child, while in 1986, the proportion had climbed to 27 percent
mother teresa, founder of the missionaries of charity and winner of the 1979 nobel peace prize, is to receive greek orthodoxy's third athenagoras human rights award at a banquet here saturday, feb. 27
the award, named for the late eastern orthodox patriarch athenagorus, is made by the archons of the order of st. andrew, an organization of greek orthodox laymen
former president jimmy carter, a southern baptist, received the award last year
a leading evangelical theologian says continued controversy in the southern baptist convention has reduced its influence as an evangelical force
the rev. carl f. h. henry, a visiting professor at southern baptist theological seminary here, said the denomination's theological-political struggle has produced the image of a divided denomination, discouraging people from identifying with it
people in the secular city feel they don't want anything to do with either'' side in the conflict over bible interpretation and organizational control, he said
he said energies that would have been devoterd to evangelistic efforts have been devoted to denominational in-fighting
two interreligious affairs leaders say catholic-jewish relations are undergoing a ``severe time of testing'' which must not be allowed to undermine the extraordinary improvements in mutual trust since roman catholicism's reforming second vatican council of 1962-65
eugene l. fisher, executive secretary of the u.s. catholic bishops' secretariat for catholic-jewish relations, told a conference real problems remain, but the past gains are ``irreversible and filled with enormous promise.''
rabbi james rudin, the american jewish committee's interreligious affairs director, said, ``in a world filled with growing religious fanaticism and extremism, we are planting the seeds of reconciliation'' between catholics and jews. ``this legacy ... must be nurtured for the future.''
works of 34 asian christian artists offer their interpretations of faith in a special exhibition, ``that all may be one,'' now touring the united states
the 40 works by artists from japan, indonesia, thailand, sri lanka, korea, australia and india are being shown feb.16-march 18 at manhattan's interchurch center, in new haven, conn., march 21-april 15, in arlington, texas, may 20-27, and in purdue, ind., july 13-18, with further showings being arranged
the exhibition is being sponsored by the east asia and pacific committee of the national councidl of churches
the u.s. catholic conference has petitioned the supreme court to throw out lower court decisions ordering extensive records about abortion turned over to a group seeking to eliminate the church's tax exemption
the conference maintained the group, abortion rights mobilization, has no standing to attack the church's tax exemption, and that allowing it would invite similar challenges to all reglious bodies by political opponents
the group wants the irs to revoke tax exemption of the church's functions, national and local _ thousands of parishes, schools, hospitals, religious orders and other agencies _ on grounds the church engaged in political activity against abortion
people who attempt to determine just what is going on in the executive suite are eyeing a vital statistic that appears to have changed direction again:
the average age at which chief executive officers are appointed to lead top corporations is declining again after a fairly steady rise since the mid- and late 1960s
the changing numbers are likely to prompt a spate of explanations, along with interpretations about the consequences for management and the economy. but, says one authority, they could signify only a tendency of herd behavior
professor eugene jennings finds that in each five-year period from 1950 through 1969 the average age of newly appointed chief executives fell, from 57.7 in 1950-1954 to 50.1 in 1965-1969
after that, the age at appointment rose steadily again, reaching 56.7 years in the 1980-1984 period
but, he advises, it is now on the way down again, and he projects it will be down to 52 years or less in the 1989-1994 period
such patterns obviously invite economic and political interpretations, but jennings cautions against reading too much into them
it may be, he speculates, that it simply ``becomes proper, smart.''
jennings, a pioneer in the study of executive mobility, has been observing corporations since 1949 and has written the book, so to speak, on the upward, sideways and downward patterns in the fortunes of high-ranking executives
his basic studies, ``the mobile manager'' and ``routes to the executive suite,'' have educated graduate students, helped executives understand where they fit in the larger scheme and guided executive recruiters
in studying the numbers, the professor _ he teaches business at michigan state university when he isn't offering confidential advise to chiefs _ found two curious, telling splits, or indications of bimodality, in the age groupings
these splits occurred in 1965-1969 and 1980-1984, and in each instance led to changes in the pattern
when the age level fell to 50.1 years in the earlier period it hardly represented uniformity. instead, 33 percent of the appointments were below age 47 and 35 percent were above 52 years
that bimodality, says jennings, was a turning point. thereafter, the average age of appointment began rising again, reaching a top in 1980-1984. but then that old bimodality came into play again
in the latter period, the split found by jennings was made up of 36 percent below age 50 and 37 percent above age 55. and just as the split back in the 1960s led to a change in direction of the age pattern, this one did also
following the latest split, the average age fell sharply in the 1985-1987 period to 54.6 years. and, jennings speculates, it should continue falling right into the 1990s
jennings recalls that in the 1960s, when he was well into a career of advising corporations about their own behavior, he had little difficulty in selling the idea that a chief executive was good for five years
the notion then, he explains, was to seek optimum power from the executive staff. ``get them at their peak, utilize them and get another.''
companies were growing. ``you didn't want to block the movement of cream to the top,'' he said
there was a strong belief in the system, in ``this is the way we do things at this company.'' executives were there to manage within the system, not necessarily to lead
eventually, however, that attitude changed and the age pattern rose, accompanied by a feeling that a good chairman was hard to find and so you kept him or her for 10 to 15 years
the feeling developed that if age plugged up the movement of cream to the top, then so be it. ``those who left because the plug was stuck in the neck of the bottle were felt to detract less from the organization than the continued contribution of a well-seasoned chief,'' jennings said
the new bimodality began showing up as early as 1982, and says jennings, probably indicates less belief in the system's strength. in fact, there is a suspicion that the whole system is probably faulty and needs changing
this split, jennings says, suggests the feeling has developed in some corporations that people are needed at the helm who aren't so enamored with the system that they wouldn't dare to change it
if my speculation is correct,'' jennings says, ``we have two or three years during which corporate systems will continue to be rebuilt.'' by younger chief executive officers
you wouldn't think perry king and lauren hutton would need a makeover to be ``perfect people'' _ until you saw them in makeup for the abc movie
king, a chiseled, matinee-idol type, spent more than two hours in makeup every morning to look like a middle-aged, overweight, out-of-shape couch potato. the same for hutton, a former fashion model
in ``perfect people,'' which abc will telecast monday, the couple take a good look at themselves and their lifestyle and decide to change
when i read the script, i said this is great but it would be physically impossible for me to play this role,'' said king. ``after they did a transformation on me and took pictures, nobody recognized me except my daughter, louise. she knew me instantly
i'd walk around in makeup and in the fat suit and see how people reacted to me. i had thinning hair, bags under my eyes, jowls. i also spent some time watching fat people to see how they moved. i also stole from tom bray, one of my co-stars on `riptide.' he's thin, but he has a lot of mannerisms and gestures. i called him up and said i was going to use some of them.''
the movie follows kenneth and barbara (ken and barbie?) as they work to regain their lost youth
everything we do is possible,'' king said. ``the plastic surgery, the hair transplants, the implants, the liposuction. but i hope that we make it very clear that it's potentially dangerous, painful and takes a long time. so the differences between the way we looked in the beginning and the way we look at the end can be done
our approach is humorous. we show how they want to look as they did 20 years earlier and the problems it causes. they're no longer grounded in reality. if you can change your appearance, what's real? they were high school sweethearts. it bothers ken that men are now ogling at his wife. it shows that you don't fall in love with someone for their looks. you fall in love with someone for what they are. it's really a sweet little movie about two good people.''
king calls it a nice change from his role as ``a terrible person'' in the miniseries, ``i'll take manhattan.''
i'm getting older and more of my life shows on my face,'' he said. ``that makes it better for me as an actor. i can be cast in different parts.''
king said he was most excited about a pilot for abc he will do with dorian harewood, with whom he has been friends since they did the tv movie ``foster and laurie'' in 1975 about two new york city policemen killed in an ambush in 1972
the projected series was developed from an idea by harewood's wife, ann mccurry, and her friend, louise hoven. the working title is ``black and white.''
we're not cops,'' said king. ``we're half-brothers. our mother has left us only one thing, an investigative newspaper. the only way we can keep it going is to work together. there's a lot of rivalry and dissention between us. hopefully, it'll have the humor of `the rockford files.' jim garner used to call his show an hour-long smile
we're two brothers who've had no contact with each other, although we knew about each other. our mother had had two marriages and two separate lives. if would be great if we could do something with this. people talk all the time about doing something together, but they never do. so, here are two friends who got an idea and decided to do something with it.''
away from work, he continues to work on his motorcycle collection. he has eight motorcycles and two sidecars
it's like owning a fine painting,'' he said. ``if you buy good stuff you'll never lose a penny. jay leno's got really beautiful stuff. mine is sort of middle of the road. he has rare motorcycles. mine are more common, like triumphs, bmws and ducati.''
elsewhere in television:
two camerons make `full house' _ teen heartthrob kirk cameron of abc's ``growing pains'' will guest on his sister's series, abc's ``full house,'' on march 4. candace cameron, six years younger than kirk, plays oldest daughter d.j. on the series. bob saget plays her dad. john stamos and dave coulier are his buddies helping him raise his kids. kirk will play d.j.'s older cousin who comes for a visit and makes her insecure when he hits it off with her dad, making her wonder if he would have preferred a son
the news lately has been anything but comforting for people getting ready to file their tax returns for 1987
when the general accounting office made test queries in the internal revenue service's telephone assistant program for taxpayers, it says it got wrong answers 39 percent of the time
when money magazine asked 50 professional preparers to compute the taxes owed by a hypothetical family, no two came up with the same number. and the preparers' fees ranged from $187 to $2,500
a person might conclude from this that the annual exercise of reckoning up with uncle sam is becoming a high stakes game played under very uncertain rules
if you can't rely totally on the irs's own people for guidance, and if the professionals appear to be taking no more than educated guesses, to whom should you turn for guidance?
even for middle-income taxpayers, a lot rides on the answer to that question. you don't want inadvertently to pay a bigger tax bill than you have to _ but at the same time, you don't want to venture into territory that invites an irs audit
and the value of, say, a $500 tax saving pales if it costs you $600 in preparation fees to get it
the whole situation is certainly troublesome, but it need not be cause for panic. as money magazine describes it, the ``financial profile'' of its theoretical family was more complicated than most people in the real world are likely to have
the tax reform law that contributed so much to all this confusion also made it possible for larger numbers of americans to file using short forms
furthermore, there have been gray areas for many years in the black and white of the income tax forms. though many people complain about this, few have been eager to give up their favorite deductions and credits to the cause of ``simplification.''
even in the present turmoil, many people relish the challenge of tackling the tax forms on their own. they reason that it is about the only chance they get to work for aftertax pay, since a refund isn't taxable income
if you prefer to let somebody else do the work, there are ways to improve your chances of coming out in good shape
first of all, says robert smith, an assistant professor of accounting at boston university school of management, it's important to figure out what kind of help you need
if you determine that your situation is pretty simple, for instance, you don't want to choose a high-priced preparer who specializes in dealing with top corporate executives or rock stars
if you're not sure whether your case is simple or complicated, smith suggests asking for a meeting with a preparer simply to evaluate the degree of service you need
get organized as soon as possible,'' smith says. ``if your preparer has to spend time sorting through your records, your bill may be higher
organized records reduce the chance that an error will occur,'' he adds
another incentive not to put the business off until the april 15 deadline approaches: that is precisely the time when preparers are the busiest and most in demand
some firms lower their fees for clients who come in early or who are willing to have their return filing date extended,'' smith observes
should you find that you need continuing and fairly elaborate tax help, it makes sense to seek out a preparer the way you would a family dentist, doctor or lawyer
as smith concludes: ``you may establish a long-term relationship that will save tax dollars for years to come.''
the u. s. catholic conference has petitioned the supreme court to throw out lower court decisions ordering extensive records about abortion turned over to a group seeking to eliminate the church's tax exemption
the conference maintained the group, abortion rights mobilization, has no standing to attack the church's tax exemption, and that allowing it would invite similar challenges to all religious bodies by political opponents
the group wants the irs to revoke tax exemption of the church's functions, national and local _ thousands of parishes, schools, hospitals, religious orders and other agencies _ on grounds the church engaged in political activity against abortion
works of 34 asian christian artists offer their interpretations of faith in a special exhibition, ``that all may be one,''now touring the united states through the fall
the 40 works by artists from japan, indonesia, thailand, sri lanka, korea, australia and india are being shown feb.16-march 18 at manhattan's interchurch center, in new haven, conn., march 21-april 15, in arlington, texas, may 20-27, and in purdue, ind., july 13-18, with further showings being arranged
the exhibition is being sponsored by the east asia and pacific committee of the national councidl of churches
two interreligious affairs leaders say catholic-jewish relations are undergoing a ``severe time of testing'' which must not be allowed to undermine the extraordinary improvements in mutual trust since roman catholicism's reforming second vatican council of 1962-65
eugene l. fisher, executive secretary of the u.s. catholic bishops' secretariat for catholic-jewish relations, told a conference real problems remain, but the past gains are ``irreversible and filled with enormous promise.''
rabbi james rudin, the american jewish committee's interreligious affairs director, said, ``in a world filled with growing religious fanaticism and extremism, we are planting the seeds of reconciliation'' between catholics and jews. ``this legacy...must be nurtured for the future.''
a leading evangelical theologian says continued controversy in the southern baptist convention has reduced its influence as an evangelical force
the rev. carl f. h. henry, a visiting professor at southern baptist theological seminary here, said the denomination's theological-political struggle has produced the image of a divided denomination, discouraging people from identifying with it
people in the secular city feel they don't want anything to do with either'' side in the conflict over bible interpretation and organizational control, he said
he said energies that would have been devoterd to evangelistic efforts have been devoted to denominational in-fighting
a university of missouri expert in church-state law contends the confirmation of justice arthur kennedy to the u.s. supreme court may result in reopening religion cases from the past four decades
law professor carl h. esbeck says kennedy, a roman catholic, can be expected to support government aid to parochial schools, a more balanced role for religion in public school textbooks, and a voluntary moment of silence for school children
mother teresa, founder of the missionaries of charity and winner of the 1979 nobel peace prize, is to receive greek orthodoxy's third athenagoras human rights award at a banquet here saturday, feb. 27
the award, named for the late eastern orthodox patriarch athenagorus, is made by the archons of the order of st. andrew, an organization of greek orthodox laymen
former president jimmy carter, a southern baptist, received the award last year
a noted church growth specialist says the ``prognosis for the sunday school in america is not good,'' with total enrollment in sunday schools falling from 40.5 million in 1970 to 26.6 million in 1986
win arn, head of the institute for american church growth, says that in 1970, only 10 percent of the adult population said they received no religious training as a child, while in 1986, the proportion had climbed to 27 percent
the minister basked in glory, so exalted that special choirs of women sang praises to him. born poor, he had become rich and famous. when he preached, people sighed and waved handkerchiefs in admiration
but he tumbled into obloquy
that happened to a third-century syrian bishop, paul samosata, dethroned as a heretic, a story recalled as resembling the fall of modern tv-famed evangelists, including the latest, jimmy swaggart
there's nothing new in this _ it's as old as the hills,'' says stanley m. burgess, professor of religion at southwestern missouri state university in springfield, mo., but tv makes it a spectacle for millions
the higher the pedestal, the heavier the winds,'' burgess said in a telephone interview. ``the higher they get up the mountain, the thicker the fog
`it's harder for them to reflect on themselves and see who they really are. with people constantly telling them how wonderful they are, that they're the `man of god for this hour,' it's not a position to be in if one wants to be honest with himself.''
it's the old egocentric problem, as old as the biblical adam who sought to be god himself, but burgess said the glorified are especially vulnerable
this is a common strand that runs through all religious literature,'' he said
as second samuel 1:25 puts it, ``how the mighty are fallen.''
swaggart's fall, over reported involvement with a prostitute, is particularly stark because of his ``hard-line preaching,'' burgess said
he had preached against almost everything imaginable, and then for him to do the very thing he preached against makes it all the more dramatic,'' burgess said
burgess, a scholar of the assemblies of god, the denomination to which swaggart belongs, said some ministers go wrong in every century, and in every denomination ``virtually every day.''
but swaggart, who lashed out at sexual lapses, becomes ``the epitome of hyprocrisy,'' burgess said. ``i do appreciate that he came out with it.''
richard champion, editor of the denomination's weekly, pentecostal evangel, said that when ``people surround themselves with those who always agree, who tell them only good things, they get tripped up in public adulation
ego takes over, and gets out of control. they see evil as something in other people, and rationalize their own behavior...with somebody like swaggart, it a very visible thing.''
clinical psychgologist larry bass of springfield, mo., said that without being specific about swaggart, his case seemed to fit the category of someone who has ``difficulty accepting his own humanness
while he is so vocal attacking other people's sexual sins, he is guilty of some of that himself and struggling with it, but he feels as if he has to be above it, and so he hides it
he comes across as very judgmental and critical of other people. he can't accept his his own vulnerability to sin, so what he has to do is hide it in a kind of self-righteous hypocrisy.''
bass, who also belongs to the assemblies of god, said that many times those who are the ``most judgmental, putting down others and condemning, are guilty of the same thing they're haranguing about
but they have to hide it, that's the shame, they're so afraid to deal with it.''
that kind of ``ego is a tremendous burden to carry around,'' bass said, adding that swaggart's preaching often was bigoted and absolutist, condemning other religions as well as other people
that was his downfall,'' bass said
he noted swaggart had been ``very, very vocal'' in condemning preachers caught in sex scandals, including fallen tv evangelist jim bakker and new orleans evangelist marvin gorman
swaggart admitted to his congregation sunday he had been involved in sin after gorman reportedly supplied church officials with pictures of swaggart at a motel with a prostitute
bass said the highly judgmental types have a ``kind of omnipotence that `i can get away with things,' that `i'm above it all,' above the rules, but it finally catches up with them
he had pushed himself and was most successful, but he had faults and inferiorities that he was hiding and running from. that isn't healthy or mature, and it finally is self-defeating.''
robert spence, president of the denomination's evangel college in springfield, said the ``eminently successful'' tend to live in an ``unreal world, filled with people who say only what they think'' is wanted
it become unreal, an artificial environment, that distorts the whole perspective, and leads a person to the point of assuming he's stronger than he really is...he's lulled to the place he thinks that `what bothers other people doesn't bother me'.''
end adv for fri ams, feb. 26
at age 65, native texan george a. mcalister is a big, friendly, drawling former coach, educator and inventor turned businessman, rancher, historian, author and dreamer
his dream was to make a film based on the battle of the alamo. that dream is coming true
with blazing cannons and bloody sabres, the heroes of the alamo relive on a giant new screen this week the fateful 13-day siege that inspired texas to win its independence from mexico in 1836. a black-tie premiere of the docudrama is set for saturday
entitled ``alamo ... the price of freedom,'' the 45-minute film is an account of the battle based largely on the research and books of mcalister, and it has stirred some controversy
academy award-winning filmmaker kieth merrill directed the movie, part of a $7.2 million project that includes a new imax theater with its 84{-foot wide, six-story high screen. the 426-seat theater is housed in the new rivercenter mall, which overlooks the alamo grounds
the imax system is designed to give viewers visually stunning images as well as a sense of participation in the on-screen activity
the price of freedom'' was filmed last summer at alamo village near brackettville, where john wayne built the set for his epic 1960 film, ``the alamo.''
saturday's premiere benefits the research library operated by the daughters of the republic of texas and includes a reception and dinner-dance and remarks by dallas billionaire nelson bunker hunt
gov. bill clements will be on hand the next day for formal dedication ceremonies, which coincide with the 152nd anniversary of the fall of the alamo to mexican gen. santa anna
there are two great symbols of freedom in america,'' mcalister said. ``first is the statue of liberty. but it is just that _ a symbol of freedom. then there is this old stone mission, the alamo, a shrine to the price of freedom
and there is a difference between a symbol of freedom and a price of freedom.''
a veteran of world war ii and the korean conflict, mcalister pointed out gently that a lot of people are willing to live for a cause but only a very few are willing to die for one
the defenders of the alamo were willing to die for freedom,'' he said. ``and more than 3 million people from all over the world came to the alamo last year to pay homage to those 189 brave men who gave their lives that texas might be free.''
mcalister once stood outside the alamo for days asking visitors if they would pay to see an authentic movie of the historic battle and if they were familiar with imax theaters
he liked the answers. and the premiere this weekend showcases the results of that private poll
while stressing the importance of authenticity, mcalister points out quickly that much of what occurred at the alamo is subject to speculation and individual interpretation
there are no chronicles of the alamo and what happened there,'' he said
still, mcalister spent 12 years researching his books. his travels took him to goliad, san jacinto, washington-on-the-brazos and other battle sites and to louisiana, tennessee, south carolina and alabama to visit the hometowns of the most famous defenders of the alamo: col. william b. travis, jim bowie, davy crockett and james bonham
mcalister also describes the alamo contribution of the tejanos, the nine mexicans who supported the texas cause
he and his colleagues say they have made their movie as historically accurate as possible without sacrificing dramatic and entertainment value
if we were going to make a movie for several generations, i did not want it to be fiction,'' mcalister said
the movie has no stars but uses 450 members of war-enactment societies across the country who are dedicated to historical accuracy, costume and customs
mcalister was surprised and dismayed when san antonio city councilman walter martinez and a group of residents accused the producers of distorting historical facts
after viewing a rough cut of the movie, martinez complained that the film demeaned hispanics by making them look like bad guys, and presented a list of objections to texas cavalcade corp., the production group headed by mcalister
kathy pena-sosa, a spokeswoman for texas cavalcade, said some objectionable scenes were deleted in the final editing from 73 minutes to 45 minutes, but professed to be puzzled by the criticism
in a community that's 54 percent hispanic,'' she said, ``we're not going to make a movie that's offensive to hispanics.''
born and raised in east texas, mcalister got his first exposure to texas history in a two-room, two-teacher schoolhouse in a tiny hamlet near commerce
he interrupted his collegiate studies at east texas state in 1942 to enlist in the marines, but returned after the war to get a master's degree in math. his minor was history
during an academic career that was interrupted when he was recalled to active duty in korea in 1950, mcalister was a dean at howard county junior college in big spring, as well as chairman of the math department, coach of the track team and an amateur inventor
in 1955, with $150, he founded a company called gamco to create and build teaching aids for math students, including a classroom computer and an electronic teaching machine. the sale of gamco in 1966 made him a millionaire
it also freed him to pursue his ranching and writing interests and to devote more time to historical research
his first novel, ``nothing is forever,'' was based on the early life of travis. that book evolved into a second novel, ``a time to love ... a time to die.''
this led in turn to ``alamo ... the price of freedom,'' a non-fiction book which mcalister describes as ``history as i view it and my personal research reveals it.''
for mcalister, ``the price of freedom'' is more than a movie or a business venture
said he: ``i would like to leave a legacy on the screen that retells the story of this sacrifice for freedom ... that demonstrates to a new generation that freedom isn't free ... that liberty rests finally on those willing to die for it.'' 2. najib, one name, is cq.</note>
the united states and the soviet union both are pushing for an end to the war in afghanistan as negotiations in geneva enter a decisive stage this week, but complex issues remain to be settled
secretary of state george p. shultz's talks in moscow last week ended on a note of optimism. the kremlin said again it wants to end the red army intervention that has cost an estimated 10,000 soviet lives in what mikhail s. gorbachev has called a ``bleeding wound.''
pakistan and afghanistan are negotiating with united nations mediation. but the two major players are the soviet union, which intervened in 1979, and the united states, which backs the moslem guerrilla forces fighting afghanistan's marxist government
the soviet leader sent hopes soaring when he pledged moscow will withdraw its estimated 115,000 troops within ten months starting may 15, provided a peace settlement is signed by pakistan and afghanistan by march 15
with the geneva talks starting wednesday, gorbachev's deadline would leave just 13 days to tie up the package of agreements designed to end nine years of fighting
after a 20-day shuttle between kabul and islamabad, u.n. mediator diego cordovez reported early this month ``virtual agreement'' on the timetable of the soviet withdrawal. the united states and pakistan still would prefer to give the soviets less than 10 months to leave
in almost six years of negotiations, accords have been reached on mutual non-interference, on superpower guarantees that afghanistan will be non-aligned, and on the return of 3.5 million afghans sheltered by pakistan _ the largest concentration of refugees in the world
but crucial aspects are still unresolved. the major issues:
_at what stage is the aid to the guerrillas to be cut off? gorbachev hinted in a feb. 8 statement the american support is no longer a problem
but washington officials have said the timing of the cutoff has not yet been determined. u.s. supplies reportedly totaled $670 million in 1987. the supplies funneled through pakistan include shoulder-fired stinger missiles said to have downed more than 200 soviet and afghan aircraft
_how should the withdrawal be phased? gorbachev has said a ``relatively greater portion'' of the soviet forces will be withdrawn rapidly. but a diplomatic source close to the talks, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there were still ``very different approaches'' to the pace of the withdrawal
_will the settlement involve iran, host to another 2 million afghan refugees and base for other moslem resistance groups pressing for a non-marxist islamic government? iran has refused to join in the talks but says it will accept any settlement satisfying the ``legitimate aspirations'' of the afghan people
the most difficult question, however, is outside the scope of the geneva talks: who will sign for afghanistan and what government will be installed in kabul during the withdrawal?
pakistan argues that a durable settlement requires the prior formation of a ``broad-based'' interim government to prevent more bloodshed and assure the refugees' safe return
president zia ul-haq said in an interview in the washington post last month that pakistan would not sign any settlement with the present marxist government headed by president najib in kabul, the afghan capital
pakistan does not recognize najib's government and insists the geneva talks be conducted in an indirect fashion, with cordovez acting as go-between. zia reportedly would like to see an interim coalition in kabul, including the anti-marxist guerrillas, afghan exiles and some representatives of najib's people's democratic party
gorbachev, who assured a visiting najib in december 1986 that moscow would not abandon him, says the makeup of the future government is an internal matter and ``none of our business.''
still, gorbachev is expected to seek some guarantee to prevent a bloodbath during or after the troop withdrawal. otherwise, najib and members of his government, as well as departing soviets, could be left defenseless against reprisal killings
the soviet union shares a long border with afghanistan and there has been no indication whether the kremlin will be willing to relinquish any attempt to influence events in the country once the red army is withdrawn
most of the pakistan-based groups representing the estimated 200,000 moslem guerrillas fighting the soviets and the kabul government's army of about 50,000 have ruled out any power-sharing with najib
last week, the guerrillas announced plans for a 28-member transitional cabinet to replace najib's government and sign the geneva settlement on behalf of afghanistan ``if the terms are deemed acceptable.''
the insurgents vowed they would not lay down their arms until an islamic government was established
kabul radio reported that najib insisted a new government should be formed after the soviet forces withdraw and the composition of a new government is a matter for ``afghans alone.''
at the same time, pakistan is trying to win allies in its push for an intersion would be similar to president reagan's proposal that was narrowly killed by the house three weeks ago, but would exclude any money for new weapons. it would retain the cia as delivery agent for the supplies, and would give president reagan the right to seek a new vote on a weapons package after may 1
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, called the democratic proposal ``the most workable kind of program'' and one that will provide ``balanced incentives'' for the contras and the leftist sandinista government to pursue peace talks called for in a regional accord
the package was unveiled late tuesday by rep. david bonior, d-mich., after two weeks of intensive negotiations among several factions of the chamber's majority party. it went before the rules committee today, where republicans were expected to demand the right to offer their own alternative
president reagan did not immediately react to the democrats' package. his own $36.2 million aid proposal for the rebels, including weapons, was narrowly rejected by the house three weeks ago
among major elements in the democratic proposal:
_about $3.6 million a month for the contras: half to buy food, clothing, medicine and shelter, and the other half to pay for delivery of the supplies to rebel troops inside nicaragua. the aid would run from march 1, after current aid expires, until june 30. it could continue until the end of the year if a cease-fire is reached by june 30
_about $1.4 million for nicaragua's miskito indians, an opposition group that has been carrying out its own battle against the sandinistas, but has consistently refused invitations to join with the contras. the indians already have worked out their own cease-fire with the managua regime
_a new $14 million ``children's survival fund,'' to provide medical help for children on all sides of the conflict. the aid would be administered by ``non-political'' private aid groups or international relief agencies already working in the region
not included in the package was any long-term economic development aid for the region, but a democratic fact sheet said ``congress will welcome proposals'' from reagan on that subject
current aid to the rebels expires feb. 29, and with it the legal authority for the cia to continue air drops of previously stockpiled weapons and ammunition. the new package contains no such authority
under the new proposal, the contras' ``humanitarian'' supplies would be delivered by private contractors supervised by the defense department until the contras and the sandinistas are able to agree on a cease-fire
the deliveries would be monitored by the congressional intelligence committees and the general accounting office, congress' investigative arm, to ensure that no weapons were included
after fighting stops, responsibility for delivery would shift to a private aid group or an international relief agency such as the red cross
the package also would provide for an expedited procedure for a vote on new military aid for the rebels _ a high priority for the reagan administration _ if a cease-fire should fall apart and the sandinistas should fail to keep their promises to democratize
the determination of whether expedited procedures should be initiated would be made by the house intelligence committees, according to a fact sheet on the package. but republicans were skeptical of the provision, saying it was not a solid guarantee that military aid would come to a quick vote in both the house and senate
wright said he was ``not necessarily'' confident of the votes to pass the package. republicans have remained aloof from the drafting process, holding out for more aid and for continued authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled eapons
the key to this really will be how much support it gets on the republican side,'' said rep. stephen solarz, d-n.y., a longtime contra aid opponent who added that he planned to vote against the package
other democrats said they expected at least 70 in their party to oppose the proposal
the party is seeking a middle ground on an issue that is not compromisable,'' said rep. robert torricelli, d-n.j. ``it appears to me to be an exercise in attempting to cover ourselves'' and avoid political blame if the contras go out of business and the sandinistas renege on promises to increase civil liberties
democrats have argued against new military aid, saying that providing it would endanger peace efforts. talks between the contras and sandinistas broke off over the weekend without progress, and no date has been set for their resumption
reagan and many congressional republicans have countered that it is only consistent military pressure from rebel attacks that has forced the sandinistas into peace talks
a dozen turbaned, bearded men with machine guns patrol a walled villa where the seven leaders of afghanistan's guerrilla alliance draw up plans for an islamic nation of afghanistan
the meetings have become almost continuous in this dusty frontier city, a short ride from the afghan border, since the soviet union announced last month it planned to pull out troops backing afghanistan's marxist government. moscow said it would withdraw its estimated 115,000 soldiers within ten months starting may 15 if pakistan and afghanistan sign a peace agreement by march 15
with the geneva talks entering a crucial stage on wednesday, the time pressure is helping fuse the often fractious mujahedeen guerrilla military alliance into a united political force
they're closer than before but the question is, for how long?'' said abdul haq, a guerrilla commander from kabul province
so far, the resistance leaders have agreed to install themselves as a joint executive over a 28-member cabinet that will include guerrillas, afghan refugees and moslems ``presently living in kabul.''
it calls for the head of a cabinet to be head of state, but the plan contains no names. it proposes to replace the soviet-backed kabul government before an accord is signed at the u.n.-sponsored talks in geneva
neither pakistan, which backs the guerrillas, nor the afghan communists appears likely to accept the proposal unchanged. the pakistanis have told the insurgents they may have to share power with the communists, at least in a transitional regime
we're in a hurry. there is little time,'' said abdul qadir karyad, head of the political wing of the fervent moslem party hezb-i-islami, led by gulbaddin hekmatyar
although his party is considered the most extreme of the ``fundamentalist'' groups, karyad indicated the hezb-i-islami was coming around to compromise with the more moderate ones in the name of unity
we want to be logical. we want to show the world we can accept responsibility for our country,'' karyad said
nevertheless, the guerrillas' blueprint for a new government does not explain just how it would come to power. it assumes the soviet-backed kabul regime will simply step aside
the flurry of compromise follows pakistan's insistence that an afghan settlement must consist of a military accord, such as the one near completion at geneva, and a political accord for a ``broad-based'' interim government that could head off a bloody power struggle as soviet troops head home
the three ``moderate'' guerrilla parties _ ittehad, the afghan national liberation front and the national islamic front for the liberation of afghanistan _ apparently have dropped their support of bringing back ousted king zahir shah to head a neutral transitional regime
it's not really proper to raise the zahir shah issue just now,'' said zabiullah mojaddedi, son of anlf leader sibghatullah mojaddedi. ``we should have a leader from within the mujahedeen. if not, then we can consider that option.''
all seven parties fully agree on one point: they refuse to join even a temporary coalition with communists
how can i work in an office with somebody who killed my brother, my neighbors?'' said karyad
hezb-i-islami, along with the jamiat-i-islami and the hezb-i-islami faction led by alliance chairman yunis khalis, have gone so far as to threaten to ignore a geneva accord as long as the mujahedeen are excluded from the talks
the indirect negotiations have been between the kabul government and pakistan, which serves as the guerrillas' headquarters and shelters about 3.5 million afghan refugees. the united states, which backs the guerrillas, and the soviet union are to be the guarantors of an accord
all seven resistance parties say they want to negotiate directly with the soviets because they view the kabul government as moscow's puppet
i hope the soviets will be wise enough to sit down and discuss the technicalities (of a withdrawal) with the mujahedeen,'' mojaddedi said
here is a brief look at what the soviet union hopes to achieve in the march 2 negotiations in geneva between its ally, afghanistan, and pakistan
_ through their afghan allies, the soviets likely will formally commit themselves to withdrawing their estimated 115,000 troops starting may 15 and to completing the process within 10 months. soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev announced the plan on feb. 8
_ the kremlin is likely to reiterate its demand that the united states, pakistan and other western countries stop supplying weapons to the moslem guerrillas fighting the pro-soviet kabul government. the soviets have suffered heavy losses of aircraft since the united states and britain first began sending the rebels stinger antiaircraft missiles, which can track and down aircraft by sensing engine heat
_ gorbachev has said his country wants no say in who governs afghanistan or the country's politics after the troops come home. even so, he is expected to seek some guarantee that a bloodbath will not occur during or after the troop withdrawal. without such a promise, afghan leader najib and members of his government, as well as departing soviets, would be left defenseless against a widespread insurgency, which could lead to reprisal killings
_ the soviets likely will resist any attempts by pakistan to tie an afghan settlement in geneva to formation of a coalition government in afghanistan. gorbachev said afghanistan's future government should be decided as ``an internal matter.'' ranking soviet officials have accused pakistan of delaying a settlement by insisting the future government issue be resolved before the troop withdrawal begins. soviet first deputy foreign minister yuli vorontsov contended in a pravda interview published thursday that the future government ``has nothing to do with the geneva agreements.''
here is a brief look at what the united states hopes to achieve in the negotiations between afghanistan and pakistan in geneva:
_ the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 soviet troops from afghanistan has been a high priority for the white house and congress since the soviet occupation began in december 1979
quick withdrawal remains an immediate goal of the united states, the anti-marxist moslem guerrillas and the pro-western government in pakistan, which has provided sanctuary for 3.5 million afghans and channels millions of dollars in covert military aid to the resistance from the united states, china and arab nations
secretary of state george p. shultz and other u.s. officials welcomed the statement by kremlin leader mikhail gorbachev that he wants to start pulling the estimated 120,000 red army soldiers out of afghanistan by may 15 if u.n.-sponsored negotiations produce an agreement by march 15
but the reagan administration is pushing the soviets to either shorten their proposed 10-month withdrawal, or to pull out most troops early
we don't see any reason why they couldn't be out by the end of the year if they start in the middle of may,'' shultz said
under a plan being discussed behind the scenes, the united states would stop sending military aid as soon as the soviets began to withdraw. half the soviet troops would withdraw within the first 90 days, 30,000 more over the next 90 days, and the remaining 30,000 over the following four months
_ a longer term goal, on which guerrilla groups and the pakistani government are split, is over the government to replace the soviet-backed regime in kabul. u.s. officials believe that no pro-soviet regime could survive after the red army leaves
shultz said this month that the guerrillas would not accept positions in a government run by president najib, the head of the kabul regime
it is difficult to imagine how an interim regime is going to be put together,'' shultz said
for the first time since 1928, a u.s. governor faces trial before his legislature monday. in the following report, an ap special correspondent offers a portrait of arizona, its people and their governor at the crossroads of impeachment
for evan mecham, arizona's governor-in-exile, it has come to high noon
here in the land of geronimo and wyatt earp and the ok corral, a part of america never known for pussyfooting, the arizona senate on monday begins the final act in a course of redress not seen in this nation in more than half a century. it will decide whether to remove the impeached governor from office
members of the senate will not predict the outcome, only that it likely will be close and that however it turns out there will be, politically speaking, a lot of blood left on the ground
it's ripping up our party and state in a fashion that's going to take years to recover,'' says u.s. sen. john mccain
when mccain and three other republican members of arizona's congressional delegation suggested that fellow republican mecham resign, the senator began receiving hate mail by the sackful
the mob that crucified our precious lord is the same kind of mob that is after our governor,'' wrote one constituent
the other day about 2,000 mecham supporters took out their anger, while raising money for his defense, by bashing an automobile with a sledgehammer, three licks for a dollar. the car was painted with slogans such as ``media bias,'' identifying what they perceived as the causes of the governor's predicament
the arizona house approved impeachment articles feb. 5 accusing mecham of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from funds raised by his inauguration committee, and trying to thwart an investigation into a state official's alleged death threat against a witness in a grand jury probe of mecham
the 63-year-old, staunchly conservative governor also had antagonized many arizonans with controversial statements on ethnic groups and social issues
after the vote, mecham stepped down provisionally as governor and moved into political exile, in an office in nearby glendale. now the house charges are to be tried in the 30-member senate, where 20 votes would convict him and remove him permanently from office
but not even the extreme measure of an impeachment trial is likely to put to rest the turmoil in arizona. if mecham survives, he still faces a criminal trial for not reporting a campaign loan and a recall election resulting from a public petition
recall election? all right then, said mecham supporters, and began circulating petitions to recall as well house members who voted for the governor's impeachment
yes, there is little stability these days in arizona politics
anywhere in arizona, for that matter
the phoenix area, maricopa county, is the second-fastest-growing urban area in america, just behind san diego. it gains one new citizen every 12 minutes. that's net gain. state figures also show that for every four newcomers, three others move out
all that coming and going causes such instability that one mental health organization recommended a state program to discourage growth. arizona, for instance, has one of the nation's highest divorce rates, a suicide rate 50 percent higher than the national average and, among adolescents, 70 percent higher. it also ranks last in per-capita funding for mental health
we have an enormous amount of work to do in this state,'' says state sen. greg lunn, a tucson republican
that's another reason why the impeachment is such a distracting turn of events. the senate will be tied up with it for weeks. important matters that should be dealt with this session will have to be deferred to the next.''
lunn has a special interest in environmental matters. well he might. the phoenix area is promoted to tourists and potential settlers as the valley of the sun. but dust and emissions and temperature inversions conspire against the sun. phoenix's smog rivals the worst in the nation. so do its traffic jams
once outside phoenix, however, or tucson, the state's only two urban areas, you can drive for hours without seeing another car. geographically as well as politically and socially, arizona is a state of stunning contrasts and contradictions
the state is sixth in the nation in size but its 3.35 million population ranks 25th. three-fourths of its people live in the phoenix and tucson metropolitan areas. the rest live in villages and towns scattered across mountains and deserts and forests staggering in their solitude, and, in many areas, their poverty
in rural areas much of the frontier west prevails, and not just in the rigorously independent attitude of the people. at cordes junction, near prescott, the cafe requires patrons to check their weapons at the door. many do just that, since in arizona it's perfectly legal to pack a gun openly
rivalry in arizona is fierce between city and country for the state's attention to their needs. mecham was supported by rural voters who saw his two election opponents as representing the phoenix elite. his impeachment intensifies those jealousies
feelings for and against evan mecham are held with such passion that some longtime friends are reluctant to bring up the subject, not knowing how the other stands
some thingsks and orientals. he dismissed those petitioning for his recall as ``dissident democrats and homosexuals.''
now it comes down to the impeachment trial itself
only 15 u.s. governors have faced impeachment proceedings. only seven were removed from office, the last oklahoma's henry simpson johnston in 1928
thomas jefferson was once impeached, in 1781 as governor of virginia. his accuser was patrick henry, who thought jefferson left the capital with unseemly haste when british troops attacked. jefferson insisted on a trial and won vindication
so evan mecham, it appears, is in pretty good company. but, then, so are his accusers
adv for release sunday, feb. 28, and thereafter
the battle for the white house won't be the only thing on the minds of some super tuesday voters. in mississippi, they'll begin choosing a new senator; in louisiana's 4th district they may elect a new congressman, and in monroe, n.c., they'll decide whether to legalize sales of mixed drinks
of the 20 mostly southern and border states holding presidential primaries and caucuses march 8, four _ arkansas, mississippi, maryland and texas _ are holding their regular state primaries at the same time
but even in places where the state primary will be held later, officials have slipped statewide or local issues onto the super tuesday ballot
it's a cost-effective measure and it would tend to draw a larger turnout for both issues,'' explains jim hamilton of the florida division of elections
in mississippi, the retirement of sen. john c. stennis after 41 years has sparked a close democratic primary race between rep. wayne dowdy and secretary of state dick molpus. ed cole, state democratic chairman, says the combination of the presidential and senate primaries ``should ensure a pretty good turnout.'' rep. trent lott is unopposed for the gop nomination
in maryland and texas, democratic sens. lloyd bentsen and paul sarbanes faces token challenges for renomination and will be heavily favored over whichever republicans win their party's nominations. texas also has primaries for five of nine seats on its supreme court, which has become a political battleground with two justices publicly reprimanded, two others quitting and republicans hoping to achieve an unprecedented majority
arkansas features a heated democratic primary in the 1st congressional district, where 10-term rep. bill alexander is challenged by campaign consultant darrell glascock, who says the incumbent neglects his district and spends too much time jetting to central america
the texas secretary of state estimated it would have cost $12 million extra to hold separate state and presidential primaries. bob fisher of the arkansas attorney general's office said the two parties would have had to ``raise filing fees to an unholy amount'' to finance separate primaries
in louisiana, voters in the 4th district will select a replacement in the u.s. house for gov.-elect buddy roemer, who takes office on march 14. roemer asked that the balloting be scheduled for super tuesday to cut down on election costs in his financially strapped state
nine democrats and one republican are competing in the open primary in which a candidate is elected if he receives a majority. otherwise, the top two finishers compete in a runoff. the field includes former rep. claude ``buddy'' leach, who lost to roemer in 1980 following leach's acquittal on vote-buying charges
in georgia, legislators added a statewide referendum to the ballot with the hope of bolstering turnout for the presidential primary. the measure asks voters whether to increase from $8,000 to $10,000 the amount of gross income people 62 and older may receive and still be exempt from some school and property taxes
every presiding officer that i've talked with, every governor, is worried about a low turnout,'' said speaker of the house tom murphy prior to pushing the referendum through the general assembly. ``we need a tremendous turnout _ the more folks the better.''
in north carolina, referendums on whether to permit mixed drink sales are scheduled in monroe and three other cities and counties
this is an excellent way to avoid the cost of a separate election,'' said state treasurer harlan boyles. ``in wake county, for example, they're having a separate election and it will cost something like $100,000.''
in tennessee, state election coordinator david haines estimates that about 40 of 95 counties will hold their primaries for tax assessor and school superintendent on march 8, mainly to save money
the tennessee legislature last year appropriated $2 million to cover the cost of the presidential primary, and gave counties the option of conducting their county primaries then at state expense or in may at their own. counties must also pay for the august statewide primary and the november general election
ironically, in oklahoma, two ballot issues relating to economic development were taken off the march 8 ballot and rescheduled for september because of fears that they wouldn't get the necessary attention because of the presidential campaign
the two were so important that we were afraid they would get lost in all the hullabaloo, in all the things going on,'' said gov. henry bellmon's assistant press secretary, wendy johnson
governing boards of two of the nation's largest energy unions have met separately in denver to discuss a possible merger, according to a union source
executive boards of the united mine workers of america and the oil chemical and atomic workers international union have been meeting privately in denver since monday, the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said tuesday
experts said the combination of the unions _ each of which report about 100,000 active members _ would consolidate the bargaining power of the two unions in their dealings with major oil companies
the supreme court has ruled that businesses may not be sued in federal court in certain cases involving their contributions to union benefit funds
the court said tuesday the federal courts have no authority over cases in which companies refuse to contribute to multi-employer union benefit funds after a collective bargaining agreement expires
in an 8-0 ruling in a case from california, the court rejected reagan administration arguments that barring lawsuits in such cases could undermine the solvency of the multi-employer pension plans
mcdonnell douglas corp. surpassed two competitors last year to reclaim the title of largest u.s. defense contractor, the pentagon says
in its annual rating of the top 100 military contractors, the pentagon said tuesday that mcdonnell douglas jumped past general dynamics corp. and general electric co. to win the top ranking for fiscal 1987
st. louis-based mcdonnell douglas increased its pentagon work by $1.1 billion during the year to a new total of $7.7 billion, easily surpassing general dynamics' $7 billion
the national governors' association has voted 30-5 to support ratification of the u.s.-canada free trade agreement despite some governors' fears that it will hurt home state industries
the governors acted tuesday after amending their resolution to express ``significant concerns about issues created or not fully resolved by the agreement,'' and demanding to be consulted on legislation to ratify and implement the treaty
nike inc., which has been using the beatles' recording of the song ``revolution'' in its advertising despite the group's protests, will discontinue the ads in late march
nike's license to use the beatles' recording expires next month, but before it runs out, the company plans to run one more new commercial with the song, gerald sobel, a new york-based lawyer for the athletic footwear company, said tuesday. the ad campaign began last spring
the three surviving beatles, through their recording company, apple records, have claimed they never intended their recordings for use in commercials
the stock market finished little changed tuesday. the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks slipped 1.17 to 2,039.12
precious metals futures fell sharply on federal reserve chairman alan greenspan's predictions of modest economic growth and continued low inflation. on other futures markets, livestock, meat, orange juice, grains, soybeans and stock indexes retreated
bond prices rose in response to falling commodity prices and greenspan's remarks
the dollar mostly was lower in choppy foreign currency trading. gold prices also fell
footwear maker nike inc., which has been using the beatles' recording of the song ``revolution'' in its advertising despite the group's protests, plans to scrap the ads next month
nike spokesman kevin brown said the athletic footwear company was happy with the results of the ads, which have been running since last spring, but wants to freshen its advertising approach
as a result, he said nike decided against exercising its option to use the beatles' recording for another year
its license to use the recording expires march 22, but before it runs out, brown said nike plans to run one more new commercial with the song. the new ad, which debuts this week, is aimed mainly at women, he said
nike's ``revolution'' commercials to date have shown people walking, playing basketball and participating in other sports while wearing nike shoes. the only sound is the beatles' recording
the three surviving beatles, through their recording company, apple records, have claimed they never intended that their recordings be used in commercials
nike, which is based in beaverton, ore., has insisted it is an innocent bystander in a longstanding dispute between apple and companies that hold the licensing rights to the beatle's original recordings
nike reportedly paid $250,000 to capitol records inc., which holds the north american licensing rights to the beatles' recordings, for the right to use the group's rendition of ``revolution'' in nike ads for a year
last july, apple records, controlled by the three surviving beatles and john lennon's widow, yoko ono, filed a suit charging that nike was using the rock group's ``persona and goodwill'' in its advertising without permission
the suit, which is still pending in u.s. district court in new york, asked for $15 million in damages and named nike and its ad agency, capitol records and emi records ltd., which holds licensing rights outside north america
nike has contended it had a valid contract to use the recording, intended no disrespect to the beatles and was an innocent victim in a dispute between apple, capitol and emi
leonard m. marks, an attorney for apple, said he felt the decision showed nike was ``being responsive to the lawsuit and the numerous complaints of beatles fans'' about its use of the recordings
he said he was optimistic that after nike's action ``we will be able to reach a settlement of the case with nike shortly.''
but brown insisted the decision not to renew rights to the music was unrelated to the suit
it was a business decision,'' he said. ``it makes sense to continuously update your ads.''
he said nike had received about 150 to 200 letters from people objecting to nike's use of the song, but said the company was generally satisfied with the performance of the ads. he said sales for the six months ended nov. 30 were up substantially from the same period a year earlier
public service co. of new hampshire, which sought bankruptcy-court protection because of the stalled $5.2 billion seabrook nuclear plant, has attracted takeover interest from a neighboring utility
the proposed takeover disclosed tuesday by new england electric system, based in westborough, mass., would not include public service's 36 percent share of seabrook
it also would require approval by a bankruptcy judge, state regulators in massachusetts and new hampshire, both companies' directors and possibly some federal agencies
public service, new hampshire's largest power company and the lead seabrook owner, sought federal bankruptcy protection last month, a move that symbolized the difficulties facing public utilities with heavy investments in nuclear power. it became the first major investor-owned utility to seek the refuge of bankruptcy court since the depression
under new england electric's proposal, public service, would be left only with its share of the reactor, which is completed but has been unable to surmount evacuation-planning obstacles to an operating license
new england electric subsidiary new england power co. owns 10 percent of seabrook. officials of the parent company would not comment on why they don't want to increase their share of the controversial plant
samuel huntington, president of the parent company, said in a statement that the takeover would let the new public service pay its share of the costs of keeping seabrook ready while plant owners keep fighting for an operating license. huntington did not explain how that would happen
a spokesman for seabrook's joint owners, david scanzoni, speculated that ``it would be likely that there would be some kind of cash infusion that would be part of the arrangement'' to let the new public service maintain its share of seabrook carrying costs, estimated at $3 million to $4 million a month
scanzoni said new england electric would want to continue supporting seabrook since it already owns a chunk of the plant
in many ways this a very positive step for seabrook station,'' scanzoni said of the takeover talks
one seabrook foe said he can't see how the takeover would let the remaining public service pay seabrook carrying costs on its own
they can't gt any revenue out of it unless they license it,'' manchester lawyer robert backus noted
new hampshire law bars utilities from charging ratepayers for power plants before they operate commercially. the state supreme court upheld that law on jan. 26, denying public service an emergency rate increase and forcing the utility to seek bankruptcy protection two days later
a wall street utility analyst, dan scotto of l.f. rothschild holdings inc., said a takeover would make business sense for new england electric since aside from seabrook, public service is a profitable company
but ``this is not going to be clear sailing,'' scotto said, partly because of unresolved questions about ratemaking authority
scotto also said the proposal indicates new england electric is showing a lack of confidence in seabrook's prospects
evacuation plans for a 10-mile zone around seabrook must be approved before the plant can be licensed. massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, a democratic presidential hopeful, has played a key role in blocking the plant by refusing to submit plans for six communities in his state within the zone
seabrook has submitted its own plans for massachusetts. no hearings have been set on them yet
american standard inc. faced intensified takeover pressure from black &amp; decker corp. after the power-tool maker raised its offer to $2.11 billion, but analysts began to query whether the price was getting expensive
black &amp; decker said tuesday it would pay $68 a share for the american standard's stock, compared with $65 a share or about $2.03 billion offered previously. it was the third time black &amp; decker has raised the offer
some wall street securities analysts were surprised and said the price was becoming inflated for american standard, a maker of plumbing, heating and air conditioning equipment. it has been maneuvering to escape a takeover
they (black &amp; decker) obviously see something i don't see,'' said guy nielsen, an analyst at brown brothers harriman and co. in new york. ``the bidding has gotten to the point where i can't justify the $68 price.''
he said the bidding ``already is a bit on the rich side.''
others had expected black &amp; decker to raise the offer or drop the takeover attempt entirely after american standard announced monday it had financing commitments for a recapitalization aimed at thwarting the hostile bid
black &amp; decker's latest offer, which would expire at midnight est march 7, compares with the initial offer of $56 a share made in late january. the towson, md.-based manufacturer had said previously it would not raise the offer above $65 a share unless it could see american standard's books
american standard has rejected both previous offers as inadequate. the new york-based company urged shareholders tuesday not to tender shares under the latest bid until it was reviewed by the board of directors
american standard stock rose 12{ cents to $68.25 a share in new york stock exchange trading, while black &amp; decker dipped 12{ cents to $19.37{
in a news release, black &amp; decker said it also intended to file counterclaims in federal court in delaware seeking to invalidate american standard's ``poison pill'' takeover defense and to halt any action on the recapitalization
the $2.1 billion recapitalization plan would make american standard less attractive as a takeover target by boosting its long-term debt to more than $2 billion and sharply increasing its outstanding shares and equivalents, such as stock options
american standard, incorporated in delaware, had asked the federal court to validate its poison pill, designed to make a takeover prohibitively expensive by diluting the target company's stock. the court last week rejected black &amp; decker's attempt to block american standard from seeking such a ruling
black &amp; decker also has challenged delaware's new anti-takeover law as unconstitutional
in addition, black &amp; decker is awaiting regulatory approval to begin a maneuver similar to a proxy fight to oust american standard's board of directors. if successful, black &amp; decker could repeal the recapitalization and the ``poison pill.''
texaco inc.'s agreement to pay the government $1.25 billion to settle claims it overcharged customers during the 1973-81 era of price-controls removes one uncertainty confronting the troubled oil giant, which has been under federal bankruptcy court protection for nearly a year
but the third-largest u.s. oil company still faces a complicated exit process from chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, a $3 billion payment to pennzoil co., a possible takeover fight with two well known corporate raiders and a back-tax bill of up to $6.5 billion from the internal revenue service
under the overcharge-dispute settlement announced tuesday with the energy department, texaco will pay the first installment totaling $400 million, with the rest to be paid over 5{ years. it is one of the largest settlements ever reached between the government and a company
james w. kinnear, texaco's president, said in a statement that the company had set aside reserves for such a contingency and it would have no impact on earnings
kinnear also said the settlement would free texaco from what he called a costly and time-consuming legal process and enable the company to concentrate its efforts on getting out of chapter 11 federal bankruptcy protection
the company sought bankruptcy court refuge last april because of its protracted legal dispute with pennzoil, which had won a record $10.3 billion judgment against the oil giant from a texas jury that ruled texaco unfairly sabotaged pennzoil's plan to buy part of getty oil co
in december texaco settled that battle by agreeing to pay pennzoil $3 billion cash, but the company's efforts to return to normal operations have been complicated by disputes over its bankruptcy reorganization
in addition, the company faces a possible takeover threat from carl c. icahn, the company's largest shareholder. t. boone pickens, another well-known takeover strategist, also has expressed interest in buying texaco stock
texaco's problems have been further complicated by the irs. company officials said last month that the irs had told texaco it may owe $6.5 billion in back taxes because of possible undervaluations of oil purchased from saudi arabia from 1979-81
some analysts have said texaco would be virtually destroyed if it had to come up with that amount, but they also speculated the final bill would be much lower
the white plains, n.y.-based oil giant is the latest in a line of companies forced to relinquish large sums of cash to resolve charges they violated pricing restrictions on crude oil and refined products during the eight-year period of federal controls
jack vandenberg, a spokesman for the department of energy in washington, said prior to the texaco settlement, it received about $6.1 billion in settlement funds. he said the department expects to collect about $1 billion more to resolve similar claims, bringing the total to $8.2 billion
the government had argued that during the era of price controls, companies illegally profited by classifying ``old'' oil _ obtained from properties producing before 1973 _ as ``new'' oil and selling it at higher prices
texaco had argued that federal regulations defining old and new oil were ambiguous, but said tuesday that challenging the government on this dispute was not worth the effort
vandenberg said about 15 percent of the $1.25 billion settlement covered refined product price violations, with the money destined to go into a fund to repay injured parties
the remaining 85 percent covers crude price violations, and a fifth of that will go into the injured party fund and the rest will be split evenly between the federal government and the states, he said
late last year, the department of energy extended the deadline for injured parties to file claims to june 30. more than 16,000 claims had been filed before the extension
the agency said at that time that a claim for a million gallons of refined products overcharged would mean about $800 coming to the claimant
most of the injured parties are businesses, school districts and municipalities that kept detailed records of crude oil and refined products purchased from oil concerns that the government accused of overcharging
other companies that have paid to settle complaints include exxon corp., amoco corp., shell oil co., mobil corp. and atlantic richfield co
ford motor co. said it was able to expand its largest automatic transmission plant without interrupting production and at less than half the cost of similar projects because of worker participation
it truly was a team approach. each plant area analyzed how the expansion and quality improvements could be achieved. issues were discussed openly and plans were refined to reflect the suggestions of each team,'' henry nickol, general manager of ford's transmission and chassis division, said tuesday
the $50 million project added 100,000 units to the plant's 795,000 yearly transmission production while improving quality and saving 190 jobs without interrupting the assembly line, ford said
the expansion has helped ease a shortage of automatic transmissions for rear-wheel-drive cars and trucks, particularly ford's popular f-series pickup, that use 4.9-liter, six-cylinder engines and 5.0-liter v-8 engines
the f-series pickup was the best-selling vehicle in the united states in 1986 and 1987, but ford was forced to offer incentives to boost sales of manual transmission trucks because it didn't have enough automatic transmissions, company spokesman rex greenslade said
greenslade said a comparable transmission plant expansion would have cost $100 million to $150 million
nickol's remarks reflect what has become cliche at ford, where top executives never note a new profit, sales or quality achievement without crediting hourly workers and their cooperation with management
but the employees, hourly and salaried, who have worked together on the project since september 1986 and who will live with its results, say it proves that cooperative management is more than a 1980s buzzword
it's certainly the way we'll go from now on, on any new program,'' said jim o'neill, the livonia transmission plant's manufacturing manager
o'neill said the expansion saved jobs that would have been cut if efficiency had improved but total production did not. trading</head>
a finance ministry committee wednesday approved a report calling for tougher laws against insider trading on japan's stock markets, where traders say information about companies frequently is leaked to selected investors
the ministry's securities and exchange council approved an advisory panel's findings, including a recommendation that insider trading be made a criminal rather than a civil offense. it proposed that the offense carry a penalty of up to three years in prison and a fine of up to 3 million yen, or $23,000, ministry officials said
the panel also called for a revision of japan's current securities and exchange law to specifically prohibit insider trading, or the use of inside information about companies to profit on stock markets
other recommendations called for an expansion of the ministry's investigation powers and a tightening of the definition of actions falling under insider trading laws, the officials said
ministry officials now will formulate legislation based on the panel's recommendations to submit to japan's parliament, probably this spring
large-scale insider trading is limited in japan because of the infrequency of corporate takeovers, analysts say. but leaks of information about company developments to certain investors is believed to be frequent, along with stock manipulation by some large brokerages, financial sources say
japan's markets are dominated by four large securities firms _ nomura, nikko, daiwa and yamaichi _ creating a climate favorable to market manipulation
the advisory panel began forming its recommendations about two months ago, after allegations of stock sales by officials at a chemical company shortly before it announced bankruptcy, news reports said
implementation of the recommendations will make japan the last major industrialized country to adopt such regulations, the japan broadcasting corp. (nhk-tv) reported
the panel said insider trading restrictions should apply to employees and others inside companies that issue stocks, to underwriting securities firms, lawyers and certified public accountants, and to reporters that have access to sensitive information
the report also recommended that securities firms be required to report the stock ownership of large stockholders
the changes are not likely to take effect before the summer of 1989 because of a one-year notice period necessary for the strengthened criminal penalties, officials said
barclays bank plc, one of britain's four major commercial banks, said wednesday that its 1987 profit plummeted 70.8 percent, largely because it raised its provisions for loans to latin american and other countries
barclays said it earned 185 million pounds, or $327 million last year, compared with 633 million pounds, or $1.12 billion, in 1986. included in the 1986 figure was a one-time gain of 21 million pounds, or $37 million, from the disposal of certain assets
on a per-share basis, that works out to 25.8 pence, or 46 cents, a share, vs. 88.9 pence, or $1.57, a share in the previous year
last summer, barclays raised its provisions against loans to lesser developed countries to 30 percent of its total loans outstanding, then increased that stake at the end of the year
as of dec. 31, its total provisions stood at 716 million pounds, or $1.27 billion _ 35 percent of the bank's total 2.026 billion pounds, or $3.59 billion, outstanding
the results achieved in our group operations through the year reflect a credible performance,'' said chairman john quinton. ``even though we decided to recognize the further deterioration in the quality of ldc debt by making further provisions, the impact on our capital has been comfortably absorbed.''
barclays de zoete wedd, the bank's investment banking subsidiary, reported a loss of 11 million pounds, or $19 million, for the year, compared with a profit of 1 million pounds, or $1.77 million, the year before
barclays said the unit was profitable up to october and in the final two months of the year, but that trading losses suffered during the crash pushed it into the red
the unit announced last november that it lost 50 million pounds, or $89 million, during the crash
profits from barclays' u.s. unit were hurt by the fall of the dollar
the bank said profit grew 14 percent in dollar terms, but only 1.6 percent in terms of pounds _ to 64 million pounds, compared with 63 million
the stock market edged upward today, bidding to resume its recent rally after a pause on tuesday
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.14 to 2,045.26 in the first half hour
gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 6 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 557 up, 480 down and 480 unchanged
big board volume came to 27.08 million shares as of 10 a.m. on wall street
analysts said confidence has slowly been recovering lately after the market's historic drop last fall
the economy has so far shown no signs of suffering any drastic harm from the crash, and interest rates have fallen since that time
but traders have been taking a gingerly approach, recalling how gains built up over many months were wiped out in a few short days in october
many wall streeters are watching to see whether the dow jones industrial average can surpass the 2,051.89 close it reached on jan. 7, which stands as its post-crash closing high
