the nation's foreign trade deficit edged down to $40.2 billion in the final three months of 1987, pressured lower by a 6 percent boost in u.s. overseas sales, the commerce department reported today
in the previous quarter, the gap had hit a record $40.4 billion, while the year finished with an overall record $159.3 billion deficit, calculated on a balance-of-payments basis
the new figures confirmed a yearend narrowing of the trade shortfall that already had shown up in the department's monthly merchandise trade reports
those parallel figures showed a $43 billion deficit for the fourth quarter and a $171.9 deficit for all of 1987
today's figures are smaller because they subtract factors such as the cost of shipping, insurance and military sales from the monthly numbers
the balance-of-payments deficit is also adjusted for seasonal variations, while the monthly merchandise figures are not
exports increased $3.9 billion, or 6 percent, in the final quarter of 1987, to $69.1 billion, bolstered by the weakening dollar, which made u.s. goods more price-competitive overseas
the report came one day after federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said he did not forsee a recession or heightened inflation this year
greenspan made his assessment in testimony tuesday before congress, where he appeared unperturbed by a commerce department report that orders for so-called ``big ticket'' american-made durable goods fell 2.8 percent in january
the fed chief, who wields enormous control over interest rates and the supply of money, said the risk of a recession is about equal to the risk of renewed inflation, but he agreed with the reagan administration that neither appears imminent
the remarks by the head of the nation's central bank were seen as inconclusive by the financial markets
the dow jones average of 30 industrials lost 1.17 points to 2,039.12, while the price of the key 30-year treasury bond rose about $7.50 for every $1,000 in face value. the dollar was lower against most major foreign currencies
the decline in orders to u.s. factories for durable goods reflected a return to more normal levels of demand for aircraft and primary metals, the commerce department said
the steep decline, only the third setback in the past 13 months, was the biggest since an 8 percent drop in january 1987. the latest figures followed a big december advance of 4.1 percent, the strongest rise since march
the numbers that were released on durable goods, if one subtracts some of the temporary fluctuations, were really quite strong,'' greenspan said during an appearance before the house banking committee
delivering the fed's semi-annual report on monetary policy to congress, greenspan took pointed exception to the economic philosophies espoused by chief white house economist beryl sprinkel
if the fed had let the nation's money supply grow to the extent sprinkel would have liked, it would have spawned an ``unduly inflationary environment,'' greenspan told the house committee
analysts suggested that greenspan's testimony did not signal any imminent fed action on interest rates
he left himself a lot of room to either tighten or loosen,'' said david wyss, chief financial economist for data resources inc. wyss said there are signs ``that the fed does not know what it wants to do yet. it is seeing some very conflicting signals from the economy and it wants to leave itself as much room to react as it can.''
the stock market declined slightly today, struggling to resume its recent rally after a pause on tuesday
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 6 points in early trading, was down 2.32 at 2,036.80 by 11 a.m. on wall street
losers outnumbered gainers by about 8 to 7 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 558 up, 669 down and 498 unchanged
