the battle for iu international corp. has intensified with the company's board of directors first endorsing a $21.50-a-share buyout from a group backed by dean witter capital corp., then neoax inc. raising its hostile bid
the board announced tuesday that it had accepted a cash offer totaling around $650 million from the dean witter group, but shortly after neoax sweetened its bid to $22 a share
after that occurred, iu issued a statement saying it would consider other alternatives
shareholders will be advised of the board's recommendations when the board has completed its review.'' said iu spokesman e.k. sheldon, refusing to elaborate
neoax, a stamford, conn., manufacturing conglomerate, has been trying since early january to take over philadelphia-based iu, which has interests in trucking, food services and waste management
neoax started the bidding on jan. 6 with an offer of $17.50 per share, increased it to $19 on jan. 17 and boosted it to $20 on feb. 1
iu's board suggested shareholders ignore the $20 iu offer, saying the board was exploring alternatives such as recapitalization or a leveraged buyout
in the agreement between iu and the dean witter group, which includes iu president william h. waltrip and other iu executives, dean witter would receive up to $15 million from iu if another bidder acquires a majority of the outstanding shares
neoax, which has acquired about 2.9 million of iu's 30.2 million shares outstanding, has filed a motion in federal court in baltimore seeking to stop payment of that fee. to be determined; picks up 3rd graf, `the judge; inserts two grafs after graf 7, ``the decision,'' with explanation of procedure, picks up 8th graf, `about 1,300 ...; also moved on general newswires</note>
a federal judge's landmark ruling that occidental chemical corp. was liable for the cost of cleaning up love canal strengthens anti-pollution laws nationwide, a federal official says
after nine years' deliberations, judge john curtin ruled tuesday that occidental was responsible because wastes generated by the company's plant were stored in a way that would eventually result in leakage
a trial expected to start in 1990 will determine the amount of damages, but state and federal officials say $200 million has already been spent on the cleanup and estimate that $50 million more will be required
the judge ruled in a 1979 lawsuit filed by the federal environmental protection agency. in 1978, earlier, toxic chemicals at love canal prompted state officials to evacuate children and pregnant women, and eventually 728 families. of those, 175 families are still waiting to learn whether it is safe to return
curtin's ruling upheld the federal comprehensive environmental response, compensation and liability act of 1980. the judge said that law was designed to compel the waste disposal industry ``to correct its past mistakes and to provide a solution for the dangers posed by inactive abandoned waste sites.''
this will strengthen environmental laws throughout the country,'' roger j. marzulla, head of the u.s. justice department's land and natural resources division, said in washington
frank ashley, a spokesman for occidental's parent company, occidental petroleum, based in los angeles, said the company did not agree with the decision and would appeal
the decision which has just been issued on partial summary judgment, without a trial and without any factual determination, that occidental had acted negligently or with fault contradicts the resolution of these problems by amicable adjustments reached in other actions involving occidental chemical corp.,'' ashley said
the law entitles a judge to determine the issue of liability, and the next stage of the case is a trial to determine the amount of damages, said martin littlefield, assistant u.s. attorney for the buffalo district
in its motions, occidental had challenged that procedure
about 1,300 former residents of the love canal neighborhood accepted a $20 million damage settlement with occidental in 1984
the eventual amount occidental pays will depend on costs proved in court and assessed by the judge. u.s. attorney roger williams' staff said that $200 million has been spent so far and it is estimated that there will be $50 million more in costs
lois gibbs, a former love canal resident who runs the citizen's clearing house for hazardous wastes in alexandria, va., said she hopes the company will be found liable for the full $250 million
that will at least make them blink,'' gibbs said
the company said it was covered by insurance and that the expenses would not adversely affect its finances
occidental contended that it was not responsible for the landfill because hooker chemicals and plastics co., which was later acquired by occidental in 1968, yielded ownership to the niagara falls school board in 1953. the board built a school on the grounds
occidental said the construction project broke a clay seal on the dump and allowed the chemicals to leach into the environment. the company acknowledged that hooker dumped 20,000 tons of chemical wastes into the canal during the late 1940s and early '50s
littlefield, assistant u.s. attorney for the buffalo district, said tuesday's decision was ``a great victory for the state because it means companies are indeed responsible for what they've done in years past.''
state attorney general robert abrams said the decision was ``a resounding defeat for occidental's strenuous and expensive public relations campaign to shift the entire blame for love canal.''
curtin's ruling does, however, allow occidental to sue other parties the chemical giant contends should share the responsibility. the company is expected to countersue the state, the city of niagara falls and its school board
nunzio loverdi, president of the love canal environmental action committee, said, ``i think occidental should accept the decision and not take action against the city and school board because if it does we will all suffer. we want to get on with our lives and put this behind us.''
a federal judge has rejected black &amp; decker corp.'s request to block delaware's new corporate anti-takeover law, but did not rule on the constitutionality of the statute
u.s. district judge joseph j. longobardi on tuesday rejected black &amp; decker's request for an injunction against the law, which it contended was hindering its attempt to acquire american standard corp
black &amp; decker, a power tool and household appliance maker based in towson, md., has a hostile $68 a share, or $2.12 billion, tender offer outstanding for american standard, which is based in new york but incorporated in delaware
american standard had rejected two previous black &amp; decker offers, and proposed a defensive recapitalization that analysts have valued at between $68 and $71 a share
american standard rose 50 cents to $68.75 a share in early new york stock exchange trading. black &amp; decker dipped 50 cents to $18.87{
delaware's new anti-takeover law was enacted on feb. 2, and immediately was challenged as unconstitutional by black &amp; decker.
black &amp; decker also claimed shareholders of american standard, an air-conditioning, plumbing and building products company, were confused by the law and reluctant to tender their shares
but longobardi rejected the request for an injunction. he ruled black &amp; decker hadn't shown it would suffer irreparable harm under the law, and therefore would not rule on its constitutionality
such a gratuitous discussion of the constitutionality of (the statute) could be used to upset the balance between the parties in the quest for their respective positions,'' longobardi said of the takeover battle
the court also noted that black &amp; decker was attempting to take control of the american standard board, and if successful then could exempt the company from the law
the boards of directors of delaware corporations have 90 days from the law's enactment to exempt their companies
under the law, any shareholder who acquires more than 15 percent of a company's stock is prohibited for three years from entering a business combination that would allow the stockholder to acquire the firm
if a takeover is launched before the law is triggered, the bidder would have to acquire 85 percent of the outstanding shares in a single transaction to complete the merger
john f. geer, vice president of american standard, said the company was ``gratified'' by the decision. richard l. templeton, delaware's assistant secretary of state, said he was ``encouraged by the decision.'' also moved on general newswires</note>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said today that he had ``objected quite strongly'' to an instance of political pressure from the reagan administration and warned that further pressure on the central bank could be counterproductive
greenspan said his protest was sparked by a letter written in january by michael darby, assistant treasury secretary for economic affairs
greenspan was questioned about the letter by sen. william proxmire, d-wis., who said the letter was one of a series of recent attempts by the reagan administration to pressure the fed to lower interest rates as a way of spurring economic growth during a presidential election year
i think it is both deplorable and counterproductive for the reagan administration to pressure you as much as they have in recent months,'' proxmire, the chairman of the senate banking committee, told greenspan
greenspan said that he had a disagreement with both darby and beryl sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser, over the matter of money growth
he said that while disagreements over policy were acceptable he was concerned about the manner in which the administration's criticism could be perceived by financial markets
when i heard about dr. darby's letter i objected quite strongly. as best as i could determine, he was not aware of the implications,'' greenspan said. ``i am reasonably sure such an action will not occur in the future.''
greenspan said his concern was that the letter was sent in the weeks before a key meeting where top fed officials were going to set monetary targets for the next year
greenspan did not say with whom he raised his objections, although it has been reported that treasury secretary james baker was instrumental in toning down criticism of the fed in the economic report of the president before it was released last week
greenspan said he fully expected to have policy disputes with this administration and the next administration, but he added, ``the only thing i hope that does not happen is that the concern over political pressure gets so extraordinary that we end up taking actions'' in the opposite direction just to prove that the fed is independent
greenspan's comments on political pressure came during the second day of his congressional testimony on the fed's economic outlook and monetary targets for 1988
in his appearance tuesday before the house banking committee, greenspan had also been critical of sprinkel's monetary arguments
in the president's report, sprinkel suggested that tight-fisted fed policies were partly to blame for the collapse of the stock market on oct. 19
sprinkel is a proponent of ``monetarism,'' the theory that steady growth in the money supply is esential to economic growth. the president's report noted that the money supply expanded very slowly last year, below the targets set by the federal reserve
one measure of the money supply, m-2, grew just 4 percent in 1987, the slowest increase in almost three decades. the advance was even below the rate of inflation, something that has occurred only three previous times. in each of those instances, a recession followed
asked about this, greenspan contended that money growth was influenced by special factors last year and that traditional relationships between money growth and economic activity have broken down since banking deregulation created a host of new types of savings accounts
greenspan said that he and sprinkel had a ``difference of opinion on this particular issue.'' he argued that the central bank could not have allowed the money supply to grow more rapidly ``without creating an unduly inflationary environment.''
private economists generally gave greenspan high marks for his testimony, contending that he steered the proper course between concern about inflation and concern about economic growth
in setting monetary targets for 1988, the fed expanded the distance between the low-point and high-point of acceptable growth by a full percentage point, saying it was now aiming for m-2 growth of between 4 percent and 8 percent
this money growth will be enough to support economic growth this year of between 2 percent and 2.5 percent, as measured by the gross national product, the fed said in its economic outlook. this would be in the range of the 2.4 percent gnp growth being forecast by the administration
greenspan left himself a lot of room to ither tighten or loosen,'' said david wyss, chief financial economist of data resources inc. ``the fed is seeing some very conflicting signals about the economy and it wants to leave itself as much room to react as it can.''
greenspan confirmed in his testimony that the fed, in an effort to keep the recovery alive, had taken a ``small easing step a few weeks ago.'' many analysts had suggested that the fed had eased slightly based on the fact that a variety of interest rates, including mortgage rates, have dropped sharply in the past six weeks
greenspan said that currently he believed the risks of a recession or accelerating inflation were about equal and said he agreed with the administration's view that neither appeared imminent
he said that it was still too early to assess the full impact of last year's stock market collapse but ``there are very few signs that we are about to tilt over'' into a recession
grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly higher but quickly turned mixed today on the chicago board of trade
talk of new soviet purchases of u.s. corn gave corn futures a boost, analysts said
