general motors corp. said today it will restore 1,900 jobs at its van nuys, calif., plant on march 14 by putting both shifts back to work six weeks earlier than expected
the announcement came as gm indicated it will be recalling about 8,600 workers nationwide to produce an extra 175,000 cars and trucks annually
the night shift at the van nuys plant was elminated feb. 15 because gm had too much unsold inventory of the pontiac firebirds and chevrolet camaros assembled there
at the time, gm said it expected the plant would operate with only one shift until at least may 2 or until the inventory was reduced
in a unique experiment that had run into stiff resistance among senior workers, all 3,800 of the plant's hourly workers were affected, with half being off for two weeks at a time, then returning to their jobs while the others were furloughed for two weeks
the staggered-layoff system was to have continued at least until may 2, or longer if necessary, gm said
similar systems of staggered layoffs have been tested elsewhere in the gm system, but at van nuys the plan had to be approved in a vote by workers
the vote was required because when the workers agreed in 1986 to adopt japanese-style work rules to speed production and cut costs, the company agreed to negotiate with the union to ease any impact from changes in staffing levels
in an initial vote, the plan was defeated by eight votes, but after some maneuvering the union agreed to hold a second vote and to do it at the plant so more workers with less seniority could cast ballots. the plan was approved on the second vote, despite grumbling by older workers that making all workers take part in the furloughs was an attack on seniority rights
the camaros and firebirds produced at the van nuys plant have been plagued for some time with slow sales. when gm announced plans for the layoffs earlier this year, the company's inventory of the two cars was well in excess of 100 days, meaning it would take that long at existing sales rates to dispose of already-assembled cars
normally, gm operates with about a 60-day inventory on its various models
with both shifts operating, the van nuys plant produces about 800 of the two car models daily. graf pvs bg'ng, the umw ...</note>
united mine workers president richard trumka said today he's disappointed by the decision by oil, chemical and atomic workers union officials to withdraw from a proposed merger and said he considers the idea dead
we thought it was a perfect fit,'' trumka said. ``the philosophies of the two unions are extremely close.''
trumka said the umw's executive board voted to rescind its merger offer in the wake of tuesday's ocaw decision
obviously, i'm quite disappointed by the outcome ... but we're going to go back and put it back together and go on,'' he said
he said the umw will look for other ways to expand
trumka said the apparent sticking point for the ocaw board was the umw's inability to guarantee there would be no dues increases during its next regularly scheduled constitutional convention in 1990
trumka said he cannot control what the delegates will do ``and therefore i consider it a closed deal.''
the ocaw board voted late tuesday to reject the merger proposal
there's a decision from ocaw not to go forward,'' spokesman rod rogers said late tuesday night. ``i don't know that that sets everything in concrete. but that's where it stands for now.''
a news conference had been tentatively set for this morning to announce the merger, but the ocaw backed out after meeting with umw leaders most of tuesday afternoon
the merger would have bolstered the strength of the two energy workers' unions, whose memberships have been shrinking throughout the last decade
the umw board has authority to approve a merger without a vote of its full membership, though rogers said any merger required a two-thirds majority vote at the ocaw convention in august
the umw and the ocaw find themselves negotiating with the same companies, ``because the major oil companies own the lion's share of the energy and coal reserves in the united states,'' rogers said
since 1986, the two unions have been sharing information about employers
the umw once had more than 400,000 members, but it now has about 85,000 active members _ about two-thirds of the nation's working miners
ocaw membership is down by half from a peak of nearly 200,000 members in the early 1970s
the computers and high technology now used to search for oil and gas would have been a mystery to anthony lucas, who relied largely on a hunch to drill the famed 1901 spindletop gusher
there was almost no science at spindletop,'' says dave kingston, a retired standard oil of new jersey geologist. ``today, it's just the reverse. we want to know all we can (about a prospect) before we drill.''
using stunning advances in geology, geochemistry and other disciplines, oilmen now analyze a broad range of information in searching for unfound storehouses of earth's most crucial commodity
there's no way to relate today to what we had in the past,'' says houston oilman michel halbouty. ``the technology has changed every day of every year that the industry has been alive.''
central to nearly all the developments has been the increasing use of computers to sift, store and massage massive amounts of data
among other things, computers can generate three-dimensional views of prospective drill sites based on information from rock samples, previous drilling and other sources, creating hypothetical composite pictures of what lies below grassy, forested or desert surfaces
in the past, the same process has been done with pencil and paper,'' said richard d. bowden, spokesman for energy software inc. of midland. ``it's like comparing the wright brothers to the concorde _ it's the same kind of advance.''
advances in seismic technology have also aided the search for oil, says don bennett, divisional vice president of exploration and production technology division of texaco inc
by measuring the movement of seismic shock waves through the earth, scientists can derive clues as to whether the waves are traveling through rock, sand or, possibly, unfound oil formations
since 1968, when plate tectonics _ the theory that earth's surface is composed of massive shifting rock plates _ became widely accepted, dramatic advances in geology have been made
what plate tectonics does, instead of just hunt and peck here and there, you now have a unifying theory about how these plates were formed,'' said manik talwani, director of the geotechnology research institute in houston. ``it helps you very much in your guessing about which might be good oil provinces.''
in addition, developments in the complicated science of geochemistry have provided clues to locating oil through testing sample rocks in the laboratory, as have improvements in sensing equipment lowered into drill holes to conduct electrical and other analyses
patrick shannon, another retired standard oil of new jersey geologist, now runs his own consulting firm specializing in analyzing satellite photos of earth for telltale signs of oil and gas deposits
in addition to being able to see large structural features that could hint of oil and gas, different kinds of rock and minerals often respond differently to varying light and infrared frequencies, shannon says
the use of those (satellite photos) is among the most important new technologies that we've got in the business today,'' shannon said, adding that future satellites may provide even more sophisticated data
most experts agree oil and gas exploration remains a risky business fraught with the potential for failure, and new techniques only help to create a more comprehensive mosaic of information for decision-making
it's like putting together a jigsaw puzzle,'' burnett said. ``you want to get as many pieces as possible.''
one reason for burgeoning technology in oil exploration has been the huge increase in drilling costs, which have risen sharply over the past 20 years, halbouty says
what's more, most of the biggest deposits of oil and gas in the united states have already been found, making discoveries of smaller, more isolated remaining pockets more difficult, and more important, said mel friedman, spokesman for the department of geosciences at texas a&amp;m university
in 1901, lucas decided to drill the spindletop gusher on a small hill where he and others suspected oil might exist, but where a number of unsuccessful wells had been drilled
when the drillers hit a huge reserve of oil, a gusher of black gold shot hundreds of feet into the air, igniting the legendary texas oil boom
during the 1950s and 1960s, kingston and shannon roamed the globe as geologists for standard oil using what might now be considered rudimentary tools and techniques
kingston takes a somewhat skeptical view of many advances
the same guy who finds oil with a computer is the same guy who can find oil without the computer,'' kingston said. ``a geologist with his hammer and his eyes and his brain is far superior to anything else
today, there are about 150 kinds of maps and studies that can be run in a certain area to study the geology, but there are only 10 or 12 that are really necessary,'' kingston said. ``the rest are just window dressing.''
for kingston, technology can only aid human intuition, which remains the primary key to finding hidden treasure troves of oil and gas
an analogy would be reading a mystery novel with half the pages torn out, you have to guess about what is in there,'' kingston said
a group of shareholders of societe generale de belgique sa said wednesday it has formed an alliance that holds a majority stake in belgium's largest holding company and wants to keep its focus in belgium
the group, which includes representation from belgium, france and luxembourg, said it controlled 52 percent of societe generale stock
italian financier carlo de benedetti, the president of olivetti spa, whotrols 43 percent, wants to turn the company into that controls enterprises throughout europe
the shareholder alliance consists of several belgian and lu has said he conxembourg firms led by groupe ag, belgium's biggest insurer. the group's french members are compagnie financiere de suez, an investment firm, companie generale d'electricite and societe financiere et industrielle gaz et eaux
suez alone controls 27 percent; groupe ag and its allies, 16 percent; cge, 5 percent and gaz et eaux, 4 percent, the group said in a statement
on wednesday, societe generale stock closed at a new high of 6,100 francs, or $174.20, up 14 percent from tuesday's 5,350 francs, or $152.90
de benedetti has offered 4,000 francs, or $114.28, a share for an additional 15 percent stake in the company. his offer expires march 4
his rival alliance said its members had ``put their signatur38, arrived in boston tuesday with the e street band and an entourage of workers and headed to the arena. fans gathered outside hoping to catch a glimpse of springsteen, guitarist nils lofgren or saxophonist clarence clemons and hear the band rehearse
i tried to get tickets and it was impossible,'' said jess adzima, of sudbury. ``i took off this afternoon to see if springsteen was hanging around. when i heard the music, i said, `that's bruce.'''
springsteen last played at the centrum in september 1984
centrum marketing director kathleen m. heinz said 39,000 tickets have been sold for the shows on thursday, sunday and monday
aidan quinn, who stars in the broadway revival of ``a streetcar named desire,'' says he's not worried about filling the shoes _ or torn t-shirt _ of marlon brando
the 1947 production of tennessee williams' pulitzer prize-winning play was brando's first major theatrical role. the film that followed, also featuring brando as stanley kowalski, is ``etched into everyone's psyche and memory,'' quinn admitted in the march issue of details magazine
but that's a real cowardly reason not to do something,'' says quinn, who starred in the film ``desperately seeking susan,'' the made-for-tv movie ``an early frost,'' and the off-broadway production of sam shepard's ``a lie of the mind.''
the truth is it's a great piece, a great play and a great role.''
the play, now in previews, opens march 10
wearing a rumpled oversize tuxedo and shoes without laces, comedian steve martin jumped up and down like a game-show contestant when he received the hasty pudding club man of the year award
i won! i won!'' he said to the delight of the audience of nearly 200 at harvard university. when he reached the podium, martin deadpanned, ``there's a cash prize for this, right?''
he received a brass pudding pot, but no cash
the nation's oldest undergraduate theatrical organization gave its annual award tuesday to martin for ``his lasting and impressive contribution to the world of entertainment,'' said program co-producer andrea campbell
martin said receiving the award made up for his movie ``roxanne'' not being nominated for an oscar. ``yes it does, because it's such a prestigious award, and so few people have gotten one,'' he said
the hasty pudding club awarded lucille ball its woman of the year award last week
tammy faye bakker wants oscar-winner sally field to play her in a made-for-tv film about the saga of her and husband jim bakker's fall from grace as leaders of the ptl evangelical ministry, a network official says
nbc has hired the bakkers as consultants for its movie. cbs also plans a film about the couple
if tammy had her way, sally field would play her in the movie,'' said ken raskoff, director of motion pictures for television at nbc
both nbc's film, ``fall from grace,'' and the cbs movie ``god and greed: the jim and tammy fae bakker story,'' are in early stages of production. both networks say it will be three months before a first draft is ready
looks like we are going to have a `who's-going-to-get-on-the-air' thing,'' said sandy emry, production coordinator at cbs
jim bakker resigned from the ptl television ministry in march after word leaked of a 1980 sexual encounter with former church secretary jessica hahn
author ken kesey has donated a $33,395 bus to the university of oregon, with the hope of preventing accidents like the one that killed his son and another member of the school wrestling team four years ago
the problem with a van is that it's not as stable as school bus construction,'' said kesey, who gained fame two decades ago for his escapades on a very different kind of bus, whose journeys were chronicled in tom wolfe's ``the electric kool-aid acid test.'' kesey himself is best known for his novel, ``one flew over the cuckoo's nest.''
kesey's son, jed, 20, and fellow wrestler lorenzo west died when their van skidded out of control on a snow-covered road between pendleton and pullman, wash. two other wrestlers were seriously injured
kesey and his wife, faye, were among those who filed lawsuits in which settlements were reached last fall. the keseys used their settlement to purchase the custom-built bus, which is loaded with safety features
historian stephen ambrose, writing the second volume of his biography about richard m. nixon, says students today don't see anything so horrible about watergate
the new orleans historian recently wrapped up a three-week visit to whittier college, nixon's alma mater. ambrose, 52, brought in former nixon administration officials h.r. haldeman, robert finch and maurice stans to add to his lectures
i suppose i had assumed that just being at whittier, they (students) would have absorbed something about nixon. it turned out, precious little,'' he said. because students ``don't see anything so horrible about watergate'' there is a national resurgence of nixon's reputation
it's the damnedest thing, but it's quite true. the nixon revival is full-blown now and well under way,'' ambrose said
the stock market pushed ahead today, struggling to resume its recent rally after a pause on tuesday
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.46 to 2,047.58 by 2 p.m. on wall street
gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 812 up, 606 down and 486 unchanged
analysts said confidence has slowly been recovering lately after the market's historic drop last fall
the economy has so far shown no signs of suffering any drastic harm from the crash, and interest rates have fallen since that time
but traders have been taking a gingerly approach, recalling how gains built up over many months were wiped out in a few short days in october
many wall streeters are watching to see whether the dow jones industrial average can surpass the 2,051.89 close it reached on jan. 7, which stands as its post-crash closing high
