general motors corp. said wednesday it boosted 1988 production plans by 175,000 cars and trucks and will recall 8,600 laid-off workers and reopen a temporarily closed assembly plant
the strengthening demand for gm vehicles reflects the ongoing product quality improvements resulting from plant modernization and employee involvement programs,'' gm president robert stempel said in a statement
this combined with very competitive retail incentive programs has increased the value of gm products,'' he said
gm will increase production by running some plants, particularly for trucks, on overtime; restoring second shifts at two u.s. plants and one in canada; and reopening its closed framingham, mass., assembly plant
at the three plants where gm had dropped the second shift, workers from both shifts were sharing jobs by alternating between two weeks on layoff and two weeks on the job, gm said
the framingham assembly plant, which gm closed abruptly nov. 30, will reopen may 9 on one shift with 2,000 of its 3,700 workers. the plant will build the oldsmobile cutlass cierra, but will not resume production of the chevrolet celebrity, gm spokeswoman kathy tanner said
gm will restore the second shift at its buick-oldsmobile-cadillac group lansing assembly plant a-system on april 11, returning 2,000 people to full-time work. the 4,350-worker plants builds the oldsmobile cutlass calais and buick skylark
the second shift at gm's 4,200-worker van nuys, calif., assembly plant will be restored march 14, bringing 1,900 employees back full time. the plant, which gm's only chevrolet camaro and pontiac firebird source, dropped the second shift last week
gm also will restore the second shift at its oshawa no. 1 plant in oshawa, ontario, bringing back 2,700 laid-off workers on march 21. the plant builds the oldsmobile cierra and pontiac 6000
meanwhile, gm said it would increase production at its cadillac plant in the detroit enclave of hamtramck by running its single shift on overtime, adding 4,700 cars between feb. 20 and june 1
cadillac general manager john grettenberger said the increased production was necessary because dealers need more of the restyled eldorado coupe and seville sedans, whose popularity has been boosted by availability of a new 4.5-liter v-8 engine
federated department stores inc.'s board of directors on thursday will consider a restructuring plan and an extended merger offer from toronto developer campeau corp., a spokesman said
however, jim sluzewski declined wednesday to disclose the site for the gathering, which he described as a regular monthly meeting
the cincinnati-based retailer, which operates the bloomingdale's department store chain, said the board will review campeau's extended $5.85 billion offer for a friendly merger
the directors also will review options for a restructuring to avoid a takeover, including selling its non-department store assets. federated said it has been negotiating with unidentified third parties that have shown an interest in acquiring the company or its non-department store divisions
federated has resisted campeau's attempts to acquire the company in either a friendly merger or a hostile takeover
on monday, campeau extended its offer to pay $66 per share for federated, which has 88.5 million outstanding shares, if the retailer agrees to a definitive, friendly merger by midnight friday
campeau said if no agreement is reached by the friday deadline, the offer reverts to a hostile, $61-per-share offer
federated has twice rejected campeau's $66-per-share offer, saying it didn't think the toronto-based corporation has the financing to complete such a deal
federated has about 650 stores nationwide, with sales exceeding $11 billion last year. it's non-department store assets include columbus-based gold circle stores, ralphs supermarkets based in los angeles, and specialty stores including the children's place in pine brook, n.j., filene's basement in boston, and mainstreet in chicago
grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed to higher wednesday in fairly light trading on the chicago board of trade
corn futures were the most consistent performers, showing strength throughout the trading session on rumors that the soviet union had purchased as much as 2 million bushels of u.s. corn overnight, said dale gustafson, an analyst in chicago for drexel burnham lambert inc
soybean prices lagged for most of the day but ended mixed on a late surge of buying led by c&amp;d commodities, a major player in soybean trading, analysts said
wheat futures ended slightly higher on talk of expected new export sales to european countries, gustafson said
gains in wheat prices were limited by an increase in supplies of wheat for near-term delivery, analysts said
at the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.18 a bushel; corn was \ cent to 2{ cents higher with march at $1.99 a bushel; oats were \ cent to } cents lower with march at $1.90 a bushel; soybeans were 2} cents lower to 3{ cents higher with march at $6.24{ a bushel
the stock market posted a slim gain in erratic trading today, struggling to resume its recent rally after a pause on tuesday
analysts said confidence has slowly been recovering lately after the market's historic drop last fall
the economy has so far shown no signs of suffering any drastic harm from the crash, and interest rates have fallen since that time
but traders have been taking a gingerly approach, recalling how gains built up over many months were wiped out in a few short days in october
many wall streeters are watching to see whether the dow jones industrial average can surpass the 2,051.89 close it reached on jan. 7, which stands as its post-crash closing high
oil prices headed lower wednesday after an early attempt to rally fizzled
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, settled at $16.46 per 42-gallon barrel, down 14 cents from tuesday's close
among march contracts for refined products, wholesale heating oil settled at 46.40 cents a gallon, down 0.06 cent from tuesday, while wholesale unleaded gasoline closed 0.6 cent lower at 46.30 cents a gallon
linda simard, an analyst at the drexel burham lambert inc. securities firm, said some traders were expecting prices to rise at the start of the session in the wake of late tuesday's weekly report on weekly oil production and supplies
the report, issued by the washington-based american petroleum institute, a trade organization, showed a larger-than-expected drawdown of heating oil inventories during the week ending last friday, but also a larger-than-expected increase in unleaded gasoline supplies, she said
crude inventories were also slightly lower, according to the report
ms. simard said traders ``were looking to sell higher at the start, but as disappointment set in, the sellers took over.''
in the end, trading wound up being dominated by technical factors more than anything else, she added
united mine workers president richard trumka said wednesday he considers the union's failed merger with the oil, chemical and atomic workers union ``a closed deal'' that won't be reconsidered
ocaw's executive board on tuesday voted 6-2 to reject a merger that would have created the united mine, energy and chemical workers of america from the two powerful unions. trumka said the ocaw board had left open the possibility of reconsidering the merger, but the umw's board voted wednesday to rescind the approval it gave on sunday
i consider it a closed deal,'' trumka told a news conference. ``their board was willing to let it go to their constitutional convention without a recommendation. i flatly rejected that.''
ocaw spokesman rod rogers said the union's executive board was still involved wednesday in its regular meeting, and ocaw president joseph misbrener was not immediately available for comment. rogers said the issue is not necessarily dead
it's always possible there could be a resurrection of the idea,'' he said
there were compelling reasons why this merger was a good idea, and those reasons haven't gone away,'' rogers said. ``this particular merger proposal is dead, yes, but we could take action to re-initiate things.''
trumka said he was ready to move on, however
i'll come back at the next (umw) board meeting and say, `that didn't work; let's try something else,''' trumka said. ``we're going to pursue a policy of growth for our organization.''
trumka said the ocaw board rejected the merger agreement because it ``wanted assurances there would be no dues increase in 1990,'' when the first constitutional convention of the combined union would have taken place
there was no way possible i could guarantee that because delegates at that convention determine what will happen,'' trumka said
the umw president said he then convened a meeting of his union's board, which rescinded its earlier approval of the merger agreement, which contained no provisions for amendment
trumka said both unions would continue to work together, especially on negotiations with employers that the two unions have in common
while he plans to look for other ways to expand the umw's influence, trumka said, he does not consider it good policy ``to merge just for the sake of merging.''
dart group corp. will continue its billion-dollar hostile takeover bid for stop &amp; shop cos. inc., which is negotiating with several other potential buyers, a dart spokesman said wednesday
stop &amp; shop confirmed wednesday it had begun talks with several parties considering a buyout of the supermarket and discount store chain, raising the possibility it might find a ``white knight'' friendly suitor to thwart dart
sandy bouzoukis, a stop &amp; shop spokeswoman, declined to name the parties interested in the braintree-based company
dart spokesman stanley rubenstein said the landover, md.-based retailing concern would continue its hostile $37 a share, $1.03 billion tender offer launched last month. dart controls about 2.7 percent of stop &amp; shop's 27.9 million common shares outstanding
dart's position is unchanged. it is premature to respond to (stop &amp; shop) until we know the details of any alternative proposal,'' said rubenstein
stop &amp; shop rose $2.37{ to $41.50 a share wednesday on the new york stock exchange
boston businessman thomas lee reportedly is a possible suitor, but neither lee nor stop &amp; shop officials would confirm they were in negotiations
stop &amp; shop directors rejected dart's $37 a share offer earlier this month and filed a federal court suit to block the bid, claiming dart did not fully disclose details of past takeover attempts and had failed to register as an investment company with the securities and exchange commission
dart countersued, claiming stop &amp; shop illegally withheld corporate information
u.s. district judge rya zobel ruled tuesday that dart must file its claim in norfolk superior court in massachusetts, where eight separate shareholder suits challenging stop &amp; shop's anti-takeover measures are awaiting a hearing
dart has mounted several unsuccessful but profitable hostile takeover attempts since selling its washington-based drug store chain in 1985
the bid for stop &amp; shop was dart's first since it abandoned a $6 billion takeover proposal for minneapolis-based dayton hudson corp. following the oct. 19 stock market crash
dart, which owns crown books and trak auto parts stores nationwide, also has made unsuccessful but profitable attempts to gain control of safeway co. and supermarkets general
since 1986, stop &amp; shop has sold several unprofitable divisions, including medi mart drug stores and almys department stores, and laid off about 450 middle-level workers
the company operates 113 stop &amp; shop supermarkets and 169 bradlees discount department stores
honda motor co. ltd. posted a 38.1 percent rise in profits in the latest three-month period, even though operating income fell, the company said tuesday
net income rose to 23.68 billion japanese yen, or about $193 million, from 17.1 billion yen in a corresponding reporting period in 1986
honda is shifting to a new fiscal year, so results for the three months ended dec. 31, 1987, were compared with results for the period ended nov. 30, 1986. dollar equivalents were based on an exchange rate of 123 yen to the dollar prevailing at the end of 1987
revenue rose 20.5 percent to 789.5 billion yen, or about $6.42 billion, from 655.3 billion yen a year earlier
honda's income from operations fell 31.4 percent to 32.4 billion yen, or $263 million, in the quarter, mainly because of the falling value of the dollar, which decreases the value of u.s. sales when measured in yen
however, honda's net profit rose because of successful foreign-exchange trading and decreased income taxes, among other factors, the company said
