the federal trade commission asked a federal appeals court tuesday to stop the merger of two of the nation's largest manufacturers of glass containers while it appeals a lower court's refusal to halt the deal
the ftc asked the u.s. circuit court of appeals for a preliminary injunction to prevent owens-illinois inc., the nation's second-largest glass container manufacturer, from acquiring brockway inc. for $750 million during the appeal
the ftc, which obtained a provisional stay from the appellate court on friday, contended that u.s. district judge joyce hens green ``erred, both factually and legally, in holding that the merger is not likely to have anticompetitive effects.''
the ftc contends that the merger, which would create the nation's largest glass container manufacturer, would reduce competition and raise the price of bottles, jars and other containers the companies make for food, soft drinks and liquor
green, who last week denied the ftc's bid to stop the merger pending administrative proceedings within the agency, accepted the companies' argument that competition from plastic and paper packaging would keep down the prices of glass containers
but the ftc said she ``disregarded extensive testimony by customers accounting for more than $450 million in annual glass container purchases that they will not or cannot economically switch from glass containers to other package forms.''
the agency said green's opinion ``disregards, without explanation, long-established legal standards for assessing the potential anticompetitive effects of horizontal mergers, including the significance of market concentration and entry barriers, as well as extensive customer testimony that prices are likely to rise as a result of the merger.''
the ftc has stalled the merger since owens-illinois, based in toledo, ohio, made its tender offer last september to buy brockway stock for $60 a share. green had granted a temporary restraining order halting the merger while she reviewed the case, but she refused to grant a preliminary injunction
owens-illinois controls 22.7 percent of the market while brockway, based in jacksonville, fla., controls 15 percent of sales
litton industries inc. said wednesday its net earnings rose 19 percent in the second quarter, mainly because of improvements in its resource-exploration and industrial-automation units
the high-technology conglomerate netted $40.7 million, or $1.56 a share, for the three months ended jan. 31, up from $34.1 million, or $1.28 a share, a year earlier
revenue for the second quarter rose 19.6 percent, to $1.16 billion from $974.5 million
litton's profit also rose 19 percent in the half. the company earned $81.3 million, or $3.07 a share, up from $68.4 million, or $2.54 a share, a year earlier. revenue rose 15.2 percent, to $2.35 billion from $2.04 billion
litton's biggest improvement was in the resource-exploration and industrial-automation units of its industrial systems and services division, in part because of acquisitions. for the half, earnings for the division jumped 183 percent to $65.7 million and revenue rose 78.5 percent to $775.3 million. cited</head>
gold futures prices plunged to the lowest level in 11 months wednesday, possibly reflecting a change in attitude among investors who had been expecting a surge in inflation, analysts said
on other markets, grain and soybean futures settled mostly higher, livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy futures retreated; and stock-index futures declined
wednesday marked the second consecutive day of sharp declines in futures prices for gold and other precious metals, which had traded listlessly in narrow ranges for nearly a month
tuesday's drop in prices was widely attributed to federal reserve chairman alan greenspan's prediction that the 1988 u.s. inflation rate would average 3.25 percent to 3.75 percent, a rate lower than many market experts had projected
demand and prices for precious metals typically rise during inflationary periods because they tend to hold their value better than other investments
greenspan's forecast, along a general weakening of commodity prices recently, may have prompted a shift in attitude among investors who feared the worst after the october stock market collapse, said craig sloane, an analyst in new york for smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
it seems to me that the market is getting more encouraged, in terms of inflation, that things are not going to get worse,'' sloane said
he said the confidence greenspan displayed in his testimony tuesday before a house banking subcommittee ``seemed to enhance his credibility,'' which in turn may have given the markets more confidence
citibank analyst sharon ziemian said wednesday's selloff of gold futures appeared to spread from european markets to the u.s. markets, including new york's commodity exchange, the country's major market for precious metals futures
the selling was substantial enough that, with only a limited amount of buying, it pushed the market down dramatically,'' ms. ziemian said
on the commodity exchange, gold settled $9.90 to $13.90 lower with the contract for delivery in april at $434.10 a troy ounce, the contract's lowest price since march 20, 1987; silver was 10.5 cents to 13.4 cents lower with march at $6.195 a troy ounce
grain and soybean futures ended mostly higher in fairly light trading on the chicago board of trade
corn was the most consistent performer, showing strength throughout the session on rumors that the soviet union had purchased as much as 2 million metric tons of u.s. corn overnight, said dale gustafson, an analyst in chicago for drexel burnham lambert inc
the agriculture department announced after the close that the soviets had bought 350,000 metric tons of u.s. corn
soybeans lagged for the most of the day but ended mixed on a late surge of buying led by c&amp;d commodities, a major player in the soybean pit, analysts said
wheat ended slightly higher on talk of expected new export sales to european nations, gustafson said
wheat settled { cent to 2{ cents higher with march at $3.17 a bushel; corn was { cent to 2{ cents higher with march at $1.99 a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent lower with march at $1.90\ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 3} cents higher with march at $6.24} a bushel
cattle futures settled mostly higher while pork futures ended mixed on the chicago mercantile exchange
cattle futures were supported by higher cash values but limited by sluggish wholesale demand for beef, said charlie richardson, an analyst in denver for lind-waldock &amp; co
lower cash prices pressured pork, he said
live cattle settled .20 cent to .43 cent higher with april at 72.20 a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .45 cent higher with march at 80.92 cents a pound; hogs were .62 cent lower to .45 cent higher with april at 44.12 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .12 cent lower to .47 cent higher with march at 52.27 cents a pound
oil prices slipped lower on the new york mercantile exchange on technical factors after an early attempt to rally fizzled, analysts said
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 3 cents to 14 cents lower with february at 15.76 a barrel; heating oil was .06 cent to .52 cent lower with march at 46.40 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .15 cent to .55 cent lower with march at 46.35 cents a gallon
stock-index futures retreated slightly on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled .30 point lower at 265.20. the underlying spot index was off .58 point at 264.44
gold prices tumbled wednesday as traders appeared to take a more optimistic view of chances for continued low inflation
the dollar, meanwhile, turned in a narrowly mixed performance on the world's foreign-exchange markets
republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price for gold of $432.80 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, down $8.70 from tuesday's late level
analysts who follow the precious metals markets said recent declines in commodity prices have convinced many traders that inflation poses little immediate threat to the economy, diminishing gold's appeal as a hedge against rising prices
they expect inflation to be moderate to subdued and that gives them very little reason to own gold,'' said gary dorsch, an analyst for lns financial group inc. in chicago
he said some traders have been liquidating tangible assets such as gold in anticipation of investing the proceeds in the stock market, which has shown some strength over the past two weeks
but jeffrey a. nichols, president of american precious metals advisors inc. in new york, said the latest decline in gold prices simply extends a trend begun late in 1987, reflecting heavier supplies in a sluggish market
he said the soviet union has sold considerable amounts of gold and mining companies have become more aggressive about selling contracts for what they expect to mine
at the same time, investors have shown little interest in gold because of ``low inflation expectations, stable world equity markets, a strong u.s. bond market and rising confidence in the federal reserve board,'' nichols said
it is not that there has been a massive selloff. it is just that there is a lack of willingness to buy gold except at lower prices,'' he said
on new york's commodity exchange, gold for current delivery fell $9.90 a troy ounce to $431.90
in london, gold fell to $434.70 a troy ounce from $442.50 late tuesday. in zurich, switzerland, gold fell to $436 from $442 late tuesday
gold fell to $444.20 an ounce in hong kong from $446.80 late tuesday
silver bullion fell in london to $6.26 a troy ounce from $6.33 late tuesday. latewr on new york's comex, silver for current delivery fell 10 cents an ounce to $6.19
in the foreign-exchange markets, the dollar traded in a narrow range for most of the day, ending mixed against the world's major currencies
dealers said traders were anxiously awaiting the scheduled release on thursday of revised figures on the u.s. gross national product for the fourth quarter. they said the consensus was that the growth rate would be revised upward from earlier estimates
dorsch said the dollar drew some support from federal reserve chairman alan greenspan's remarks to a congressional panel that ``he was not in favor of driving the dollar lower to increase exports.''
but the dollar wound up lower in new york against the japanese, canadian, italian and british currencies, while it edged up against those of west germany, france and switzerland
in tokyo, the dollar rose to 128.75 japanese yen from 128.50 yen late tuesday. later in london, the dollar traded at 128.57 yen. the dollar slipped to 128.82 yen in new york from 129.00 yen late tuesday
the british pound fell to $1.7640 in london from $1.7655 late tuesday. later in new york, the pound edged up to $1.76355 from $1.76325 on tuesday
other late dollar rates in new york, compared with late rates tuesday, included: 1.69575 west german marks, up from 1.69475; 1.39535 swiss francs, up from 1.39325; 5.7340 french francs, up from 5.7330; 1,248.00 italian lire, down from 1,248.50; and 1.26505 canadian dollars, down from 1.26765
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late rates tuesday, included: 1.6925 west german marks, down from 1.6945; 1.3908 swiss francs, up from 1.3895; 5.7240 french francs, unchanged; 1.8990 dutch guilders, down from 1.9000; 1,246.25 italian lire, down from 1.246.60, and 1.2651 canadian dollars, down from 1.2712
greyhound corp. said wednesday it has reached an agreement in principle to purchase the household products business and assets of the 20 mule team division of u.s. borax &amp; chemical corp
the purchase price was not disclosed
among the products made by the los angeles-based company are borateam dry bleach, borax powdered hand soap and 20 mule team borax
the product line, which is sold in the united states and canada, has annual revenue of about $30 million, company officials said
the purchase was negotiated wednesday by dial corp., greyhound's consumer products group
dial, with sales of $866 million last year and net income of $41.4 million, makes such products as dial and tone hand soaps, purex laundry and household goods and armour star canned foods
u.s. borax &amp; chemical corp. is a subsidiary of rtz corp. plc of britain
greyhound, based in phoenix, is a diversified company with revenue last year of $2.5 billion. its principle operations are in consumer products, services, transportation, manufacturing and financial businesses. graf pvs, bgng: ``greenspan, in ...''</note>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan on wednesday criticized what he said was administration pressure for lower interest rates, but president reagan denied knowledge of such an effort and voiced support for the fed chairman
in congressional testiony, greenspan had cautioned that further white house efforts to influence the central bank could boomerang. he referred in particular to a letter written by a treasury department official pleading for easier credit
asked at his wednesday night news conference about greenspan's complaint, and whether he still had confidence in greenspan, reagan replied: ``yes i do. and i'm going to have to find out what this is all about that you're talking about, because nothing of that kind had been directed to me.''
greenspan, who was appointed to the fed post by reagan last summer, issued his warning as the administration sought to dampen its dispute with the central bank
beryl sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser, said the administration currently is ``delighted with monetary policy.''
greenspan, in testimony before the senate banking committee, was highly critical of a letter sent by assistant treasury secretary michael darby to top fed policy-makers 10 days before they were to meet to set monetary growth targets for 1988
the fed tries to supply enough money to the economy to support sustained growth while guarding against over-doing money creation and thus re-igniting inflation. both darby and srinkel have complained that the money supply grew so sluggishly in 1987 that it raised concerns about a possible recession during this election year
the darby letter was brought up in questioning by sen. william proxmire, d-wis., who cited it as just one of numerous examples of administration pressure on the fed. while proxmire did not release the text of darby's letter, the senator said the clear implication was that the administration was pressuring the fed to ``ease up on the money.''
he said darby's letter to each member of the federal open market committee was the most overt effort he had ever seen on the part of the administration to influence fed decision-making
i think it is both deplorable and counterproductive for the reagan administration to pressure you as much as they have in recent months,'' proxmire said
greenspan said while the central bank was not being unduly influenced by the administration, he was worried about the perceptions in financial markets
the only thing that i hope does not happen is that the concern of our responding to political pressures gets so extraordinary that we will feel the necessity to do precisely the opposite,'' greenspan said
greenspan said, ``when i heard about dr. darby's letter i objected quite strongly. as best i can judge, he was not aware of the implications of doing this just prior to an fomc meeting.''
greenspan indicated he had received assurances that there would be no repeat of the darby letter
greenspan and the other four members of the federal reserve board were all appointed by president reagan, the first time one president has named all members of the board since franklin roosevelt. there is one vacancy
the normal fed term is 14 years, a tenure designed to insulate the board from political pressures and also make it harder for one president to name all the board members
proxmire said the current situation was raising concerns that the central bank would bend to administration pressure and boost money growth so much during this election year that the country would suffer another round of debilitating inflation in 1989
greenspan did not say which administration official he contacted concerning the darby letter, but it has been reported that treasury secretary james a. baker iii was instrumental in toning down criticism of the fed in the economic report of the president issued last week
sprinkel, in a separate appearance wednesday before the house budget committee, said that while he believed the fed had been too stingy in supplying money to the economy last year, things have improved in the past six weeks
since that time, we've been delighted with monetary policy,'' sprinkel said. ``they're dedicated to a policy of moderate expansion. ... they have the power to do it, and i'm confident they will do it.''
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan says the risk of a recession is as great as the risk of renewed inflation, but he agrees with the reagan administration that neither appears imminent
greenspan made his remarks tuesday during the fed's semi-annual congressional testimony on its conduct of monetary policy
greenspan also confirmed that the central bank had eased credit slightly a few weeks ago in an effort to keep the economic expansion alive
orders to u.s. factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods fell 2.8 percent in january, the biggest decline in a year, according to the commerce department
durable goods orders fell to a seasonally adjusted $112.23 billion last month, a drop of $3.28 billion from december, reflecting sharp drops in demand for aircraft and primary metals, the government said tuesday
the steep decline followed a december advance of 4.1 percent, which was the strongest rise since march
a massachusetts electric holding company has begun talks aimed at taking over ailing public service company of new hampshire, except for its 36 percent share of the stalled seabrook nuclear plant
public service, the lead seabrook owner, filed for federal bankruptcy protection last month
new england electric system, based in westborough, mass., said tuesday the potential takeover would let public service pay its share of seabrook preparation costs while its owners keep trying to get an operating license
black &amp; decker corp. has sweetened a hostile bid for american standard inc. a second time, raising its offer to $68 from $65 per share and promising court action to block the target's recapitalization plan
the latest offer from black &amp; decker on tuesday _ worth about $2.11 billion _ surprised some analysts who said the bidding was becoming inflated
texaco inc. has agreed to pay $1.25 billion to the government to settle claims it overcharged customers for oil during the 1973-81 period of price controls
the nation's third largest oil company said tuesday it would make a first installment of $400 million when the agreement was closed and pay the rest over the following 5{ years
the white plains, n.y.-based oil giant is the latest in a series of companies forced to pay billions to resolve charges they violated pricing restrictions on crude oil and refined products during the period of federal controls
a federal judge has ruled occidental chemical corp. is liable for the estimated $250 million cost of cleaning up the love canal landfill that became synonymous with environmental disaster
after nine years of deliberations, u.s. district judge john curtin said tuesday that occidental produced the wastes that created the disaster and stored them in a way that would eventually result in toxic leakage
occidental spokesman james green said the company was disappointed by the ruling but would not comment until its attorneys had studied the decision
grammy goose met granny goose in court on tuesday to decide an issue that has ruffled a lot of feathers
granny goose foods inc. has accused the grammy goose baby boutique of ``diluting'' the food company's name and logo. granny has asked for a preliminary injunction against grammy
granny goose, the nation's third largest potato chip manufacturer, is arguing the boutique in nearby petaluma has created confusion by using a similar name
the name and logo ``represent the most valuable asset my client owns,'' granny attorney kate spellman told sonoma county superior court judge lloyd von der mehden. ``where there is confusion, dilution has occurred.''
sandy gotelli, the petaluma grandmother who owns the baby shop, said she'll be forced out of business if the injunction is granted. she said she picked the name by combining her liking for geese with her granddaughter's nickname for her
ms. spellman told the court the company made a three-point offer to grammy goose: to help design a new sign, to help phase out printed paper goods and to help find a new name that retains part of the current name
we understand she is a small business and we would like to mitigate the harm to her,'' ms. spellman said
she acknowledged there had ``not been a great decrease in sales,'' but said the case had resulted in negative publicity for the corporation
the judge gave mrs. gotelli one week to respond in writing to the points made by ms. spellman. granny goose's attorneys then will have another five days to respond
system one direct access inc., a texas air corp. affiliate that markets a computer reservations system to travel agents, filed an antitrust lawsuit tuesday against united airlines, which runs a rival system
system one described in its complaint a pattern of actions undertaken by chicago-based united since 1984 to inhibit competition and unfairly preserve market dominance
the lawsuit, filed in a houston federal court, says that united's action also violated regulations adopted by the civil aeronautics board in 1984, which prohibit airlines that own a system one computer reservations system from directly or indirectly prohibiting travel agents from obtaining or using another system
the anticompetitive actions undertaken by united, according to the lawsuit, include rollover requirements, which extend the contract for a new five-year term every time the agent adds new equipment or services and punitive damages clauses based on future airline booking fees, which may amount to hundreds of thousands of dollars in the event an agent switches systems
the lawsuit also alleges that united airlines' contractural clauses prevent travel agents from using additional systems and the filings of lawsuits against individual travel agencies that select an alternative computer system vendor
matthew gonring, spokesman for united, said he was aware of the lawsuit but would not comment further
texas air is the parent company of eastern and continental airlines
united, through an affiliated company called covia corp, operates apollo, the second largest computerized reservation system in the country behind american sabre, affiliated with american airlines. system one is third
